<HEADLINE>
MALONE WANTED KENNEDY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Los Angeles Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone
was forced to hire Davey Johnson as manager by President Bob
Graziano, according to three sources with ties to the team.
</P>
<P>
   Malone's choice was Kevin Kennedy, but Graziano insisted on
Johnson, who was named manager a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Graziano felt the team needed a high-profile manager with a
proven record and went with Johnson,'' said one source. ``Believe
me, the job was Kennedy's until Graziano intervened.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson won the World Series with the New York Mets in 1986. His
managerial record is 985-727 and his .575 winning percentage is
tops among active managers.
</P>
<P>
   The sources all said former Dodgers general manager Tom Lasorda
also was in favor of Kennedy, a Dodgers minor-league manager from
1984 through '91 and San Fernando Valley native who wanted to
return to the organization.
</P>
<P>
   Graziano and Malone couldn't be reached for comment on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   During his interview with Kennedy, Graziano reportedly spent
most of it probing the one-time manager of the Boston Red Sox and
Texas Rangers about his lifestyle when he was a Dodgers employee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kevin was a little wild when he was younger and Graziano was
more interested in that than he was in Kevin's baseball knowledge
and leadership skills,'' said another source. ``Graziano still
listens to Charlie Blaney (recently ousted Dodgers minor-league
chief), who didn't like Kennedy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
