<HEADLINE>
AUTUMN LEAFLETS OF A LABOR PROTEST  
 SURGERY INSTEAD OF DISCOVERY  
 BROADCAST NOTES  
 HAPPY BIRTHDAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New-York Historical Society's white-columned
museum on Central Park West is not a happy place. Union workers,
complaining that their contract expired 20 months ago, have been
handing leaflets to big-name guests arriving for events.
</P>
<P>
   The workers, who object to the society's offer of a 2 percent
wage increase, were on the sidewalk on Monday evening as guests
arrived for two events, one a discussion with former Police
Commissioner WILLIAM BRATTON and Queens District Attorney RICHARD
BROWN.
</P>
<P>
   The leafleting went more smoothly than it did earlier in the
month. On Oct. 13, the executive director, BETSY GOTBAUM, got into
a shouting match after she accused the workers of trying to
``force'' a leaflet into the hands of REBA WHITE WILLIAMS, a
sponsor of the reception she was attending.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was completely outrageous,'' said FRED JOHNSON, an official
of Local 2110 of the Technical, Office and Professional Union,
affiliated with the United Auto Workers. Of Mrs. Gotbaum, he said,
``She was going on that we had absolutely no right to be there.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Gotbaum said she was ``infuriated'' that the workers had
followed Mrs. Williams up the museum steps. ``I went out and said,
`You're not supposed to do that,' '' Mrs. Gotbaum said. ``They
said, `Given your husband, how could you do this?' I said, `Given
who I am, how could I not?' '' She said that she later complained
about the mention of her husband, the labor leader VICTOR GOTBAUM.
``He has nothing to do with this,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The president of Local 2110, MAIDA ROSENSTEIN, said, ``One would
assume that we would be on the same page, at least in terms of the
broad issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Surgery instead of Discovery
</P>
<P>
   Why wasn't TED TURNER in Cape Canaveral, Fla., for the launching
of the space shuttle Discovery on Thursday? He was in Rochester
(N.Y.) General Hospital, where he had back surgery on Wednesday to
repair a herniated disc.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the hospital, JOHN TURNER (``I'm not related,
darn''), said that Ted Turner was in satisfactory condition and
might be discharged Friday. John Turner said Ted Turner's physician
in Atlanta had referred him to the surgeon who did the operation,
DR. PAUL MAURER.
</P>
<P>
   Broadcast Notes
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ SAM DONALDSON may have his hands full as the host of
the annual Broadcasting and Cable Hall of Fame dinner at the New
York Marriott Marquis Hotel on Nov. 9. One of the inductees is JANE
PAULEY, who was replaced as an anchor of the ``Today'' show on NBC
by one of the people who has RSVP'd, DEBORAH NORVILLE. One
broadcaster who attends the event every year said it would be the
first time the two have been in the same room since Ms. Pauley left
the ``Today'' studio in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine sponsoring the dinner, Broadcasting &AMP; Cable,
reported this week that HAROLD FURCHTGOTT-ROTH, a member of the
Federal Communications Commission, is no couch potato: He does not
own a television and does not plan to buy either a conventional
model or a $7,000-plus digital set before the FCC-mandated
changeover to high-definition television broadcasting begins on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   That does not mean that he does not keep an eye on what he
regulates. ``He has a television in his office,'' said his
assistant, GINGER CLARK.
</P>
<P>
   Happy Birthday
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The crowd at ALEXANDRA STYRON'S table could carry a
tune _ the filmmakers SUSANNA STYRON (her big sister), DAN ALGRANT
and GRIFFIN DUNNE were among those who sang ``Happy Birthday'' to
the 32-year-old novelist _ but the man at the next table at Bambou,
on East 14th Street, joined in. Then STEVIE WONDER sang his own
version of the song.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the most astonishing moment,'' Ms. Styron said later.
``I thought, `Oh, my God, he's singing.' It was the coolest thing I
could possibly imagine having happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
