<HEADLINE>
BULLET IN KNAPSACK COULD FIGURE IN LEVIN MURDER TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A police investigator testified Thursday that she
found a .22-caliber bullet _ the same type of bullet used to kill
Jonathan Levin _ in the front pocket of a knapsack belonging to a
former student accused of killing Levin, a popular Bronx high
school teacher.
</P>
<P>
   Police investigators said that no fingerprints were found on the
bullet. Because until now there has been little direct evidence
linking the former student, Corey Arthur, 20, to the firing of the
shot that killed Levin, the discovery of the bullet could prove to
be important evidence. Earlier at the trial, a former girlfriend of
Arthur said he had confessed to her.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Arthur, who faces life in prison without parole if
convicted of first-degree murder, have admitted that he was in the
apartment of his former teacher on the night of the slaying, May
30, 1997. But they have said that Montoun Hart, 26, Arthur's
co-defendant, or other accomplices still at large committed the
murder. Hart will be tried separately on second-degree murder
charges in January.
</P>
<P>
   After the trial recessed, defense lawyers tried to cast doubt on
the discovery of the bullet in a crime laboratory by the Police
Department investigator, Mary Eng. They questioned how
investigators who first searched the backpack at the murder scene
could have missed anything as important as a bullet.
</P>
<P>
   While stopping short of suggesting that police had planted the
bullet, one defense lawyer, George Goltzer, called the sequence of
events curious. ``It's highly unusual to have a knapsack found at a
crime scene and a bullet discovered inside it two weeks later,'' he
said. ``It's not only highly unusual. It's remarkable.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, prosecutors also released a 1993 graduate school paper
written by Levin, containing a glowing description of his
relationship with Arthur. He wrote that the relationship was an
inspiration: ``So much of what I am and what I want to do in this
life, and profession, revolves around what I've established'' with
him.
</P>
<P>
   If Arthur did kill his former teacher, Levin's emotional
statements about his former student, read publicly for the first
time Thursday, suggested a new degree of cold-bloodedness to the
crime. The former teacher voluntarily let Arthur into his apartment
on the day he was killed, according to prosecutors who accuse
Arthur of taking advantage of his former teacher's good intentions.
</P>
<P>
   The nature of Levin's relationship with his accused killer is a
central to the trial. Defense lawyers have argued that Arthur was
so close to his former teacher that he would never have killed him.
But prosecutors say the relationship was not as close as defense
lawyers contend, adding that the two had grown apart by the time
the killing occurred.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Levin, the son of the Time-Warner chairman, Gerald Levin, wrote
the paper while getting a master's degree at New York University in
the fall of 1993. In the paper, he cited his relationship with
Arthur as one of the primary reasons he wanted to become a teacher
and said receiving a thank you note from Arthur was ``one of the
most moving experiences I've had in a very long time and has made
me extremely proud of what I've accomplished so far.''
</P>
<P>
   He described Arthur, then his student at William Howard Taft
High School, as a ``remarkable combination of talent and tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never met a 16-year-old who has been through and seen
what he has, and seems incredibly rough and intimidating on the
outside,'' the young teacher wrote, ``and, yet, he harbors some
positive goals and aspirations that he can share with no one,
because most of his peers would find them ridiculous.''
</P>
</TEXT>
