<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-TAPE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT SHOWING THIS WEEK: GATES' TAPED TESTIMONY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST) 
(lb) 
 By JERI CLAUSING   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two blocks away, on Capitol Hill, it would have
been called a filibuster. At the federal courthouse, however, it
was simply a defensive strategy.
</P>
<P>
   In pursuing a laborious cross-examination of the second witness
in the Microsoft antitrust trial, lawyers for the company foiled
plans by the Justice Department to close the week with the
much-anticipated _ and in Microsoft's case, much-dreaded _
videotaped questioning of the company's chairman, Bill Gates.
</P>
<P>
   The tape, a recording of Gates answering questions from
government lawyers in a pretrial deposition, has been the source of
a struggle between the two sides from the beginning. Microsoft
asked U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson to block the
playing of the tape, arguing that if government lawyers wanted the
court to hear from Gates, they should call him as one of their 12
witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson ruled on Tuesday that antitrust laws do not limit the
use of depositions of the chief executive of the company on trial.
</P>
<P>
   Asked Thursday whether he thought that Microsoft had engaged in
a filibuster to delay the showing of the videotape, the Justice
Department's lead lawyer, David Boies, said, ``I'm not going to
second-guess Microsoft's defensive strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   Boies, who on four different occasions this week had told
reporters that he planned imminently to present portions of the
Gates tape, added, ``We just didn't get to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the word ``filibuster'' was heard repeatedly in murmurs
among the politically savvy observers packed into the courtroom
Thursday as Microsoft's lead lawyer, John Warden, tried, at a
painful pace, to pick apart the testimony of David Colburn, a
senior vice president of America Online.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the murmurs were no doubt a result of sheer
disappointment. Anticipation of the Gates testimony had brought
renewed interest _ and long lines for seats _ to Jackson's
courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft officials denied any effort to delay the playing of
the tape. Mark Murray, a Microsoft spokesman, said outside the
courthouse Thursday that when the tape was finally shown, ``You
will see a witness who won't let the government put words in his
mouth _ who won't be bullied.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
