<SLUG> BC-FBC-USCNOTE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KENDRICK WINS AGAINST GRAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The changing of the left guard became almost
official Thursday, when USC coach Paul Hackett said that junior
college transfer Donta Kendrick will probably start in place of
Jason Grain.
</P>
<P>
   It's the second consecutive week Kendrick has beaten out Grain,
who started the Trojans' first six games. Kendrick tweaked his leg
in practice Thursday, but if he's OK, he should start.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been more Donta's improvement (than anything else),''
Hackett said. ``I believe he's starting again.''
</P>
<P>
   At one point earlier in the season, Kendrick had fallen to third
string, but his stock has risen recently. Grain fell behind last
week with some problems during practice drills, but he will share
time with Kendrick on Saturday against Washington.
</P>
<P>
   __ It'll be wristbands: Freshman quarterback Carson Palmer
sported a wristband with about 15 plays Thursday, as USC will
probably abandon signaling most plays from the sideline against
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``It actually works good. I like it,'' Palmer said. ``I think it
just speeds up the process. The more wordy plays are on the
wristband.''
</P>
<P>
   One play has 10 words on it, which meant quarterbacks coach Ken
O'Brien would previously signal in the entire 10-word play.
</P>
<P>
   Said Hackett: ``This is just going to hopefully help. We're
probably overstating it if we think it will make a heck of a lot of
difference. We need to to be more aware of the 25-second clock.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmer appeared to take more repetitions than normal, but
Hackett said it was just to make sure both quarterbacks get a fair
chance to run all the pass plays.
</P>
<P>
   __ Fighting mad: In just his second day of practice, freshman
Jason Thomas made quite an impression. After being tackled by
defensive end Sultan Abdul-Malik, the pair got into a scuffle.
Malik repeatedly punched Thomas in the face, although Thomas was
wearing his helmet and was unharmed.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long he didn't hurt (Malik),'' Hackett joked.
</P>
<P>
   __ Williams available: Defensive tackle Aaron Williams (neck
stinger) did not practice Thursday but is expected to play.
Shamsud-Din Abdul-Shaheed, who has been a defensive end, will
start.
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker Mark Cusano (sore thigh) won't start but will also
play.
</P>
<P>
   __ Collins to redshirt: Darren Collins, a defensive tackle who
hurt his ankle early in training camp but has practiced the past
few weeks, will redshirt. Hackett said he wants to have Collins and
Kansas State transfer Matt Childers as juniors to provide depth
next season on the defensive line.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of redshirts, tailback Sultan McCullough has practiced
at wide receiver, but Hackett said he still envisions the ex-Muir
High star as a running back.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a ton of versatility,'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   __ DeSaussure makes comeback: Former Taft High wide receiver
Andre DeSaussure had a career-high 167 yards receiving and two
touchdowns for Washington last week against Oregon State. It was
his first start of the season. He will make his second start
Saturday. It's a big turnaround for DeSaussure, who was suspended
part of last season for violating team rules.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
