<SLUG> BC-NY-CAREY-PROFILE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUGH CAREY: OUT OF POLITICS, BUT NOT OUT OF OPINIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (DUPLICATION NOTICE: Also sent in category `a') 
(bl) 
 By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``Do you want to take my pulse?'' former Gov. Hugh
Carey inquired on the other end of the phone.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, yes. Carey, 79, was responding to an interview request
_ Who does he like in the Senate race? What's he been up to? Etc. _
and within minutes had reduced the situation to its essence. But as
it turned out, he was speaking in classic Carey black humor as well
as metaphor.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 14, Carey had surgery for an inflamed prostate, and on
Oct. 19 he came home. Then, earlier this week, his pulse evidently
strong, the former Democratic governor of New York held forth for
more than two hours in his Upper East Side Manhattan apartment,
hurtling from descriptions of his friendship with Gov. George
Pataki to his admiration for Mayor Rudolph Giuliani to his bizarre
second marriage, to Evangeline Gouletas, who, he said, threw plates
at him.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was pretty good with those plates,'' Carey said. ``She had
a Mediterranean temper, yeah.''
</P>
<P>
   In brief, Carey's wit is intact, and he looks good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a pretty active pulse, they tell me,'' Carey said when
he called back to insist that he had not become more politically
conservative. ``Except for the plumbing that's just been fixed,
they say I have the physique of a moderately middle-aged man.'' His
hair, which was varying shades throughout his political career, is
now a light brown, with small bits of gray. ``It's pretty close to
my natural color,'' Carey said. ``Whatever that is.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike former Mayor Ed Koch and former Gov. Mario Cuomo, Carey
has largely stayed out of politics since finishing his second term
in 1982. Considered brilliant by his fans, quirky by everyone else,
Carey is the governor who rescued New York City and New York state
from financial collapse.
</P>
<P>
   But he did not seek a third term, or run for president, after he
married Ms. Gouletas, a real-estate developer whose third
ex-husband _ she at first said she had two _ surfaced only after
her marriage to Carey.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Carey has opinions. He thinks the Senate race between
Sen. Alfonse D'Amato and Rep. Charles Schumer is far too close to
call, but that if ``Schumer doesn't make this, he might be in the
run for mayor. Either way, Schumer's made his mark.''
</P>
<P>
   Carey wouldn't say who he was voting for, but did say he differs
with Schumer on some issues, including Schumer's vote against the
ban on ``partial-birth'' abortions.
</P>
<P>
   Carey was not overly enthusiastic about D'Amato, either, but did
say in an interview five years ago, ``I suspect if somebody drops a
watch down a culvert, he calls D'Amato and he'll get the watch
out.''
</P>
<P>
   In the gubernatorial race between Pataki and City Council
Speaker Peter Vallone, Carey said that ``here you've got two very
competent men.'' His favorite is clearly Pataki, who in 1994 put
Carey on his transition team. ``I made a habit as governor of
courting former governors,'' Carey said. ``I would always make the
mansion available, or send a plane or a car to pick them up.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Cuomo, whom Carey said never invited him to the mansion,
Pataki has.
</P>
<P>
   Carey described his life as the pleasant one of a country squire
who enjoys 12 children and 15 grandchildren on some 30 acres the
family bought last year on Shelter Island. (Carey retired as
executive vice president of W.R. Grace &AMP; Co. in 1995, and is now of
counsel to two law firms. He also serves on boards.)
</P>
<P>
   It was Carey's idea to buy the property, which he saw was for
sale while he was laid up for spinal surgery in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I was in the hospital, the kids keep coming in to check on
me, and I say, `The will is not in action yet! No will yet!'''
Carey said. The Carey Trust _ Carey said he has turned over all his
assets to his children _ eventually bought the property. ``We do
everything by caucus,'' he said. ``I'm really not the patriarch.
I'm one lonely vote. Especially since they now have control of the
loot.''
</P>
<P>
   Carey said he would have run for president in 1984 against
Ronald Reagan had he not married Ms. Gouletas, and that he looked
back on his failed marriage with her as ``a religious lesson'' for
which he paid a high price. ``It made me look ludicrous in the eyes
of the state,'' he said. Before, he added, ``I was respected as a
governor, I was a sole parent, I had dates with nice girls. So the
worst is, I gave scandal. You do not give scandal. When I gave
scandal, I left politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Carey's first wife, Helen, died in 1974. Two of his sons died in
an automobile accident in 1969. His 36-year-old son, Paul, a member
of Securities and Exchange Commission, is recently back at work
after treatment for cancer of the endocrine system, but stays with
his father when he is in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The younger Carey said Thursday that he remembers how his father
was lauded as a ``governor for hard winters,'' but in his eyes he
is a ``father for hard winters.''
</P>
<P>
   In the mornings these days, Carey takes an early walk, stops in
to chat with his old friend the doctor, Kevin Cahill, and goes to
daily Mass at St. Vincent Ferrer Church on Lexington Avenue. ``It's
a very easy half-hour in beautiful surroundings,'' Carey said.
``Not a bad way to kick your day off.'' And, he said cheerfully,
``I figure as I'm getting to the evening of my life, I'm beginning
to pack my bags for the journey.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
