   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-TV (Atlanta) _ A portrait of three hours of American
television in six cities, six days before the election. By Kevin
Sack.
</P>
<P>
   IND-HOUSE-RACE (Jeffersonville, Ind.) _ One of the first clues
next Tuesday night about the trend in this year's elections will be
the early returns from the congressional race here in southeastern
Indiana. Rep. Lee Hamilton, a Democrat, is retiring after 34 years
in Congress. The race to succeed him, which by all accounts is
extremely close, matches two aggressive, well-financed candidates
who take positions that vary not a whit from the dogma of their
respective national parties. By David E. Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-OUTLOOK (Washington) _ With the midterm elections just
five days away, Republicans are tamping down expectations that they
can expand their majority to 60 seats in the Senate. By Katharine
Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT34) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-FISCHER (Washington) _ Brazil is the bailout of the
month, and Stanley Fischer is the closest thing the world economy
has to a battlefield medic. As the No. 2 official of the
International Monetary Fund, Fischer has been in constant
negotiations with Pedro Malan, Brazil's finance minister. By David
E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo showing Stanley Fischer has been sent to NYT
photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Undated) _ Despite signs that the red-hot labor
market has cooled a bit since last spring, the pay of workers is
rising faster than it has in years. By Sylvia Nasar.
</P>
<P>
   CBS-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ Fixing CBS will not be easy. But
investors in the company that owns the storied television network
appear to have faith that Mel Karmazin, the new chairman and chief
executive, has the ability to do it. By Geraldine Fabrikant.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET.)
</P>
<P>
   TOYS`R'US-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ The advertising that promotes
Toys ``R'' Us Inc. for the holiday shopping season is always
crucial for the company, the United States' largest toy retailer,
which rings up 50 percent of its annual business in the weeks
leading up to Christmas. This year the stakes are even higher than
usual. By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BAKER-COLUMN (Undated) _ Russell Baker recalls Winnie Judd,
trunk murderess.
</P>
<P>
   ROSENTHAL-COLUMN (Undated) _ A.M. Rosenthal exposes some Mideast
myths.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RUN-VECSEY-COLUMN (Undated) _ Sports of The Times column on
Alberto Salazar, the last American to win the New York Marathon and
now a father of two living in Portland and working for Nike. By
George Vecsey.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT32) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   BKN-NBA-TV (New York) _ NBA players are unhappy that both NBC
and TNT, the networks that have NBA broadcast rights, are making
full payments to the league even though a month's worth of games
have already been canceled. The players think the league and the
networks are conspiring against them and are talking of refusing to
do interviews with NBC and TNT as a retaliatory measure. By Mike
Wise.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-MATCHUPS (Undated) _ Pro football matchups. By Mike freeman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WEEKEND (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MOMA-POLLOCK-EXHIBIT (New York) _ Review of the landmark Jackson
Pollock retrospective at the Museum of Modern Art. By Michael
Kimmelman.
</P>
<P>
   BOSTON-GRAVES (Boston) _ Time flies. Remember you must die.
Those words are carved in stone, a few steps from busy Tremont
Street. The phrases are actually in Latin (``Fugit hora, memento
mori''), but their meaning is vividly clear by what appears beneath
them, a carving of Father Time with an hourglass and a skeleton
with an arrow, both reaching to snuff out a candle. The scene turns
up a few times on the gravestones in King's Chapel Burying Ground,
Boston's oldest graveyard, which I recently visited on a tour of
historic graveyards in and around Boston. By Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT28) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   NY-ETHNIC-THEATER (New York) _ For a place as wildly diverse as
New York, the city's major commercial theater can often seem
considerably less so. Sure, ``The Beauty Queen of Leenane'' is an
Irish play, and ``Art'' is French. The list, and the world, seem
pretty much to end right there. But while Broadway's idea of exotic
fare may be a West End import, in neighborhoods throughout the
city, smaller nonprofit theaters are serving up a feast of original
work, seldom-seen plays and new translations from a wide variety of
ethnic backgrounds. By Jesse McKinley.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT23) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   KENNEDY-VIOLIN (New York) _ Probably the first thing to know
about the English violinist Nigel Kennedy is that having returned
to the classical concert stage after a five-year self-imposed
exile, during which he worked almost exclusively on rock projects,
he is no longer using his first name. ``I suppose it was partially
a contemptuous thing to do, to rile the British critics,'' Kennedy
said during a recent stopover in New York, before starting a tour
that includes a run of performances with the New York Philharmonic
and a recital at Avery Fisher Hall this weekend. By Allan Kozinn.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT21) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   WHITNEY-REORG (New York) _ It did not take long for Maxwell L.
Anderson, the new director of the Whitney Museum of American Art,
to start making his mark. After less than 60 days on the job,
Anderson has announced changes in the museum's curatorial and
management organizations that will add more rigor to programming
decisions, decentralize decision making and require hiring two
curators and three senior administrators. By Judith H. Dobrzynski.
</P>
<P>
   VAMPIRES-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``John Carpenter's Vampires'':
With James Woods, Daniel Baldwin, Sheryl Lee, Maximillian Schell.
Reviewed by Lawrence Van Gelder.
</P>
<P>
   LOUD-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Living Out Loud'': Richard
LaGravenese, writer/director; With Danny DeVito, Holly Hunter,
Rachel Leigh Cook, Queen Latifah, Richard Schiff. Reviewed by Janet
Maslin.
</P>
<P>
   ANGELS-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Talk of Angels'': Nick Hamm
with Polly Walker, Vincent Perez, Franco Nero, Frances McDormand.
Reviewed by Stephen Holden.
</P>
