<DOCNO> NYT19981030.0014 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-30 00:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5026 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON30-COX     10-30 0488
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Upbeat Clinton speaks at fundraisers after attending Glenn
launch
 &HT;    By Tim O'Meilia
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ President Bill Clinton flew to Palm
Beach County on Thursday on the euphoria of John Glenn's shuttle
launch, hoping to buoy candidate Buddy MacKay into the governor's
mansion.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's four-hour side trip to South Florida was aimed at
raising $600,000 from deep-pocketed Democrats in a late hour effort
to help MacKay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why did we all love John Glenn's trip back into space? Because
it was about possibilities. And that makes us all feel good. This
election is about possibilities,'' Clinton told 70 people who paid
$5,000 to $20,000 for a dinner with the president.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was the featured guest for an 8:30 p.m. at Slim-Fast
founder S. Daniel Abraham's eighth floor penthouse in the Palm
Beach Biltmore condominium overlooking the Intracoastal Waterway.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-five minutes earlier he also spoke at a cocktail reception
downstairs in a party room for another group of 50 people who paid
$2,500 to $10,000 to pose for photographs with the president.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's trip came 364 days after he last visited the county.
Like that trip, this was to make up for a trip he missed. This trip
made up for an Oct. 13 trip he cancelled to deal with budget
concerns and the Middle East talks.
</P>
<P>
   Air Force One arrived at Palm Beach International Airport at
5:35 p.m. and Clinton disembarked with MacKay and Gov. Lawton
Chiles at his side.
</P>
<P>
   A raucous group of 30 or so boosters met Clinton at the airport
and Clinton paused to chat with them for several minutes. Among
them were Palm Beach County Commission Chairman Burt Aaronson,
State Reps. Suzanne Jacobs, Lois FrankeypG9 E)YX6ey, and State
Sens. Steve Geller and Ron Klein
</P>
<P>
   Aside from boosters who could write big checks, Clinton's
biggest welcome came from schoolchildren gathered outside Palm
Beach Public School on Cocoanut Row.
</P>
<P>
   As the motorcade passed, they cheered and held up welcoming
signs that couldn't be read in the dimming twilight. Another group
of cheers came from people gathered on the sidewalk outside E.R.
Bradley's Saloon near the Biltmore.
</P>
<P>
   The diners in Abraham's marble-floored condominium were crowded
around tables of 10 for a meal of acorn squash and vegetable soup,
Chilean sea bass and white truffles and warm chocolate tart with
vanilla sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was flanked by Abraham and real estate developer Pritam
Singh. MacKay introduced the president, calling him a friend of his
and ``a great friend of Florida.''
</P>
<P>
   Upbeat following the Discovery launch, Clinton said MacKay stood
up for him when Clinton first campaigned for the presidency in
Florida in 1992. ``That showed a lot of foresight, and foresight is
a quality you need in a governor,'' Clinton joked.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
