</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-BLOCK-REACTION-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RE-ELECTION CAMPAIGN TO CONTINUE DESPITE SHERIFF'S DEATH, MANAGER
VOWS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY LEE CONDON AND DOUGLAS HABERMAN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES -- Los Angeles County Sheriff Sherman Block died
Thursday, five days &UR;  &LR; before the most difficult election of his
16-year career as head of the nation's largest Sheriff's
Department. He was 74.
</P>
<P>
   Block's death came at 7:52 p.m., a few hours after his condition
began to deteriorate badly. On Monday, the underwent surgery at USC
University Hospital for a blood clot deep within his brain that
doctors said has caused him to fall at his home in the suburban Los
Angeles community of West Hills hit his head on Saturday. He never
regained consciousness after surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Block's challenger, former sheriff's Chief Lee Baca, had focused
on Block's age and health, saying it made him unfit for office.
Block has survived two bouts with cancer and was undergoing weekly
kidney dialysis treatments.
</P>
<P>
   Block's death Thursday prompted an outpouring of sympathy from
public officials throughout the area.
</P>
<P>
   And Thursday night, his campaign manager said the drive to win
Block a fifth term will continue despite his death -- a move which,
if successful, would allow county supervisors to name his successor
until 2000 election.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sheriff made clear to me last Sunday in the hospital that
he wanted the campaign to continue no matter what happened,'' said
Jay Grodin. ``Voters should vote their conscience. Our campaign
continues forward to continue his vision for the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Baca, who ran a close second in the June primary, issued a
statement joining in the condolences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our family has lost its leader,'' he said. ``Sherman Block was
a giant in the law enforcement family. His dedication and
commitment to his profession was unparalleled. Those of us that
served under Sherman Block are unlikely to experience another who
can match that commitment.''
</P>
<P>
   Supervisor Zev Yaroslavsky said acting Sheriff Jerry Harper
would be named to hold the post until after the Nov. 3 election.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a tough cop but a compassionate cop (who) ``conducted
himself with integrity and honor at all times,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he will be remembered for his innovation, his
willingness to reform, for managing a law enforcement agency at one
of the most difficult times to manage a law enforcement agency.''
</P>
<P>
   Block's name will still appear on the ballot. If voters elect
him, supervisors would have 20 days to name a successor. Possible
candidates include retired Los Angeles Police Department Deputy
Chief Mark Kroeker and Undersheriff Mike Graham.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing the death outside the medical center, Natalie
Macias, a civilian spokeswoman for the department, said Block's
condition worsened quickly and unexpectedly.
</P>
<P>
   ``His family, including his wife Alyce, were at his side.
Sheriff Block had a sudden and rapid deterioration in his condition
late this afternoon. The cause of death was determined to be
recurrent intra-cerebral hemorrhage,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   First elected in 1982, Block was seeking a fifth term for the
$234,016-a-year job, despite his failing health. He was the highest
paid elected official in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Harper said said the department has stable leadership to operate
through the transition period.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a management team the sheriff put into place and this
is a management team that will make sure the department carries out
its mission.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles County Supervisor Michael D. Antonovich called Block
a ``man of honor and integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He was not an armchair sheriff. he was involved in all
segments of the community,'' Antonovich said. ``On behalf of the
board of supervisors, I extend condolences to Alyce, the children
and grandchildren.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles Police Chief Bernard C. Parks said the 13,000 LAPD
officers and staff extended their condolences to the sheriff's
family.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has been a regional leader, a national leader, and many of
the programs that he initiated will go on forever as an appropriate
legacy of what the community needs, and always needs,'' Parks said.
</P>
<P>
   Supervisor Don Knabe called Block ``a man of honor.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My thoughts and prayers are with the Block family,'' he said.
``Sherm Block was a man of honor, a friend and a role model to me,
and I am a better person for having known him. Whether in his
personal life, or his professional life, Sheriff Block was a hero.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Sen. Dianne Feinstein. D-Calif., said in a statement: ``I
am an unabashed fan of Sheriff Sherman Block . . . the department
did have its problems, but Sheriff Block was always there to work
with the men and women of the department in a no-nonsense way.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the week, even as rumors about Block's health swirled
through political circles, doctors said he was regaining
``alertness'' and that he underwent his weekly kidney dialysis with
no complications.
</P>
<P>
   But a blackout was maintained on virtually all information about
his condition.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-30-98 0044EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
