<HEADLINE>
ALL EYES IN BIG EAST ON UCONN SOPHOMORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By FRANK LITSKY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ For the first time in the 17-year history of Big
East women's basketball, a sophomore was named the preseason player
of the year Thursday. She hardly seemed thrilled by the honor, and
neither did her coach.
</P>
<P>
   At its annual day for the news media, the conference announced
that the head coaches had chosen Svetlana Abrosimova of
Connecticut. She is a 6-foot-2-inch forward (up from 6-1 last year)
who also starts for the Russian national team. Last season, she
averaged 14.4 points and a team-high 6.8 rebounds a game for
Connecticut. She is barely 18 years old.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel apprehensive for her,'' said UConn coach Geno Auriemma,
``because to be that young, that far from home, to have that thrown
on her shoulders is a lot. She doesn't need to go through all this.
I'm anxious to see how it plays out.''
</P>
<P>
   What did Abrosimova think?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how to explain it,'' she said with a smile that
seemed to say she would rather not have this burden or have to
explain it. ``It's OK I'm enjoying college basketball. I was home
this summer, and the whole summer I was looking forward to coming
back to Connecticut.''
</P>
<P>
   Abrosimova is a key player for UConn, which reached the National
Collegiate Athletic Association tournament's regional finals last
season. Its only experienced upperclassmen returning are Amy Duran,
a 5-11 senior forward/guard; Paige Sauer, a 6-5 junior center, and
Stacy Hansmeyer, a 6-1 junior power forward. UConn has five
freshmen in an exceptional recruiting class, and one of them _ 5-8
Keirsten Walters or 5-9 Sue Bird _ may start at point guard.
</P>
<P>
   Nine coaches chose UConn to win the league title again, and the
four others picked Rutgers. The key players for Rutgers are Tasha
Pointer, a 5-6 sophomore whom Rutgers Coach C.Vivian Stringer calls
the best point guard in the nation, and Tomora Young, a 5-10
shooting guard. Pointer will miss the next five to seven weeks
after arthroscopic knee surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Rutgers' third under Stringer, the team reached the
NCAA tournament regional semifinals. This year, she said with great
optimism, ``We can be a Final Four team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-30-98 0047EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
