<SLUG> BC-BBO-FREEAGENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEAMS PLAY WAITING GAME ON FREE AGENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Talk is cheap, so general managers continued calling
representatives of free agents Thursday, a week before they are
allowed to begin negotiating for players' services.
</P>
<P>
   No major player was among the seven who filed for free agency
Thursday: Joey Cora and Doug Jones of Cleveland, Terry Steinbach of
Minnesota, Dave Magadan of Oakland, Bobby Witt of St. Louis, Ricky
Bones of Kansas City and Tim Naehring of Boston. The free-agent
list grew to 116.
</P>
<P>
   Yankees general manager Brian Cashman said he was unable to
reach the agent for Kevin Brown but talked to the agents for Randy
Johnson and Devon White.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees will at least see what it might cost to sign Johnson
or Brown, the top two pitchers on the market this off season.
White, who graduated from Park West High School in Manhattan, holds
some conditional interest for the Yankees. White, who will be 36 in
two months, plays center field, and the Yankees may need a center
fielder if Bernie Williams signs elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees will not make definitive free-agency plans until
they have their organizational meeting in Tampa, Fla., next week.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Phillips, the Mets' general manager, said he also
continued talking with agents but declined to identify the players
he talked about. He said his primary interest was in second and
third basemen and right and left fielders. ``Most agents are just
taking temperatures,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clubs can negotiate with and sign their own free agents, but
other clubs cannot initiate contract talks until Friday, Nov. 6.
</P>
<P>
   Although Cashman has said Williams is the Yankees' No. 1
priority, it is not clear if they will make him an offer before
other clubs can begin making their own offers.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston Astros, on the other hand, plan to meet with Johnson
before next Friday. The dominating pitcher so excited the Astros
during his two-month stay with them this year that Drayton McLane
Jr., the team's owner, planned to participate in the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, however, is not expected to commit to any team until he
sees what kind of market value he has. In the same way, the San
Diego Padres would like to re-sign Brown, but he will see what is
available before he makes a commitment. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-30-98 0048EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981030.0022 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-30 00:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5042 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-TOUR-CHAMPIONSHIP     10-30 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-TOUR-CHAMPIONSHIP-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EDDIE SEFKO  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Nobody was sure what was more shocking Thursday at the
Tour Championship _ how awesome Vijay Singh was or how awful Tiger
Woods was.
</P>
<P>
   That they were paired together in the first round at East Lake
Golf Club made the disparity all the more stunning.
</P>
<P>
   Singh humbled what was supposed to be a mean-spirited tract of
land with a 7-under-par 63 to take a three-stroke lead in the $4
million end to the PGA Tour's official season. The Fiji native, who
won the PGA Championship and Sprint International back-to-back in
August, tied the lowest score ever shot by the legendary Bobby
Jones at his home course. His score tied the lowest round in Tour
Championship history, although the 63s carded by Wayne Levi in '89
and '90 and by Jim Gallagher Jr. in '93 were 8-under-par totals.
</P>
<P>
   Singh also made liars out of everybody who predicted lots of
bogey tricks but no birdie treats this Halloween week.
</P>
<P>
   ``From tee to green, it's the best I've played all year,'' Singh
said. ``It was an exceptional round for anybody and one of the best
rounds I've played in my life. I never expected to shoot anything
like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods might be saying the same thing. The Feline struggled.
Big-time. He finally scraped it around East Lake with a 5-over-par
75, some 12 strokes off the blistering pace Singh set.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't hit the ball well at all,'' Woods said. ``In fact, I
hit it all over the map. And the score showed it.''
</P>
<P>
   Did it ever. Typical of Woods' round was a double bogey on the
par-5 ninth hole, where he drove into the right rough and hit his
recovery shot into the water. He then launched his fourth shot over
the green and needed three shots to clean up the mess.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Singh was turning it into an 18-hole rout. He made
eight birdies in the first 15 holes before finally proving he was
human with a three-putt bogey on the par-3 18th.
</P>
<P>
   ``My caddie asked me on No. 18 if I could believe what Vijay was
doing,'' said Justin Leonard, one of nine players to break par-70.
``I said, `What is he, 8-under?' I was joking. Then I looked on the
scoreboard, and he really was 8-under.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eight-under never crossed my mind. Maybe 8 under bogey golf,
but that's about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Singh shot 30 on the front nine and credited his iron play for
the sensational results. He hit three approach shots within a foot
and two more within six feet. Of his birdie putts, only one, a
15-footer on No. 9, would be considered a surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Singh actually had a chance to threaten a round of 60 or perhaps
even 59 when he was staring at a 25-foot eagle putt on the par-5
15th. He missed and settled for a birdie that got him to 8-under.
</P>
<P>
   On No. 18, his 2-iron left him 40 feet short, and he missed a
five-foot comebacker for par.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a 62 in my mind,'' Singh said. ``It's always
disappointing leaving 18 with a bogey. It's a good round. But it
could have been one less.''
</P>
<P>
   But as Singh said, there were a lot of other shots he hit well _
far more than he hit poorly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was unbelievable,'' Singh said of the day. ``I drove the
ball really long and straight. I was going into the greens with
short irons and middle irons. If you're doing that, you can go at
the flags, and the greens are putting so true that you can make
some putts.''
</P>
<P>
   Billy Mayfair shot a 66 and was the closest to Singh. Tom Lehman
and Jim Furyk each had 3-under 67, and Jeff Sluman and Leonard were
another shot back.
</P>
<P>
   The top contenders for Player of the Year, David Duval and Mark
O'Meara, both struggled. Duval matched Woods' 75. O'Meara looked
like he was headed for a similar score but rallied with three
birdies on the last five holes to get back to 1-over 71.
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara said his No. 1 asset was his experience, which
translated into patience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of struggled at the start, and I was 4 over par after
11 holes,'' O'Meara said. ``But this is a long tournament. There's
no cut, and there's only 30 of us here. I started to make some
putts and played well down the stretch.''
</P>
<P>
   Like everyone else, though, he marveled at Singh's play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw Vijay on the tee at No. 18, and I asked him what the
heck he was doing,'' O'Meara said. ``He said he was getting ready
for the grand slam (next year).
</P>
<P>
   ``That's an incredible score on this course. But there are three
more rounds to go.''
</P>
<P>
   A fact comforting to everybody who was ambushed by Singh's
sizzler.
</P>
<P>
   On a breezy but pleasant day for golf, a lot of players
struggled. One-third of the field was lodged at 3-over 73,
including Fred Couples, Jeff Maggert, Phil Mickelson, Tom Watson
and Mark Calcavecchia, who triple-bogeyed No. 18 to account for all
his strokes over par. It was that kind of start at East Lake.
</P>
<P>
   Singh said he's taking nothing for granted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't easy,'' he said. ``I mean all the putts you have to
be very careful with. And I'm still worried about the rough. I'm
going to hit it in there sooner or later. And that's a good workout
trying to get out of there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
