<HEADLINE>
TV SPORTS: RUNNING INTERFERENCE AGAINST THE ELEMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Those who will produce the New York City Marathon on Sunday
hope, as usual, for great racing and moving human interest stories.
</P>
<P>
   But their fervent wish is to avoid last year's weather nightmare
that made television screens periodically snap, crackle and pop and
then rendered crucial cameras useless as Franziska Rochat-Moser
took the lead in the women's race.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it was as bad at the start as it was at the finish, it
would have been a disaster,'' said Gary Critchlow, the senior
production and operators manager for Trans World International,
which is producing the event.
</P>
<P>
   A ceiling of clouds as low as 100 feet off the ground made it
virtually impossible for the motorcycle-carried cameras following
the lead men's and women's packs to transmit their signals to the
five helicopters above them. The choppers dipped as low as 200
feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were concerned the helicopters would collide,'' said Brian
Williams of TWI, the marathon's producer.
</P>
<P>
   Critchlow added, ``A half hour before we went off the air, half
the monitors were blank.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams wondered which was more prudent: stick with the men's
race entirely as John Kagwe raced to a possible course record, or
cut intermittently to the women's race despite the continuous
breakup of the video signal.
</P>
<P>
   Williams stayed with the men's race for 14 key minutes until
transmission from the women's race cleared up in Harlem.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was real frustrating because the audio from Katharine
Switzer told us it was a great race,'' Williams said, referring to
the on-course reporter for the women's race.
</P>
<P>
   The production team can't do much to avoid what happened last
year, except to pray for sun. The forecast calls for partly cloudy
skies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've earned five years of good weather,'' said Paul
Bissonette, general manager of Channel 11.
</P>
<P>
   Still, TWI has mapped out every bridge and trestle over the
26.2-mile course to avoid places where the most video interference
occurs. TWI has added fixed cameras in the Bronx that are not
dependent on helicopter transmission.
</P>
<P>
   ``With 35 cameras, eight mobile units, four motorcycles and a
pickup truck to cover the lead men's and women's packs, seven
helicopters _ two of them with cameras _ the sheer logistics and
coordination is huge,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond trying to handle weather-related woes, TWI has made other
changes from last year's broadcast. The co-anchors Al Trautwig and
Marty Liquori have left the disembodied studio inside the Channel
11 building on East 42nd Street for a new outdoor perch on Central
Park West, near Tavern on the Green.
</P>
<P>
   There will also be a camera mounted high above the
Verrazano-Narrows Bridge to look down on the runners from the
starting point as they run to Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   TWI's production will be seen from 10:30-1:30, ET, on ESPN2.
Cable viewers will not see the local stories being pursued on the
Channel 11 broadcast, including the Five Borough Challenge Cup, a
race-within-a-race between selected runners from each of the city's
boroughs.
</P>
<P>
   HDTV'S Garden Party
</P>
<P>
   Madison Square Garden began its era of high-definition
television Tuesday night when it telecast the Rangers-Sabres game
in the new format, which more than doubles the resolution of
standard TV pictures.
</P>
<P>
   Starting this season, all Rangers and Knicks home games on the
MSG Network will be produced in HDTV. Starting next season, so will
all Yankees home games on MSG and Mets home games on Fox Sports New
York. The Garden is making HDTV a big priority, including
renovating studios inside the arena and leasing a $9.8 million
mobile production truck, the only one of its kind in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the game could be seen in HDTV only on HDTV sets on
display at the Garden's Theater, and in a Nobody Beats the Wiz
store in Carle Place on Long Island. Like the Garden, Cablevision
Systems owns the 39-store Wiz chain.
</P>
<P>
   It is a no-brainer to say that watching hockey, or any sport, in
HDTV is better than traditional TV. The enhanced resolution
produces pictures that are crystal clear and wider so the viewer
receives a broadened, more vivid perspective. The format made it
easier to see plays developing and to see the blemishes on fans
sitting in the ninth row.
</P>
<P>
   It will be years before there are enough HDTV sets to see
programming at home that is shot in that format. But your friends
at Cablevision will soon offer its telecasts at the Garden's
restaurants, inside the arena's luxury suites and at the 39 Wiz
stores, where they will happily sell you a $4,000 set.
</P>
<P>
   Miscellany
</P>
<P>
   _ ESPN is aware of Joe Morgan's part in a group seeking to buy
the Oakland A's, but will not discuss his future as its lead
baseball analyst unless the deal progresses.
</P>
<P>
   _ Negotiations by MSG to sell local broadcast rights to 50 Mets
games are still ongoing, with no deadline set.
</P>
<P>
   _ Michael Wach, Channel 5's general manager, said it may be
months before he hires a two-announcer team to call Yankee games
next season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
