</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-CANADIENS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS TIME, REMATCH IS A DRAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Same teams, different city, very different game.
</P>
<P>
   Only 24 hours before, the Bruins had left the Molson Centre with
a remarkable 9-2 blowout victory over the Canadiens in the first
game of a home-and-home series. They had taken advantage of a nasty
elbowing incident to score three goals during a five-minute major
penalty to Dave Manson that gave them a six-goal lead and for all
intents and purposes ended the game halfway through.
</P>
<P>
   There were no such fireworks Thursday night as the teams battled
to a 1-1 overtime tie at the FleetCenter.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a lot of character on that hockey club and there's a
lot of pride when you wear that sweater,'' said Bruins coach Pat
Burns, a former Habs coach. ``When things happen like (Wednesday),
I knew they were going to come out like gangbusters, and they did.
We had nothing in our favor whatsoever. It was our first game back
after a long road trip, we played (the night before), we beat a
team bad in their own building. If I pick up 3 of the 4 points in
48 hours against the Montreal Canadiens, would you expect me to be
upset? No. I'm not upset. I'm very, very happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Manson was no factor because he was suspended for three games by
the NHL, and his victim, left wing P.J. Axelsson, was held out for
precautionary reasons when he woke up with a headache. He was
diagnosed with a slight concussion and said he hopes to be back
Saturday against Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   The rematch was much closer to the vest than the first game.
There were no offensive barrages, no heavyweight bouts (only
skirmishes), and the teams played tighter defense. On Wednesday
night, the Habs didn't play any defense and the Bruins didn't
really have to.
</P>
<P>
   Goalie Byron Dafoe, who faced 35 mostly harmless shots
Wednesday, had far fewer to fend off Friday night (23), but the
chances were more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   While power plays were the order of the day Wednesday _ the
Bruins went 5 for 9, their high in the past 8 1/2 years _ they had
a hard time generating anything on the man advantage in Round 2,
going 1 for 9.
</P>
<P>
   ``We fumbled on the power plays,'' said Burns. ``We could
probably have won the game, but we'll take what was given to us and
be very happy with it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins were 1 for 6 in the first period, Steve Heinze
connecting as the Habs tried to grab a physical edge as a revenge
factor but wound up parading to the penalty box. Ironically, Heinze
had been told he wasn't playing because of his injured right ring
finger, which kept him out Wednesday. But when Axelsson couldn't
go, Heinze got the call.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hoping, but I didn't know if I could hold the stick when
I got out there,'' said Heinze. ``Fortunately, I could. It was kind
of weird. It's tough getting ready for a game you don't think
you're going to play. Actually, you go out there without any
pressure, just let it hang loose. I wasn't thinking about it all
day, so it was easy to go out there and play.''
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Don Sweeney, positioned along the far left edge of
the left faceoff circle, dished the puck down to left wing Ted
Donato behind the net. Donato relayed it out to Heinze in the left
circle, and he fired it past goalie Jocelyn Thibault at 15:32. It
was Heinze's third goal of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Only moments before, he was smarting from the vibration off his
stick after attempting a one-timer. Center Joe Thornton made a pass
and Heinze tried to connect, but his finger, which was gashed
against New Jersey Saturday, was too painful for him to complete
the shot. However, he quickly recovered and banged in his 100th
career goal.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if he hurt himself on the first attempt, Heinze
laughed. ``Oh yeah,'' he said. ``The vibration made it sting a bit.
It made it numb, and you don't feel it on the next shot, I guess.''
</P>
<P>
   The lead lasted until the final minute of the second period when
the Canadiens, who had far fewer man advantages than Boston, pulled
even on the power play.
</P>
<P>
   Center Chris Taylor was bagged for closing his hand over the
puck in the right corner of the Bruins' zone at 17:37. With only
40.2 seconds left in the period, Dafoe, who had lost his stick,
tried to fend off a Habs flurry but couldn't.
</P>
<P>
   Vincent Damphousse, behind the net, threaded a pass through the
crease for Brian Savage. While falling forward, Savage punched a
shot past the goalie at the left post.
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe's biggest save came at 13:55 of the third when he stoned
Savage from the right circle. The Bruins nearly ended it with 6.5
seconds left in regulation when defenseman Grant Ledyard, who had a
goal and two assists Wednesday, fired a shot from deep in the right
circle that Thibault snagged with his glove.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't quite get it high enough,'' said Ledyard. ``But we
got 3 out of 4 points and we're happy with that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-30-98 0117EST &QL; 
