<HEADER>
A5064 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-REPUTATI     10-30 1375
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-REPUTATION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOT REPUTATION DOESN'T ADD UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH _ Sometimes you don't have to talk to anybody to
understand the situation. Sometimes you just have to know how to
count.
</P>
<P>
   For the past two weeks, there has been much gnashing of teeth in
New England because The Flying Elvises, also known as your New
England Patriots, have lost back-to-back games to the New York Jets
and Miami Dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   Again and again, we hear: How can so talented a team find itself
mired in fourth place in the AFC East as midseason approaches? How
can a team that has been labeled _ and said little to argue against
the label, we must add _ among the most talented in the AFC lose to
the Jets and Dolphins, two division rivals most people would insist
are not as talented as the Patriots?
</P>
<P>
   Well, here are the facts, folks.
</P>
<P>
   This oh so talented team is 11-10 since it opened 1997 with a
4-0 rush against a group of opponents who finished that season with
an aggregate record of 20-44.
</P>
<P>
   This oh so talented team's 10 losses have come against teams
that had an aggregate record of 112-52 in 1997-98. Its 11 victories
have come against teams that are an aggregate 82-79 in 1997-98. If
one goes back to the start of last season, the Patriots have 15
victories in their last 25 games (including playoffs). If the four
season-opening victories last year are added in, their victims have
an aggregate record of 102-123.
</P>
<P>
   Does this make them the Peter McNeeley of the NFL? Well, no. But
it doesn't make them Evander Holyfield, either. So what does this
tell us?
</P>
<P>
   It tells us it has been a mistake all along for so many to talk
so often about how talented this Patriots TEAM is, because
apparently, the TEAM is not as talented as all except the few
naysayers accused of terminal gloom and doom have argued.
</P>
<P>
   There are individual players of great skill in Foxborough.
Several, like Ben Coates, Drew Bledsoe, and Bruce Armstrong, have
been consistent Pro Bowl performers and remain among the elite. But
the TEAM has been consistent in only one thing since the Bill
Parcells-Bledsoe-Pete Carroll era began in 1993. It beats up on the
Sisters of the Lake and loses to the Monsters of the Midway.
</P>
<P>
   In the opinion of Carroll, the so-called elite teams have ``no
more than three or four losses'' in a season. But for the purposes
of this discussion, we were slightly kinder and included teams that
are 11-5 or better among the elite.
</P>
<P>
   What we found was an amazing consistency each year in how many
such teams exist in the NFL. From 1993, when Parcells arrived, to
the end of last season, there were 26, an average of just over five
a season. In fact, every year but last year, there were five teams
at 11-5 or better.
</P>
<P>
   Only once during that stretch has the talented TEAM known as the
New England Patriots been among them.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Patriots have met such teams with some regularity.
On average three times a season during the 1993-97 stretch, they
faced opponents who ended the year 11-5 or better. What did this
most talented TEAM do against those elite opponents?
</P>
<P>
   It went 2-14, including playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Do we begin to see a trend here?
</P>
<P>
   The rebuilding Patriots were 0-3 in 1993 against the heavy iron,
but that was predictable considering what was here when Parcells
arrived. In 1994, things were not much better. The team went 10-6
and reached the playoffs but was 1-2 against top opposition.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, it was back to the future, the Patriots going 0-3
against the best of the best. And in 1996, when they made their
playoff run without having to face such a team in the final two
months until running afoul of the Green Bay Packers in the Super
Bowl, the Patriots were 0-2 against opponents who were 11-5 or
better.
</P>
<P>
   Last year? They went 1-4 in such key games.
</P>
<P>
   This season is only half over, so a statistical breakdown like
this has less validity, but the early evidence indicates nothing
has changed. No one can know yet how a season will turn out for any
NFL team, but after seven games, these would be considered the
``elite teams'' the Patriots have faced, based on their records:
Denver (7-0) and Miami (5-2).
</P>
<P>
   Need I remind you they lost to both?
</P>
<P>
   What we seem to have here is a Charles Dickens novel in shoulder
pads. We have ``Great Expectations.'' But as good as that novel
was, it wasn't ``David Copperfield'' or ``A Tale of Two Cities,''
and as great as some Patriot players may be and as well paid as
most of them are, they are thus far Great Expectations Unfulfilled.
</P>
<P>
   Why?
</P>
<P>
   One reason is that a high salary does not make you a great
football player or a superior employee in any endeavor. It makes
you well off. It doesn't mean you perform when the heat is on now;
it means somebody hopes you might in the future.
</P>
<P>
   That's how it's done in pro sports today. You don't pay for
production. You pay for potential, which my father always said
means you haven't done a damn thing yet. Clearly, there is some of
that on both sides of the ball in New England and all over the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, never has so talented a team so consistently shot
itself in the foot against top opposition.
</P>
<P>
   A stupid penalty here cost you a field goal early, so at the
end, Dan Marino needs 3 points to tie the game. Hey, who knew?
</P>
<P>
   A stupid penalty there and the Denver Broncos are on their way
to 17 easy points almost before the game has begun. Stuff happens,
man!
</P>
<P>
   A dropped pass in the end zone, an overthrown ball with a
receiver running free for a sure touchdown, a block not made
downfield, an unwise use of the clock, a wasting of several
timeouts, a ``once-in-a-lifetime'' interception by a wandering nose
tackle from Pittsburgh. Bad luck, right?
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who is honest about this most talented team knows this is
what has happened again and again over the past five-plus years.
Score a touchdown to get some momentum in the Super Bowl. Allow a
kick returner to go from New Orleans to New York on the next play.
These are not fictions. These are hard facts. And the hard facts
need to be faced by Carroll and the most talented team he's
coaching or they will be repeated before this year is out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are what we are,'' vice president of player personnel Bobby
Grier said. ``I've said all along, until we beat the elite teams
and play with consistency in those kind of games, you're not an
elite team. People can talk all they want about how much talent we
have. I think we do have a lot of talent. But until it's
demonstrated on the field in those games, what do you really
have?''
</P>
<P>
   You have frustrations and gray hair if you're Grier and you have
a team in the middle of the pack if you're Carroll. You have a team
whose self-image is superior to its real image. You have a team
that is very likely to spank the Indianapolis Colts Sunday and
Atlanta if the Falcons go with aged Steve DeBerg in two weeks and
Buffalo a couple of times down the road and probably even Miami
here at home.
</P>
<P>
   If one looks at both the Patriots' individual talent and track
record in recent years, it is not inconceivable to postulate that
this most talented team could run off five straight wins. If the
Patriots do, they'd be 9-3 and people again would be talking about
how they are among the most talented teams in the AFC. They would
be making reservations for the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   This we have seen.
</P>
<P>
   But then that most talented team will have to go to Pittsburgh,
which is struggling this year but still is 5-2 and seems to end up
11-5 nearly every season (three of the last five). Two weeks later,
that most talented team will have to host San Francisco before
ending the season in New Jersey against the hated Jets.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps this most talented TEAM can do this year what it has
failed to do since it was put together. Perhaps it will beat the
heavy iron. Perhaps it will go to Three Rivers Stadium and whip up
on the Steelers even if they are again the Steelers they used to
be.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it will host the 49ers and send them home limping, too.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe.
</P>
<P>
   But after 5 1/2 years of watching the most talented team in the
AFC, I'll believe it when I see it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
