<HEADLINE>
FINALLY, A RETURN TO BACK-TO-BACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When he first saw the schedule, Harry Sinden's eyes got big and
wide. It was a clear case of deja vu all over again.
</P>
<P>
   WED OCT 28 BOSTON AT MONTREAL
</P>
<P>
   THU OCT 29 MONTREAL AT BOSTON
</P>
<P>
   Oh boy! Sacre bleu! Honest-to-God, true back-to-back games.
Bring back the Garden. Bring back the Forum. Bring back the trains.
Bring back John Kiley. Bring back Frank Fallon. Make sure the
Canadiens get a good rate at the Hotel Madison. This is NHL hockey
as it ought to be.
</P>
<P>
   For two nights, we were all in a time warp. On Wednesday, the
Bruins went up to the Molson Centre and hammered the Canadiens,
9-2. Thursday night the aroused Canadiens fought our lads to a 1-1
standoff. They will play five times this season, and we just had
two of them within 48 hours. The games hardly could have been more
different, which should not come as a great big shock.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was to be expected,'' shrugged Pat Burns. ``They've got
character on that hockey club. There's a lot of pride involved when
you're wearing that sweater. I know that.''
</P>
<P>
   In case you forgot, he used to coach up there.
</P>
<P>
   Don't let anyone try to slip any jive by you implying this was a
great game, or even a good one. It was a more competitive game, but
what wouldn't be?
</P>
<P>
   The Canadiens took 12 penalties, seven of them in the first
period. They were sent off for every infraction known to man, save
loitering and impersonating a Hab. The Bruins managed to score on
one of their nine power-play tries. The only Montreal goal also
came on a power play. The goaltending of Byron Dafoe and Jocelyn
Thibault was good, but there was no highlight stuff. It was not
gripping entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Burns doesn't need entertainment, however. The main concern in
his professional life is points, and he liked the arithmetic
provided by the back-to-back get-together with the Canadiens.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had nothing in our favor,'' Burns observed. ``It was our
first game back after a long road trip. We beat them badly in their
building the night before. If I pick up 3 of 4 points over the
Montreal Canadiens in 24 hours, am I upset? No.''
</P>
<P>
   There used to be back-to-backs all the time in Ye Olden Days.
The NHL had them and the NBA likewise had them. Players would ride
either the train or plane together after Game 1. I well remember
some Saturday night/Sunday afternoon Knicks-Celtics sets
highlighted by an interesting scene at LaGuardia. The Knicks would
get in first class and the Celtics would get in coach. But we
digress.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins agreed that the world would be a better place if
there were more of these. ``This is how you build rivalries,'' said
Steve Heinze, who scored the Boston goal. ``It's good for hockey,
especially when you're talking about two of the Original Six. It's
absolutely a good thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Original Six, huh? You could never guess he's from around here.
</P>
<P>
   Sinden was front and center for the tail end of the Original Six
days, and he remembers the back-to-backs with great fondness. ``I
remember them beating us up there something like 8-2 on a Thursday,
and us turning around and beating them something like 8-0 back here
on Saturday,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It's not like these two asked for this fortuitous scheduling.
``It was just a scheduling quirk,'' explained Nate Greenberg,
Harry's official Righthand Man. ``I used to love the
Saturday-Sunday ones. You'd love to have more of them, but it's the
reality of the '90s. It is what it is.''
</P>
<P>
   For the record, this was the first true back-to-back (i.e.,
successive days) on the Bruins' regular-season schedule since Jan.
15-16, 1992, when they beat the Hartford Whalers, 4-3, the first
night in the Civic Center and beat them by an identical score 24
hours later in the Garden.
</P>
<P>
   If Burns were making out the schedule, you'd see more of them.
``Oh yeah,'' he said. ``I think it's a damn shame we don't do this
more often. How are fans going to develop a hate for a team if you
don't play them more often? If you want to develop good rivalries,
you've got to play each other.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins knew very well that they would have been better off
playing anyone else after what they did to the Canadiens the night
before, but they were good sports about it. ``Any win up there is a
good win,'' said Don Sweeney. ``We knew they'd come back and
respond the way they did. But 3 out of 4 points, even early in the
season, is critical.''
</P>
<P>
   So much for Back To The Future Night at the Fleet. Now I have a
question. On my way out of the building, I noticed some panes of
rectangular glass, to which an orange ring was affixed. Does
anybody know what those things are supposed to be?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
