<SLUG> BC-HKN-MANSON-NHLSUSPENSION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NHL HITS MANSON WITH 3-GAME SUSPENSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you do the crime, you'll do the time.
</P>
<P>
   The National Hockey League continued pursuing its objective to
rid the game of flagrant hits to the head Thursday by suspending
Canadiens defenseman Dave Manson for three games after he elbowed
Bruins left wing P.J. Axelsson. Manson also was fined $1,000, the
maximum allowed under the collective bargaining agreement.
</P>
<P>
   In Wednesday's 9-2 rout of the Habs, Manson wound up and
delivered a nasty blow to Axelsson's head at 6:10 of the second
period along the boards behind the Canadiens' net, sending the
sophomore forward sprawling to the ice.
</P>
<P>
   Axelsson returned to the game after resting on the bench, but
the NHL, which has been cracking down on such incidents, felt
Manson deserved to sit for three, including last night's rematch at
the FleetCenter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Manson delivered a flagrant elbow to Axelsson's face,'' said
Colin Campbell, the league's senior vice president and director of
hockey operations. ``Whether by elbow, stick, or otherwise, the
league will continue to punish players for deliberate blows to the
head of an opponent.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the hit, Manson was assessed a game misconduct
and five-minute major penalty for elbowing. The Bruins scored three
power-play goals in a span of 51 seconds to boost their lead to
6-0.
</P>
<P>
   The league has not been hesitant to mete out supplementary
discipline for hits such as Manson's. A year ago by this date, the
NHL had issued three suspensions, two of which were given out in
the preseason. Manson's suspension was the 11th this season _ and
it's still October.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadiens were upset with Bruins coach Pat Burns because he
sent his top power-play unit out during a two-man advantage with
Boston riding a 7-1 lead. Coach Alain Vigneault thought Burns was
running up the score.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what else you call it,'' he said. ``They had a
7-1 lead and a two-man advantage and they had their No. 1
power-play unit out there. We'll remember that.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns labeled Manson's hit a cheap shot. He and the big
defenseman were jawing at each other when Manson was banished for
the evening, but he said it was ridiculous to say he ran up the
score.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why would I want to humiliate the Canadiens?'' said Burns,
their former coach. ``I just did my job. We have players with
clauses in their contracts (with scoring incentives). When you have
a two-man power play, it's just normal you'd go with your best
players. Who are they expecting me to go to? Ken Baumgartner? Jay
Henderson? Marquis Mathieu? If I would've called a timeout with a
5-0 lead, I'd understand why he'd be upset.''
</P>
<P>
   One reason Burns was angry was Manson's history of picking on
the more diminutive players, such as Axelsson.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't give (the elbow) to Baumgartner,'' said Burns. ``But
P.J. Axelsson? Let's go.''
</P>
<P>
   Manson wasn't happy about the banishment but wasn't shocked,
either.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not surprised, but it's a bit of a joke,'' he said. ``I
watched tapes of the same incidents, and the players who were
suspended got two games. It looked a lot worse than it was. I
touched him with the back of my shoulder. I guess they made the
judgment because of my name.''
</P>
<P>
   Manson felt he was hurt by his reputation and his past brushes
with supplementary discipline.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately,'' he said, ``they don't burn your records.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-30-98 0131EST &QL; 
