<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-CSUNBKW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABRAHAM'S ARREST STARTS TO HIT HOME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The impact of Cal State Northridge women's
basketball coach Michael Abraham's arrest was more devastating the
second day than the first, especially for the players.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's practice was cancelled. The team held a closed
practice on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think once (the players) were seeing it in the newspapers
and on television, it hit home,'' CSUN athletic director Paul Bubb
said. ``It's a totally different situation then.''
</P>
<P>
   Bubb and acting coach Judy Brame, the school's associate
athletic director, thought the day off would help the team cope
with events from Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Brame is an experienced coach but hasn't been on the bench in 15
years. Her task is to get the team ready for the season, which
begins with an exhibition game Nov. 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I hope to do is be able to provide leadership as we make
the adjustments and the transition,'' Brame said. ``It's my
anticipation the assistant coaches will continue to do what they
have done, and they may have additional responsibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Abraham nor CSUN assistant coaches Frozena Jerro or
Karon Howell returned phone calls. Players continued their stand of
not making any comments.
</P>
<P>
   The public-relation nightmares that haunt CSUN surfaced again
when FBI officials announced Wednesday the arrest of Abraham. He
was indicted on charges of conspiracy to distribute and possession
with the intent to distribute 50 grams or more of crack cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted, Abraham faces a minimum 10-year sentence and a
maximum term of life in prison. Abraham, in the second year of a
two-year deal worth $67,000 annually, is on paid administrative
leave from the university. Abraham is free on bail, but Bubb said,
``I don't expect him to be on campus.''
</P>
<P>
   For the team, there are other issues, including the acceptance
of Brame. She inherits a team that went 14-14 last season and was
picked to finish second by the coaches and third by the media in
the Big Sky Conference. The polls were released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dr. Brame has experience as having headed the program before,
and to me that was a logical choice,'' Bubb said. ``I don't see it
as a giant setback for the program. We have an individual who's
been alleged to be involved in an incident, or whatever, and he
needs to deal with that. We've got a total program that we're
continuing to move forward with.''
</P>
<P>
   Brame last coached in 1983, but she does have a wealth of
experience. She spent eight seasons as the Matadors head coach and
is the program's all-time wins leader with a 101-89 mark. She's one
of two women's basketball coaches with winning records at the
school and tops CSUN's list with a .532 winning percentage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the players understand what we've done and why we've
done it,'' Bubb said. ``I expect them to accept (Brame) right
away.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Brame will periodically be pulled away from basketball
because of her other duties. Brame said at the request of Bubb,
she'll attend the Big Sky Conference meetings Sunday and Monday in
Ogden, Utah, and therefore won't be at practice.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the coaching duties, Brame plans on continuing in
her capacity as administrator of internal affairs. She deals with
financial aid, housing and academics as well as being the NCAA
liaison and doing compliance work with the NCAA.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you end up finding is that you don't do as good a job in
any one area because you feel that you're stretched so thin,''
Brame said. ``The frustration of 1979-80, when I became an
assistant coach, I was always feeling that I should be at
administrative things and I was coaching. Or that I should be
coaching and I was at the adminitstrative meetings. That wore me
out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
