A5073 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKW-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     10-30 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE MORE MESS TO CLEAN UP AT CSUN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A women's volleyball coach is accused of sleeping
with his players. A football player is shot at a party and the
athletic department covers it up. The women's basketball coach is
arrested at a gymnasium on campus and charged with trafficking
cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Felicity,'' it is not.
</P>
<P>
   Lately at Cal State Northridge, the truth has been stranger than
any fictional television series. Even a 32-year-old writer passing
herself off as 19 would have better sense than to touch the slices
of college life that the Matadors' athletic department has been
gagging on the past few years.
</P>
<P>
   The arrest of basketball coach Michael Abraham on
drug-trafficking charges is the latest scourge on an athletic
program that has overseen measured athletic successes and
unmitigated moral failures.
</P>
<P>
   The ongoing serial drama that is CSUN's quest to win a modicum
of respect has grown so old and tired it's a wonder anyone
continues to pay attention.
</P>
<P>
   The athletic facilities are an eyesore and the athletic
department a growing embarrassment to a student body that already
suffers from an inferiority complex. Sadly, a month that began with
the football team cracking the Division I-AA rankings for the first
time will be remembered for Abraham's arrest Tuesday on charges of
conspiring to distribute crack cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   As the news of Abraham's arrest fanned out over the campus, CSUN
president Blenda Wilson reacted as she is wont to do in a crisis.
The school's most visible representative made herself scarce. As
was the case last year when the school announced it was dropping
four men's sports programs, she wasn't available for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, she issued a statement through a spokesperson when
asked what affect the incident would have on the perception of the
university: ``Most people recognize the difference between an
individual's alleged behavior and the entire work of the
university.''
</P>
<P>
   Her silence Wednesday in a situation that was crying out for
comment spoke loudly of the lip service paid to accountability in
the CSUN corridors of power.
</P>
<P>
   In the absence of responsible authority figures, the buck stops
with the student athletes who are left to deal with the mess. To be
sure, the athletic department could use a few more like men's
basketball coach Bob Braswell, who wears his principles on his
sleeve.
</P>
<P>
   It's unconscionable that an athletic director would hire a head
coach knowing the candidate was under investigation at the time for
NCAA violations. And yet that's exactly what CSUN's Bob Hiegert did
in 1995 when he lured Abraham away from Oregon State, where he was
serving as the women's basketball recruiting coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   Hiegert's choice was a slap in the face of integrity and an
affront to every qualified _ but maybe not-so-well-connected
candidate _ scrambling for a Division I job. To be fair, it must be
reported that the NCAA never sanctioned Oregon State. Just the
same, if someone with even a hint of impropriety was the best man
Hiegert could find for the job, then perhaps he should have looked
at some women.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Paul Bubb replaced Hiegert, presumably because CSUN
wanted the athletic department steered toward financial solvency.
But in the sea of integrity, the department remains adrift.
</P>
<P>
   The year after Bubb took over, Matadors running back Shayne
Blakey was shot during an argument at a party. Bubb and then coach
Dave Baldwin lied to cover up the incident, glossing over Blakey's
gunshot injuries by saying he had undergone an appendectomy.
</P>
<P>
   In the process, Bubb demonstrated that he regards the truth the
same way the medical profession does the appendix _ as superfluous.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson sanctioned Bubb, suspending him for five days without
pay. It's too bad there's no one to fine Wilson for her silence
Wednesday. The circumstances demanded that her voice rise above the
chaos, if only to comfort the shaken in the CSUN family.
</P>
<P>
   The women's basketball team has every reason right now to feel
like its insides have been ripped out. But time can heal at least
the surface wounds. For proof, the players need look only as far as
the women's volleyball team, which advanced to the NCAA Tournament
three years after being rocked by scandal.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, two members of the previous year's team accused then
coach Walt Ker of sexual harrassment. Ker, who had led the Matadors
to three Division II national titles and eight conference
championships in 18 seasons, resigned shortly before a few players
came forward anonymously with stories of his coercing them into
having sex.
</P>
<P>
   Judy Brame, an associate athletic director in charge of internal
affairs, will take over the basketball coaching duties on an
interim basis. Upon hearing of the latest incident to smear a good
university's reputation, Brame said she was ``disheartened,
disillusioned, disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   She left out disgusted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
