<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OIL-PIPELINE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
5 KEY NATIONS ENDORSE CASPIAN OIL PIPELINE 
</HEADLINE>
   By FRANK VIVIANO  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
    PARIS _ With a huge push from the United States, five nations
issued a joint declaration Thursday endorsing a controversial oil
pipeline from the Caspian Sea to the Mediterranean.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Meeting in Ankara, the presidents of Turkey, Azerbaijan,
Georgia, Kazakstan and Uzbekistan signed an accord committing their
governments to the 1,080-mile conduit.
</P>
<P>
   It would link the Azeri capital and chief refining center, Baku,
to the Turkish port of Ceyhan, passing through Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Energy Secretary Bill Richardson looked on as the
declaration was signed in the Turkish parliament. The agreement
follows years of intense competition and diplomatic maneuvering
over the route of the Main Export Pipeline (MEP) for Caspian oil.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most environmentally sound, economically rational
project for the export of Caspian oil,'' Turkish President Suleyman
Demirel said.
</P>
<P>
   An American official in Central Asia told The Chronicle that the
United States is ``unwavering in its support'' for the Ceyhan
route.
</P>
<P>
   But construction is far from assured. The Azerbaijan
International Operating Consortium (AIOC), the 12-company energy
cartel that owns a lion's share of pumping rights in the region,
must agree to to pay most of the estimated $4 billion cost.
</P>
<P>
   The consortium _ which includes such U.S. giants as Exxon,
Amoco, Unocal and Pennzoil _ is expected to issue its own decision
on Nov. 9.
</P>
<P>
   The plan would also have to win the tacit cooperation of other
multinationals with significant investments in the region, among
them San Francisco-based Chevron, Royal Dutch Shell, France's Total
and Elf, and firms from Japan, Italy, Great Britain, Australia and
Russia.
</P>
<P>
   The Caspian basin's energy reserves are believed by some experts
to rival those of Saudi Arabia, the largest source of oil on Earth.
</P>
<P>
   Although current oil prices, the lowest in decades, have stifled
early production efforts, Caspian oil and natural gas are expected
to fuel a major share of industrial development in the 21st
century.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly a dozen proposals, involving countries as far-flung as
China and Romania, have been submitted for the pipeline.
</P>
<P>
   But the Baku-Ceyhan facility's primary competitors are expanded
versions of existing routes to the Georgian Black Sea port of
Supsa, and through Russia to the Black Sea port of Novorossisk.
</P>
<P>
   Both proposals have been fiercely opposed by Turkey, which
claims that increased shipments of oil from the Black Sea to the
Mediterranean _ which would have to transit the narrow and
freighter-packed Bosporus, cutting through the heart of populous
Istanbul _ pose enormous health and environmental dangers.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has lobbied just as fiercely against the Baku-Ceyhan
route, which would deprive it of a multibillion-dollar windfall in
oil transport fees.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Iran and Turkmenistan, which has been the most loyal
of Moscow's former Soviet possessions, it is one of three nations
bordering the Caspian that were absent from the Ankara declaration
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Turkey warned that it will boycott all domestic
purchases of Caspian oil if the Ceyhan proposal is turned down, and
implied that it may take steps to prevent shipments elsewhere
through the Bosphorus.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Ankara-based Anatolian News Agency, Foreign
Minister Ismail Cem told U.S. envoy Richard Morningstar that
``Turkey will not allow the straits to be turned into an oil
pipeline.''
</P>
<P>
   Wherever the pipeline winds up, it will be vulnerable to
political risks.
</P>
<P>
   Turkish officials point out that the Russian pipeline crosses
the violence-torn, self-proclaimed republic of Chechnya. But
Russians note that the Ceyhan route runs directly through the area
where Turkey's Army is at war with Kurd separatists.
</P>
<P>
   On October 19, Georgia was rocked by the latest in a series of
attempted coups d'etat that have erupted since the country declared
its independence in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   In a radio interview one week later, when the uprising had been
quashed, President Eduard Shevardnadze blamed the incident on
unnamed ``foreign secret services'' _ a code phrase for Russian
intelligence agents _ trying to block Georgia's pipeline bid.
</P>
<P>
   In the eyes of many observers, the only route that offers both
security and low construction cost, with the lowest environmental
risk, passes through Iran to the Persian Gulf.
</P>
<P>
   But unremitting American hostility to Tehran _ and unceasing
diplomatic pressure, exerted by a steady stream of high-level
delegations from Washington over the past 18 months _ has all but
ruled out any Iranian role in the transport of Caspian oil. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
