<HEADER>
A5134 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAIN-CELLS-SFCHRON &LR;      10-30 0525
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAIN-CELLS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST EVIDENCE OF NEW BRAIN CELLS IN HUMAN ADULTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By CARL T. HALL  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; Scientists have discovered new nerve cells sprouting deep
within the adult human brain, undercutting the ancient biological
dogma that dead brain cells can never be replaced.
</P>
<P>
   Neurons _ the precious functional cells of the central nervous
system _ have been thought to stop multiplying about the same time
children lose their baby teeth, then gradually die off throughout
adulthood.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it seems that certain regions of the brain may remain young
_ or at least able to carry on a process known as ``neurogenesis''
well into adulthood.
</P>
<P>
   The research findings, published Friday in the journal Nature
Medicine, could lead to new ways to treat brain diseases and
strokes that destroy vast populations of brain cells.
</P>
<P>
   If even a few cells with the power to regenerate could be
harvested from such patients, doctors might be able to induce them
to grow in a laboratory dish and then graft them back into the
diseased area, in the same way that some burn victims can be
treated with grafts of freshly grown skin cells.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's enormous potential,'' said Dr. Ben Barres, a
neurobiologist at Stanford Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   The new study was done by researchers in Sweden and at the Salk
Institute for Biological Studies in San Diego. They took advantage
of a special dye, called BrdU, that had been injected into
late-stage cancer patients in order to label actively dividing
cells.
</P>
<P>
   When the patients eventually died, autopsies revealed clear
evidence of new neurons within the hippocampus, a region of the
cerebral cortex involved in learning and memory. The study subjects
were gravely ill and in their 50s and 60s (one was 72) when the
cellular rebirth was occurring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our study demonstrates that cell genesis occurs in human
brains and that the human brain retains the potential for
self-renewal throughout life,'' the researchers concluded.
</P>
<P>
   The newborn cells could be a previously unknown mechanism in the
elaborate circuit-building system that the brain uses to lay down
memories. Thus, the research implies, learning new things might be
physically expanding brain capacity even in late adulthood.
</P>
<P>
   But study co-author Fred Gage of the Salk Institute noted that
there is still no evidence that the late-blooming neurons actually
assumed any functional role.
</P>
<P>
   Mature neurons typically form elaborate branches and connections
with other cells to transmit nerve impulses. The newborn cells
identified in the study formed in a primitive state from so-called
progenitor cells.
</P>
<P>
   That represents a cellular fresh start for an adult brain, but
no one knows whether that is merely a trivial vestige of childhood
or a dynamic element of the adult's neurobiology.
</P>
<P>
   The biochemical signals that trigger neurogenesis also remain a
mystery. Unlike other organs, the brain shows little tendency to
repair itself when damage occurs.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we have done is show there are some new neurons here,''
Gage said. ``We don't know if those new neurons can become wired up
correctly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-30-98 0330EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981030.0041 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-30 03:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5136 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CALIF-GOVRACE-SFCHRON     10-30 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-GOVRACE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA GOVERNOR'S RACE COULD DETERMINE WHO RULES CONGRESS 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARC SANDALOW  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The man whose job it is to oversee 435 Republican
House campaigns and preserve the GOP majority in Congress expressed
no doubt this week about his party's top priority in Tuesday's
elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important House race in America,'' said Rep. John
Linder, the Georgia Republican who heads the National Republican
Congressional Committee, ``is the governorship of California.''
</P>
<P>
   Linder's comments underscore an often overlooked political
reality: As California voters choose between Gray Davis and Dan
Lungren, they will be deciding a matter of national importance _
who will have the final say when the state's congressional
districts are redrawn after the 2000 census.
</P>
<P>
   With nearly one in eight members of Congress representing the
Golden State, it is no exaggeration to say that the difference
between a Davis or a Lungren victory Tuesday could determine who
controls Congress for the first decade of the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   Political experts believe that a partisan gerrymander, with
districts drawn to maximize the power of one party, could affect
the party affiliation of as many as a dozen seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a narrowly divided Congress, having complete control of
(the governor's seat and the Legislature) could have the effect of
changing control of the House,'' said Joe Shumate, a
Sacramento-based GOP consultant and veteran of California
redistricting wars.
</P>
<P>
   The high stakes in the California governor's race is not lost on
the national political leaders. It is why President Clinton tried
to persuade Sen. Dianne Feinstein to enter the race in January when
it looked like she would be the Democrats' most electable
candidate, and it explains why the national parties have spent
millions of dollars on the California election.
</P>
<P>
   California is the ``grand prize'' of the nation's 36 governors
races that will be settled Tuesday, according to the Democratic
Governors Association, which has contributed $570,000 to the Davis
campaign _ nearly twice as much as it gave to any other candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Lungren has also benefited from huge contributions from his
party's national headquarters, receiving $250,000 from the National
Republican Congressional Committee and at least another $250,000
from the Republican National Committee, Linder said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very important to have a Republican at the table,'' said
RNC spokesman Tim Fitzpatrick.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats currently hold majorities in both the state Assembly
and Senate, although it is the 2000 election that will determine
who holds majorities for the next redistricting.
</P>
<P>
   The California Constitution lays out a clear process for
redrawing congressional districts, as well as state Assembly and
Senate districts, after each census. The Legislature is given the
responsibility to draw up the districts, which must be contiguous,
respect the natural divisions of cities and counties to the extent
possible, and be numbered consecutively from north to south. The
redistricting proposal requires the support of the governor.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, with so much power at stake, the process has
degenerated into a bitterly partisan exercise in the past three
decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``Legislatures do many things well,'' said California Secretary
of State Bill Jones, who served in the Assembly during each of the
past two fights. ``But reapportionment is not one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   In California's rich history of nasty redistricting battles, the
fiercest came in 1980, when San Francisco Democratic Rep. Phil
Burton drew up a plan approved by the Democratic-controlled
Legislature and Gov. Jerry Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans charged that the boundaries were so misshapen for
partisan purposes that one Los Angeles district was contiguous only
when the tide was out. Those boundaries were ultimately rejected by
voters in a referendum and redrawn by the courts.
</P>
<P>
   The courts also took over the process in the 1970s, when the
Democratic Legislature could not agree on a plan with Governor
Ronald Reagan, and in the 1990s, when another Democratic majority
butted heads with Governor Pete Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   The matter could once again end up in court, regardless of who
wins Tuesday, but the political persuasion of the next governor is
certain to heavily influence the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``Redistricting is the purest form of political self-interest,''
said Shumate.
</P>
<P>
   California's influence in determining the shape of Congress
grows with each census.
</P>
<P>
   After the 1960 census, California had 38 seats in the House,
fewer than New York at the time. That number rose to 43 in the in
1970s, 45 in the '80s, 52 in the '90s, and is expected to grow from
one to five more seats by the 2002 election. The next largest
state, Texas, has 32 seats; New York now has 31.
</P>
<P>
   The state's 52-member congressional delegation consists of 29
Democrats and 23 Republicans, although the shift of several key
precincts could dramatically alter the political equation.
</P>
<P>
   For example, in Contra Costa County, where Democrat Ellen
Tauscher is campaigning vigorously to keep her seat in the 10th
Congressional District, a new boundary constructed by Republicans
might move predominantly Democratic neighborhoods in Walnut Creek
into George Miller's heavily Democratic Seventh Congressional
District and replace them with more conservative precincts to the
east.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats might decide to move Republican-leaning neighborhoods
in Orinda over to Barbara Lee's safely Democratic Ninth
Congressional District, and give Tauscher portions of heavily
Democratic Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the chance, Democrats could gain 10 seats, 11 seats,''
said Linder. ``And if they did it as cleverly as they did it with
Phil Burton . . . in 1981, they could gain a lot more.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
