<HEADER>
A5366 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECH-AUSTERITY31-COX     10-30 1010
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-AUSTERITY31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    INTERNET FIRMS SEE BELT-TIGHTENING AS IPO MARKET FADES
 &HT;    With TECH-AUSTERITY-DATA. Moving in (w) Washington and (f)
financial categories for release Saturday, Oct. 31.
 &HT;    By MARY BETH REGAN
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Last spring, when Internet entrepreneurs Ross
Garber and Greg Peters were planning to take Vignette Corp. public,
they had visions of raising an amazing $30 million overnight. Their
Austin, Texas, company, they hoped, would join the ranks of such
Internet blockbusters as Yahoo! and Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   But before the team could even plan a road show to advertise its
initial public offering (IPO) of stock, their Morgan Stanley
bankers brought sobering news: In only 45 days, comparable Internet
companies had lost as much as 50 percent of their valuations.
Institutional investors were balking at new offerings. In short,
the IPO window was slamming shut.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was wrenching,'' recounted Garber. ``We were so close. But
in the end, we couldn't taint the company by taking it public in
these disastrous market conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   The Vignette team has joined the legions of executives across
the country postponing or shelving plans to sell stock to the
public. In the third quarter of 1998, a record 71 IPO filings have
been withdrawn, according to Securities Data Co. Some prominent
Internet companies scratching or delaying IPOs include
barnesandnoble.com inc., Healtheon Corp., the globe.com inc.,
Internet America Inc. and CitySearch Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``The IPO market is dead,'' says Gary Craft, an electronic
commerce analyst with BancBoston, Robertson, Stephens in San
Francisco. ``Internet companies are holding up better than most,
but executives need to adjust their strategies and valuations to
meet the current market conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   For Internet entrepreneurs, the darlings of Wall Street since
1994, the coming months could be the testing period that will
separate solid cyber-concepts from fly-by-night Web ideas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a belt-tightening time,'' predicted Guy
Hoffman, chief executive officer of Deja News, an Austin Internet
company that plans to hold off on any public offering plans.
</P>
<P>
   Venture capital _ pools of private funds invested in companies _
will continue to flow for the next 18 months, but investors may be
more selective about backing new ventures if market conditions
don't improve, economists predict. Some analysts even predict
investors will see consolidation within the Internet industry, with
weaker companies being snapped up by cash-flush firms at bargain
prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``You won't be able to put up a Web site and get money
anymore,'' said Jesse Reyes, managing director of Venture
Economics, a New Jersey company that tracks venture capital trends.
``The strong companies will survive, but the competition for
venture money is going to get fiercer.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, venture capitalists pumped an estimated $13.1 billion
into private companies nationwide. Of that money, 78 percent went
into information technology firms, mostly to more established
companies. Today, there's still plenty of money, about $5.5 billion
waiting to be invested. Reyes said.
</P>
<P>
   Of that, about 25 percent, or nearly $1.5 billion, is slated for
early-stage startups. Nearly all early money _ called seed capital
_ has gone into the Internet sector in recent years because
investors are looking for astronomical returns.
</P>
<P>
   The online flea market, eBay, was the last Internet company out
of the blocks before the market soured. Its stock price soared 163
percent on the first day of trading. And since its September debut
at $18 per share, the company's stock price has quadrupled.
</P>
<P>
   But with the IPO market drying up, executives such as Vignette's
Garber will be returning to venture capitalists for more money.
That could make investors wary of financing new projects until the
companies can get a product to market with their existing
investments, said Doug Carlisle, general partner with Menlo
Ventures of Menlo Park, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``The venture guys have been making money hand over fist on
these companies,'' says Mark Saul, chief executive officer of
Austin-based Acuity Corp., an Internet software firm. ``But the
heady days are over. So you're likely to see the losers float up on
the beach and die.''
</P>
<P>
   For Saul, brought in from Silicon Valley to run Acuity last
year, it's time to generate revenue. The company sells software
that makes it possible for clients to operate online customer
service operations or e-commerce businesses on the Web. Last week,
it signed its biggest deal yet, a $1 million contract with Ascend
Communications Inc., of Alameda, Calif. Saul expects the company to
turn a profit on a cash basis by December. ``We're in a good
position to ride it out, `` he says.
</P>
<P>
   Other companies without proven products or revenue may have more
difficulty, investors say. One example is Healtheon Corp. of Santa
Clara, Calif. The company, backed by James Clark, a founder of
Netscape Communications Corp., plans to raise $40 million from
existing investors after dropping IPO plans last week. But
according to the company's filings with the Securities and Exchange
Commission, it has lost $71.7 million since its inception in 1995
and expects continued losses through 1999 because the business
model is yet unproven.
</P>
<P>
   Computer industry veterans such as Jimmy Treybig, founder of
Tandem Computers Inc., who advises a number of young startups, say
Internet entrepreneurs would be well-served to focus on the
fundamentals. That means coming up with a solid product, putting
together a top-notch management team and having a strategy to
introduce the product into the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of these Web deals have gotten overheated,'' Treybig
said. ``But it doesn't really matter what's happening with the
times. ... You have to identify why you have an advantage, put
together a good management team and have a strategy to win.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
