<HEADER>
A5368 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LATINO-VOTERS31-COX     10-30 1178
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATINO-VOTERS31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BUSH BROTHERS' FORMULA MAY BRING HISPANICS BACK TO THE GOP
 &HT;    650&AMP;add. With LATINO-VOTERS-DATA. For release Saturday, Oct. 31.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republican strategists are watching the
gubernatorial campaigns of the Bush brothers in Texas and Florida
for clues on how to woo Hispanic voters in the next presidential
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   And some Democrats are worried.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen Republicans who just innately understand that
vote the way the Bush brothers do,'' said Celinda Lake, a leading
Democratic strategist.
</P>
<P>
   Lake, part of a team that conducts a series of ``Battleground''
election-year polls, said that if the GOP follows the lead of Jeb
and George W. Bush, Hispanics will be ``a real battleground vote''
in the 2000 presidential contest.
</P>
<P>
   Republican pollster Ed Goeas, Lake's ``Battleground'' poll
partner, is not as certain. He believes it may take his party a
decade to repair relations with Hispanics that have been damaged by
polarizing battles over immigration, welfare, welfare, affirmative
action and education.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is ... a majority of Hispanics have now come
to believe that Republicans would rather have an America that did
not include them,'' Goeas's Washington-based firm, the Tarrance
Group, concluded in a strategy paper distributed to GOP leaders and
congressional candidates this year.
</P>
<P>
   The Tarrance Group has been studying Latino voting trends for 10
years, long before most political strategists in either party
recognized the demographic and political tidal wave that Hispanics
represent. But until recently, its advice that ``conservatism can
be compassionate without losing its conviction'' has largely been
ignored.
</P>
<P>
   Not so with the Bush brothers, however. Their campaigns are
expected to become models for a GOP strategy to win back a group of
voters who were solidly Republican in the glory days of Ronald
Reagan _ and thereby reclaim the White House.
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush won only 28 percent of the Hispanic vote when he
was elected governor of Texas in 1994. But since then, he has
promoted issues of importance to Hispanics _ education and economic
opportunity, in particular _ and has stood up to anti-immigration
legislation in the GOP-led Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Today Bush _ who Spanish in campaign radio ads and regularly
appears in Hispanic media _ is overwhelmingly popular with all
Texans, including Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   His brother Jeb has had an easier time of it in Florida, where
most Hispanics are of Cuban descent, overwhelmingly Republican and
not as attuned to immigration issues as the Hispanics of Mexican
descent in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   In his unsuccessful campaign for governor in 1994, Jeb Bush got
71 percent of the Cuban-American vote. But he is not taking that
vote for granted this year. His campaign even has a
Spanish-language Web site.
</P>
<P>
   And on the issues, he sounds more like his brother in Texas than
himself in 1994. The hard-edged conservatism is mostly gone,
replaced with a unifying message of education and economic
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats question whether simply modeling a presidential
campaign on the Bush brothers can undo the hard feelings caused by
the GOP's treatment of Hispanic voters since 1992. It may take one
of the brothers themselves: George, who is quickly emerging as the
front-runner for the 2000 GOP nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are Hispanic voters up for grabs this year? No, because the
Republicans are doing everything they can to make Hispanics mad,''
said Gov. Roy Romer of Colorado, the general chairman of the
Democratic National Committee. ``Republicans don't even want to
count them in the census. We couldn't have had a greater gift in
terms of getting the Hispanic vote than what the Republican Party's
record has been.''
</P>
<P>
   Goeas's strategy paper puts it in less harsh terms:
``Republicans should realize that ten years have passed and their
image among the Hispanic community has not improved. And it may
take that long to simply turn it around.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The trouble began in 1992 with the anti-immigrant tirades of Pat
Buchanan as he challenged incumbent George Bush for the Republican
presidential nomination. That same year, Bill Clinton, in defeating
Bush, became the first Democrat in four presidential elections to
win a majority of Hispanic voters.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing has driven Hispanic voters into the Democratic Party
more than California Gov. Pete Wilson's championing of ballot
measures beginning in 1994 to cut off state benefits to illegal
immigrants, outlaw the state's affirmative action programs and
eliminate bilingual education.
</P>
<P>
   As Wilson was waging his campaign, the Republican Party took
control of Congress and immediately began pushing a similar agenda,
including a proposal to cut benefits for illegal and legal
immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, however, the GOP national leadership has taken steps
to improve its standing with Hispanics. The Republican National
Committee now has a Hispanic ``outreach'' program, for example, and
congressional leaders, once advocates of ``English only''
legislation, routinely translate their weekly national broadcasts
into Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   But the GOP is currently fighting to prevent scientific sampling
of the population in the next census, a procedure designed to
prevent an undercount of minorities and ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
   A ``report card'' this month by the National Hispanic Leadership
Agenda gave House Speaker Newt Gingrich of Georgia a ``zero''
rating in support of Hispanic issues. House Democratic Leader Dick
Gephardt of Missouri scored 75.
</P>
<P>
   And a generic congressional ballot test by the Tarrance Group
found Hispanics supporting Democrats over Republicans by a 20-point
margin, 52 percent to 32 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1992, the number of Latinos registered to vote has risen
30 percent, to 6.6 million, and 75 percent of them have registered
as Democrats in states that have party registration. In California,
home to half of the nation's Hispanics, Latino registration has
grown 600,000 since 1994, to 2 million.
</P>
<P>
   However, a survey earlier this year by the Thomas Rivera Policy
Institute, a leading Hispanic research institution, found evidence
of hope that the Republican Party could recover lost ground. More
than two-thirds of Latino voters in California and more than half
in Texas and Florida told the institute's researchers that their
party affiliation is weak.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats ``should be asking how strong the Latino shift to
their party is,'' said Harry Pachon, the institute's president.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Goeas's associate, Geoff Becker, contends that Hispanics
are ``strong believers in family, church and hard work'' and hold
many of the ``same virtues and values'' as Republicans. Winning
them back will require a campaign emphasizing tax relief,
bolstering education and ``standing up against immorality in our
community,'' Becker said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
