<SLUG> BC-GAY-CYBERTIMES-ARTS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARTS(AT)LARGE 
 SITE FOR CELEBRATING GAY ART 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: The Queer Arts Resource site and the Net Selections '98
exhibit contain strong sexual language and graphic homoerotic
imagery.) 
 By MATTHEW MIRAPAUL 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Things Are Queer'' is a sequence of nine photographs by Duane
Michals in which the first and final frames are one and the same.
In this Moebius strip of images, every shift in the camera's
perspective alters the way the viewer perceives the artist's
universe.
</P>
<P>
   A visit to the Queer Arts Resource (QAR) can have a similar
effect. The two-year-old site, which on Thursday is launching its
first exhibition of Web-based art, is devoted to the works of
non-heterosexual artists. Seen in this focused context, their
pieces often gain additional meaning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roundabout,'' for example, is one of six Web-art projects in
the new Net Selections '98 exhibit. If this multimedia journey
through a maze of barren public spaces was viewed on its own, it
would seem to be merely a well-crafted exploration of urban
alienation.
</P>
<P>
   Because the project is included in the exhibit, though, viewers
may also wonder whether the work depicts a popular pick-up spot or
is commenting upon some aspect of an alternative lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't get any overt queer content from this piece,'' said
Barry Harrison, director of QAR. ``But then queer content has
historically been coded or intended for those 'in the know.' I
think it is more suggestive than anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Girlie Movies,'' part of the multiple-artist showcase
Fantasmagoria, is similarly open to divergent interpretations. The
lightly animated work could be construed as a repressed male's
monologue, but when viewed through a lesbian prism, it is reborn as
a coming-out-to-oneself saga.
</P>
<P>
   Not all of the works in the Net Selections show are quite so
ambiguous. ``Positive,'' which uses a tray of brightly colored
pills as a navigation device, is a meditation on AIDS. ``In My
Fantasy,'' another Fantasmagoria entry, is an overt lesbian reverie
-- albeit one set subversively in a traditionally male environment.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the featured works contain strong sexual language and
graphic homoerotic imagery (although ``Women with Beards'' is
clearly intended to be a parody of X-rated Internet sites).
</P>
<P>
   But these elements are employed for serious artistic effect, as
is made clear in the almost-scholarly remarks posted online by the
exhibit's all-star panel of jurors, including Aaron Betsky, curator
of architecture and design for the San Francisco Museum of Modern
Art, and the multimedia artist Shu Lea Chang.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Harrison founded the not-for-profit site as ``an
alternative to all the sex-oriented sites and chat rooms that often
pretend to be about gay art or queer art, and are not.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``I remember the first time I went surfing, a friend
and I did a search for gay art and the first thing we found was a
site called 'Men in Spandex.' I thought, what about Michelangelo,
what about da Vinci, what about Warhol?''
</P>
<P>
   Since its launch in October 1996, the site has presented nearly
two dozen shows, ranging from a collection of George Platt Lyne's
sensuous photographs of male nudes to a reexamination through gay
eyes of Gustave Caillebotte's Impressionist paintings.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibits, which are assembled by free-lance curators and
usually accompanied by brief but well-written essays, are
commissioned by a committee, a subset of QAR's 10-member board. ``I
didn't want this to be Barry's art site, and the only way to avoid
that was to give up a certain amount of control and allow other
people to make decisions,'' Harrison said.
</P>
<P>
   A former architect who has lived in New York and Chicago,
Harrison decided to launch the site after moving to San Francisco
and taking a career-planning course for creative people. But he is
driven by a political agenda, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a long, long, long time, artists have been making work
that has queer content,'' he said. ``In other words, it speaks in
some way either of same-sex desire or same-sex experience. Up until
very recently, it has been routinely suppressed, ignored and
censored, either by critics and historians or by the artists
themselves. We need to let the world know what we contribute, and
this is my little corner of that very big mission.''
</P>
<P>
   But Harrison asserted that the Net Selections exhibit, which is
intended to become an annual event, signals QAR's new emphasis on
digital work from the Queer Arts Resource site -- even though the
call for submissions only resulted in a handful of entries.
</P>
<P>
   ``In that queer artists have been at the forefront of all the
other arts,'' he said, ``it's reasonable to believe that they will
carry on in that tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor is Harrison concerned that, by concentrating on
non-heterosexual artists, their work will be relegated to a
sexual-orientation ghetto.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is about the biggest, most diverse, most wonderful ghetto
in the universe,'' he said. ``Even if you just look at the QAR
site, what you get is this diverse spectrum of artistic
expression.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrison added: ``It doesn't show you that gay artists work like
this (in a particular style). It shows just the opposite.''
</P>
<P>
   -------
</P>
<P>
   RELATED SITES: (each address preceeded by http://www.)
</P>
