<HEADER>
A5466 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ADAPTER-CYBERTIMES-TR     10-30 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ADAPTER-CYBERTIMES-TRAVEL-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ADAPTER TO FILL IN THE GAPS 
</HEADLINE>
  By STEPHEN C. MILLER 
 Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   I was trying to be helpful. A colleague at one of the other
newspapers owned by The New York Times Company was in town covering
the baseball playoffs. He had accidentally left the power cord for
his laptop at home. His battery was drained and he was in a panic.
Fortunately, I had a power cord that would work with his computer.
Unfortunately, it was the one to my personal laptop and it was the
only one available. Not a problem, the battery on my laptop is
fully charged and I can use it for several hours.
</P>
<P>
   The plan was for him to use the cord during the game and drop it
off after the game was over. It would be easy; his hotel was just a
few blocks away. Of course, he forgot and took off for Cleveland
with my cord. His office had sent overnight a replacement cord to
his Cleveland hotel and it was waiting for him when he arrived. He
now has two cords and I had none.
</P>
<P>
   It was my turn to panic. I now have a drained battery and no A/C
cord. Actually, I have a cord; it's just that it's in Cleveland. To
compound the problem, I was leaving that day for Los Angeles. I had
planned to use the time on the plane to finish my column. The
timing was a little tricky, but if the plane wasn't late and there
was no great tie-up on the 405, I could get to my hotel and still
file my column just in time to meet deadline.
</P>
<P>
   As I was making frantic phone calls trying to find a replacement
cord, a package arrived from Port Inc. Inside was the new Universal
AC Adapter. The adapter is intended to act as a backup for the AC
adapter for a range of electronic devices, including laptops, cell
phones and battery chargers. If your power cord is lost, stolen or
in my case, loaned, the Universal AC adapter is designed to fill
the void.
</P>
<P>
   It did.
</P>
<P>
   While I might quibble over calling the product ``Universal,''
since it does not support all laptops, cell phones and battery
chargers, it does work with enough of the major brands (IBM, Compaq
and Toshiba) to make it worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to a slim power adapter, it comes with a number of
adapters called Power Tips that match the connector on your
particular laptop. It also comes with a US/Canadian/Japanese outlet
plug; you can order optional plugs for other countries.
</P>
<P>
   I like the slimness of the adapter. It take up little room in
the carrying case. However, the plug fits directly into the brick,
and that means the brick will be flush with the wall. I had trouble
plugging it in one of the hotels because the outlet was close to
the floor and there was not enough room. The base of the desk came
down so far that there wasn't enough room at the top either. I had
to drag the desk from the wall. This was one of those hotels with
heavy antique furniture. I hope housekeeping has forgiven me
because I didn't move the desk back when I hurriedly packed to
catch my flight home.
</P>
<P>
   The adapter is suppose to adjust the voltage depending on the
kind of Power Tip used. I found that the unit got quite warm. It
didn't get hot enough to cause real concern, but it did move the
temperature up a notch or two.
</P>
<P>
   My suggestion is to use it only long enough to charge the
battery and then run the computer off the battery until it drains
completely. The adapter can spur you into conditioning the battery.
</P>
<P>
   Several weeks ago, I mentioned adapters from Global Webmasters
(now on the Web as Traveladapters.com) that managed to handle any
outlet and phone plug in the world. I had just discovered it and
had not had a chance to test it. Since I have not left the confines
of the U.S. of A. and with nothing on the horizon until next year,
I sent the adapters to a friend who was heading for Cairo, London,
Rio and Johannesburg. Being the taciturn type, his report consisted
of ``worked without any problems.'' From him this is a ringing
endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   -------
</P>
<P>
   RELATED SITES: (each address preceeded by http://www.)
</P>
<P>
   _ Port Universal AC Adapter: port.com/docs/acadapt.htm
</P>
<P>
   _ Global Webmasters: traveladapters.com
</P>
<P>
   -------
</P>
<P>
   (Stephen C. Miller is assistant to the technology editor at The
New York Times.)
