<P>
   &UR; STARTING A SUCCESSFUL HOME BUSINESS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (1,400 words) &QL; 
 &UR; By BARBARA WELTMAN &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; From ``The Complete Idiot's Guide to Starting a Home-Based
Business'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Home-based businesses are exploding. Young and old,
professionals and hobbyists, singles and working parents are
capitalizing on the technological revolution that has made working
at home a viable option. Steven Jobs and Calvin Klein launched
their businesses from home. Weltman examines the growth as well as
the pros and cons of the work-at-home trend. (slugged:
BC-STARTING-A-SUCCESSFUL-HOME-BUSINESS-(HOME-BUSINESS-WEEK)-NYTSF,
priority code r, category code l and b)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IS WORKING AT HOME RIGHT FOR YOU? &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (1,500 words) &QL; 
 &UR; By ELLEN H. PARLAPIANO and PATRICIA COBB &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; From Child magazine &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This quiz can help readers determine if they have the right
personality and work habits to be successful working out of the
home. It addresses how one prioritizes tasks, deals with a
child-care crisis, handles loneliness and more. (slugged:
BC-WORK-AT-HOME-QUIZ-(HOME-BUSINESS-WEEK)-NYTSF, priority code r,
category code l and b)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUYING THE RIGHT EQUIPMENT FOR YOUR HOME OFFICE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (1,600 words) &QL; 
 &UR; By ANN ORR &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; From Working Mother magazine &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Orr, senior editor of the Children's Software Revue newsletter,
offers recommendations on what computers, printers, phone equipment
and software are best for home offices. In an accompanying sidebar,
she lists some of the online resources designed for small and
home-based businesses. (slugged:
BC-EQUIPPING-HOME-OFFICES-(HOME-BUSINESS-WEEK)-NYTSF, priority code
r, category code l and b) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A TYPEWRITER KIND OF GAL STRUGGLES IN A PC WORLD &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (750 words) &QL; 
 &UR; By Eve Glicksman &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Odgen Nash was onto something when he observed that progress
might have been all right once, but it has gone on for far too
long,'' begins Glicksman in this humorous essay. She fondly recalls
the days when ``a laptop was where you sat a child'' and ``a
compatible interface was what you hoped for on blind dates.''
Echoing the frustration of many a PC user, she wonders, ``Why can't
they write a decent manual, given the thickness of a Russian
novel?'' (slugged:
BC-A-TECHNOPHOBE'S-LAMENT-(HOME-BUSINESS-WEEK)-NYTSF, priority code
r, category code l and b)
</P>
