<DOCNO> NYT19981030.0069 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-30 11:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5511 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OIL-FUTURE-$ADV31-COX     10-30 1440
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OIL-FUTURE-$ADV31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PROBLEMS LOOM WHEN OIL GLUT ENDS, EXPERTS AND VOTERS AGREE
 &HT;    EDs: Optional add begins at 1000 words.
 &HT;    With OIL-DATA-$ADV31.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (w) Washington and (f) Financial categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., Nov. 1 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Enjoy today's low gasoline prices and worldwide oil
glut, because they won't last forever, most Americans, including
energy experts, agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best analysts think we're in good shape for the next five
to 10 years, but in the long term, South Asia and East Asia will
grow out of their troubles, and their demands will start putting
pressure on global markets,'' said David Nemtzow, president of the
Alliance to Save Energy, a coalition of consumer, government,
business and labor representatives.
</P>
<P>
   Nemtzow said that will coincide with another uncomfortable
trend: ``Existing supplies in the democratic nations, from places
like Alaska and the North Sea, will start running out and that is
going to mean OPEC (the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries) is back in the driver's seat at some point in the next
10 to 15 years.''
</P>
<P>
   While agreeing that Asian demand will bounce back, independent
oilman Steve Layton of Spring, Texas, said U.S. production could
continue at current levels for decades -- 62 years for oil and 68
years for natural gas -- under more supportive policies on taxes,
the environment and use of public lands.
</P>
<P>
   ``America's remaining oil and gas resources are greater than our
cumulative production from 1857(CQ) to the present,'' said Layton,
president and chief executive of Equinox Oil Co. ``Further
exploration, aided by technological innovations, may yet find large
fields that are presently unknown.''
</P>
<P>
   At the American Petroleum Institute, whose members include
several hundred oil companies of all sizes, chief economist Michael
E. Canes said he was confident the world's oil suppliers could deal
smoothly with a steady increase in demand.
</P>
<P>
   A bigger problem would be a random, temporary interruption that
could make the markets ``skittish'' enough to cause price spikes,
Canes said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's say there was a revolution in Saudi Arabia and everybody
was in arms there, and they shut in their oil fields. That's at the
cataclysmic end of the scale,'' Canes said. ``But in different
circumstances, say it's Nigeria (with much less production than
Saudi Arabia). It would depend on the market's perceptions of how
long it would take others to make up for the disruption, whether
that could be done within a few months.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the economic benefits of importing cheap oil year-in and
year-out far exceed the economic costs of occasional short-term oil
shocks, according to a study by nonpartisan analysts from the
General Accounting Office, the investigative arm of the U.S.
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``GAO estimates that the U.S. economy realizes hundreds of
billions of dollars in benefits annually by using relatively low
cost imported oil, rather than relying on more expensive domestic
sources of energy,'' said the report. ``By comparison, oil shocks
impose large but infrequent economic costs that, when annualized,
are estimated to cost the U.S. economy tens of billions of dollars
per year.''
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't count the human costs of wars to protect
foreign oil supplies, said Burl Haigwood, managing director of the
Clean Fuels Foundation, chaired by retired Air Force Gen. Lee
Butler, a strategic planner for Desert Storm, which evicted Iraqi
troops from oil-rich Kuwait in early 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``The root cause of Desert Storm was the world's dependence on
Middle East oil, and the consequences of that war continue to
threaten stability in the area,'' Haigwood said.
</P>
<P>
   Oil shocks abroad disrupted the U.S. supply of oil imports for a
few months during the Suez crisis of the 1950s, the Arab oil
embargo of 1973, the revolution in Iran and Iran's war with Iraq in
1979-80, and the Iraqi invasion of Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Most American voters are well aware of that, and it worries
them, according to a poll of 1,003 registered voters released last
month on the 25th anniversary of the Arab oil embargo by the
Sustainable Energy Coalition. The coalition's 35 consumer,
environmental and industry groups say that renewable energy and
greater efficiencies could lower dependence on oil from here or
abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Answering a series of questions, 75 percent or more agreed that
U.S. dependence on foreign oil is at least a somewhat serious
threat to ``the nation's economy and people's jobs,'' ``our
standard of living'' and ``national security.''
</P>
<P>
   A smaller majority recalled personally experiencing (57 percent)
or had heard of (5 percent) the energy crises of the 1970s that
resulted in increased energy bills, long gasoline lines and the
doubling of gasoline prices.
</P>
<P>
   After being reminded that the United States imported about a
third of its oil in 1973, they were asked what the percentage is
today. Their estimates averaged 58 percent. Ronald H. Hinckley, who
directed the poll, said that was ``a figure fairly close to the
actual figure of 53 percent of gross imports, or 48 percent of net
imports.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Department of Energy estimates that net imports will
rise to 66 percent of U.S. consumption by 2020, as U.S. consumption
grows faster than U.S. production.
</P>
<P>
   Hinckley's poll asked voters to grade ``our elected officials
for dealing with our dependence on foreign oil.'' A plurality of 48
percent picked ``C'', with 18 percent choosing ``A'' or ``B'' and
31 percent choosing ``D'' or ``F''. The rest didn't say.
</P>
<P>
   Nemtzow the advocate, Layton the oilman and Canes the economist
were more lenient graders as they discussed three improvements in
the past quarter century:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  With the demise of federal regulation of oil and gas supplies,
government-caused shortages that would complicate efforts to cope
with a foreign-caused shortage have disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The federal government created the Strategic Petroleum
Reserve, which contains crude oil that can be released quickly to
make up temporarily for cut-off of foreign oil.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Oil supplies have been diversified. The Middle East provides a
smaller portion of the world and U.S. oil supplies.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is why the (U.S. Energy) Department is actively engaged
in promotion of energy development in Latin America, Asia, and the
Caspian regions,'' said Robert W. Gee, assistant energy secretary
for policy and international affairs.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Today, the price signals that reveal balances or imbalances in
supply and demand are sent by open, global markets, rather than by
governments or secret negotiations between oil buyers and
exporters.
</P>
<P>
   Speculators on futures markets help lower financial risks and
smooth out changes in prices, demand and supply, Nemtzow said.
``There are very creative people in the market both on Wall Street
and Main Street today,'' he emphasized.
</P>
<P>
   ``A supply disruption would be reflected in higher prices,
instead of gas station lines,'' Canes said. ``Accommodations could
be made to ease the pain for people who are especially hard hit.''
</P>
<P>
   In an emergency, the president can dip into the Strategic
Petroleum Reserve, which was created after the 1994 embargo. The
SPR consists of government-owned salt caverns in Texas and
Louisiana big enough to hold about 680 million barrels of crude oil
-- just over two-thirds of the one billion barrels called for in
the original plan.
</P>
<P>
   At today's importing pace, the 558 million barrels now in the
reserve could make up for the loss of 57 days' worth of imports --
down from 78 days worth four years ago. In those four years,
imports have grown, but the amount of crude oil in the reserve has
dropped because some was sold off to pay the cost of operating the
reserve.
</P>
<P>
   This year, a Senate plan to resume filling the reserve for the
first time since 1994 was killed in budget negotiations with the
House.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least they've stopped drawing it down,'' said Canes, who
advocates a 90-day supply.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we used the Strategic Petroleum Reserve properly in an
emergency, we couldn't stop the damage, but we could limit it,'' he
said. ``Instead of rising 50 cents a gallon, prices might rise only
30 cents a gallon.''
</P>
<P>
   Layton, who recommends expanding the reserve and filling it with
one billion barrels of crude oil, said, ``With oil prices low, this
is the time to buy and store oil for future emergencies.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
