<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Friday, Oct. 30, 1998      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Saturday and Sunday. If you have questions, call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-POLL (Sacramento, Calif.) _ Despite four gubernatorial
debates and tens of millions of dollars in TV advertising, a new
San Francisco Examiner poll shows Democrat Gray Davis favored by
the same comfortable margin of voters he secured months ago over
Republican Dan Lungren. By ROBERT SALLADAY. (Will also be filed in
the ``p,'' or POLITICS, category.)
</P>
<P>
   EDUCATION-POLL (San Francisco) _ The question of whether a
for-profit company, the Edison Project, should be allowed to run a
struggling public school has become the hot-button issue in next
week's San Francisco school board election. As a result, little has
been discussed about what candidates would do to improve the
schools. By JULIAN GUTHRIE. (Will also be filed in the ``p,'' or
POLITICS, category.)
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO-MONEY (San Francisco) _ More than $34 million in
campaign cash poured into California races within the last week
with a tobacco industry effort to stamp out a cigarette tax leading
the way, a San Francisco Examiner analysis of campaign finance
reports shows. By CHUCK FINNIE. (Will also be filed in the ``p,''
or POLITICS, category.)
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ABORTION-ESCORTS (Schenectady, N.Y.) _ They stand in front of a
Planned Parenthood clinic and wait. When a car pulls up, they hurry
to meet it and accompany the patient into the building. They are
Planned Parenthood escorts, volunteers who whisk patients past the
gauntlet of demonstrators that congregate outside clinics. The job
of an escort has become more dangerous. By CAROL DeMARE.
</P>
<P>
   CLOTHES-PINS (Albany, N.Y.) _ The clothespin has been a common
convenience for more than a century. The modern clothes dryer would
seem to have made the clothespin a thing of the past. But not
quite. There's still nothing like the fresh smell of clothing just
off the clothesline. By FRANCES INGRAHAM. (For release Sunday, Nov.
1)
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   WORKING-COLUMN (Undated) _ As the population ages, employers
have to make changes to their benefit plans to avoid a big
financial hit in a few years as more baby boomers turn 50. By L.M.
SIXEL.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-COLUMN (Undated) _ An Austin, Texas, software company
that collapsed is giving away all its code on the World Wide Web.
It's the way the head of the company is living with the failure of
a business started to build a game that never made it to market. By
DWIGHT SILVERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   With: COMPUTER-HELPLINE
</P>
<P>
   JAPANESE-TOURISTS (San Francisco) _ San Francisco, long a
favored destination for traditionally free-spending Japanese
tourists, faces increasing pressure to hold onto this lucrative
trade. The rise of rival destinations like Las Vegas and the
stagnant Japanese economy, which makes travel more expensive for
Japanese consumers, are the main culprits, experts say. By DAVID
ARMSTRONG.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   VAMPIRE-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ In ``John Carpenter's
Vampires,'' James Woods plays a dedicated vampire slayer, the
leader of a contingent of Vatican mercenaries battling against an
unpleasant 600-year-old vampire. By BRUCE WESTBROOK.
</P>
<P>
   LIFE-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ In ``Life Is Beautiful,'' a father
shields his small son from the brutal reality of life in a
concentration camp by pretending that the whole thing is just part
of a contest to win an army tank. This tragi-comedy is from Italian
director Roberto Benigni, who also stars in the film. By LOUIS B.
PARKS.
</P>
<P>
   LOVE-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Love Is the Devil'' is based on
the relationship between the English painter Francis Bacon and his
lover, George Dyer, who was also the model for many of Bacon's
paintings in the 1960s. Derek Jacobi plays Bacon, and Daniel Craig
plays Dyer. By JEFF MILLAR.
</P>
<P>
   LIMITS-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Without Limits'' wins as a
sports film precisely because it's not really about sports or a
great victory. The film manages to be surprisingly involving by
focusing on the personality of cocky, charismatic, attractive
runner Steve Prefontaine, looking at what made him succeed and
sometimes fail spectacularly. By LOUIS B. PARKS.
</P>
<P>
   TV-SHUTTLE (Undated) _ This is the way it used to be, in the
black and white and early technicolor days, when space was scary
and vital and anchors like Walter Cronkite had models of big rocket
ships on their desk. Words like ``T-minus,'' and ``gimbal'' and the
other technical jargon, we knew all that. And those moments right
after lift-off were tension conventions that knotted our stomachs.
All that flame, all that smoke. Would it be all right? By MARK
McGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ If history is any guide, it'll
happen before Tuesday morning. The phone will ring, and somebody
will identify himself or herself as a pollster. Just a few
questions, please. At this late date in the political season,
pollsters who phone probably will be conducting what politicians
call a ``push poll.'' By DAN LYNCH.
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ If he were a free man _ in other
words, not a politician running for governor of California _ Dan
Lungren could stand up whenever he felt like it and do what has
come so naturally to him for decades: unequivocally condemn
abortion. By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
</TEXT>
