<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HAITI AT-A-GLANCE
 &HT;    With HAITI-POLITICS-$ADV01.
 &HT;    For Use Sunday, Nov. 1 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Aid to Haiti from foreign institutions and governments:
</P>
<P>
   1995 $540 million
</P>
<P>
   1996 $420 million
</P>
<P>
   1997 $351 million
</P>
<P>
   Economic growth:
</P>
<P>
   1995 4.4 percent
</P>
<P>
   1996 2.7 percent
</P>
<P>
   1997 1.1 percent
</P>
<P>
   Source: U.N. Development Program.
</P>
<P>
   HAITI: AT-A-GLANCE
</P>
<P>
   Population: 8 million
</P>
<P>
   Capital: Port-au-Prince (Pop. 3 million)
</P>
<P>
   Location: Haiti occupies the western third of the Caribbean
island of Hispaniola, which it shares with the Dominican Republic
</P>
<P>
   Languages: Haitian Creole; French
</P>
<P>
   Life expectancy: 54.5 years
</P>
<P>
   Illiteracy: 50 percent
</P>
<P>
   Unemployment: 60 percent
</P>
<P>
   1998 economic growth: 2 percent
</P>
<P>
   1998 inflation rate: 11 percent
</P>
<P>
   President: Rene Preval
</P>
<P>
   Political situation: A current political impasse is due to a
power struggle between former President Jean-Bertrand Aristide,
who's expected to run for president in 2000, and the Organization
for the People's Struggle, the dominant party in Parliament that's
critical of Aristide. Caught in the middle is Preval, regarded as a
competent leader with a pro-Aristide tilt who has difficulty
communicating with the population.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. involvement: The Clinton administration hailed Haiti as a
foreign policy success after 20,000 U.S. troops invaded in 1994 to
overthrow a brutal dictatorship and restore Aristide to power three
years after he was ousted and sent into exile by the military.
</P>
<P>
   Sources: U.S. and Haitian governments.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
