<HEADER>
A5522 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HAITI-GEORGES-$ADV01-     10-30 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAITI-GEORGES-$ADV01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A MONTH AFTER GEORGES UNLEASHED ITS FURY, ITS DESTRUCTION
BECOMES CLEAR
 &HT;    With HAITI-POLITICS-$AVD01.
 &HT;    With photos to be placed in the International folder on the Cox
Server.
 &HT;    For Use Sunday, Nov. 1 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti _ As Hurricane Mitch churned through the
Caribbean this week, a clearer picture is emerging of the
destruction imposed by Hurricane Georges on the hemisphere's
poorest country little more than a month ago.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of cardboard homes in the squalid slums that surround
this capital city have been washed away.
</P>
<P>
   The southeastern border town of Fonds Verrettes nearly wiped
out, killing more than 100 residents.
</P>
<P>
   And in central Haiti, 20 inches of rain dumped by Georges
devastated crops in the Artibonite Valley, the breadbasket of a
nation that can't feed itself even in good times.
</P>
<P>
   ``People in this country have suffered so much and so long that
it seems particularly unjustified that they have had to suffer
through this storm,'' said U.S. Agency for International
Development Administrator Brian Atwood, who visited Haiti last
month(CQ).
</P>
<P>
   Georges ripped through the eastern Caribbean and the Florida
Keys in late September, pummeling island after island like a
violent enemy looking for vengeance.
</P>
<P>
   The storm killed more than 500 people and inflicted more than $5
billion in property damage before making its exit as an innocuous
fall rainstorm over Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   But hardest hit was Hispaniola, an island shared by Haiti and
the Dominican Republic, two countries ill-prepared for a natural
disaster of such magnitude.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of Georges, the Haitian government said a
combination of mudslides and flooding killed more than 200 people,
left another 332,136 homeless and killed 56,828 animals.
Agricultural damage is estimated at $300 million.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, Port-au-Prince, Haiti's bustling capital and
home to 3 million people, wasn't affected by the hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   But in other parts of Haiti, the country's extreme poverty put
it at the mercy of Georges even moreso than other nations ravaged
by the hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   The storm aggravated an already precarious economy, weak
agricultural production, and a deteriorated network of roads.
</P>
<P>
   ``In such a poor country, the economic effect is going to be
greater than it would be elsewhere,'' said Alex Knowles, head of
the Haitian-American Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the effect really won't be felt for another three or four
months,'' he said. ``That's when prices will start rising as more
food has to be imported.''
</P>
<P>
   An unfortunate by-product of the storm is a drop in attendance
at some schools by as much as 30 percent. With Georges wiping out
crops, many parents couldn't come up with the money needed to pay
for enrollment last month(CQ), the start of the new school year.
</P>
<P>
   Yet another by-product, with the United States bearing the brunt
of it, will undoubtedly be increased illegal migration and drug
trafficking -- which were already growing concerns for U.S.
officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would think you'd see more Haitians trying to get to the
United States because of miserable conditions,'' said Ken Boodhoo,
an expert on Haiti at Florida International University in Miami.
``And, because of poor communication, I am sure the extent of the
hurricane's damage isn't even known yet.''
</P>
<P>
   According to an AID report on the hurricane, escalating prices,
increased food shortages, and widespread hunger are expected as the
traditional flow of food supplies falls far short of already low
historical levels during the next nine months to a year.
</P>
<P>
   Tempering that sentiment are U.S. observers saying the
government here responded faster, surprisingly, than the government
in the neighboring Dominican Republic, a better-developed country.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bright spot in all this has been the efforts by the
Haitians themselves to provide relief and set up shelters,'' said
Phyllis Forbes, director of AID in Haiti.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
