<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMMENTARY-BJT-1031-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE COMMENTARY BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These columns for release Saturday, October 31, 1998 are moving
today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   BORDERS-COLUMN _ I have set about building a wooden cabinet to
hold my cassette tapes a few weeks back. My primary motivation was
the chance to finally enjoy my little shop now that the temperature
has dipped down to tolerable levels. Lord knows I could buy a
cabinet to hold tapes for a fraction of what I'm spending on pieces
of oak and poplar. This is a middle-aged male thing, I realize,
this urge to putter around with my limited collection of carpentry
tools, radio sending forth classical music, the smell of sawdust
filling the air. It's a shame I don't have a clue to what I'm
doing, though that has never stopped me before in any aspect of my
life. (Borders, Cox News Service) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   GLASS-COLUMN _ WASHINGTON _ At any one time, only about 75
spectators can squeeze into the small federal courtroom where the
most important antitrust case in many a decade is being tried. Step
out for any reason, and you'll lose your seat to the next person
waiting in line. The other day, U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield
Jackson, who presides over the legal fate of Microsoft Corp.,
invited a visiting group from the former Soviet republic of Moldova
to observe an afternoon session. The delegation bumped a dozen
people who had been trying for hours to get in. Of the 75 places on
the hard wooden benches, 40 are reserved for reporters. We lucky
few are guaranteed seats _ so long as we toe the line. (Glass, Cox
News Service) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ Some 3.9 million Americans have been stripped of
their right to vote _ 1.4 million of them African-American men,
disenfranchised at a rate seven times than of white men. Is a
bombshell a bombshell if no one hears it go off? With the exquisite
timing at which do-gooders excel, Human Rights Watch and The
Sentencing Project dropped their voting report at the moment when
Congress had just adjourned in notable chaos, the Mideast talks
were at riveting stalemate and John Glenn was suiting up for space.
What might have been a goodly boom on a slow news day made barely a
plink. (Teepen, Cox News Service) MOVED WEDNESDAY
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ Many years back, when Mel Ott still was
hitting home runs down the short right field line in the Polo
Grounds and when Rita Hayworth was knocking 'em dead simply by
letting her hair fall on her bare shoulders, I could name all the
models of American cars. There were three kinds of Buick:
Four-door, two-door and convertible. There were three kinds of
Packard: Four-door, two-door and convertible. And so on. Chapstick
was Chapstick, one kind. Now Chapstick comes in more delicious
flavors than Jello used to, and I can't even recognize an American
car let alone tell you the models. The wide selection of goods
available to today's consumers, I suppose, is a benefit but it
confuses me. (Kleinberg, Cox News Service) MOVED WEDNESDAY
</P>
<P>
   NETHAWAY-COLUMN _ SESTRIERE, Italy _ In the march of time armies
commanded by Roman rulers, Celtic kings, European nobles, Christian
crusaders, Napoleon I, Nazis and others have come this valley. To
those bygone warriors, the surrounding mountains looked dangerous
and forbidding. To me, lounging in the morning sun in front of an
Alpine cafe amid the smells of cappuccino and fresh-baked Italian
bread, the same scenery looks postcard perfect, which you can buy
for about 1,000 Italian lira on postcards all around the village.
The Italians ought to do something about their money. (Nethaway,
Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED WEDNESDAY
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
