A5536 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BORDERS-COLUMN31-COX     10-30 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COLUMN31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    I'm dangerous if given the proper tools
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I have set about building a wooden cabinet to hold my cassette
tapes a few weeks back. My primary motivation was the chance to
finally enjoy my little shop now that the temperature has dipped
down to tolerable levels. Lord knows I could buy a cabinet to hold
tapes for a fraction of what I'm spending on pieces of oak and
poplar.
</P>
<P>
   This is a middle-aged male thing, I realize, this urge to putter
around with my limited collection of carpentry tools, radio sending
forth classical music, the smell of sawdust filling the air. It's a
shame I don't have a clue to what I'm doing, though that has never
stopped me before in any aspect of my life.
</P>
<P>
   Here is what I own, tool-wise: a circular saw, a cordless drill,
a hammer, wrenches, screwdrivers, etc., an orbital sander and a
router. I have owned the router for some time but haven't gotten up
the nerve to use it. Truth be told, I don't know how to use it. It
seemed like a good idea at the time, since it wasn't very expensive
and I've always wanted to rout. Or maybe it's
</P>
<P>
   route; I'm not sure what the verb form is. But routers are
necessary to doing fine carpentry, I'm told, like creating
decorative edges, grooves in wood and such. So I bought one on
sale.
</P>
<P>
   I've since discovered that one must own a router table to make
any use of a router. This keeps the router stationary while the
wood passes over it. Learning this cleared up a few matters that
had me befuddled. I would experiment with scrap pieces of wood, the
result being nothing more than a heck of a mess on the floor and
some rather bizarre pieces of wood. For the life of me, until I
learned about the table, I couldn't figure out just how one went
about using this cool-looking piece of machinery.
</P>
<P>
   I have been checking out router tables, all of which cost more
than the actual router, but haven't made the plunge yet. I am not
an impulse buyer of anything but books and music. I must
contemplate the purchase for some time. It takes me months to get
around to buying shoes, for example. I've been thinking about
buying a router for years. Since it's useless without a table, I
will have to decide soon whether to accessorize.
</P>
<P>
   I had no set of plans to go by in building my tape cabinet. I
drew
</P>
<P>
   something up on a legal pad, a rough blueprint that I've since
abandoned. I just went to the home-improvement store, bought some
wood, screws, nails and glue, and came home.
</P>
<P>
   It's been trial-and-error, and you can guess which one is
winning. What little skills I had were so rusty that it took a
while just to get back into the basics of cutting a straight board
and nailing it to another without splitting the wood or missing
altogether. Then a friend offered to loan me his table saw, after I
complained about how hard it is to cut something straight with a
circular, hand-held saw.
</P>
<P>
   This is a scary machine. Every time I use it I have visions of
having to learn to type with two or three fewer fingers. Boy, this
could really mess up my golf grip, I think, as I rip a piece of
wood, the key thought being, ``Keep your fingers away from the
blade, dummy.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, so good. Table saws are wonderful for cutting things
straight and being able to duplicate different pieces. I was so
impressed that I tore down the first two drawers I made with the
circular saw and started over.
</P>
<P>
   The now-10-year-old daughter joins me on occasion, hammering
together pieces of scrap wood to make some type of wooden
sculpture. I've been trying to teach her proper hammering
techniques _ holding the hammer at the end, swinging smoothly but
firmly _ but she still hammers like a girl, tiny taps
</P>
<P>
   while holding it near the head. She'll learn or move on to
something else.
</P>
<P>
   Progress is slow. The drawers look OK, but I'm not happy with
the first version of the cabinet that will hold the drawers. I may
start over. I make semi-weekly trips to the home-improvement store
to buy more wood. I could have bought a tape cabinet and furnished
it with tapes for what I've spent so far, and I haven't even broken
down and bought the router table _ yet.
</P>
<P>
   This project is looked upon by my wife with great amusement. She
calls me Tim the Tool Man when I bring up the subject of the router
table, or hint that a table saw with my name on the gift tag would
look great under the Christmas tree.
</P>
<P>
   There is a patina of sawdust over everything in the shop, which
also doubles as a golf-cart shed and storage area, for boxes of
Christmas decorations and such. The smell of sawdust reminds me of
my maternal grandfather's shop. He was a real carpenter, could
build anything _ and did. His widow still lives in the house he
built out in the country more than 30 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   If Grampa was alive, I'd be able to get routing lessons. As it
is, I'm on my own.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor and publisher of The Nacogdoches Daily
Sentinel. His e-mail address is gborders(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
