<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUGAR31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sweet opening for new U.S. Sugar refinery
 &HT;    WITH PHOTO
 &HT;    By Julie Waresh
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEWISTON, Fla. _ J. Nelson Fairbanks had a lot of folks to
thank at Thursday's unveiling of U.S. Sugar Corp.'s giant new sugar
refinery _ the first to be built in the United States in 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   But the president and chief executive officer of the 67-year-old
company wasted no time in calling attention to one very important
group in the audience of more than 600.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to recognize our bankers,'' Fairbanks told the crowd
of employees, elected officials and reporters who gathered under a
tent after a tour. ``Without them, this would not be possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Privately held U.S. Sugar won't reveal the cost of the
300,000-square-foot structure, except to say that it tops the $70
million the company spent on its citrus-processing plant that
opened in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   But industry analysts say it probably cost $100 million or more
to build this computerized and highly automated refinery, which
converts raw milled sugar into the white sugar used in candy,
cookies and coffee.
</P>
<P>
   The Clewiston-based company is banking on the gargantuan
investment to increase its returns in a low-margin business that
essentially has been flat for a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Hammock, one of about 60 smaller farmers who sell their
sugar cane to U.S. Sugar, expects the refinery to benefit him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't help but think that, if U.S. Sugar is in better shape
financially, it will help the growers that sell to them,'' Hammock
said.
</P>
<P>
   To market the refined sugar, which the company will produce for
the first time this year, U.S. Sugar has joined a Minnesota-based
sugar marketing cooperative, United Sugars Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The co-op, whose other members are Midwestern beet sugar
producers, will distribute and sell U.S. Sugar's product, some of
which will be packaged under the Pillsbury Best national brand.
</P>
<P>
   The refinery has created about 150 jobs since construction began
in March 1997, and another 20 positions are expected to be filled
as the sugar harvest that began this month hits full swing.
</P>
<P>
   Primary owners of U.S. Sugar are its employees and charitable
foundations set up by the company's founder, Charles Stewart Mott.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Alcee Hastings, D-Miramar, who attended the opening
along with U.S. Rep. Mark Foley, R-West Palm Beach, said he expects
the refinery to also help create jobs outside U.S. Sugar.
</P>
<P>
   ``My belief is that it will cause other light industry to
consider locating here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
