<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SHUTTLE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME ENCHANTING TELEVISION ON `OLD TIMERS' DAY' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK McGUIRE  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ This is the way it used to be, in the black and
white and early technicolor days, when space was scary and vital
and anchors like Walter Cronkite had models of big rocket ships on
their desk. Everyone, except maybe the Communists, cared and were
pulling for the same outcome.
</P>
<P>
   Words like ``T-minus,'' and ``gimbal'' and the other technical
jargon, we knew all that. And those moments right after liftoff
were tension conventions which knotted our stomachs. All that
flame, all that smoke, would it be all right?
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, it was. Shuttle Discovery blasted off _ even that
seems like an archaic expression _ 19 minutes late. Despite the
delay, much of the country paused to watch.
</P>
<P>
   In almost every respect this was a routine launch, yet still it
was enchanting television. While most shuttle liftoffs are pretty
much ignored, all the networks broke out their heavy-hitters for
this one, with CNN putting out the biggest pinch-hitter of all.
</P>
<P>
   It was the images, not the commentary, that provided the drama.
Sometimes there was just nothing to say. Then finally the rockets
fired.
</P>
<P>
   ``Liftoff of Discovery with a crew of six astronaut heroes and
one American legend,'' NASA launch commentator Lisa Malone said in
a monotone you'd expect to hear in an off-track betting parlor.
</P>
<P>
   The legend was John Glenn. And another legend, Cronkite, the man
America trusted when it could still trust, watched and commented
from a CNN broadcast vantage 2 miles away from the launch pad.
</P>
<P>
   Those two are why we cared again. Shuttles _ with the tragic
exception of the doomed 1986 Challenger mission _ lift off into
space with regularity, their safety numbing anxiety and interest.
</P>
<P>
   It's just not like the old days of Mercury and Gemini and
Apollo, where experimentation and providence were the only things
that got some astronauts there and back.
</P>
<P>
   Cronkite is 81 now, a little of hard of hearing, and certainly
not as quick a wit or tongue as he was anchoring the ``CBS Evening
News'' from 1962 to 1981. His insights offered were few but
welcome.
</P>
<P>
   And Glenn, the hero astronaut turned senator, is 77, no longer
the rock-cut Marine who become America's poster boy in his first
historic orbital flight in 1962.
</P>
<P>
   But we weren't looking for these guys in their prime Thursday.
This was Old Timer's Day: A smile, a wave, a few words were all we
asked for or needed.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn did his part, so did Cronkite.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to lift off Apollo 12 astronaut Alan Bean said that out of
all the people he asks in his travels, about one in four say they
would want to go on the shuttle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, sure they would,'' Cronkite said slowly, sadly. He knows
his longtime dream to be the first journalist in space was lost
with the Challenger disaster.
</P>
<P>
   It may be his only mission he will never accomplish.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. E-mail:
mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-30-98 1144EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
