<SLUG> BC-CLOTHESPINS-$ADV01-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLOTHESPINS: SIMPLE BUT ESSENTIAL PART OF LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Nov. 1)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRANCES INGRAHAM  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The clothespin, like the staple and paper clip,
so simple in design, has been a common convenience for more than a
century.
</P>
<P>
   The modern gas and electric clothes dryer would seem to have
made the clothespin a thing of the past. But not quite. There's
still nothing like the fresh smell of clothing and bedding just off
the clothesline.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, The Wall Street Journal noted that 900 million
peg-and-spring clip clothespins were sold in the United States
every year in the mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
   In February 1998, the Smithsonian launched a show of
clothespins, which will run through March 1999, including 41
clothespin patent models from its collection. The first clothespin
was patented in 1832, followed by another 146 between 1852 and
1887.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Suit Janssen, curator of the exhibit, in her research
found something similar to the clothespin dating back to the
ancient Egyptians. In its history, the clothespin has been used not
only to hold wet sheets on a clotheslines, but it was also popular
for making dolls, rubber-band guns and holiday ornaments, according
to the Smithsonian.
</P>
<P>
   Today, there remain several varieties of clothespins from which
to choose, including the basic push-on friction fit with no moving
parts and the v-shaped spring clips, which are readily found in any
homewares department for under $3 a pack. Many are made from
plastic in a variety of colors, as well as the traditional pale
bleached smooth wood _ made from maple, white birch, oak and pine.
</P>
<P>
   Plastic clothespins were actually made as early as the 1940s,
when red was the color of choice, making them easy to find when
dropped in the grass. Molded acrylic clothespins in sky blue,
cherry red, avocado and mauve were also popular in the 1940s and
'50s.
</P>
<P>
   The metal used for spring-clip pins, if it rusts, can leave
unslightly marks on clothing.
</P>
<P>
   In the 19th century, clothespins were also called clothes pegs.
Some were made of carved walrus or whale bone with simple beading
or rings carved at the neck and bottom with the familiar ball top.
Some were slender in size, while others were fat with rubber pads
for gripping carpets and such without leaving an imprint.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 19th century, clothespins also were carved by hand,
from a single piece of wood with no iron nails to keep them from
splitting. Some of these may have featured a carved decoration or
initials. Such pins were often said to be a type of love token and
are valued today at between $30 and $45.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-30-98 1151EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981030.0086 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-30 12:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5588 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ABORTION-ESCORTS-HNS &LR;      10-30 0559
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABORTION-ESCORTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABORTION CLINIC VOLUNTEERS DEFY VIOLENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CAROL DeMARE  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCHENECTADY, N.Y. _ Their job is simple _ they stand in front of
a Planned Parenthood clinic and wait.
</P>
<P>
   When a car pulls up, they spring into action, hurrying to meet
the vehicle and accompany the patient into the building.
</P>
<P>
   They are Planned Parenthood escorts, volunteers available to
whisk patients past the gauntlet of demonstrators outside clinics.
</P>
<P>
   With violent episodes happening more frequently against doctors
who perform abortions, the job of an escort has become more
dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, Dr. Barnett Slepian, an obstetrician/gynecologist
who performed abortions, was shot dead at his home outside of
Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   The incident has resulted in an increased number of potential
volunteers at places like the Upper Hudson Planned Parenthood in
Albany.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since last weekend, we have seen an increase in the numbers
who want to be escorts,'' people who said ``they were outraged or
upset about what happened,'' Upper Hudson spokeswoman Blue Carreker
said.
</P>
<P>
   The callers said they had ``to make this commitment,'' Carreker
said. ``Some had been escorting before but had stopped. Some are
new.''
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of women's health organizations from across New York
told a news conference Thursday that the state needed to take
strong action to curb anti-abortion violence.
</P>
<P>
   The killing of Slepian demonstrates the capacity for violence of
some abortion opponents and the need to better protect patients and
workers at women's clinics in New York, the coalition of womens
groups said. Representatives of Family Planning Advocates, Planned
Parenthood of New York City and other groups called on the state
Senate to drop its longstanding opposition to a bill criminalizing
the barring of access to health care facilities where abortions are
performed.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday morning, five escorts stood outside the Planned
Parenthood Health Services of Northeastern New York building in
Schenectady. Alongside the curb, a dozen protesters sang hymns,
chanted but mainly prayed clutching rosary beads and prayer books.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters show up ``on days they know we are performing
surgeries,'' said Linda Scharf, spokeswoman for the Schenectady
clinic. There's been no measurable impact on potential escorts
since the Slepian shooting, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Demonstrators typically arrive shortly before 9 a.m. and stay
about an hour. They then retreat to their storefront building
directly across from the two-story brick Planned Parenthood
building, which has bullet-resistant glass in its front windows.
</P>
<P>
   After Thursday's protest, none of the demonstrators wanted to
discuss their activities. A leader of the demonstrators who said he
was a Roman Catholic priest but declined to give his name. He
called the gathering ``a prayer group'' that hands out
anti-abortion literature.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every person coming to Planned Parenthood is approached by
protesters who want to give them literature,'' Scharf said. The
escorts are on hand ``to support their access. We don't want
someone frightened away.''
</P>
<P>
   She said fewer than 10 percent of the clinic's services are
abortion-related.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want someone frightened away from getting a pap
smear,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-30-98 1206EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
