   &UR; ATTENTION EDITORS: &LR;  The following is the budget for the New
Scientist for material available the week of Mon., Nov. 2 and
anytime thereafter. This material is free for use for New York
Times News Service clients. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AMERICAN BIOTECH GIANT FACING CRITICISM &LR;  _ Monsanto, the
American biotech giant, is facing an unprecedented wave of
criticism from within the industry. Many of Monsanto's rivals
believe that the company is largely to blame for the collapse of
consumer acceptance of genetically modified food in Europe. New
Scientist. By Andy Coghlan. 700 words. (slugged:
BC-BIOTECH-GIANT-FACES-CRITICISM-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AUTISTIC ANIMALS MAY HELP SCIENTISTS &LR;  _ Neurologists from Paris
and New York have bred guinea pigs with behavioral traits typical
of autistic patients. The team believes that an animal model for
autism could be useful to understand the condition better. By
Patrice Horovitz. 300 words. (slugged:
BC-AUTISTIC-ANIMALS-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RAIN FORESTS ARE BEYOND HOPE &LR;  _ Attempts to save most of the
world's tropical rain forests are doomed to failure and should
probably be abandoned according to a study coordinated in Italy.
The report concludes that there is no hope of stopping
deforestation in major rain forest regions such as Indonesia and
Brazil, due to pressure by logging companies and farmers. By Fred
Pearce. 500 words. (slugged: BC-NO-HOPE-FOR-rain
forestS-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GREAT VIBES FROM BIG SURF &LR;  _ A system designed to detect
gravitational waves from black holes could soon be a surfer's best
friend. By Sharon Ann Holgate. 300 words. (slugged:
BC-BLACK-HOLES-AND-SURFERS-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF) &QL; 
