<SLUG> BC-BLACK-HOLES-AND-SURFERS-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREAT VIBES FROM BIG SURF 
</HEADLINE>
   By SHARON ANN HOLGATE  
 Copyright 1998 New Scientist  
 (Distributed by New York Times Syndicate)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A system designed to detect gravitational waves from black holes
could soon be a surfer's best friend. Researchers at the University
of Western Australia, near Perth, say devices used in their
experiments to cut out vibrations could measure the height of waves
at sea.
</P>
<P>
   As waves head toward land, they interact with the rising
seafloor, creating tiny _ but proportional _ seismic waves, which
travel inland.
</P>
<P>
   In a test reported in Measurement Science and Technology (vol.
9, p. 1772), the UWA team measured these seismic waves on their
vibration isolator from 10 kilometers inland.
</P>
<P>
   The results showed a 92 percent agreement with wave data from a
buoy that was 40 kilometers out to sea.
</P>
<P>
   Vibration isolators are used under delicate equipment in
experiments where readings would be ruined by shaking _ whether
caused by footsteps or a distant earthquake _ and are designed to
keep equipment still.
</P>
<P>
   UWA's vibration isolator is made from aluminum, and has a
30-centimeter long horizontal plate suspended from a frame by
flexible titanium hinges.
</P>
<P>
   The hinges enable the plate to remain still to about one tenth
of a nanometer when the frame is shaken. The seismic waves cause
the frame to move by a few micrometers, and an optical sensor
detects the relative motion between frame and plate. This
difference is directly proportional to the wave height.
</P>
<P>
   UWA's David Blair suggests that the devices ``could create a
system to image the ocean waves coming in all round the coast.'' He
also plans a smaller version for surfers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (This article is excerpted from New Scientist, a weekly science
and technology magazine based in London.) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
