used our collective personal knowledge of where deforestation was
happening to compile these maps,'' he says. And he agrees with the
pessimistic conclusion. ``Southeast Asia has had it. There is
little old-growth forest left there anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   He named the Indonesian island of Sumatra as the hottest of the
deforestation hot spots. An island twice the size of Britain, it
has lost virtually all its lowland forests in just 25 years, along
with the animals that lived in them. A similar situation is
developing in Kalimantan, says the report. And one of the last
forested areas, the ``golden triangle'' along the Burmese-Thai
border, is now threatened by Chinese plans to open up access to its
Yunnan province by building road and rail links to the Bay of
Bengal.
