A5607 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IVOR-CATE-BLANCHETT-A     10-30 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IVOR-CATE-BLANCHETT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CATE BLANCHETT REIGNS IN 'ELIZABETH' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Hollywood Stars
feature.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly column with color art.) 
 World rights except Great Britain and Australia 
 Color slides and black and white photos of Cate Blanchett in
``Elizabeth.'' 
 By IVOR DAVIS 
 Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    She's the buzz of Hollywood: suddenly a front-runner for a best
actress Oscar for her stunning portrayal as England's Queen
Elizabeth I. It's a role that every actress in Britain would have
killed for.
 &HT;    But Australia's rising star Cate Blanchett has only one thing on
her mind: Getting home to Sydney with her husband of just over a
year Andrew Upton so they can spend Christmas with their families.
 &HT;    ``I have a very small family but Andrew's is enormous,'' she
said, ``so I'm hoping for a chaotic, loud, happy family
Christmas.''
 &HT;    The 28-year-old actress has already earned rave reviews for
portraying the troubled and naive English monarch in the film which
costars fellow Aussie Geoffrey Rush, Richard Attenborough, John
Gielgud, Joseph Fiennes (brother of English actor Ralph Fiennes)
and Christopher Eccleston.
 &HT;    Since finishing Elizabeth she has worked nonstop. She is just
finishing up ``The Talented Mr. Ripley'' opposite Matt Damon and
Gwyneth Paltrow in Italy for ``English Patient'' director Anthony
Minghella, as well as ``Pushing Tin,'' a black comedy about air
traffic controllers with John Cusack and Billy Bob Thornton. Both
films are due out in l999.
 &HT;    There follows a movie version of Oscar Wilde's play ``An Ideal
Husband'' and next March (Oscar time in Hollywood) she's returning
to Britain to appear on the London stage in David Hare's ``Plenty''
_ which was made into a movie in l985 with Meryl Streep and Sam
Neill, with direction by Australian Fred Schepisi.
 &HT;    Looking pale but beautiful after such a hectic work schedule and
sipping iced water in a Los Angeles hotel suite, Blanchett is
buoyed by all the talk of Oscar nominations. However she admits
that getting the role of Elizabeth was something of a coup.
 &HT;    Word was that she was going to be passed over because she was
not well known internationally, despite great reviews for l997's
``Oscar and Lucinda'' opposite Ralph Fiennes. Producers were
looking for someone more famous in Britain to star in a role about
a British monarch and so she had to do a screen test for Indian
director Shekhar Kapur.
 &HT;    The movie is a spectacular costume drama set in London in the
middle of the 16th century. Elizabeth, the daughter of Henry VIII
and Anne Boleyn, is imprisoned at 16 by her half-sister Mary, but
swept onto the throne and crowned Queen of England at 23. To
survive she must sort out the machiavellian agendas on the
battlefield, in the church and in her court. Her enemies, most of
them powerful men, would appear to have the advantage, but
Elizabeth deploys whatever means necessary to keep her crown.
 &HT;    ``The main thing about getting the part was that the director
had confidence in me,'' she recalls. ``He had seen me in a trailer
of 'Oscar and Lucinda' and thought I was right for the part.
 &HT;    ``I must admit though, I was flabbergasted to get 'Oscar and
Lucinda.' And then 'Elizabeth.' I asked myself how did I find the
courage to do it. But I plunge into something and when it's done
sit back and say, my God.''
 &HT;    Blanchett grew up in Melbourne and says in her early years she
didn't yearn to be an actress. She was just 10 when her Texan
father Bob, a flamboyant advertising man, died suddenly, leaving
her mother June, a teacher, to bring up her and two siblings.
 &HT;    ``I was so fortunate that my mother was remarkable and held
things together for us. She introduced me to acting when I was 12
when she took me to see a production of 'They Shoot Horses Don't
They?' I was smitten by it.''
 &HT;    Nonetheless she started out studying economics and fine arts.
``I failed miserably at the economics and so I became sort of the
black sheep of the family,'' she laughs.
 &HT;    Unlike many Aussie actors, Blanchett didn't get her start on
Aussie soaps but learned her trade at the National Institute of
Dramatic Art in Sydney where she won plaudits on the boards in
``The Tempest,'' ``Hamlet,'' ``The Seagull'' and David Mamet's
``Oleanna.'' Her first film splash was as Susan McCarthy in Bruce
Beresford's ``Paradise Road.''
 &HT;    Just as her international movie career was taking off in June
l997 she married boyfriend Upton in a ceremony in the Blue
Mountains in New South Wales. Their home is in a Sydney beach
suburb, in a non-movie-star house which they've seen very little
of.
 &HT;    ``When I made 'Elizabeth' I saw very little daylight and had
virtually no social life,'' she says. ``I wore elaborate costumes
and very tight corsets. I had my eyebrows bleached, my eyelashes
bleached, my hairline shaved, half my hair dyed white _ so I didn't
get out much looking like that.''
 &HT;    She says her husband understands the demands her career makes on
her _ professionally and personally. ``I am very fortunate to have
a partner who is incredibly supportive of me.''
 &HT;    However she does admit she is a little torn between the demands
of a burgeoning career which could take her to the very top and her
desire to enjoy a normal life with her husband out of the
limelight.
 &HT;    For instance there's the question of a family _ to start one or
not. ``I think children are one of the few miracles left,'' she
says carefully.
 &HT;     c.1998 Ivor Davis  (Ivor Davis is a Hollywood-based
<TEXT>
reporter.) &LR;  &QL;
</TEXT>
