<DOCNO> NYT19981030.0101 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-30 12:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5630 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      10-30 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUNGREN CAN'T HAVE IT BOTH WAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In a way, I almost feel sorry for Dan Lungren.
If he were a free man _ in other words, not a politician running
for governor of California _ he could stand up whenever he felt
like it and do what has come so naturally to him for decades:
Unequivocally condemn abortion.
</P>
<P>
   With all the passion and zeal that public opinion polls allow
him to show on another issue _ the death penalty _ he could shout
out what he says he has always believed, that elective abortion is
immoral and that _ if it were in his power _ it would become
illegal tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   But Lungren is not a free man. He deeply wants to become
governor. As much as anything though _ and despite Lungren's hopes
that the issue will just go away _ abortion remains one of his
trickiest obstacles.
</P>
<P>
   The majority of Californians still believes, as Lungren's
Democratic opponent, Gray Davis, does, that a woman has a right to
choose what does or does not occur in her own womb. That majority
includes some 65 to 70 percent of Republican women. So, the
attorney general (no doubt on the advice of battle-hardened
campaign consultants) has softened his lifelong, absolutist
anti-abortion rhetoric and narrowed his focus to an almost absurd
degree.
</P>
<P>
   The longer Lungren talks, the more he and his wife explain in
campaign ads that it's their ``deeply held religious and moral
convictions'' that make them anti-choice, the more the veteran
champion of the ``unborn'' comes off as disingenuous and a bit of a
sellout.
</P>
<P>
   Lungren's bending and twisting started early this year when he
began to paint his anti-abortion views as inconsequential in the
big scheme of things. It really doesn't matter what his
``personal'' feelings are about abortion, he said, because the law
that legalized abortion _ Roe vs. Wade _ is a federal statute and
thus out of the domain of a state governor.
</P>
<P>
   In the state domain, Lungren chose instead to focus on a couple
of the most inflammatory and least understood aspects of abortion
law. As governor, he said, all he plans to do about abortion is to
resurrect California's overturned parental consent law and keep
taxpayers from financing abortions for the poor _ especially
late-term or partial-birth abortions.
</P>
<P>
   As a ``pro-life'' package for 1998, how reasonable and
mainstream can you get, right? Wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Lungren insults even minimal intelligence with his argument that
governors are like ineffectual functionaries with their hands tied
when it comes to abortion law.
</P>
<P>
   In nearly every state in this country, legislators and many
governors are working hard to limit a woman's control over her own
reproductive system. Dozens already have succeeded. In most states,
the reproductive rights of poor women have been so severely
curtailed, Roe vs. Wade does not exist for them.
</P>
<P>
   And how about the political momentum that governors and other
high-ranking state officials can and do affect outside the
statehouse? Was the $50,000 in leftover campaign funds that Matt
Fong _ a mere state treasurer _ donated to the far right Family
Values Coalition an ineffectual trifle? You can buy some quality
radio time or print up a lot of photos of fetuses in formaldahyde
with $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   At an anti-abortion rally, how much is a ``pro-life'' governor's
appearance worth? What if the rally is during a national convention
where everyone vows to support only anti-abortion candidates and to
work to get Roe vs. Wade overturned?
</P>
<P>
   Pushed into a defensive corner by the Davis campaign, Lungren
and his wife, Bobbi, insist that their Roman Catholicism demands
they be anti-choice. This may be the most grotesque of all of
Lungren's bending and twisting.
</P>
<P>
   If your Catholicism won't allow you to support legal abortion,
it won't allow you to be the head cheerleader for state-sanctioned
executions. Them's the rules. Yet, in answer to this obvious
contradiction in his own Catholic credo, Lungren distinguishes
between killing fetuses and convicts.
</P>
<P>
   This past spring he said: ``If you don't understand the
difference between innocent life and non-innocent life, then you
have missed a fundamental proposition of not only the teachings of
the Catholic Church, but the fundamentals of American democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, Dan, but you're wrong about the Catholic Church. It
teaches redemption of the sinner along with protection of the
unborn. One of its most fundamental propositions is that all human
life is sacred, innocent or on death row.
</P>
<P>
   His desire to be governor makes Lungren want a lot of things
both ways. Too bad he can't have them.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
