<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEWARE OF LAST-MINUTE POLLS 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ If history is any guide, it'll happen before
Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   We're in the home stretch of the general election. All over
America, candidates for public office are sweating. They're
exhausted, stressed out, whipped up to a state of towering
paranoia.
</P>
<P>
   The ones who are ahead are wondering what horrible dirty trick
their opponents might pull to beat them in the campaign's closing
days. The ones who are behind are wondering what horrible dirty
trick they might be able to pull to salvage their candidacies.
Meanwhile, you and I probably will be sitting home, watching
television. For a number of us, the phone will ring. On the other
end of the line will be somebody who identifies himself or herself
as a pollster. Sorry to bother you, the pollster will say; just a
few questions, please.
</P>
<P>
   At this late date in the political season, any pollster who
calls probably will be conducting what politicians call a ``push
poll.'' That's a proven technique for turning around an election at
the last minute. It works like this:
</P>
<P>
   The pollster will ask you which candidate you like in a
particular race. If you say ``Jones,'' the pollster will ask you if
you're for that candidate strongly or weakly. If you respond that
you're behind Jones in a big way, then the pollster will remind you
to get out to vote on Tuesday. You might even be asked if you need
a ride.
</P>
<P>
   If you say that you're for Jones, but only as the less loathsome
of two repelling choices, the pollster will ask you if your support
would be more vigorous if you knew that Jones loves both dogs and
cats, is kind to small children and old people, holds the
Congressional Medal of Honor and is a candidate for next year's
Nobel Peace Prize.
</P>
<P>
   In a push poll, things get really interesting if you say that
you're not for Jones but for his opponent, Smith. If you tell the
pollster that you're for Smith in a big way, and that nothing could
change your mind, then the pollster reminds you that election day
will be Dec. 3 and points out that plane fares are down now, so you
would be foolish not to take an immediate trip to see the Grand
Canyon.
</P>
<P>
   If you say that you're for Smith but that you'll have to hold
your nose when you vote for him, then the pollster will ask if
you're aware that Smith goes out of his way to kick cats and small
dogs, is routinely nasty to children and old people, hasn't paid a
bill on time in 17 years and wants to repeal all those silly laws
that criminalize sexual contact between adults and kids.
</P>
<P>
   If any of this happens this weekend, then you can figure that
Jones is paying for this poll. What the pollster is doing is
``pushing'' you toward a particular candidate.
</P>
<P>
   That strategy was employed with great effectiveness in suburban
Albany last year in a race for Rensselaer County executive. Neither
candidate was wildly popular with voters _ not incumbent Republican
Henry Zwack, and not county legislator Marilyn Douglas, his
Democratic challenger. Each had ``high negatives.'' Many of their
supporters were of the nose-holding variety.
</P>
<P>
   In races like that _ close contests in which an opponent's
support is only lukewarm _ politicians can employ a last-minute
push poll to turn around the election. That's what Zwack did, and
he managed to beat Douglas by a slim margin.
</P>
<P>
   So, if a pollster calls you this weekend, you should know that
the call probably isn't really about finding out what you think.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it's about pushing you to think the way a particular
candidate wants you to think before Tuesday rolls around.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
