<HEADER>
A5675 &Cx1f; kan-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAMMEUS-NORMAL-$ADV01     10-30 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAMMEUS-NORMAL-$ADV01-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVERY ONE OF US COMES FROM THE `IRREGULAR BIN' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL TAMMEUS  
 c. 1998 KANSAS CITY STAR 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Editor's note: Bill Tammeus recently addressed an annual dinner
sponsored by a Kansas City-area nonprofit agency that operates a
sheltered workshop and provides other services for mentally
retarded and developmentally disabled persons. His stepson is
employed at the workshop. This column is adapted from that talk.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In getting to know some of you in recent years and some of your
stories _ and really getting to know my stepson Chris, who is
employed at the sheltered workshop _ I have come to a new
understanding of what it means to be ``normal.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that the term normal has come to mean something
elitist, something, well, perfect. But it is impossible to be
surrounded by groups of developmentally disabled people without
gaining a visceral understanding that disability is a normal part
of life, even if we are at a loss to explain why that is. The human
species is, in fact, defined by the rule that perfection is
abnormal. None of us is perfect. We all have come from the
irregular bin. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This idea that aberration is part of the norm is easily seen if
we simply look at the collections of people we call families. If
normal means perfect or nearly so, are there any normal families?
Even one? Even in the White House? Of course not. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Once you get past the facade that most families erect to protect
themselves from embarrassment, you find all kinds of
out-of-the-ordinary conditions _ both horrifying and funny. Pain,
it turns out, is a normal part of life. There's no way to escape
it, though, of course, Americans spend a lot of time and money
trying. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So if we understand that all of us wrestle with something, we
can acknowledge that for a certain percentage of us that something
will be developmental disabilities. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The American Association on Mental Retardation says that 2.5 to
3 percent of the general population has mental retardation. Based
on the 1990 census, that would mean 6.2 million to 7.5 million
people. That level of occurrence, by the way, means mental
retardation is 12 times more common than cerebral palsy and 100
times more common than total blindness. But if we know those
figures, we also know it's normal for such people to be in our
midst. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The figures on disability seem remarkable to people who've never
given the subject much thought. For instance, the Census Bureau
reports that some 54 million Americans _ about one in five _ say
they have some kind of disability. Some 26 million of them _ about
one in 10 _ say they have a severe disability. And about 9 million
people over the age of 14 have disabilities so severe they require
personal assistance to carry out everyday activities. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   My point is that it's normal to expect a certain percentage of
developmentally disabled people within any general population. And
if that's true, maybe our smug definition of what's normal and what
isn't needs to expand to include such people. And our way of
treating them needs to acknowledge the fact that, in reality, they
are us. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That's because in every way that matters in an eternal
perspective, my stepson is as ``normal'' as I am. People with
disabilities are like those of us without such problems in that
something out of the ordinary has happened to them, too. What's
happened to them is what's happened to us _ life. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Does the world understand it's normal to expect people with
disabilities to be part of our society? No. The stark and
disagreeable truth is that many people think of agencies like yours
as genetic janitors. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And so we must pool our resources to educate everyone and to
meet the needs of the special people your agency assists. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If we don't help people grasp the notion that it's normal to
have people with disabilities in our society we risk creating
exactly what too often we've allowed to be created _ second-class
citizens. And that's a condition we simply cannot allow to become
normal. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Tammeus is a columnist for The Kansas City Star. This
article was distributed by The New York Times News Service. E-mail:
tammeus(at)kcstar.com.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (This column is for use Sunday, Nov. 1, and after.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
