<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPANESE-TOURISTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAN FRANCISCO SEEKS TO SHORE UP JAPANESE TOURISM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVID ARMSTRONG  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Long a favored destination for traditionally
free-spending Japanese tourists, San Francisco faces increasing
pressure to hold onto this lucrative trade.
</P>
<P>
   The rise of rival destinations like Las Vegas and the stagnant
Japanese economy, which makes travel more expensive for Japanese
consumers, are the main culprits.
</P>
<P>
   The drain of Japanese visitors is troubling for a city whose No.
1 revenue producer is tourism, at nearly $4 billion per year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Japanese are neck and neck with the Germans as our leading
overseas visitors,'' said David Bratton, research manager for the
San Francisco Convention and Visitors Bureau, which targets
Japanese tourists with a Japanese-language World Wide Web site, a
newsletter and special promotions.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, according to Bratton, 370,000 Japanese tourists
visited the city, spending a mean of 3.7 nights here. Japanese
tourists are particularly lucrative for hoteliers, as 90.6 percent
stayed in hotels in San Francisco _ a higher portion than any other
nationality except Italians, at 90.7 percent. At $160.24 per person
per day, Japanese also spent more money than other foreign tourists
_ way ahead of the runner-up French, who spent $130 per person per
day.
</P>
<P>
   No one is pushing the panic button, but Japanese tourism is
slipping, tourism officials and merchants say.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect that 1998 will see it off about 15 percent,'' said
Deborah Reinow, the vice president for tourism at the Convention
and Visitors Bureau. The weak Japanese yen and growing strength of
the promotions in Vegas are the reasons why, she said.
</P>
<P>
   In the past few years, huge casinos have attracted more tourists
to Las Vegas. About 16,000 hotel rooms will be added over the next
year in the Nevada city, where the average daily hotel room rate is
$73; in San Francisco, it's $140.
</P>
<P>
   ``Las Vegas is definitely in the picture,'' Reinow said.
``They've been grabbing market share. The Japanese are very
interested in big attractions. It doesn't cost anything to get in
the lobby, and there are pirate ships going everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Complicating matters is transportation. More airlines fly
between Japanese cities and Los Angeles than to San Francisco.
Moreover, small Asian carriers such as Malaysian Airways offer
cheaper round-trip flights to Los Angeles International than major
carriers do to the San Francisco airport.
</P>
<P>
   That could change. All Nippon Airways is starting a daily direct
flight between Tokyo's Narita airport and San Francisco on Dec. 1.
</P>
<P>
   One big draw San Francisco still has is shopping, and prices on
many luxury goods are better than in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   At the Chanel Boutique on Maiden Lane, director Michael Moser
said the Japanese are still coming, albeit not quite as often.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in the same situation as any other luxury goods
retailer,'' Moser said. ``We have noticed a change. It's down.
Retailers are developing their local clientele.''
</P>
<P>
   The Convention and Visitors Bureau is taking steps to lure
Japanese visitors. In addition to the Web site and newsletter, the
city is being billed in Japan as the wine and food capital of the
United States, Reinow said.
</P>
<P>
   The bureau also is working to book San Francisco chefs on the
popular Japanese television show ``The Iron Chef.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Japanese really value their travel,'' Reinow said. ``It's
a big part of their lives.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
