<SLUG> BC-TEST-TEX </SLUG>
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDITORS:
</P>
<P>
   This is a test from the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-30-98 1317EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981030.0108 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-30 13:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5707 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-SLIPPING-HNS &LR;      10-30 0457
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-SLIPPING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPAN MAY BE SLIPPING OUT OF THE FIRST DIVISION 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BERNARD D. KAPLAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Two developments this week suggest that Japan, the
world's second largest economy since the 1970s, may be slipping
down the ladder.
</P>
<P>
   A report by the respected inter-governmental Organization for
Economic Cooperation and Development in Paris predicted that the
Japanese economy will shrink by more than 2.5 percent this year and
could go on falling in 1999 and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   Japan has been in a heavy slump for the past five years.
However, this is the first time it has been suggested that the
country's recession, largely brought on by property speculation and
a resultant banking collapse, is likely to have long-term
repercussions.
</P>
<P>
   Tokyo's woes were further underlined by a government
announcement that about half of the 80 Japanese banks with overseas
operations will be asked within the next few months to close their
foreign branches.
</P>
<P>
   The move forms part of a restructuring of the badly battered
banking system. Its huge losses _ the greatest in history _ have
come fully to light only within the last month. Under the
government's plan, viable financial institutions will be
strengthened while others will be allowed to go to the wall without
the kind of rescue with public money that Japanese officials have
usually ordered in the past.
</P>
<P>
   The sharp reduction in the number of branch banks in cities like
New York, London and Frankfurt will mark the end of an era. The
omnipresent, big-spending Japanese market dealers and business
executives with their retinue of assistants who symbolized Japan's
meteoric rise will be no more _ or at least their number will be
severely cut.
</P>
<P>
   This development has more than a picturesque side to it. The
Japanese were usually prepared to take bigger risks and invest
larger sums in western enterprises than were many of their rivals.
Often, the risks were ill-judged. Some of Japan's problems result
from the impetuosity of its investors and their lack of grasp of
western business practices. But they will be missed in many
deal-making quarters.
</P>
<P>
   If Japan does continue to slip, the United States will be the
foreign nation most concerned. Over the years, America has seen the
Japanese as rivals and, sometimes, a menace. Yet to a large extent,
U.S. economic policy has been built on the premise that Washington
and Tokyo were the two essential pillars of world trade. If all was
well with them, a stable economic future would be assured.
</P>
<P>
   Now, one of these pillars is cracking under the strain and no
one can be as confident as before about what the future holds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-30-98 1325EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
