<SLUG> BC-PINOCHET-ARREST-BAD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUNISHING PINOCHET MAY NOT BE THE ANSWER 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By FLORA LEWIS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    PARIS _ The instinctive reaction to word that Chile's Augusto
Pinochet has been arrested in London and faces extradition for
crimes against humanity is: Good, at least one bloody dictator can
be held to account.
 &HT;    But it isn't a simple issue, and the simple answer can have very
bad consequences.
 &HT;    It is no accident that the French government congratulated
itself on having foreseen possible embarrassment and refused
Pinochet a visa earlier this month. Nor is it surprising that
Spain's Prime Minister Jose-Maria Aznar commented that ``the best
outcome would be if the government doesn't even have to decide,'' a
reference to the fact that the Spanish judiciary still has to rule
on whether to advance the extradition request.
 &HT;    The implications involve all the jumble of issues provoked by
the collision of demands for pure justice and the demands of
politics, the demands of peace, the demands of reconciliation.
Further, the new emphasis on the international right to judge
certain crimes complicates the question of who is to judge whether
circumstance or unyielding moral dictates should prevail.
 &HT;    It has been pointed out that the peaceful, constructive
transition of Spain from a fascist dictatorship to a sturdy
democracy was achieved, despite ominous predictions of another
civil war, by refusing to judge the past. South Africa found relief
from intolerable prospects of confrontation and revenge in its
Truth and Reconciliation Commission. Archbishop Desmond Tutu, who
led it, will have some profound guidelines to offer from the moral
insights the experience has provided.
 &HT;    Many countries, El Salvador, Guatemala, Argentina, ex-communist
countries of eastern Europe as well as Chile, have sought to
transcend ferocious or deeply wounding civil strife by trying to
tell the truth instead of by insisting on punishment. Is their
choice to be overruled on the grounds that crimes committed were
crimes against humanity, not just their own nation?
 &HT;    The Spanish judge, Baltasar Garzon, who asked to question
Pinochet as a step toward extradition had been working on testimony
collected by victims for several years. He is a man of rigor, who
pushed corruption cases and the tracks of the ``dirty war'' by
police against Basque terrorists during the previous Socialist
government, to its great discomfiture.
 &HT;    His document calling for Pinochet's arrest and listing 91 people
kidnapped, tortured or killed also lists a long series of
international declarations and agreements which Britain has signed
prescribing genocide, war crimes, torture. There may be some
question about the jurisdiction of a Spanish court (or of a British
court since it has been suggested Britain could hold the trial
instead of granting extradition.)
 &HT;    But there is no question about the straightforward legal
sincerity of Garon or that crimes were committed.
 &HT;    There has been a tendency of late, particularly in connection
with the atrocities in former Yugoslavia, to proclaim the
inevitability of eventual punishment as a kind of consolation for
not being able to stop the terror and not being able to catch the
perpetrators. The Pinochet arrest gives the satisfaction of being
able to feel that some day they will get their due.
 &HT;    The new treaty on establishing a permanent international
tribunal, which the United States has refused to sign, has been
hailed as a signal advance that will deter future criminal
monsters. This is fantasy. If anything, an advance, locked-in
provision for punishment makes it harder to end a conflict short of
total victory. It leaves no room for negotiation or compromise, one
of the reasons I don't think it's a good treaty.
 &HT;    Of course, a possible answer is that there never should be
compromise with evil. Justice must be complete, there must be no
escaping the highest law.
 &HT;    That leaves the underlying question of what we really hope to
achieve and what standards are to be applied. Even today in Chile,
there are people who consider Pinochet a savior rather than a
murderer. He was able to make his deal for lifetime immunity there
because he still had considerable support when he turned power over
to a freely elected president.
 &HT;    It isn't just a matter of who is to decide. It is whether the
desired outcome should be punishment, revenge, blind justice
regardless of its consequences or removal of civil conflict, a
better chance of peaceful life. When, as was the case at Nuremberg
after World War II, it is possible to achieve all at once, so much
the better.
 &HT;    But the best in moral terms must not destroy the chances of
improving how people live.
 &HT;     (Flora Lewis is the former foreign-affairs columnist for The
New York Times.) 
 &HT;     c.1998 Flora Lewis 
