<DOCNO> NYT19981030.0129 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-30 13:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5785 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VENICE-IN-VEGAS-NYTSF     10-30 1629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENICE-IN-VEGAS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENICE COMES TO LAS VEGAS (WHY NOT?) 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By RICHARD KADREY  
 FROM: Wired  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 World rights excluding Japan  
 NOTE: Full-length article (2,300 words) available on request  
 &HT;    Hollywood and Las Vegas have a lot in common. Both towns _ twin
oases in different deserts _ feed greedily on our collective dreams
and desires.
 &HT;    The strongest connection between the two places is that neither
really cares much about history, but both are loaded with
mythology.
 &HT;    The biggest difference between them is that in LA, when the
movies are done shooting, the sets come down. The sets where Las
Vegas dreams _ the casinos and theme hotels _ have to last for
years and years.
 &HT;    Now the biggest long-duration set of them all is under
construction on 63 acres of prime real estate in the middle of the
Las Vegas Strip. In one gigantic engineering feat, this ``set of
the century'' will culminate in a hotel-casino complex called The
Venetian. Among other things, it conjures D. W. Griffith building a
massive Babylonian temple in Hollywood for his film
``Intolerance.''
 &HT;    This Renaissance Venice is on the exact site of the old Sands
Hotel, where Dino, Frank, Sammy and the other Rat Pack boys whooped
it up at least a thousand years ago.
 &HT;    The price tag for this bit of old-world charm is about $2.5
billion and, as its promoters never tire of saying, when it's
finished it will be the biggest resort of its kind in the world.
 &HT;    The Venetian will, of course, sport canals. More than a quarter
mile of them, including 650 feet of outdoor waterways that will run
parallel to the Strip. The canals won't go through the casino, but
will slide gracefully through the 800,000-square-foot enclosed
shopping complex _ built to mirror Piazza San Marco and,
conveniently, house 150 upscale shops and restaurants.
 &HT;    Phase I of The Venetian _ the area with a replica of Saint
Mark's Square at its center _ broke ground on April 14, 1997, and
is expected to open in the spring of 1999. Phase II, The Lido, a
``beach resort'' containing a marina, then begins construction.
When both phases have been completed, their hotels alone will
contain more than 6,000 rooms.
 &HT;    The Mirage and Treasure Island hotels across the street already
look less like big-time resorts and more like Disneyland rides.
 &HT;    When Bovis, principal construction manager for The Venetian,
poured the foundation of Phase I, it was the largest continuous
concrete pour in U.S. history. To be precise, Bovis used 300
workers and 125 trucks to pour 20,600 cubic yards of concrete in 30
hours, creating a 68,000-square-foot foundation slab 8 feet deep.
 &HT;    According to Kurt Ouchida, publicist for The Venetian, Bovis
could have poured more concrete that day, but it would have meant
shutting down all construction in LA for a weekend.
 &HT;    The Vegas Venice will offer the greatest hits: the Doges'
Palace, the Campanile tower, the Rialto Bridge and Bridge of Sighs,
the Contarini Palace and Saint Mark's Square, sited like a
Renaissance rummage sale.
 &HT;    But then Vegas has pretty much always epitomized a certain kind
of hospitality, the malleable kind. The fantasies here are generic,
populist, with the promise of extravagance. This is the home of the
water feature, the deluxe discount, the Ideal Guest Experience, in
addition to being the home of the evanescent lucky streak.
 &HT;    Even the dusty, pre-theme-hotel Vegas (talk about ancient
history) had it, this quality and enticement of the extraordinary.
The saloons and bordellos were like something out of a John Ford
western: functional and minimal and alluring.
 &HT;    What could be more dreamlike, right here, right now, than
bringing Venice, a city of water, to the middle of the American
desert?
 &HT;    When The Venetian is finished, besides the surreal ribbon of
canals and the humming craft (gondoliers plying poles for show
while serenading their customers), the first thing you'll see is
the looming Campanile tower _ 315 feet tall. You'll also espy the
Doges' Palace, serving as a grand entrance to the
116,000-square-foot casino. The tower will lead to the Palace via
the Rialto Bridge. The bridge will feature a people mover on which
tourists will glide into the Saint Mark's shopping area.
 &HT;    A company called Treadway is in charge of the multitude of
planned statuary and ornately carved cornices and moldings and
friezes. Venice is a city that is lousy with marble, but The
Venetian will not be, except for floors in places like the Doges'
Palace. (In a city of illusions, the Vegas crew scored big here:
They're getting their stone from the quarry that supplied it for
the original palace.)
 &HT;    Most of the ``marble'' will be made of polyurethane foams,
expanded polystyrene, and sign foam (aka polyiso foam) _ the same
materials used to carve large structures on many movie sets _ then
hand-painted with marble texturing. Some of the sculptures will be
made from glass-fiber-reinforced concrete. It's a strong material,
and Treadway has developed a formula that looks remarkably like
marble.
 &HT;    Despite all the synthetic materials and techniques (including a
computer-driven cutter that roughs out giant foam sculpture blocks
for Treadway's artists), much of the fabrication is like that of a
Renaissance workshop, and concrete pieces are cast using a process
similar to the one artists have used for hundreds of years.
 &HT;    So can we expect Elvis in wrap-around shades and Cesare Borgia's
cardinal's robes, waving to us from the Doges' Palace?
 &HT;    Well, wasn't Venice the Vegas of its day, full of overblown and
sexy distractions, warring families, political and power factions?
Is the Venice of the Renaissance really all that different from the
Vegas of Bugsy Siegel, $2 shrimp cocktails and nude ice-skating
spectaculars?
 &HT;    Consider the famous Campanile tower: While it's a lovely thing,
and the subject of high praise by many critics, including John
Ruskin in his exalted book `The Stones of Venice,'' the one now
standing in Venice isn't even the real tower. The original one
collapsed in 1902, and a new tower was built in 1912. A
reproduction.
 &HT;    Consider also Saint Mark in the Vegas pantheon. He's the patron
saint of the actual city. He rates a major square and a cathedral
in his name. But Mark isn't Venice's first patron saint. That was
Theodore, a warrior saint, and defender of the Venetian city-state.
But Saint Mark had a better spin than Theodore, and in the year
828, when a couple of plucky merchants smuggled Mark's remains from
Alexandria back to Venice, Saint Theodore was out of luck.
 &HT;    It's not hard to see Theodore as the spiritual version of Bugsy
Siegel in this little tale. Both were early supporters and
protectors of their cities, both were warriors and both, after
their deaths, were swept under the carpet of convenient history.
Saint Theodore fared a little better. His statue, standing atop a
crocodile, is situated across from Mark's winged lion on the Piazza
San Marco.
 &HT;    There are no memorials to Bugsy, the man who pretty much
invented the idea of the big hotels on the Strip. In fact, when it
came time to expand the Flamingo in 1993 _ the hotel Bugsy helped
finance and build _ the new owners bulldozed Bugsy's special
bulletproof bungalow-office and tossed the remains out with the
trash.
 &HT;    What's especially striking about The Venetian, in the context of
Vegas' current building boom (according to the Las Vegas Sun, as of
July 1997, there were 15,000 new hotel rooms under construction),
is that it's the best and brightest example of the city's latest
romance _ with the past.
 &HT;    For sure, if Venice isn't to your taste, you can try another
city-themed complex, Bellagio _ or Paris (Paris) or Burma (the
Mandalay Bay) _ built to re-create its past glory. But it should go
without saying that none of the new resorts is about re-creating
the past, The Venetian least of all.
 &HT;    These hotels, really vast self-contained entertainment
arcologies, are Big Gulp Super-Size Monuments that are _ surprise!
_ really about Vegas itself, and the Swell Future to Come.
Capitalism triumphant. Boundless optimism. Sex and youth and
vitality forever and getting rich quick. As long as there's sun and
land to expand into, we'll never die, never even grow old, never
end up like Europe, with its sad weight of history, collision of
languages and soon, some weird common currency that's less
convincing as money than the Jimi Hendrix chips at the Hard Rock
Casino.
 &HT;    Leave it to a Frenchman, though (Jean Baudrillard, the
postmodernist poster boy), to observe that there ``is something
stronger than sex or happiness: the passion for illusion.'' Maybe
he was passing through Vegas. It's all here, in Vegas as in
Hollywood, and in the empty spaces in between, and on the grounds
of The Venetian _ still waiting for its Renaissance sculptures
carved from expanded polystyrene and sign foam. Collapsible time,
where the past, present, and future merge into an endless,
revisable dream.
 &HT;     (c.1998 Conde Nast Publications Inc.) 
<TEXT>
