<SLUG> BC-WORKING-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BABY BOOMERS HAVING MAJOR IMPACT ON RETIREMENT PLANNING, FUNDS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By L.M. SIXEL 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Baby boomers spawned the Summer of Love in San Francisco, gave
birth to the Me Generation in the 1970s and turned America into a
land of Yuppies during the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Their impact has been just as powerful at work. They've lobbied
for help to tend to their aging parents, pushed companies for
on-site child care and no longer work long enough for one employer
to collect a gold watch when they retire.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as boomers get older they're going to affect employers in
another key way: in the pocketbook. Older workers use more health
care and their retirement plans are more expensive to fund.
</P>
<P>
   It's a huge group. For the next 15 years, every day another
11,000 boomers will turn 50, said Bill Partridge, retirement
practice leader in the Houston office of Watson Wyatt, an employee
benefits consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the average length of employment with one company has
increased from 12.3 years in the early 1990s to 13 years, said
Partridge.
</P>
<P>
   That's a double whammy because so many employee benefit programs
are tied to age and length of employment, he said. For example,
most companies dole out vacation time based on the years an
employee has been with the company and base pay typically increases
the longer someone stays with a company.
</P>
<P>
   Companies are just beginning to look at their own demographics
and are discovering they have to make some plans to ensure they can
afford the financial crunch _ and the potential loss of workers,
Partridge said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Challenge is to keep boomers &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The boomer population is so big that companies may need to
rethink whether they should continue to offer sweeteners to
encourage employees to retire early, Partridge said.
</P>
<P>
   Once those boomers are gone there won't be enough Generation
Xers, the workers who range in age from about 23 to 34, to fill the
jobs, he said. It will be a challenge to companies to keep boomers
in the work force in new roles, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Retirement plans are another big concern of employers, Partridge
said. While most people wouldn't think that an older population
would affect 401(k) plans, older workers are more likely to
participate in their company's 401(k) plan and at a higher level.
</P>
<P>
   Most companies offer a 50 percent match up to the first 6
percent an employee contributes, so if an older employee boosts his
contribution from 4 percent to 6 percent, that costs a company
money, Partridge said.
</P>
<P>
   Traditional pension plans also become more costly when employees
are older. The cost of funding a pension for an employee who is 25
years old is relatively insignificant because the pension won't be
paid out for so many years, Partridge said. It's quite expensive,
on the other hand, if an employee is 55 because retirement is so
much closer.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid those big costs down the road, some employees are
coming up with alternatives to traditional pension plans, Partridge
said. Cash balance plans, for example, give employees a percentage
of their salary each year that they can take with them when they
leave the company or retire.
</P>
<P>
   Cash balance plans introduced &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Memorial Herman Healthcare System replaced its traditional
pension plan with a cash balance plan this year that uses a point
system based on age and years of service to determine how much the
hospital contributes each year to each employee's account. The
amounts range from a low of 2.5 percent to 7 percent, plus
employees also earn interest equal to 1 percent more than the U.S.
Treasury Bill rate.
</P>
<P>
   The plan was designed to reward employees for their length of
service, said Gene Ross, vice president of human resources. And the
plan was also designed to make it easier for employees to
understand what they'll receive at retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Employees were given a starting balance that equaled the money
they had in the system's traditional pension plan, Ross said. One
of the downsides of the plan is that it doesn't reward older
workers as much as the traditional pension plan did. So the
hospital put in extra credits for older workers to create
equalization.
</P>
<P>
   Bank One Corp. also has its eye on the future, replacing its
traditional pension plan with a cash balance plan this year.
However, it doesn't have the worries that many other employers
have.
</P>
<P>
   John A. Russell, spokesman for Bank One in Columbus, Ohio,
estimates that 50 percent of its work force is younger than 27.
Those folks are very interested in vacation benefits, support for
children and health care, Russell said. ``They couldn't care less
about retirement.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Send e-mail to lm.sixel at chron.com &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
