<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VAMPIRE-FILM-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHN CARPENTER OFFERS ONE OF THE BEST VAMPIRE FILMS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BRUCE WESTBROOK 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The teen-slasher rehashes that sparked today's horror
renaissance have already gone stale. We know what they did last
summer. So, what new blood can be summoned for fall?
</P>
<P>
   ``John Carpenter's Vampires'' has the answer.
</P>
<P>
   Not that we expect greatness again from the creator of
``Halloween.'' Carpenter hasn't made a good movie since 1988's
``They Live.'' But just when we thought his creative well had run
dry, he delivers one of the best vampire films of the modern era.
</P>
<P>
   Inspired by ``The Wild Bunch,'' ``From Dusk Till Dawn'' and
actor Sam Raimi's armed-for-bear horror heroes, Carpenter has
concocted an audacious, brashly energized action flick about a band
of fearless vampire killers led by James Woods. As such an intense,
overbearing actor, Woods is ideal as the indomitable Jack Crow, a
cool cat in dark duds who works with ruthless efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   Backed by a shadowy arm of the Catholic Church, he and his men
roam remote New Mexico like western bounty hunters, seeking
vampires who nest by day in shuttered shacks. They wield firearms
to slow down the bloodsuckers until Crow, with his chrome crossbow,
can snag and drag them into the incinerating sunlight.
</P>
<P>
   Crow explains such rules in a delightful tirade to a naive
priest (former Houstonian Tim Guinee), laying to rest quaint
notions that vampires are tuxedo-wearing seducers who fear garlic
and crosses. No, the vampires of John Steakley's novel on which
this film is based aren't so delicate. They're the vile vermin of
Bram Stoker's ``Dracula'' and Stephen King's ``Salem's Lot.''
</P>
<P>
   As such, they're also one-dimensional compared to Anne Rice's
anguished characters. But they're also strong villains who are
tough to kill _ especially a ``master vampire'' (Thomas Ian
Griffith) who wipes out everyone but Crow and his lieutenant
(Daniel Baldwin).
</P>
<P>
   Desperate, they take in tow a prostitute (Sheryl Lee) who's been
bitten and has a psychic link to their prey. Thus begins a cat and
mouse game that erupts in over-the-top gore, giving this what's
known in the trade as a ``hard R'' rating.
</P>
<P>
   Yet gore is no exploitative crutch. ``Vampires'' is skillfully
crafted, from its gorgeous cinematography to its vibrant rock score
(composed by Carpenter and performed by him and his Texas Toad
Lickers) to its fervent performances.
</P>
<P>
   The only trouble is that Woods is so powerful that his enemies
seem mundane. Griffith looks like Howard Stern crossed with Marilyn
Manson, and he has little chance to bare more than fangs, much less
a heart of darkness.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the action is grandly galvanized; Crow and Carpenter
don't mess around. But it's fantasy violence, not reality violence,
making it more outrageous than truly appalling.
</P>
<P>
   While likable and flamboyant, Woods has a fierce expediency that
may disturb some. Lee is slapped around, and Guinee's priest is
tortured to reveal a secret. But Woods' Crow doesn't relish
brutality toward innocents. He simply doesn't have time to
negotiate or cajole, and he figures his end _ ridding Earth of
hellish scum _ justifies his means. Besides, he shows a human side,
slinging sarcastic zingers at his thin-skinned cohorts and bonding
closely with Baldwin.
</P>
<P>
   These men may be violent, but they're the good guys, laying
their lives on the front lines of a secret war against evil. It's a
mean, dirty job, but someone's got to do it, and by championing
their cause, Carpenter and Woods have done a genre proud. &QL; 
 &QL; 
``John Carpenter's Vampires'' &QL; 
Starring: James Woods, Daniel Baldwin and Sheryl Lee &QL; 
Rating: R &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
