<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-HELPLINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIRUSES ARE ONLY CARRIED BY CERTAIN TYPES OF FILES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I've been using a virus checker faithfully since I got my
first computer a year ago. I run it every week and check for
viruses on my hard drive, and I scan every program I put on my
computer. So far, so good, no viruses. But these checks take a long
time. I have my virus checker set to scan all files, because a
friend told me viruses can hide in any file on your hard drive. But
someone else said they can only be in certain files, though she
wasn't sure which ones. What's the truth?
</P>
<P>
   A. Your second friend is right. Viruses can reside only in
certain kinds of files, so there is no need to scan every single
thing on your computer.
</P>
<P>
   Most viruses either hide in, or attach themselves to, what are
known as executables. These are program files that actually launch
and run. For example, when you double-click on an icon in Windows,
that usually fires up one of these kinds of files. Executable files
have an extension of .EXE or .COM.
</P>
<P>
   However, viruses also can be hidden away in .DLL files. That
stands for Dynamic Link Library, and they essentially are
components another program calls on when needed. For example, if a
program needs a ``Save As ... '' dialog box, it can be stored
inside a .DLL file.
</P>
<P>
   Viruses also can be found in Microsoft Word and Excel documents.
These are called macro viruses, because they take advantage of
those programs' ability to run automated routines called macros.
Word 97 and Excel 97 have built-in safeguards against macro
viruses, but Word and Excel 95 are fairly vulnerable. This is why,
in general, you should be careful about reading any Word or Excel
documents sent to you, and why it's better to send plain-text
attachments instead of Word documents over the Net.
</P>
<P>
   Viruses also can hide in the boot sectors of your hard and
floppy disks. These are areas on the disks that contain information
about the operating system and how the computer should start up.
</P>
<P>
   Most virus checkers have a setting that only checks the boot
record, memory and program files, and that's a fairly safe way to
go. More modern antivirus programs also can look inside ZIP archive
files and scan macro viruses, too. But it's usually unnecessary to
scan every file on your hard drive.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I've noticed in your reviews, as well as in some of the
computer magazines, that the sub-$1,000 computers often are
criticized for not having enough free slots for add-on cards. But
many of them come with everything you'd need. Why is this such a
big deal?
</P>
<P>
   A. Because even with the sub-$,1000 systems, you don't want to
limit your options.
</P>
<P>
   Most of these computers do indeed come ``loaded'' _ they are
excellent values. But what if your needs change over time?
</P>
<P>
   Let's imagine that you have a child who enjoys educational
software. But in two years, he wants to play games that require
higher 3-D power than you have in your machine. You can buy an
add-on 3-D card, such as a Voodoo2-based graphics board (by then it
will be Voodoo3!) _ but only if you have the spare slot.
</P>
<P>
   You may already have filled up your slots with an SCSI board, if
you decide you want a fast scanner. Or, if you've started a home
network, a slot may be taken up with a network interface card, or
NIC.
</P>
<P>
   So given that there are sub-$1,000 PCs that do have plenty of
open slots _ I'd say at least two free PCI slots and one free ISA _
then why limit yourself?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Got a question about your computer? Maybe Computing columnist
Dwight Silverman can help. Send e-mail to dwight.silverman at
chron.com &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
