<SLUG> BC-LIFE-FILM-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CREATOR MILKS PATHOS TO EXTREMES IN CHAPLINESQUE `LIFE IS
BEAUTIFUL' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JEFF MILLAR 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whether or not you end up liking ``Life Is Beautiful,'' you will
likely credit its star-director-co-writer, Roberto Benigni, with
audacity for keeping true to his premise: Charlie Chaplin sends his
Little Tramp character to a Nazi concentration camp and even there
finds laughter.
</P>
<P>
   Audacity may have to count a lot for you, for the film is
``Chaplinesque'' past the point of aggression. Although Guido, the
Italian-Jewish waiter Benigni plays, neither looks nor moves like
the Little Tramp, the ways Benigni works the character for humor
and poignancy _ pounds of pathos _ are hugely derivative of
Chaplin.
</P>
<P>
   Benigni would like us to think that not only is the film about
the late '30s, it was made in the late '30s.
</P>
<P>
   Consider these museum-reproduction jokes that are the film's
credit-sequence tone-setters: When Guido arrives in a small town in
Tuscany, the car he's driving loses its brakes. This results in his
bumping into a barn and Dora (Nicoletta Braschi), with whom he will
fall in love _ she literally falls from the hayloft into his lap.
Then, directing traffic, Guido's arm gestures are interpreted by
the local fascists as Mussolini salutes.
</P>
<P>
   Dora will turn her back on her aristocratic family to marry the
little Jewish waiter. They have a son. Giosue (Giorgio Cantarini)
is about 6 when, after escalating anti-Semitism, it happens: Guido
and Giosue are loaded on the cattle cars. Dora will demand to be
taken, too.
</P>
<P>
   The humor Benigni extracts from this situation is driven by
genuine pathos. The measure of Guido's love for his son is his
shielding the child from the horror into which he has been plunged.
</P>
<P>
   Since the boy is still young enough to believe his father
entirely, Guido is able to keep the boy believing that everyone in
the camp is there voluntarily, in competition to win a big army
tank.
</P>
<P>
   Guido's loving fabrications are fragile things. Each of
Begnini's repetitions will devalue our credulity for the next
repetition. And there are many.
</P>
<P>
   Chaplin's addiction to sentiment is wearing, and so is
Begnini's. The way he escalates it feels competitive, like a pole
vault. It almost feels as though he doesn't care if we react to it
with tears or cynicism. He's just blissed by thinking it up and
raising the bar. &QL; 
 &QL; 
``Life is Beautiful'' &QL; 
Starring: Roberto Begnini &QL; 
In Italian with English subtitles &QL; 
Rating: PG-13 (for Holocaust-related elements) &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-30-98 1414EST &QL; 
