<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOVE-FILM-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISJOINTED SCREENPLAY MAKES `DEVIL' OF A FILM 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JEFF MILLAR 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Each time you begin to think that ``Love Is the Devil'' may be a
bit on the excessive side, a small voice of reason asks you to
consider, again, the subject and the subtitle.
</P>
<P>
   Sir Francis Bacon (1909-1992) was the English painter of
grotesque canvases, often of human shapes distended by unspecified
agony.
</P>
<P>
   Writer-director John Maybury, who came to music videos from
painting, makes his feature debut with this. He subtitles it ``A
Study for a Portrait of Francis Bacon.''
</P>
<P>
   The borrowing of the term ``study'' from the lexicon of art,
bringing with it implications of experimentation, the unfinished,
the tentative, explains (and excuses) a lot.
</P>
<P>
   It excuses, for example, the filmmakers from fidelity to the
facts of its subject's life. It explains why we see Bacon eternally
in preparation but never in execution of his work (the absence of
any of Bacon's canvases from the film is attributable to a business
reality rather than an aesthetic decision: Either the production
could not afford to license them, or Bacon's estate would not
license them).
</P>
<P>
   But accepting this as a ``study'' can't conjoin the two
unsynchronous films that exist within the space defined by the
title: the film on the screen and the film coming from the
speakers.
</P>
<P>
   The one on the screen is engrossing. The one to which we listen
is labored, with the dialogue sometimes rather silly.
</P>
<P>
   The film concerns the seven or so years, beginning in 1963, when
Bacon (Derek Jacobi) lived with George Dyer (Daniel Craig).
</P>
<P>
   Sir Francis was in his cum laude years. As the narrative begins,
in 1971, Bacon was in Paris being proclaimed the greatest living
painter as his work was installed in the Grand Palais. Back in the
hotel room, Dyer was gobbling enough pills and drinking enough
alcohol to result in his death.
</P>
<P>
   They had met when Dyer fell through a skylight into Bacon's flat
attempting to burgle it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not much of a burglar,'' said Bacon. ``Take your
clothes off and come to bed, and you can have whatever you want.''
</P>
<P>
   By Maybury's account, Bacon was an extraordinarily unpleasant
man. Although early on he may have exhibited a bit of affection to
Dyer in private, Bacon was in public contemptuous and controlling
of his young lover, who modeled for Bacon and whose image dominated
Bacon's work during this period.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon called Dyer his ``odd job man'' in his presence and locked
him out of the house in the rain while he had sex with other men.
Bacon, who sought dissipation the way some acquire Beanie Babies,
introduced Dyer into the scariest of sadomasochistic practices.
</P>
<P>
   When he hesitantly tells Bacon that he loves him, Bacon asks
Dyer what bad television show he took that line from.
</P>
<P>
   Dyer's response: drugs and dissolution.
</P>
<P>
   Maybury and cinematographer John Mathieson take license to turn
the lens into Bacon's eye. The image is often distressed. A long
scene in the bar where Bacon traded speak-to-hurt chat with artists
and mavens was photographed through wine and whisky glasses.
Filters, which change the depth of field in different areas of the
image, go on the lenses.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobi and Craig are first-rate. The screenplay, though, is a
tangle, and the dialogue generally falls short of whatever
objective it has. Almost anything the characters are asked to say
sounds written.
</P>
<P>
   The film at this point may ask you to re-read the first and
third paragraphs of this review. But this exculpates the filmmakers
only so far. The reason artists make studies is to sort the bad
ideas from the good ones. A few too many of Maybury's bad ideas got
all the way to canvas. &QL; 
 &QL; 
``Love is the Devil'' &QL; 
Starring: Derek Jacobi and Daniel Craig &QL; 
Not rated &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL; 
 &UR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-30-98 1414EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
