<DOCNO> NYT19981030.0141 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-30 14:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5823 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LIMITS-FILM-REVIEW-HN     10-30 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIMITS-FILM-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WITHOUT LIMITS' WITH HUMAN SIDE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LOUIS B. PARKS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Without Limits'' wins as a sports film precisely because it's
not really about sports or a great victory.
</P>
<P>
   There are several beautifully filmed, exciting running scenes
that give an unusually strong sense of a heated track competition.
But ``Without Limits'' manages to be surprisingly involving by
focusing on the personality of cocky, charismatic, attractive
runner Steve Prefontaine, looking at what made him succeed and
sometimes fail spectacularly.
</P>
<P>
   Until eight days ago, Warner Bros. was saying ``Without Limits''
would not open in Houston due, apparently, to its disappointing
box-office showing in New York. A track film is no sure
blockbuster, even if Tom Cruise is the producer. (Cruise even
considered playing the lead role early on.)
</P>
<P>
   The movie, directed by Robert Towne, is fueled by two excellent
performances. Billy Crudup is wonderfully self-assured and
convincing as the sexy, daring track idol Prefontaine.
</P>
<P>
   And Donald Sutherland gives an appealing, richly textured
performance as Prefontaine's famous coach, Bill Bowerman, who
started Nike.
</P>
<P>
   There's also good work by Monica Potter as Mary Marckx,
Prefontaine's most significant of many girlfriends, in what could
have been simply a pretty-girl part.
</P>
<P>
   Prefontaine died in a car crash in 1975 at age 24, just as he
was entering the prime years of a middle-distance runner. If he did
not live long enough to dominate on the track, he certainly
dominated the imagination of thousands of track fans who made
``Pre'' their hero. His driving, no-holds-barred attitude on and
off track made him stand out even in a sport where individualism is
the norm.
</P>
<P>
   The film follows Pre from his recruitment by Bowerman to the
University of Oregon track team, through the ill-fated 1972 Munich
Olympics (marred by terrorism) to his sudden death. Towne's theme
(he also co-scripted with former Olympic runner and Prefontaine
friend Kenny Moore) is the fruitful conflict between the runner and
the coach, and their opposite approaches to competition and life.
</P>
<P>
   Bowerman says in the film that Prefontaine taught him that the
Olympic motto of ``higher, faster, stronger'' does not mean higher,
faster, stronger than anyone else in the race, as he, Bowerman,
interpreted it. Simply, higher, faster, stronger.
</P>
<P>
   Bowerman tried to teach Prefontaine to win through tactics such
as working with teammates or letting other runners wear themselves
out in the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Prefontaine contended that the only true way to win was by
direct frontal assault and by withstanding more pain than anyone
else.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to win unless I do my best, and the only way to
do that is to run flat out until I don't have anything left,''
Prefontaine insists in the film.
</P>
<P>
   When Prefontaine first bursts to attention in a track meet by
charging out front and leading a race all the way, fans in the
stands begin chanting his name as he circles the track, increasing
his lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are they saying the rube's name?'' groans Bowerman. ``They're
only encouraging the little showboater.''
</P>
<P>
   The core of the film is their conflict, which is always _ almost
always _ tempered by respect and growing affection.
</P>
<P>
   Towne, who is better known for writing (``Chinatown,'' ``The
Last Detail,'' ``Days of Thunder'') than directing (``Tequila
Sunrise,'' ``Personal Best'') keeps the film interesting with a
deft touch. He prevents this from becoming the cliche ``smart
coach-cocky jock'' of too many sports films. He focuses on the
human elements as the film races from running scenes to romance to
the coach relationship and back. The movie has a fast pace, plenty
of humor and never turns into a ``Rocky''-style ``big win'' movie.
</P>
<P>
   The film makes Prefontaine so interesting we wish it told what
made him the way he was, besides just hinting at childhood
persecution for being small and German.
</P>
<P>
   Crudup (``Everyone Says I Love You''), a handsome actor whose
lean face and body look right for a distance runner, perfectly
captures the self-assured brashness and charm of Prefontaine. He's
cocky, but impossible not to like.
</P>
<P>
   Still, wise old Sutherland cagily steals the movie. If the film
gets enough exposure, Sutherland should have the inside track for a
best supporting actor nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without Limits,'' which was originally titled ``Pre,'' is the
second film on the runner in two years. Last year's ``Prefontaine''
starred Jared Leto in the title role. &QL; 
 &QL; 
``Without Limits'' &QL; 
Starring: Billy Crudup, Donald Sutherland, Monica Potter &QL; 
Rated: PG-13 for brief sexual material and brief strong language. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
