A5835 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-COLU     10-30 0607
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAVE YOUR EYES CHECKED, TOO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: We have a 56K modem, and the audio/video
quality is blurry and muffled. I was told we need a T-1 cable to
improve the quality of the picture and sound.
</P>
<P>
   _ Fuzzy
</P>
<P>
   DEAR FUZZY: It might improve the quality of the picture, but
your quality of life would go in the dumper. T-1 lines are so
expensive, you'd have to eat cat food for Sunday dinner for the
rest of your days. And even if you mortgage the kids to get a T-1,
that's no guarantee you're going to get good video.
</P>
<P>
   There's lots of stuff conspiring to muddy up the picture.
Primarily, though, it takes a whole bunch o' bytes to make up even
a single video frame. It takes some real doing to cram it all
through the Net. Imagine sending a bowling ball through a garden
hose, and you get the idea. Crunch the ball into little bitty
pieces and it makes it through, but it still has to be reassembled
on the other end. Of course, lots of those pieces get lost along
the way.
</P>
<P>
   The faster the pieces get to the other end, the faster they can
be reassembled. Your 56K modem lets you download things around
53,000 bits per second (Kbps), assuming conditions are ideal, and
they never are. A T-1 does it at 1.544 million bits per second
(Mbps). ISDN digital lines can do it at 64 or 128 Kbps, those
little satellite dishes at 400 Kbps, and cable modems usually start
around 512 Kbps. The Ethernet network at your office runs at either
10 Mbps or 100 Mbps. Starting to feel like the small and
insignificant nonentity that you are?
</P>
<P>
   To get a semi-decent picture, many video-conferencing systems
have to use three dedicated 128 Kbps ISDN lines. Good luck with
your dinky little analog phone line and modem, especially when it
rains.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if there's heavy traffic on the Net or the sender's
using a crummy camera and a dime-store microphone, or the frame
rate is too fast for the conditions or any of about a hundred other
things, you'll still get a lousy picture. Is it worth spending all
that money just to watch some tired hooker on a live-sex video
feed? Whoops! Sorry, that's what I was watching.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: I'm prepping my old computer for use by my
mother. Where can I find a copy of every virus ever written?
</P>
<P>
   _ Diabolical Evilman
</P>
<P>
   DEAR LOSER: You, sir, are a pinhead. Go away.
</P>
<P>
   STUPID HARDWARE TRICK: Just to prove it's not just the Microsoft
guys who goof off, here's one that somebody at Hewlett Packard must
have thought validated making classical music his minor at good ol'
Dweeb U.
</P>
<P>
   Did you know your HP ScanJet 5Pse can play music? Turn it off,
then set the SCSI switch in back to 0. That's a zero for all you
old guys who need bifocals.
</P>
<P>
   Now press and hold the green Scan button in front as you turn
the power back on. Voila! It should be playing ``Ode to Joy'' by
varying the pitch of the scanner motor. Not exactly CD-quality
sound, but you still have to be impressed that somebody went to all
that trouble to include something that'll probably burn your motor
out if you don't stop playing with it.
</P>
<P>
   (Noted computerologist Dr. Emilio Bombay offers occasionally
accurate advice about most things electronic. He can be reached on
Internet at drbombay(at)star-telegram.com; via snail-mail at Fort
Worth Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth 76101; or fax: (817)
390-7257. His real name is Michael Gerst, editorial systems manager
for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
