<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-30 14:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5853 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ASTRONAUT-IN-LAW-TEX     10-30 1066
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASTRONAUT-IN-LAW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASTRONAUT IN-LAW CARRIES FAMILY'S PRIDE TO NEW HEIGHTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LAURA VOZZELLA 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. _ Just a few pictures graced the walls of
my grandparents' home. Wed in the darkest days of the Depression,
they took care of the few things they had, hiding their couch under
a slipcover and storing just about everything else in mothballs.
They weren't the kind to make nail holes in the wall willy-nilly.
</P>
<P>
   But right by the front door hung a framed photo of the astronaut
who married their granddaughter, my cousin Gail.
</P>
<P>
   An 8-by-10 glossy of Scott Parazynski, a sunny blond in a navy
blue NASA uniform, smiled at all who came and went from John and
Rose Vozzella's suburban Boston town house. Pictures of their three
sons and 14 grandchildren, meanwhile, crowded the coffee table and
dining room buffet.
</P>
<P>
   Those of us relegated to table-top status jokingly griped that
only Scott _ an in-law, for crying out loud _ rated high enough for
a nail in the plaster.
</P>
<P>
   A little jealousy aside, we can't deny there's something special
about having an astronaut in the family.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest thrill came Thursday, when Scott went up in space
with John Glenn and the rest of the space shuttle Discovery crew. I
was among about a hundred family members and friends who traveled
to Florida to watch the shuttle roar into space.
</P>
<P>
   This is Scott's third trip into outer space. But long before
Scott left the planet, we all knew he had the ``right stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Six years ago, family news bulletins about the guy then getting
serious with my cousin kept getting better and better. Gail was
dating a doctor out in Colorado, where she worked as a nurse. He
had studied at Stanford, undergrad and med school. He was handsome.
He was nice. And oh, by the way, they'll be moving to Houston
because he has been accepted into the astronaut program.
</P>
<P>
   Later we would learn a few more details that, for anyone else,
might merit top billing: He had competed on the U.S. luge team and
was among the top 10 Americans at the 1988 Olympic trials; he was a
scuba diver, mountain climber and amateur pilot; he spoke Greek.
</P>
<P>
   When Scott came to the Boston area to meet the family, he proved
to be a genuinely friendly, personable guy. He seemed as proud of
Gail's accomplishments _ she was then training for a marathon _ as
his own. He wasn't one to brag. He even volunteered a particularly
unglamorous space-program tidbit: Because of the long hours spent
on the launching pad before takeoff, astronauts have to wear
diapers.
</P>
<P>
   Scott's unassuming manner hardly put a damper on the family's
excitement. When Gail and Scott tied the knot in 1993, my aunt and
uncle threw a grand wedding reception with an ice sculpture shaped
like a space shuttle.
</P>
<P>
   His first space trip came in 1994. A number of family members
traveled to Florida for the shuttle launch, and those who didn't
tuned in on TV. Scott also invited one of his heroes, Jacques
Cousteau, and Cousteau made the trip.
</P>
<P>
   Scott's second mission was supposed to have been a long-duration
stay aboard the Russian space station Mir, but he had to withdraw
after five months of training in Russia. At 6-foot-2, Scott turned
out to be too tall to fit safely in a cramped Soyuz escape capsule
in the event of an emergency.
</P>
<P>
   To the rest of the world, that may have looked like a setback.
To my family _ a bunch of vertically challenged Italians _ it was
yet another accomplishment. No Vozzella will ever be too tall for
anything.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, Scott got his second chance to go up in space. He
helped deliver one astronaut to Mir and bring another back to
Earth. During the mission, Scott and a Russian cosmonaut conducted
a five-hour spacewalk while Atlantis was docked with Mir.
</P>
<P>
   This third trip is an even bigger thrill because of Glenn's
participation, and I wish my grandparents, who died within a month
of the second mission, could have lived to see it. I watched the
liftoff with my parents and two of their friends on the banks of
the Banana River inside the sprawling Kennedy Space Center, about
five miles from the shuttle.
</P>
<P>
   A day earlier, we had snatched up T-shirts, pins, caps and
refrigerator magnets with Scott's name or photo on them. At the
launch, we had four cameras among the five of us, and we snapped
eagerly as smoke billowed from the engines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go. Go. Go. Go,'' my father whispered. ``I hold my breath till
that thing is up.'' My mother covered her mouth and cried.
</P>
<P>
   As one of two doctors on the flight, Scott will be collecting
most of Glenn's blood samples for studies on aging and
weightlessness. The 77-year-old Glenn reportedly calls Scott his
``vampire.''
</P>
<P>
   The NASA Channel is already a well-worn button on family remote
controls. But all of the extra media attention showered on this
mission means we're also seeing Scott pop up on ``60 Minutes'' and
CNN, in magazines and newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is hard to believe that he (Glenn) is not reminded of his
old Project Mercury self more by this fresh-faced 36-year-old
doctor than by anyone else on the mission,'' The New York Times
Magazine gushed in June. ``The astronaut corps is a large pack to
break out of these days, but Parazynski's forthright talk about
hoping to go to Mars someday and of wanting to give `110 percent'
to the folks on the ground recalls a younger Glenn delighting
assembly-line workers on visits to contractors.''
</P>
<P>
   All of this could easily take its toll on the mere mortals in
the family. Over the phone, the bigwig banker who married Gail's
sister has taken to greeting my aunt and uncle with, ``This is your
nonastronaut son-in-law.''
</P>
<P>
   He's joking, I'm sure. Just like I joked about being left off my
grandparents' wall. Deep down, some of us may wish that we, too,
were doing something remarkable, if not flying through space. The
rest of us have normal jobs as teachers and lawyers and computer
nerds and reporters. No one but Scott seems destined for the
history books.
</P>
<P>
   But so what if the closest we're likely to come to greatness is
that nice astronaut on the other side of the dining room table at
Christmas? That's still close enough for a vicarious thrill.
</P>
<P>
   (Laura Vozzella is a reporter for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
