<HEADER>
A5854 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CATLETT-ART-PROFILE-$     10-30 1491
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CATLETT-ART-PROFILE-$ADV1-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CATLETT-ART-PROFILE$ADV1 
 
ARTIST URGES STUDENTS TO LEARN ALL THEY CAN ABOUT TECHNIQUES, ART
HISTORY 
 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, NOV. 1) 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
EDITORS: Photo of Elizabeth Catlett moving on the New York Times
photo service. By PATRICIA C. JOHNSON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Elizabeth Catlett carves wood and stone, models clay
and casts bronze. Her primary subject is the female body, whose
appearance may be stylized like an African mask or as voluptuous as
a classical nude.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on the individual sculpture and point of view, the
figure is the archetypal mother, Everywoman or an African queen.
</P>
<P>
   It dominates the retrospective of Catlett's work at the Blaffer
Gallery in Houston, where 60 sculptures created during five decades
testify to the artist's steadfast vision and mastery of hand.
</P>
<P>
   The figure may be tenderly realistic, as in a 1956 mother and
child modeled in clay, or provocatively abstract, as in the 1987
``Nude Torso'' carved from mahogany, or thoughtful, as in the 1993
``Seated Woman'' coaxed from a chunk of butterscotch-yellow onyx.
</P>
<P>
   But there is an underlying message of individual power in the
work, implicit in the strength of sculptural volumes and the
figure's stance. The political impulse is clarified in works dating
from the 1960s to the early 1970s. The shocking ``Target,'' a
bronze dated 1970, frames the stoic head of a black man behind
cross hairs. The 1968 ``Homage to My Young Black Sisters,''carved
from cedar, is an abstracted standing figure with its right arm
raised in a fisted salute.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have gradually reached the conclusion that art is important
only to the extent that it aids in the liberation of our people,''
Catlett said in 1971.
</P>
<P>
   Alice Elizabeth Catlett was born in 1915, the youngest of three
children, and always knew she wanted to be an artist. Her father,
who taught mathematics at Tuskegee Institute and in schools in
Washington, D.C., died before she was born. Her maternal
grandparents were about 18 years old when they were freed from
slavery, Catlett says. Her grandfather earned enough money to buy a
farm in North Carolina and send his eight children through college.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of a weeklong series of public events organized in
conjunction with her exhibition, Catlett took time out to talk
about her life and her art.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother was educated,'' Catlett said, ``but she didn't have
anything to do a job with. She washed floors and was a checker in a
nightclub until some friends got her a job as a truant officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was very supportive of us. My sister liked dance, so she
took dancing lessons. My father used to play the violin and carve
wood, and my mother felt I was taking after him. She used to buy me
stuff to work with and paid my tuition for my first quarter at
Howard University.''
</P>
<P>
   Catlett was on her own after that. She competed for
scholarships, sewed her own clothes, worked as a lifeguard and, for
a small fee, helped fellow students apply for grants.
</P>
<P>
   She was politically active, too. Catlett worked with Thurgood
Marshall, then an attorney with the National Association for the
Advancement of Colored People, in a campaign for equal pay for
black teachers in Durham, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   And she protested the showing of D.W. Griffith's ``Birth of a
Nation'' in New York. The landmark film was considered a great
advance in the art of picture-making, but it embraced black
stereotypes of the worst kind and portrayed the Ku Klux Klan as
heroes protecting white people from the inherent evil of blacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've fought against this image of the darky, the white-face,
all my life,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She graduated from Howard University with a bachelor's degree
and went on to study with painter Grant Wood, leader of the
American Regionalist school, and with the Russian cubist sculptor
Ossip Zadkine &UR;  &LR; at his Manhattan studio. She taught at Dillard
University in New Orleans and at her alma mater, where beloved
Houston painter John Biggers was among her students, and exhibited
in numerous shows.
</P>
<P>
   She is considered by many to be the greatest African-American
sculptor, yet she came of artistic age in Mexico, where she became
a citizen 36 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Her move to Mexico was prompted by two compelling factors.
First, leaving New York was a condition for the renewal of her 1945
Julius Rosenwald Foundation award. The mightier impetus was her
desire to visit a country that fascinated her and that she knew
only through research.
</P>
<P>
   Catlett had read about the Mexican muralists _ Diego Rivera,
Jose Clemente Orozco and David Alfaro Siqueiros among them _ while
preparing a mural commission of her own. She was also keenly
interested in the politically active print collective Taller de
Grafica Popular in Mexico City, which she had heard about from some
of its principal artists on their visits to New York.
</P>
<P>
   So Catlett and her husband, renowned painter Charles White,
moved to Mexico City. A year later, he returned to the United
States. But she had discovered something important, and she stayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was interested in art for people,'' the artist explains in
her husky and resonant voice.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, she had fallen in love with the handsome Francisco
Mora, an artist member of the collective.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pablo O'Higgins (an American artist and collective member)
introduced us,'' Catlett says. ``He suggested I teach Pancho (Mora)
English and he would teach me Spanish.''
</P>
<P>
   She laughs at the memory of a dinner in a restaurant where she
sat admiring Mora's ascot and raincoat _ he later confessed he had
no shirt _ and his arrival later at her apartment, serenading
guitar in hand. Fifty-two married years and three sons later, they
are as tender and affectionate as young lovers.
</P>
<P>
   Art in Mexico in the 1940s was about reaching the public. The
Taller de Grafica Popular had been founded in 1938 by idealistic
artists who, like the muralists, believed in the power of art to
educate and inspire. The collective produced broadsheets that sold
for pennies, so the poorest person could afford them, and
educational brochures on subjects such as how to plant corn, which
were distributed in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
   The ``black Northamerican,'' as friends and colleagues referred
to Catlett, responded strongly to the collaborative work and
camaraderie of the collective. And inspired by the idealistic
artists around her, who were committed to creating work for the
Mexican people, Catlett determined that she would do the same for
black people. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Her leftist associations had put her under the scrutiny of both
the U.S. and Mexican governments, and in 1958, she was arrested and
slated for deportation. After two days and nights in jail, while
Mora, O'Higgins and others sought ways to free her, Mexico's
secretary of education interceded and secured her release. Catlett
believes her name was on a list provided by the American Embassy
that also included the names of Americans who had run from Sen. Joe
McCarthy.
</P>
<P>
   Catlett had continued to study and teach. She enrolled in
classes at La Esmeralda, the government-supported art school in
downtown Mexico City, studied ceramics with renowned sculptor
Francisco Zuniga, and learned linocut technique at the collective.
She was included in international exhibitions of Mexican art from
Cuba to Czechoslovakia, and in 1959, became the first woman to head
the sculpture department of the National Autonomous University of
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   In 1962, Catlett became a Mexican citizen. It did nothing to
soothe her relationship with the State Department, which denied her
visas to visit the United States numerous times, but made sense in
light of her family life and artistic interests. Six years later,
when her sons were in high school and the university and Mexico
City was in the throes of the student rebellion that culminated
with the bloody ``Massacre at Tlatelolco,'' her Mexican passport
also meant that the government could not force her departure as it
did that of other resident aliens, including artists Leonora
Carrington and Lucas Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Catlett &UR;  &LR; divides her time between studios in New York
City and Cuernavaca, Mexico, and is a grande dame of sculpture on
both sides of the Rio Grande. Her energy doesn't appear to have
abated.
</P>
<P>
   At age 83, Catlett is not only active but also determined and
self-assured. Asked what she would advise younger artists today,
Catlett doesn't hesitate.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should learn as much as they can about techniques and as
many things as they can about art history,'' she says. ``To know
what is possible in art means you don't get stuck in little ruts.''
</P>
<P>
   Her retrospective at the Blaffer Gallery in Houston, which is
complemented by a smaller showing of Mora's paintings, is a
celebration of an artist's life. Both also have works on display at
Houston's new Gallery Thirty-nine 17. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-30-98 1427EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981030.0149 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-30 14:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5855 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOP-SOUTH-2TAKES-$ADV     10-30 0951
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-SOUTH-2TAKES-$ADV1-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP-SOUTH-2TAKES-$ADV1 
 
DEMOCRATS SEE A CHANCE TO STAND THEIR GROUND IN THE SOUTH 
 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, NOV. 1) 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Republican Party's Sherman-like march across the
South appears to have slowed, and Democrats who have been on the
run for much of the decade see a chance to stand their ground.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans now hold a majority of the U.S. House and Senate
seats _ and most of the governor's offices _ in the 11 states of
the old Confederacy, which means pickings are slim for the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   While the recent trend has firmly entrenched the two-party
system in the South, Republicans ``have topped out in the South,''
said Merle Black, an Emory University professor who specializes in
Southern politics.
</P>
<P>
   This year, only minor changes are forecast for Southern House
seats, and none are expected in the Senate. The outcome of a
handful of governor's races will provide clearer signals of whether
the South has been transformed from a Democratic stronghold to the
foundation of the GOP's national constituency.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty years ago, Democrats held virtually every seat in the
U.S. House and Senate and every governor's office in Dixie, the
southeastern states stretching from Texas to Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP began breaching the region's Democratic wall in the
1950s in presidential elections, then by winning statewide
elections in the early 1960s in Texas and Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the South, the Republicans began making big gains with the
electorate in the 1980s under Ronald Reagan,'' Black said. But it
was not until the 1994 midterm elections that the GOP would
dominate Southern politics, thus ending 125 years of Democratic
control of the South.
</P>
<P>
   ``That tide has run its course,'' said Olivia Morgan of the
Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee. ``Now the Republicans
are the incumbents, and for the first time in a long time, that
will work to our advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Each of the governors elected on Tuesday will have veto power
over the redrawing of legislative and congressional district
boundaries after the 2000 Census. That process will help determine
the partisan makeup of their state legislatures and their
delegations to the U.S. House.
</P>
<P>
   Redistricting in the early 1990s was overseen in the South by
seven Democratic governors and four Republicans, all working with
Democratic-controlled legislatures. This year, four governorships
are held by Democrats and seven by Republicans, and the task of
changing legislative and congressional district boundaries is still
three years away.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a state has a Republican governor during redistricting,
this gives Republicans a big advantage'' when districts are being
redrawn, even by Democratic state legislators, said Michael
Binford, a political science professor at Georgia State University.
</P>
<P>
   Of the seven Southern governorships up for election this year,
two have no incumbents on the ballot. The rest are held by
Republicans, and two of them _ Fob James of Alabama and David
Beasley of South Carolina _ are in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only two guys who are in trouble in the South are the ones
trying to govern on socially conservative, Christian issues,'' said
Black. ``They've gone too far to the right, and they've begun to
alienate part of their base'' _ Republicans and independents who
are conservative on economic issues but not social issues.
</P>
<P>
   Both James and Beasley have opposed efforts to create state-run
lotteries. Their Democratic challengers _ Lt. Gov. Don Siegelman in
Alabama and state Rep. Jim Hodges in South Carolina _ have pushed
the lottery as a way to raise money to improve public education,
much as Democratic Gov. Zell Miller did in neighboring Georgia to
finance college scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   James, who switched from the Democratic to Republican parties in
the early 1980s, won this year's GOP gubernatorial nomination after
a bitter and expensive primary against businessman Winton Blount.
The campaign ended with James' negative ratings at an all-time high
and many of Blount's top supporters moving to the Siegelman camp.
</P>
<P>
   A survey last week by Southern Opinion Research, an independent
polling firm hired by the Birmingham News, showed Siegelman ahead
of James, 60 percent to 35 percent. In early October, the same
polling firm found Alabama voters favoring Siegelman over James 52
percent to 39 percent.
</P>
<P>
   James has come from behind before, and observers are reluctant
to count him _ or his social conservative supporters _ out of the
running. In early summer, polls showed him in a dead heat with
Blount going into the June 30 GOP runoff. James won, 56-44.
</P>
<P>
   In South Carolina, arguably the most Republican state in the
South, Beasley alienated a large segment of his white GOP
supporters by proposing to remove the Confederate flag from atop
the state Capitol. His opposition to a state-run lottery has
alienated some Republican business leaders who see it as a way to
finance education improvements without increasing taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Gambling interests have poured money into Hodges' campaign, and
a poll in mid-September showed the two candidates in a dead heat.
This prompted Beasley to launch a series of television
advertisements attacking Hodges as a tool of the gambling industry.
More recent surveys show Beasley ahead of Hodges.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome of the South Carolina governor's race also could
determine who might be appointed to replace one of the state's two
U.S. senators _ Republican Strom Thurmond, 95, and Democrat Ernest
``Fritz'' Hollings, 76 _ should either of them vacate his office
before his term ends.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hodges has said he would appoint a caretaker senator who would
not seek re-election to a full term. Beasley has made no such
promise, but GOP activists predict he would pick popular former
Gov. Carroll Campbell, a Republican who currently is working as a
top-dollar lobbyists in South Carolina and Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Incumbent governors Mike Huckabee in Arkansas, George W. Bush in
Texas and Don Sundquist of Tennessee have moderate records and hold
double-digit leads over their Democratic challengers. In Florida's
race for governor, Bush's younger brother, Jeb Bush, has moved away
from his hard-right rhetoric of four years ago and is leading
Democratic Lt. Gov. Buddy MacKay.
</P>
<P>
   In Georgia, the last Southern state with no Republican governor
since Reconstruction, businessman Guy Millner has put up $11.6
million of his own money to finance his third statewide race.
Millner, a Republican who failed in two previous bids for statewide
office, has raised $3.3 million in contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Millner, founder of the temporary employment agency Norrell
Corp., was not the first choice of Georgia Republican leaders to
take on state Rep. Roy Barnes, the Democratic nominee. But the GOP
turned to Millner after the leading candidate, former state
Attorney General Mike Bowers, a Democratic turncoat, disclosed a
long-term adulterous affair.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes, who compiled a moderate voting record as a House member
and earlier as a state senator, is being painted as a liberal by
Millner, who is struggling to keep from appearing inept.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the campaign, Millner ran a television ad showing a
woman accusing Barnes of being soft on drunken drivers. The ad was
pulled after it was discovered the woman herself had been charged
with drunken driving.
</P>
<P>
   During a televised debate last week, Millner was unable to
respond to a question _ ``how many seats are in the state House of
Representatives'' _ until an aide scribbled the answer (180) on a
tablet and held it up just off camera.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, Southern Democrats held a 15-7 advantage
over Republicans in the U.S. Senate. Today, the number has
reversed.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the Democratic Party's only hope of recovering a
Senate seat in the South is in North Carolina, where first-term
Republican Sen. Lauch Faircloth faces a well-financed challenge
from attorney John Edwards.
</P>
<P>
   Republican hopes of picking up another seat from the South
seemed fairly good two months ago in South Carolina, where GOP Rep.
Bob Inglis was positioned to knock off Hollings, a 32-year
incumbent.
</P>
<P>
   But Hollings' narrow lead in the polls over the underfunded
Inglis campaign has held steady since Labor Day.
</P>
<P>
   A sign that the South has for now achieved partisan equilibrium
is the radical difference between the anticipated outcome of this
congressional election and the 1994 and 1996 elections.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, Republicans won control of the House after major
victories in the Midwest and West, but none as big as in the South
where Democrats yielded 16 seats to the GOP. Two years later,
Democrats recovered in other areas of the country, but those wins
were offset by the party's continuing loss of House seats in the
South.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Republicans occupy 72 House seats from southern states,
up from 47 prior to the 1994 elections. Democrats hold 53 seats,
down from 77 earlier this decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``You shouldn't expect to see gains this year like we had in
1994 simply because we swept them all then,'' said Todd Harris of
the National Republican Congressional Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans best chances of taking southern House seats from
Democrats are in North Carolina, where incumbent Rep. Mel Watt's
district was radically redrawn since his last election and where
Rep. Bill Hefner decided against seeking re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Watt's district, which was dominated by African-American voters
when he was elected in 1992, was redrawn by federal court order to
include counties with mostly white voters. The reconfigured
district now is one-third black and almost one-third Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Opposing Watt, who is black, is Scott Keadle, a dentist who is
making his first run for political office.
</P>
<P>
   In Hefner's district, former GOP state Rep. Robin Hayes, a
Cannon textile heir and unsuccessful gubernatorial nominee in 1996,
is heavily favored to take the seat. Little-known Mike Taylor, a
lawyer, is being outspent four-to-one by Hayes.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats have a long-shot chance at picking up an open seat in
Mississippi, where Republican Rep. Mike Parker is quitting.
</P>
<P>
   State Highway Commissioner Ronnie Shows, a socially conservative
Democrat, is making a populist pitch that nudged him into
contention with Republican tax attorney Delbert Hosemann, whose
campaign was battered and broke after the GOP primary.
</P>
<P>
   The best chance for Democrats to knock-off an incumbent is in
Louisiana, where Republican Rep. Richard Baker's nine-parish
district around Baton Rouge was redrawn since the last election in
a fashion that more than doubled the black population.
</P>
<P>
   The two-term Republican, who faces a campaign-fundraising
complaint before the Federal Election Commission, is being
challenged by Democrat Marjorie McKeithen, the daughter of
Republican Secretary of State Fox McKeithen and former Democratic
Gov. John McKeithen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our best candidates are not cookie-cutter Democrats, but
candidates who fit their districts,'' said Morgan of the Democratic
Congressional Campaign Committee. ``They're not letting the
Republicans lay claim to any issue, whether its prayer in schools
or fighting crime. We're staying competitive.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
