<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-30 14:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5858 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-ADS-BOS &LR;      10-30 0996
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-ADS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADS TARGET CLINTON IN BID TO SWING MOMENTUM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the last midterm congressional election, the
Republican Party ran on a ``Contract with America'' filled with
major issues and picked up 52 House seats. But as this year's
campaign careens toward a frenetic end, the GOP is betting that a
$10 million ad blitz highlighting President Clinton's sex scandal
will prove decisive.
</P>
<P>
   The difference in strategies has divided Republicans, who worry
they could lose control of Congress, and has delighted Democrats,
many of whom are convinced the ads reinforce the idea that the
GOP's top priority is to prolong an increasingly unpopular probe
into the president's sex life and his alleged lies about it.
</P>
<P>
   Republican strategists acknowledge that the party's slipping
fortunes in the past three weeks led to the decision to run the
ads.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things haven't been going well the last two or three weeks,''
said Republican pollster Linda DiVall. ``With the closing of the
congressional session, many conservatives were disenchanted.''
</P>
<P>
   The new ads are ``obviously risky,'' said DiVall, who helped the
party test them. But they could make a significant impact in a
couple of dozen key races, especially in rural Southern districts,
she said. Republican Party officials, meanwhile, said the ads are
being wrongly characterized by the press as a new national
strategy; the ads are running only in carefully tested markets
where they will be well-received, they said.
</P>
<P>
   But Democratic officials said the GOP ads have had the ironic
effect of underscoring that Democrats have this year's version of a
Contract with America. Democrats are relatively united in running
on the issues of saving the budget surplus for Social Security,
implementing health care reforms, reducing school class size, and
other matters. While the GOP ad also focuses on issues, it says the
major question in the campaign is whether to ``reward Bill
Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Democratic National Committee launched an ad Thursday
that seems to play into the notion this election will be a
referendum on whether Clinton should be impeached. ``Republicans,
so focused on attacking the President, they've forgotten about
us,'' the ad says. ``Next Tuesday, vote Democratic and tell
Congress we're ready to move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the professed Democratic glee about the GOP ads,
Democrats said that private polling shows most of the key races are
too close to call, with the next few days before Election Day being
crucial in determining which party will have power in Congress, and
therefore, whether Clinton will be impeached.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign endgame is focusing on a small number of volatile
races. Nearly all House incumbents are likely to be reelected, and
only a handful are in danger in the Senate. Political analysts said
there are 26 highly competitive House races out of 435, and fewer
than a dozen close Senate races out of 34. The most endangered
Democrats include Senators Carol Moseley-Braun of Illinois and
Barbara Boxer of California, while Republicans in trouble include
Senators Al D'Amato of New York and Lauch Faircloth of North
Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Nicholson, chairman of the Republican National Committee,
said in an interview that the ads are ``generic'' and are running
in 68 districts. ``These ads seem to be ones that will work in
those races,'' Nicholson said.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, a Nicholson aide said the ad asking whether voters
should ``reward Bill Clinton'' _ the toughest of three _ is running
in only three districts, in South Carolina, North Carolina, and
Georgia. In each, the Democratic candidate is an imcumbent.
</P>
<P>
   Republican concerns about the election were underscored with the
release of a poll by The Wall Street Journal and NBC-TV that showed
Democrats leading in the ``generic'' congressional vote by 43
percent to 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats said the ads will provoke a backlash during the
crucial last week of the campaign. ``This is a major strategic
blunder on the part of Republicans,'' presidential adviser Paul
Begala said. Indeed, Democrats noted that few Republican candidates
until now have tried to make an issue out of Clinton's affair with
Monica S. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   While the ads don't mention Lewinsky, they do raise the question
of whether Clinton should be rewarded for his misleading testimony
about the affair.
</P>
<P>
   ``In every election, there is a big question to think about,''
one ad says. ``This year, the question is, `Should we reward Bill
Clinton?'''
</P>
<P>
   Republican consultant Ron Kaufman said that the ads should not
be viewed as a national GOP strategy. Instead, he said, they
represent a ``tactical move'' in key races where the party needs to
motivate Republican voters. Kaufman said that while Democrats are
pleased about the possible backlash, the reality is the ads may
work in enough key districts and wind up swinging some races toward
Republican candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may be dumb but we're not stupid,'' Kaufman said. ``Money,
in the end, makes a difference.'' He noted that in the 1996
election, the Democrat infusion of money into Massachusetts races
played a major role in defeating House Republicans Peter Torkildsen
and Peter Blute.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans control the House by a 228-206 margin, and the
Senate by 55-45. Republican officials this week said they expect to
pick up no more than 15 seats in the House, while some independent
analysts said the GOP gain may be closer to seven. Congressional
Quarterly, a Washington magazine that analyzed every House race
this week, predicted Democrats would wind up with a two-seat gain,
and Republicans would still control Congress.
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate, Republicans had hoped to pick up five seats to
get the filibuster-proof majority of 60. But analysts at the Cook
Political Report said the GOP gain is more likely to be between one
and three seats.
</P>
</TEXT>
