<DOCNO> NYT19981030.0154 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-30 14:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5863 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-EFFECT-2NDTAK     10-30 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-EFFECT-2NDTAKE-$ADV1-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON-EFFECT-2NDTAKE-$ADV1 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  CINCINNATI: will move.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Also angry at the president is 67-year old Georgia Triplett, who
attended a debate in Ironton, Ohio, between incumbent Democratic
Rep. Ted Strictland and GOP challenger Nancy Hollister, who are
locked in a tight race.
</P>
<P>
   `` I was a teacher for 32 years and I find it difficult to say
the president is a good role model,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Triplett, who had already voted by absentee ballot, said that
she usually votes Republican and this year, she noted, ``I did not
even hesitate,'' to choose the GOP candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Cracchiola, a Democrat from Kentucky who voted for Clinton
in 1996, said he has been tempted not to vote this year because the
scandal had turned him off to politicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the point,'' he said. ``You vote for a guy. He does a
good job. Then you find out he's lying.''
</P>
<P>
   Responding to the last-minute GOP barrage, the Democrats have
fired back with their own ads warning that Republicans are so
focused on investigations they are ignoring issues such as
education and Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   ``Republicans _ so focused on attacking the president _ they've
forgotten about us. Next Tuesday, vote Democratic and tell Congress
we're ready to move on,'' the announcer says in the spot.
</P>
<P>
   That sentiment is shared by a number of voters.
</P>
<P>
   In Donaldson, Ga., Ashley Register, a semi-retired stockbroker
who has voted Republican in the last three elections said this year
the GOP emphasis on scandal has soured him on the party.
</P>
<P>
   ``All this is going to make me vote Democrat,'' he said. ``I
think the Republicans have run it into the ground. They are using
the scandal as vehicle to hurt Clinton and the Democrats, and it is
going to backfire.''
</P>
<P>
   In Clinton, N.C., Sharon Royal, the proprietor of Sharon's
Country Diner, took a break from fixing eggs and grits to talk
about the scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Royal said she initially believed the president should have been
impeached because of the lying. But then she changed her mind when
the media refused to let go of the story.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been covered so much that people just got tired of it.
Let him run the country like he's been doing,'' she said. Royal
said she will probably vote for Democrats this year.
</P>
<P>
   First lady Hillary Clinton, Vice President Al Gore and the Rev.
Jesse Jackson have been barnstorming the country trying to energize
key Democratic constituencies, including African-Americans who are
particularly angry about the investigation. However, the president,
who usually relishes campaigning, has traveled the country to raise
money for Democratic candidates but has avoided large rallies.
</P>
<P>
   African-American turnout could well determine the outcome of
North Carolina Senate race where GOP incumbent Lauch Faircloth is
locked in a tight race with Democratic lawyer John Edwards.
</P>
<P>
   Faircloth has tied Edwards to Clinton in numerous ads to
energize conservative voters. But at the Omega House restaurant in
Winston Salem two African-American women rushed up to embrace
Edwards, and later said they were even more determined to vote for
Democrats this year because of the scandal.
</P>
<P>
   One of the women, Cynthia Mack, a 40-year-old government worker
said the investigation into Clinton's behavior was ``political rape
and character assassination.''
</P>
<P>
   Her friend, Terry Spaugh, 44, said that she is not concerned
about Clinton's conduct, saying her husband would also have been be
tempted by Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``What man wouldn't want that,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite ebbing interest in the scandal, candidates still are
confronted with the issue at various events.
</P>
<P>
   At the debate between Strictland and Hollister, the sole
question about the impeachment came at the end of the 90-minute
forum.
</P>
<P>
   Hollister, who has called on Clinton to resign, said she was
``appalled'' at his behavior and defended the Republicans
open-ended probe of the president.
</P>
<P>
   While Strictland said he was keeping an open mind on how to vote
on impeachment, he also justified his vote for the Democratic
proposal to limit the scope and time of any inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not good for this thing to drag on for months and years
in the future,'' said Strictland. ``We need to bring this matter to
a conclusion and them move on to improve health care, improve
education and save Social Security, the matters that really count
for most citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   His answer drew sustained applause from the audience. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
