<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENE-LONGEVITY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`METHUSELAH' GENE THAT CONTROLS LONGEVITY   IS FOUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Scientists have discovered a longevity gene that protects
against environmental stress and extends life by more than
one-third _ at least among fruit flies.
</P>
<P>
   The gene, which they have dubbed ``methuselah'' after the
character in Genesis who supposedly lived 969 years, is another
piece in a fast-accumulating mosaic of evidence that longevity is
not an immutable fact of life but a trait that can be manipulated
genetically _ perhaps eventually in humans too.
</P>
<P>
   The existence of longevity genes has been demonstrated so far in
yeast, roundworms, and fruit flies. The new gene, reported Friday
by scientists from the California Institute of Technology in the
journal Science, is ``the first such gene that has been well
identified in drosophila,'' or fruit flies, said David Finkelstein,
a National Institute on Aging scientist.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a long step from drosophila to healthy 90-year-olds, but
this is all part of a field that is beginning to close in on the
aging process and think about ways to intervene in ways that are
practical and socially useful,'' added Daniel Perry, executive
director of the Alliance for Aging Research.
</P>
<P>
   Fruit flies are a favorite animal for genetic studies because
their normal 80-day lifespan enables scientists to observe the
effect of various genes over generations in a relatively short
period of time. It takes two years to observe lifelong genetic
effects in a single generation of mice.
</P>
<P>
   It's a good bet, scientists say, that longevity genes in
primitive species play a role in all organisms' metabolism and
response to stress. ``Now it's inescapable that aging is regulated
deliberately by genes,'' San Francisco geneticist Cynthia Kenyon
wrote in a Science commentary on the Caltech work. ``Since it
happens in both worms and fruit flies, you have to be crazy not to
think it won't happen in vertebrates.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier studies have demonstrated that fruit flies can be inbred
for longevity. Michael Rose and his colleagues at the University of
California at Irvine have bred flies with twice the normal lifespan
or more, and are on the trail of perhaps 100 genes they believe
contribute to long life.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most striking thing about the Caltech results is
that a single gene protected the insects against the wear and tear
of different kinds of stress _ starvation, high temperatures, and a
diet laced with the weedkiller paraquat.
</P>
<P>
   Normal flies fed paraquat became sluggish within 12 hours and by
48 hours nearly 90 percent were dead. But flies carrying the
``methuselah'' gene were still active 24 hours after eating the
toxin, and at 48 hours, more than half were still alive.
</P>
<P>
   Fruit flies bearing the ``methuselah'' mutants were 20 to 30
percent heavier than those with the normal version of the gene,
suggesting that it has something to do with regulation of
metabolism.
</P>
<P>
   The normal function of the unmutated gene is not known, but it
is obviously important. Fruit fly embryos that lack it entirely die
before hatching.
</P>
<P>
   The Caltech scientists found that the mutant gene is the
blueprint for a protein that sits on cells' surfaces and hooks onto
chemicals that are probably involved in the stress response. They
hypothesize that the gene is part of cells' defense system against
so-called free radicals _ highly reactive oxygen molecules that are
byproducts of normal metabolism.
</P>
<P>
   Free oxygen radicals can damage cells in various ways, so
scientists are focusing on mechanisms to soak them up or defend
cells against them with antioxidant chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   Raj Sohal of Southern Methodist University, an expert on such
oxidative stress, said the Caltech findings are potentially
important. But he stressed that researchers must demonstrate that
the increased longevity is not merely a result of slowing the fruit
flies' metabolism _ a well-known but not particularly illuminating
way to extend various species' life spans.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really hopeful and really interesting,'' added Rose.
``I expect to see many more mutants like these generated. We'll
have to sort through them to see which really stands the test.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
