A5875 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLENN-COMMENT-SFCHRON     10-30 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLENN-COMMENT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UP IN THE SKY! A RICH OLD GUY! 
</HEADLINE>
   By JON CARROLL  
 c.1998, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   I am bewildered by the amount of attention that John Glenn's
flight into space is getting. I am bewildered by the messages that
people are reading into the event. I am bewildered by the event
itself.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what happened, insofar as I understand it. Sen. Glenn,
never exactly a shrinking violet, decided it would be an amusing
capstone to his career to go into space one more time.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps you remember the characterization of Glenn in Tom
Wolfe's ``The Right Stuff'': a prissy sort of fellow who seemed to
sense that, someday in the far future, private detectives might be
sent to dig up dirt on his every youthful indiscretion _ a problem
he solved by having no youthful indiscretions.
</P>
<P>
   Not a bad guy, but just quivering with ambition. Every aspect of
his public life since then seems to match that impression. Good
moderate politician, works hard, a little too impressed with his
own virtue. That's OK _ there are worse things in the world.
</P>
<P>
   So Glenn gets that old counting-backward itch again. He has a
lot of juice, being a senator and all. He leans on NASA in
not-so-subtle ways. NASA finally caves.
</P>
<P>
   Why is this a triumph of anything other than the commonplace but
unlovely truth that there are different rules for the powerful? Is
this somehow a victory for senior citizens, that a powerful ancient
politician can be hurled into the ionosphere? Does it give new hope
to anyone besides other powerful old guys?
</P>
<P>
   It's like celebrating Mayor Willie Brown's ability to get a
table at Postrio without a reservation as a triumph for African
Americans everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   So NASA, which probably welcomes all the positive publicity but
resents the extra work, had to come up with post-facto reasons why
catapulting a senator into ovoid orbit has (set ital)scientific
significance.(end ital)
</P>
<P>
   Well, science is wonderful that way _ science can test anything.
Science can test the effects of aging on the ability to withstand
the rigors of zero gravity. Kind of a well-down-the-list
experiment, one would think, since the likelihood is that any trips
into space taken by 80-year-olds will be of the Timothy Leary
variety, one-way and postmortem.
</P>
<P>
   But still. They design some tests. Glenn goes down for a final
medical workup, and it turns out that he has some mysterious
ailment that disqualifies him from participating in one of the
principal tests.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with your regular astronauts, that might be an automatic
disqualification. But John Glenn is not really an astronaut; he's a
public relations device. He's a symbol of some damn thing. So
suddenly the scientific experiment is (set ital)not that
important.(end ital)
</P>
<P>
   (Were you bothered, by the way, by how everyone turned coy when
John Glenn's unfortunate condition was discussed? Here's a guy
whose blooming good health, whose fitness for this task, is yet
another symbol of the Best Is Yet to Come, and when a ``condition''
is uncovered _ many 77-year-olds have ``conditions''; the challenge
is to understand them and live with them _ all of a sudden it's a
big secret.
</P>
<P>
   (Disease is shameful, one more time. He's even selling out his
own symbolic value.)
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Glenn going into space will act as a symbolic Miata for a
million older Americans. Maybe it will be like Viagra without the
side effects. I dunno. I myself am over 50, and it sure doesn't do
anything for me.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly I think it's hype that has been, for curious reasons,
largely unexamined by the media. It's almost as though this were
some high-tech version of the Special Olympics, and the point is
just taking part and trying your best and, darn it, everyone gets a
medal.
</P>
<P>
   But it is a bunch of taxpayer money that could go to other
things, perhaps even to other NASA projects. It is turning science
into showbiz. I hope he makes it back safe and sound, but it seems
to me the rocket should have had a big banner streaming along
behind it reading: Was This Trip Necessary?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
