<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SAD WINDING DOWN OF AN UGLY CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Political struggles never end nicely. Feelings are too
strong, passions too raw, stakes too high for pretty endings.
</P>
<P>
   As we close out this governor's race, it's hard not to conclude
that it was less illuminative than it could have been and a lot
more negative than it had to be. The media bear part of the blame;
that has to be said as well.
</P>
<P>
   It was a sad event when Ray Flynn, the fading Boston Strongboy,
a working-class hero when he was mayor and a man down on his luck
now, showed up for a hollow
endorsement-that-was-not-technically-an-endorsement of Republican
Acting Governor Paul Cellucci.
</P>
<P>
   It took place in a barroom, the same tap where Jolly Olde Bill
Weld quaffed an ale with then-Mayor Flynn for benefit of cameras in
a previous election. But this time hundreds of angry building
trades workers marched outside, denouncing Flynn's apostasy.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, Ray nominated himself for the Gyppo Nolan role,
after the IRA traitor who betrayed the cause he'd spent a lifetime
serving. Ray is down on his luck, out of work, apparently needing
the palship or patronage of a conservative Republican running
desperately to defeat the AFL-CIO and labor's consensus choice,
Scott Harshbarger.
</P>
<P>
   So Ray swallowed hard and stood at the bar with Cellucci, both
men looking uncomfortable on TV, as the union pickets outside
picked their old champ from City Hall. ``This is the most
disappointing night I've ever had,'' said a grim-faced Bobby
Haynes, the formidable Ironworkers chieftain who heads a
rejuvenated state AFL-CIO.
</P>
<P>
   The chant from countless Bruins games rang through the
neighborhood: ``Na-na-na-na ... hey-hey-ay, gooooood-bye!'' So
long, Ray. Your buddies of the denim-and-dungaree brotherhood have
written you out of their club. It was sad to see. Ray did a lot for
working people, always fighting the kind of politics Cellucci
springs from.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci mumbled some neutral phrases about liking working-class
people. I'm sure he feels he's sincere. But the politics he
practices is opposed to too much of what the unions and the
non-union workers who benefit from union muscle need.
</P>
<P>
   Hours before the building trades' protest, Tom McIntyre of the
Bricklayers Union gulped his lunch in Amrhein's on Broadway in
South Boston. He'd gotten word Flynn was about to leap the fence
and was stunned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going out from here to get some signs painted, `Let's Make
a Deal, Hello Monty Hall,''' said McIntyre sadly. He'd always been
a Flynn guy; he'd been one of the handful who signed on to the
doomed Flynn-for-governor campaign last winter. And now Ray was
going out to stab the Democrats on election eve. And McIntyre and
his brickies, and the ironworkers, plumbers, carpenters, glaziers,
electricians, ``a little bit of everything'' under the building
trades' ample awning, would be picketing Flynn for the first time
in his and their life.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't belong there,'' said McIntyre later. ``Ray turned
his back on lots of people who put him in the mayor's office.
Loyalty is not a frivolous bit of business. He was never more in
error.'' Harshbarger is a handful back of Cellucci, in the Globe
poll a week out, but the Democrat's advisers say he's within a
point or two. Hillary Clinton cut a new TV spot for him and told a
Bay State Democrat, ``I'm doing everything I can for Scott.''
</P>
<P>
   Down at the level of street campaigning, the old bricklayer
voiced pride in his comrades. ``It's great to be in the company of
people that stand for something _ and these guys, they are not
unsophisticated people, they weren't there just because we asked
them to be there. They had a clear understanding of why they were
there. There's too much winking and blinking going on. This
election is about working people. And Harshbarger is our guy.'' As
he spoke, Harshbarger was running around with Mayors Mike Albano in
Springfield and Ray Mariano in Worcester, Attorney General Mike
Moore of Mississippi, the antitobacco champion, and pocketing
endorsements in Lawrence and Lowell.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci's chief of staff, Virginia Buckingham, had played the
ethnic card, accusing the attorney general of being
``anti-Italian'' and offering nothing convincing by way of
evidence. That clumsy bid to energize the Italo vote was a pathetic
coda to a campaign year in which more opportunities were lost than
seized. For a guy who is always complaining about negative
politics, Cellucci practices an awful lot of it.
</P>
<P>
   The most important corner turned in Massachusetts Tuesday may be
Question 2, the referendum on public campaign financing, up by 3-1
in polls. There are 6,000 volunteers behind this important reform
initiative, with $1 million behind it. This is our version of what
Maine and Vermont have already done. It's the voters' chance to
take the candy away from bloated politicians who gorge on campaign
cash like crack.
</P>
<P>
   State-by-state, up-from-the-bottom reform is the only way our
corrupt system of campaign funding will be brought to heel. If the
Yes on 2 forces win here with the state version of the national
effort US Representative John Tierney spearheaded in the House this
year, our politics will be a lot less susceptible to the election
time thumb-on-the-scale of special interests.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-30-98 1446EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
