<DOCNO> NYT19981030.0160 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-30 14:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5886 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-THING-BOS &LR;      10-30 0398
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-THING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANIC ABRASIVENESS THAT LACKS IMAGINATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE LAST BIG THING &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed and written by: Dan Zukovic &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Starring: Zukovic, Susan Heimbinder, Mark Ruffalo, Pamela
Dickerson, Andrew Falk, Sibel Ergener, James Lorinz &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 98 minutes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R (strong language) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Last Big Thing,'' a would-be millennial comedy, can't find
a way around its central problem _ rendering watchable a
transparent, self-important bore who tools around L.A., jeering at
scenesters. His self-proclaimed agenda consists of confronting and
verbally abusing wannabe actors, rockers, comedians, and models who
believe his line about interviewing them for a new mag he's putting
out called The Next Big Thing, but which, in fact, doesn't exist.
</P>
<P>
   Long before he starts ranting into his tape recorder about the
pathetic ego thirst of his subjects, the truth beneath his
overpitched diatribes and obsessive agenda becomes dispiritingly
obvious. Far from being genuinely outraged, or even offended, he
only wants a piece of the same action his subjects want to get in
on. But unlike most hypocrites and con men, this one is charmless
and tedious. Only the terminally insecure would hold still for his
projectile invective.
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, may be the film's point, assuming it has one.
Writer-director-star Dan Zukovic brings nonstop manic abrasiveness
to his character named, none too imaginatively, Simon Geist. But
Zukovic the actor has only himself to blame for not giving himself
more to work with and forfeiting any claim to trenchant comment on
LA nothingness. The film flickers momentarily to life only when he
finds himself rationalizing his deepening association with a model
who seems to get a kick out of him and brings him into a music
video project.
</P>
<P>
   What makes this funny is the reaction of his depressed, intense,
virtually silent disciple, Susan Heimbinder's Darla, a trust-funded
Gen Xer paying for the aggressively bland tract house that serves
as their base, hiding her collection of '70s lunch boxes, fearing
his scorn. When Simon glibly speaks of switching tactics and
subverting the system from within after he's finally offered real
work, the things she does with her eyes say more than all his
strident one-note braying.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-30-98 1448EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
