<DOCNO> NYT19981030.0161 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-30 14:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5887 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      10-30 0571
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LET HISTORY JUDGE ALEX HALEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ I am a sucker for the desperate cause, the long shot,
the quixotic endeavor. Certainly, Philip Nobile's 19-year campaign
to have the Pulitzer Prize board rescind the 1977 special award to
the late Alex Haley for ``Roots'' would fall into that category. On
the one hand, I think Nobile is doomed to fail. Successive board
chairmen have told him to go fly a kite. Last year's chair, Geneva
Overholser, quoting one of her predecessors, Russell Baker, told
Nobile: ``We are not in the business of passing judgment on the
dead.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand ... well, you be the judge.
</P>
<P>
   Since ``Roots'' was published, plenty of derogatory information
about its creation has surfaced. In a 1978 trial, Haley admitted to
plagiarizing from Harold Courlander's ``The African'' and had
copied from four other public domain sources. He paid Courlander
$650,000 in an out-of-court settlement. Furthermore, some key
``Roots'' episodes have been revealed to be fiction. (The book was
and is sold as a work of nonfiction.) For instance, Haley's
dramatic account of learning of his ancestry from an African
``griot'' appears to have been staged.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview for a 1997 BBC documentary never aired in this
country, Judge Robert Ward, who presided over the Courlander trial,
said: ``In academia, if someone were to have obtained a degree and
it later came out that he had copied major portions of his thesis,
the degree would likely be taken away. I don't know if there's a
parallel with respect to the Pulitzer Prize, but I think ... an
award that was not properly earned could very well be taken away.''
(According to Pulitzer administrator Seymour Topping, a prize has
never been rescinded. In 1981, The Washington Post returned a
Pulitzer Prize awarded to Janet Cooke, who had fabricated portions
of her winning entry.)
</P>
<P>
   Haley died in 1992, and many people acquainted with Nobile's
jihad prefer to let him rest in peace. But, curiously, Haley does
live on in two posthumous works, both clearly labeled as fiction.
Both of them _ the ``Roots'' sequel called ``Queen'' and the
just-published ``Mama Flora's Family'' _ were primarily written by
Newburyport's David Stevens, who befriended Haley toward the end of
his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``This campaign is one of the most mean-spirited things I've
ever come across,'' Stevens says. ``In hindsight, the world would
have been easier on Alex's ghost if `Roots' had been published as
fiction. This book changed the thinking of a nation, about slavery
and about history. I wonder where this lack of generosity is coming
from. ... How is this different from those marvelous poets we call
Homer?''
</P>
<P>
   Let history judge. History-like, it is already judging. Haley is
distinguished by his absence from the recently published ``Norton
Anthology of African American Literature'' co-edited by Harvard's
Henry Louis Gates Jr. ``Let's speak candidly,'' says Gates, who was
friends with Haley and is close to his family. ``Most of us feel
it's highly unlikely that Alex actually found the village whence
his ancestors sprang. `Roots' is a work of the imagination rather
than strict historical scholarship. It was an important event
because it captured everyone's imagination.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Alex Beam's e-mail address is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-30-98 1449EST &QL; 
