<DOCNO> NYT19981030.0162 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-30 14:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5889 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SLEPIAN-MURDER-ABORTI     10-30 1181
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLEPIAN-MURDER-ABORTION-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MURDER INC. 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By Katha Pollitt  
 c.1998 The Nation  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   On Oct. 23, Dr. Barnett Slepian, who performed abortions, was
shot and killed by a sniper while standing with his wife and son in
his kitchen in the Buffalo suburb of Amherst, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   They had just returned from synagogue. Slepian, father of four,
beloved gynecologist and obstetrician, is now a statistic in the
annals of antiabortion violence: the seventh medical practitioner
to be killed since 1992 in a wave of violence that in 1997 touched
one in four abortion clinics _ arson, acid attacks, stalkings,
assaults, death threats.
</P>
<P>
   His death leaves Buffalo, a city of 350,000, with only three
doctors who perform abortions. As I write, two of them are ``in
seclusion.''
</P>
<P>
   Slepian's death is being treated in the media as an occasion for
revelations about the violent wing of the antichoice movement. It's
great copy. By now, every reporter in America has probably visited
``The Nuremberg Files'' website, where, on pages decorated with
pictures of supposedly aborted fetuses and lines of dripping blood,
Neal Horsley of Carrollton, Ga., maintains detailed personal
descriptions, including photos, addresses and phone numbers, of
abortion providers, as well as the names and ages of their spouses
and children.
</P>
<P>
   On his list the names of the wounded are in gray; those of the
dead are struck through with a line. Horsley, who calls himself a
``journalist,'' denies that he advocates violence or is in touch
with those who commit it, although Slepian's name was crossed out
within hours of his murder.
</P>
<P>
   The press has also made much of the fact that Slepian was the
fifth abortion provider, one other in Western New York and three in
Canada, in the past four years to be shot in their homes by a
sniper around this time of year, apparently in honor of Veterans'
Dayfor Canadians, a Remembrance Dayon which the antichoicers mourn
the ``unborn.''
</P>
<P>
   Did you know about that? I didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Did you know that New York's Attorney General Dennis Vacco was
the U.S. attorney in Buffalo in 1992, when the city was targeted by
Operation Rescue's ``Spring for Life,'' and that he defied a
federal judge by refusing to prosecute Operation Rescue for its
many flagrant violations of the Freedom of Access to Clinic
Entrances Act (FACE)? One of his first acts as attorney general was
to abolish the Office of Reproductive Rights.
</P>
<P>
   Did you know that Sen. Al D'Amato, recent recipient of
endorsements from the Human Rights Campaign and from influential
New York-based black clergymen Floyd Flake and Calvin Butts, voted
against FACE, and that his two narrow re-elections came from votes
on the Right to Life Party line?
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times poll shows 69 percent of New Yorkers don't even
know that D'Amato is antichoice. As New York Observer columnist
Richard Brookhiser put it, the state's pro-choice majority forces
the senator to keep quiet about ``the good he does'' and his ``love
of the unborn.'' But what kind of pro-choice majority needs 18
years to figure out where its senator stands?
</P>
<P>
   If zealots like the ones who burn down abortion clinics and kill
doctors and stalk their children were committing the same crimes
against, say, dermatology clinics or convents or the U.S. Marines,
we'd probably know all these things and more.
</P>
<P>
   We'd know about the annual White Rose Dinner in Washington at
which the antichoice leaders celebrate their heroes. We'd know that
four out of five of the doctors shot around Remembrance Day were
Jewish.
</P>
<P>
   But then, if antiabortion violence was treated like the
terrorism it is, the perpetrators might have been caught by now. It
was the National Abortion Federation, not the police, who warned
area doctors of the Remembrance Day pattern.
</P>
<P>
   We are told that violent antichoicers are a mere fringe.
Obviously, few antichoicers commit murder or arson. But, as the
Matthew Shepard case reminds us, extreme vocabulary creates a
climate of moral permission for extreme acts. This is a movement
whose main spokespeople, many of them mantled in clerical or
political authority, regularly use words such as ``babykillers,''
``murder,'' ``holocaust'' and ``Nazis,'' thus legitimizing just
about anything.
</P>
<P>
   If antichoicers are so opposed to violence, how come Eric
Rudolph, the suspect in the bombing of a Birmingham, Ala., clinic,
which killed a security guard and seriously injured a nurse, has
had no trouble swimming like a fish in the sea of the people of
North Carolinaeven now that he has been charged with the Atlanta
Summer Olympics bombings?
</P>
<P>
   At the practical level, antiabortion violence makes it harder to
choose abortion, to find it, to afford it. Like all terrorism, it
aims to terrify, not just the brave doctors who still perform
abortions but also the doctors of tomorrow, who simply choose
another specialty. It also aims to terrify the support staffs and,
of course, women.
</P>
<P>
   More subtly, the violence makes ``mainstream'' antichoicers look
reasonable by moving the debate ever further onto their turf. In
Michigan this past summer a prosecutor made a 12-year-old who'd
been raped by her brother a ward of the state to prevent her
parents from taking her out of state for a late abortion. In
Louisiana, a woman awaiting a heart transplant was denied a
medically necessary abortion by the hospital that had been treating
her because the chances of her dying in childbirth weren't higher
than 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Also in Louisiana, a mentally disabled 17-year-old raped by her
father was denied a Medicaid abortion. (Both eventually had
abortions in Texas, thanks to the National Abortion Federation,
which arranged and paid for them.) And these are the ``hard
cases''involving rape, incest and risk to lifethat the media
assures us will always be protected!
</P>
<P>
   The middle ground keeps moving right. And it will do so as long
as pro-choicers leave activism to the other side.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SIDEBAR: WHAT YOU CAN DO?
</P>
<P>
   Donate your time. Volunteer for clinic defense,a genuine
grassroots political act. Donate your voice. Speak outeverywhere.
Donate ... your moneycontributions will be gladly accepted by the
National Abortion Federation, 1755 Massachusetts Ave. N.W., Suite
600, Washington, D.C. 20036.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Katha Pollitt, a poet and columnist for The Nation, is the
author, most recently, of ``Reasonable Creatures.'') &LR;
</P>
<P>
   -------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
