<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-30 14:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5891 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     10-30 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE WERE YOU IN '62? ASK GLENN, AND HE'LL TELL YOU: WHERE I AM
TODAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It lasted only a moment, a few seconds at most. But for those
fleeting seconds, it was 1962 again. John Glenn was soaring into
space atop a fiery rocket, carrying with him the hopes and
aspirations of a nation that desperately needed to believe in
itself.
</P>
<P>
   The surge of deja vu couldn't have lasted for more than an
instant, of course, because so much has changed since February of
'62, when Glenn became the first American to orbit the Earth.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, the United States was losing the space race to the
Soviet Union. Today, the Soviet Union is merely an unpleasant
memory, and America virtually holds the patent on space travel.
Non-Americans who want to see the world from the top down are
inclined to hitch a ride with us.
</P>
<P>
   When John Glenn squeezed into his one-seater Mercury space
capsule for a three-orbit, five-hour space flight in 1962, he was a
40-year-old adventurer, one of America's original seven astronauts.
Today, Glenn is but one of seven crew members embarked on a
nine-day mission aboard the space shuttle Discovery _ and he is 77
years old, less a pioneer on this space flight than a human guinea
pig who won a seat on the shuttle by offering himself as a subject
for scientific studies of the aging process.
</P>
<P>
   So much has changed.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, space was the new frontier. Glenn and his fellow
astronauts were the 20th-century counterparts of Daniel Boone, Davy
Crockett, Lewis and Clark. Now these space flights are so routine
that the TV networks rarely bother with live coverage; astronauts'
names are familiar only to the most fanatical of space buffs.
</P>
<P>
   But for a few moments on Thursday, as fire spewed from the
rockets that boosted Discovery into space, the mundane spectacle of
space travel seemed new again. When the countdown to liftoff
reached the final seconds, even the most jaded launch-watcher must
have felt the heart-stopping combination of excitement,
anticipation and fear that Americans used to feel every time one of
these flaming spaceships set off on a mind-boggling journey into
the heavens.
</P>
<P>
   I felt the excitement, and I count myself among the jaded.
</P>
<P>
   For me, the space program lost its luster when the shuttle
Challenger exploded in January 1986, killing schoolteacher Christa
McAuliffe and everyone else on board. Space travel didn't seem
thrilling after that; it seemed dangerous and unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
   I fully understand the argument that exploring new worlds can be
hazardous, that many Earth-bound pioneers suffered and died while
spreading civilization across the wilderness that once stood
between the greatest nation on earth and its full potential. None
of that changes my post-Challenger perception of space travel as a
frivolous risk and an extravagant expense.
</P>
<P>
   It's just my opinion and I'm entitled to it, even though I've
rarely found anyone who agrees with me. When I've written on this
subject in the past, I have usually been rewarded with a barrage of
phone calls and letters from readers who dismiss my misgivings
about the space program as ignorant and shortsighted.
</P>
<P>
   But then, ``ignorant'' and ``shortsighted'' is how some readers
describe most of my opinions.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of Glenn's return to space have ridiculed his mission as
a publicity stunt _ or worse, as a political payoff to a senator en
route to retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Some have dismissed the former astronaut's flight as a
transparent ``victory lap'' for a onetime hero of the space race.
</P>
<P>
   I prefer to take Glenn and the space program honchos at their
word when they insist that Glenn's participation will provide
significant scientific benefits, not just for space travelers but
for those of us who plan to live out our lives right here on Earth.
Doesn't a man who has devoted his entire adult life to serving his
country deserve the benefit of the doubt?
</P>
<P>
   Of course he does, just as he deserves the unqualified gratitude
of countless Americans who remember Glenn's first trip into space _
and who were thrilled to relive it on Thursday, if only for a
moment.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
