<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-30 14:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5894 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-TEMPTATIONS-BOS &LR;      10-30 0627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-TEMPTATIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TEMPTATIONS' WORKS BETTER AS CONCERT THAN BIOPIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE TEMPTATIONS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by: Allan Arkush &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On: NBC &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: Sunday and Monday at 9 p.m. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rated: TVPG &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Purists won't find sunshine on a cloudy day in ``The
Temptations,'' a two-part movie fictionalizing the ups and downs of
the hugely successful soul group. It's as TV-ized as TV-ized gets,
with open schmaltziness and character arcs that span three scenes
and every plot turn listed in the TV-movie recipe book under
``pathos,'' from substance abuse and adultery to cancer, the death
of a child, a shooting, and suicide. Based on the 1988
autobiography of original Temptation Otis Williams, who coproduced
the movie, it's also factually skewed, with significant events
omitted and a highly romanticized view of the group's formative
years on the streets of Detroit. We see the Temptations' early-'60s
Motown audition as if through a sepia haze, with an unusually
gentle Berry Gordy announcing: ``I didn't like it'' _ pause,
worried looks all round _ ``I loved it.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, most everyone else will overlook the biopic cliches
and dramatic inanities and succumb happily to ``The Temptations,''
which airs in two parts on Sunday and Monday nights at 9 on
WHDH-Ch.7. The music is, of course, absolutely irresistible _ the
beautifully parsed harmonies, the dynamic lead singing, the lush,
sweet melodies. Wisely, the makers of ``The Temptations'' have
fitted in as many song sequences as possible, most of them using
original recordings, and so for every bit of condensed soap opera
(wait until you catch Melvin Franklin's death scene in Part 2) we
are given an electrified Temptations performance as compensation.
Once the group receives the Motown makeover, the musical numbers
are accompanied by sensational dancing _ that lighthearted, campy
choreography that is a distant cousin to mime.
</P>
<P>
   Director Allan Arkush's presentation of the group's creative
hours _ on the street, onstage, in the studio _ is consistently
outstanding. The mostly unknown actors, all energetic, lip-synch
the songs convincingly and unself-consciously, and the close
camerawork manages to capture the intensity and pleasure of making
such full-bodied music. You can almost suspend disbelief and
pretend you are really watching Smokey Robinson teaching the young
group ``My Girl,'' or David Ruffin joining them onstage for the
first time, or the recording of their first Motown hit, ``The Way
You Do the Things You Do.'' In one effective sequence, we see two
screens of ``Ball of Confusion'' in performance, one by the
original group on tour and the other by former members Eddie
Kendricks and David Ruffin, who have vindictively decided to tour
as the Temptations.
</P>
<P>
   The acting is fine all around, as the Temptations' personnel
constantly shifts. Leon gives an arch spin to David Ruffin, the
bespectacled Temptation dogged by drug abuse and ego. With his
pusher/manager in tow, Ruffin makes a power play and insists the
group rename itself as David Ruffin and the Temptations.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Malik Whitfield is the model of loyalty as Otis
Williams, and DB Woodside plays Melvin Franklin as a sweet-natured
sidekick. While they squeeze the most out of their uninspired
dialogue, the actors are at their best during the musical
performances.
</P>
<P>
   And of course, they are helped along by the amusing hairstyles,
which evolve along with the eras. Naturally, when the
high-school-age Otis decides to become a singer he goes right to
the local barbershop, submits to the pain of having his hair
straightened, and orders up a popular cut known as the ``Tony
Curtis.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
