<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-30 14:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5895 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX     10-30 1117
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINISERIES ABOUT THE MOTOWN PHENOM MISSES A FEW BEATS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For anyone who lived through The Temptations' heyday, the
knowledge that there's more there _ and that it isn't all that
pretty _ has long been severed from the soul group's sleek aura as
the quintessential song-and-dance men with a string of infectious
hits.
</P>
<P>
   Now along comes ``The Temptations,'' the miniseries,
enlightening us with the real lowdown, warts and all.
</P>
<P>
   Airing at 8 p.m. CST Sunday and Monday on NBC, the musically
rich ``The Temptations'' will make you move, but I can't vouch for
how ``moving'' it ultimately will be. That might have more to do
with your personal stake in the music and the real lives behind the
lyrics.
</P>
<P>
   A definitive story of The Tempts, whose rise is well-documented
but whose fall has always been somewhat sketchy, certainly offers
great promise. (Aren't those promos tempting?) But ``The
Temptations'' doesn't even attempt to explain this mythic phase of
American music, staging instead a production that is essentially
great music masking melodramatic, mushy and often simple-minded
storytelling.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the 1988 biography of Otis Williams, the last surviving
original Temptation, the film is told in narrative, chronological
order. It begins with Williams' (Charles Malik Whitfield's)
wide-eyed obsession with starting a singing group, even though his
voice was merely adequate. If anything, he was superb at finding
talent and blanketing himself with it.
</P>
<P>
   Early on, we see him literally chasing down Melvin Franklin
(D.B. Woodside), portrayed here as a mama's boy who hid behind a
tree while Williams asked his mother whether he could join the
group.
</P>
<P>
   Williams recruited Eddie Kendricks (Terron Brooks) and Paul
Williams (Christian Payton) along the way, and even came up with
the group's name off the cuff after Motown's Berry Gordy refused to
audition them without one.
</P>
<P>
   Try as it might, ``The Temptations'' doesn't make the connection
that Detroit in general and Motown in particular was, during the
'60s, the center of the music universe, a tiny outfit kicking out
monster hits from folks like The Supremes, Stevie Wonder and Smokey
Robinson, who wrote much of The Temptations' early material.
</P>
<P>
   In the early '60s, The Temptations grew as Motown grew, melding
doo-wop with the house band's blues and the pop/R&AMP;B inventions of
Gordy's stable of producers. In many ways, The Temptations were the
ultimate Motown act, a group whose hills-and-valleys career
paralleled the changing fortunes of Motown.
</P>
<P>
   They broke out in 1964 with the hit ``The Way You Do the Things
You Do.'' The floodgates opened: ``My Girl.'' ``Cloud Nine.''
``Can't Get Next to You.'' ``Ball of Confusion.'' ``Psychedelic
Shack.'' During their most successful stretch, they had five
platinum albums, four Grammy awards and 12 gold albums.
</P>
<P>
   But The Tempts also had their share of underlying drama and
tragedy, and ``The Temptations'' zeros in quite closely on those
elements.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Williams was lost in alcohol and eventually killed himself
with a gun while sitting in his car. (His drinking, wife-beating
descent is chronicled artistically with a glorious video montage
covered by ``Papa Was a Rolling Stone.)''
</P>
<P>
   Tumultuous lead singer David Ruffin (Leon) fell into drug abuse
and is shown here being tossed out of a moving car at the front
door of a hospital, bloody and dying.
</P>
<P>
   Heavy cigarette smoker Kendricks died of lung cancer, and
Franklin had rheumatoid arthritis, which broke down his immune
system and contributed to a stroke. (In one of the final scenes, he
is laughing and talking with his mother and Otis Williams one
moment; the next, he's dead.)
</P>
<P>
   All the while, the group continued, reloading with members _
there have been 19 so far, with some, like Dennis Edwards (Charles
Ley), leaving and returning, only to leave again.
</P>
<P>
   One irksome problem is that the film telegraphs scenes rather
than simply developing them. Songwriter Norman Whitfield (Mel
Jackson), responsible for hits like ``Ain't Too Proud to Beg'' and
``My Girl,'' wafts through the proceedings like a talented but
egotistical sleazebag. Even Gordy (Obba Babatunde) and longtime
manager Shelly Berger (Alan Rosenberg) are stuck in shallowly
conceived roles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Temptations'' tries mightily to capture this drama while
telling a cohesive story, showing the group in rehearsals and
performing and yelling at one another, usually about Ruffin's slide
into the darker side.
</P>
<P>
   As for Ruffin, he's thoroughly demonized. Leon, who plays him
quite well, accordingly breathes fire and wears horns. Ruffin was
known for his womanizing, drug addiction and mood swings, but why?
He is first seen as a ladies' man, recording solo with Motown,
until The Temptations needed a lead singer. One scene shows Ruffin
nearly in tears waiting for the tour bus. ``Nothing's wrong,'' he
says to one of the Tempts. ``For the first time, everything's
right.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet a few scenes later, Ruffin is showing up at a picnic with
his personal drug supplier.
</P>
<P>
   After his dismissal from the group, Ruffin showed up at so many
of The Temptations' performances that they began to employ security
to stop him. But he never made it close enough to swipe the mike
from Edwards, leap on stage and lead the group in song, as is
dramatically played out in the film.
</P>
<P>
   It should be noted, too, that Williams is the film's
co-producer, and the most clearly defined of the original members.
He's shown here as a family man (even though his wife divorced him
for spending too much time on the road and not enough with their
son), as a level-headed survivor who was one of the least-known of
the Tempts but actually was the glue that held them together.
</P>
<P>
   Over four hours, you'd think writers Kevin Arkadie, Robert P.
Johnson and Alan Landsburg could have shown the Motown era more
vividly, illustrating why, for instance, the Tempts at one point
came to a complete standstill. (It was during the period Gordy
turned his attention to making movies instead of records, and all
the Motown artists found their instant success no longer so
instant.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The Temptations'' is nearly saved by the music, which becomes
even more poignant as the troubles mount. Even with the movie's
many flaws, at least one thing's certain: You won't listen to the
music the same way again.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is television critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kpp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services
on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
