<SLUG> BC-NASALSPRAY-FLU-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASAL-SPRAY FLU VACCINE IS NOTHING TO SNEEZE AT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   No needle, no tears. For Rhonda Powell, an elementary-school
social worker in Temple, Texas, the decision to have her 8-year-old
son vaccinated against the flu was easy this year.
</P>
<P>
   Powell's son is one of 15,000 children in the Temple-Bolton area
eligible to receive a new nasal-spray vaccine that promises to
protect children against the flu and painful middle-ear infections.
The free nasal inoculations are part of a five-year National
Institute of Health study involving doctors at the Influenza
Research Center at the Baylor College of Medicine in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers are trying to determine whether widespread
immunization of children 18 months to 18 years old will provide
communitywide protection against influenza. The nasal spray being
used is FluMist, a product developed by the Aviron pharmaceutical
company that may hit the consumer market by next fall, pending Food
and Drug Administration approval.
</P>
<P>
   Powell, like many parents, has a flu shot each year. But she
didn't consider giving her child the annual vaccine until she heard
about the new no-pain alternative.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hadn't thought of giving my son a flu shot until the nasal
spray became available,'' she said. ``I watched him take it, and it
was quick and easy. He said he would much rather have it than a
shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Gayla Herschler, coordinator of the study in Temple, has
observed hundreds of children being immunized (about 1,900 of the
15,000 targeted children have been given the spray), including her
3-year-old granddaughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``She just sat there and smiled the whole time. My daughter was
laughing because she says when kids get shots, she has to be
prepared to hold them down,'' Herschler said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the children blink their eyes and react with a little
surprise when the spray suddenly hits their noses, but they do just
great. It's amazing. I tell people, you need to come and watch us
vaccinate. You won't believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   The flu vaccine is important for children for several reasons,
according to Pedro Piedra, pediatrician and associate professor of
microbiology and immunology at Baylor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Preschool and school-aged children are at high risk and play
an important role in the transmission of flu to family members and
the community,'' Piedra explained.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need universal immunization to reduce the impact in
children, which we tend to underestimate. Children have the highest
infection rate and one of the highest medically attended illness
rates. The hospitalization rate is comparable to that of the
elderly. Children just don't die from flu at as high a rate.''
</P>
<P>
   Pediatricians see a lot of children with flu problems, plus a
lot of ear and sinus infections that are flu complications, Piedra
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a pediatrician, I support universal immunization,'' he
said. ``For universal immunization, you need a very good vaccine
that is accepted by the public. If children and parents are afraid
of it, they are less likely to receive it. It must be safe,
well-tolerated and something children don't dread receiving. Where
the vaccines are equally good, I prefer the one that doesn't have
pain associated with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Herschler says most children have had no reaction to the spray.
``A few have had a little runny nose and slight fever that develop
the second day after receiving it,'' she said, but that goes away
in four to 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   In the first three years of the study, the vaccine has been 93
percent effective in preventing the flu and 98 percent effective
against influenza-associated ear infections in children.
</P>
<P>
   It is estimated that there were 30 million doctor visits last
year for acute ear infections, a 300 percent increase in office
visits since the mid-'70s. It is the most common illness for which
parents take their children to see a pediatrician. By age 3, more
than 80 percent of children have had at least one episode of acute
otitis media, and nearly 50 percent have had three or more
episodes.
</P>
<P>
   The nasal-spray flu vaccine surprised researchers last year by
protecting not only against the anticipated flu strains to which it
was targeted, but also against A/Sydney, an unanticipated strain
not found in the vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, flu shots provided virtually no protection
against A/Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got broader protection than could have been expected,''
Piedra said. ``We need more data, but right now, the studies are
very supportive of the notion that nasal spray may provide a
greater breadth of protection than the injected vaccine.''
</P>
<P>
   The primary difference between the traditional shot and the new
spray, other than method of administration, is that the injected
vaccine is made from killed viruses and nasal spray is derived from
weakened strains of live virus. The spray is easier to produce in
large amounts, and easier to administer. Both types of vaccine are
grown in eggs, but the injectable vaccine needs one egg per dose,
and one egg can produce 1,000 doses of the nasal vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   (Carolyn Poirot writes on health issues for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
