<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-HISTORY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN INTENSE LOOK AT WHITE SUPREMACY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMERICAN HISTORY X &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by: Tony Kaye &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Screenplay by: David McKenna &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Starring: Edward Norton, Edward Furlong, Beverly D'Angelo, Avery
Brooks, and Stacey Keach. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 118 minutes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R (graphic violence, pervasive language, sexuality and
nudity) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``American History X'' is that rarest of Hollywood commodities _
an intelligently provocative film. It's doubly controversial, first
because of its refusal to simply demonize neo-Nazi skinheads,
second because its director, Tony Kaye, publicly disowned it after
a dispute over the final cut.
</P>
<P>
   But a viewing of the film can't help leaving you wondering what
Kaye's problem was. Centered by Edward Norton's stunning
performance as Derek Vinyard, a charismatic California white-power
icon who repudiates neo-Nazism after a prison term and tries to
keep his worshipful kid brother from going the skinhead route,
``American History X'' jumps off the screen with a power and impact
matched by few films whose directors emblazon their names across
the screen.
</P>
<P>
   Told through the eyes of Edward Furlong's Danny, younger brother
of Derek, the story is of a California working-class family
struggling to stay together after their firefighter father is
killed fighting a blaze in a crack house, and Norton's embittered
big brother is imprisoned for killing two African-Americans he
catches stealing his truck. The title refers to an afterschool
project that Danny's high school principal (Avery Brooks) assigns
him after he hands in a book review praising Hitler's ``Mein
Kampf.'' His first assignment is to relate his older brother's
story.
</P>
<P>
   The first thing the film does right is to make Norton's
protagonist, Derek, not only charismatic, but intelligent. It's
easy to see how he could become the Hitler of Venice Beach, a
magnet for his disaffected going-nowhere contemporaries, supplying
legitimacy and justification for their thuggery, manipulated from
the wings by hate-mongering businessman Stacey Keach. Although the
film is self-servingly facile in providing the rationale for
Derek's racism (some of its speeches are lifted almost verbatim
from the campaign rhetoric surrounding California's
anti-affirmative action Proposition 209), it takes the trouble to
examine the roots of racist rage.
</P>
<P>
   It's shocking to watch the transition from grumbling and
scapegoating among the rudderless malcontents to an organized raid
on a Korean grocery store. Regarded as a young god by the
riff-raff, Norton's Derek blazes with rage that erupts when he
throws his widowed mother's Jewish date (Elliott Gould) out of
their house. There's more than indignation at theft when he
finishes off the two young black men outside his house. None of the
Nazi paraphernalia covering the walls of the brothers' bedroom is
as startling as the sight of Norton himself, naked to the waist,
head shaved, swastika tatooed over his heart, barbed wire tattoos
circling his biceps, eyes bright with fury.
</P>
<P>
   He's so tightly wound you can all but hear him crackle like a
high-tension wire in a performance that has Oscar nomination
written all over it. While Derek serves time, Furlong's Danny is
welcomed into the skinhead clique. All he wants is to follow in his
brother's footsteps. But when Derek is released, his younger
brother is confused by the fact that the hero he has worshipped has
undergone a change of heart behind bars. After disillusioning
contact with skinheads in jail and a friendship with Guy Torry's
black fellow inmate, Derek has outgrown his racist views and wants
to yank Danny back from what he now sees as a self-destructive
path. He's a Venice Beach Odysseus, back from a spiritual journey,
determined to put his house in order.
</P>
<P>
   He has enough street smarts to know that this about-face places
him and his kid brother in peril. Although the motivations are
sketchy, the feelings connected to them are played out with fierce
intensity, and the social pathology is etched with clarion
immediacy by Kaye, who did his own camerawork and clearly knows how
to impart visceral punch to his images. It isn't often that a film
maintains the danger level this one does. Although Kaye has
previously made his living directing beer, car, and running shoe
commercials, he draws uniformly fresh and gripping performances
from his cast.
</P>
<P>
   ``American History X'' isn't just Norton throwing off sparks
and, later, ruefulness, as Derek, in a stunning performance arc.
Beverly D'Angelo's chain-smoking sickly mom and Jennifer Lien's
ambitious sister convince us there's love in the beleaguered house,
and Furlong projects an essential sweetness that makes his lost kid
doubly poignant.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks' principal persuades us not only that's he's intelligent
and nobly motivated, but was himself once a young firebrand and was
pained by Derek's embrace of hate because he valued Derek's
intellectual promise. Ethan Suplee, as a hulking follower unable to
reach Derek's level of enlightenment, is another plus. ``American
History X'' doesn't suggest that there are any easy answers. But it
spotlights real social ills with heightened urgency. Unlike most
films, it wants to matter _ and does.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
