<HEADER>
A5900 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-LIFE-BOS &LR;      10-30 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-LIFE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SUNNY FABLE IN A CONCENTRATION CAMP? IT WORKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIFE IS BEAUTIFUL &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by: Roberto Benigni &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Screenplay by: Vincenzo Cerami, Benigni &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Starring: Benigni, Nicoletta Braschi, Giorgio Cantarini,
Giustino Durano, and Sergio Bustric. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 122 minutes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG-13 (Holocaust-related thematic material) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Chaplin in a Nazi death camp? It sounds like a recipe
for disaster, but it's the second half of a major career stretch
for Italian comic Everyman Roberto Benigni in his new film, ``Life
Is Beautiful,'' and it works more serendipitously than you'd have
any reason to believe.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, ``Life Is Beautiful'' is two films, linked by a
quality of fairy-tale charm that Benigni conjures up, keeping the
spectres of sentimentality and bathos at bay with a masterly
lightness and delicacy of touch.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly a student of Chaplin, Benigni always tries for childlike
buoyancy, and has never before come so close to successfully
generating it as in this most serious and ambitious of his films.
The first half, set in the Tuscan town of Arezzo in 1939, is bright
and feathery and romantic as Benigni's penniless but gallant and
upbeat Guido arrives from the country to try his luck with the help
of his uncle, maitre d' in the fanciest local hotel.
</P>
<P>
   En route, he meets and courts an attractive local schoolteacher
(Benigni's wife and frequent co-star, Nicoletta Braschi, who
captures perfectly the look of a well-bred young woman of the
period). Guido's way is to cheerfully do his thing, relying, if
necessary, on a healthy dose of denial. Although he's Jewish, he
follows his uncle's lead and ignores what he figures he can't
change, even to the extent of daring to woo the woman he loves even
though she's engaged to the local fascist big shot.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he has his way of taking a stand, and his gesture in a
hotel dining room is as joyous a fantasy scene as any in Italian
cinema since Fellini's heyday. But a few brief years later, when
he's married, is the father of a young son, and the proprietor of
his own bookstore, things change gravely. Without warning, he's
bundled off to a boxcar with other Jews and sent to a camp,
followed by his loyal wife.
</P>
<P>
   This sets the stage for the film's grand conceit. Concealing the
fact that he has brought his young son, Guido hides the boy in the
camp barracks. He warns the boy never to reveal himself to the
Germans but shields him from the terrors of the place by pretending
that it's all a huge game with rules they must obey to get a big
prize. There are a few close calls as the anxious father sustains
the clowning, using the nimbleness of his imagination to cloak the
boy from the surrounding horrors.
</P>
<P>
   Part of what makes the film so watchable is knowing the
largeness of the gamble Benigni is taking. He's not only shielding
the boy; he's diverting us from the intruding thought that
maintaining his noble deception wouldn't really be possible, that
the boy would surely notice something that would shatter the
illusion. Yet we want to keep believing in it, and we keep our own
disbelief at bay as we watch Benigni's comic inventiveness do
battle with the impending credibility problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life Is Beautiful'' frankly goes on a little too long to
sustain its high-wire act. But Benigni pushes himself to new
heights, realizing the drama is inherent enough to compel a
watchful eye lest pathos leak in and dilute the impact of this
generous and life-affirming fable. It does more than a lesser
perfect movie does; it makes us want it to succeed. In the end,
Benigni's physical gracefulness translates into a gracefulness of
spirit that shines forth as the antithesis of fascism and all the
other isms.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, Benigni has created a film that is as
powerful as the best fables. Skirting the sentimentality inherent
in any rendering of any ``little man,'' he compels belief in the
childlike purity his character keeps alive _ and uses to keep his
son alive. In short, he translates the sunny innocence of his
characters into a sunny tone that carries the film's tricky
balancing act, making it seem the expression of a life force
finding a way through evil like a dandelion finding its way through
cement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-30-98 1453EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
