<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-CELEBRATION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIMMERING SECRETS ERUPT IN VINTERBERG'S `CELEBRATION' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE CELEBRATION
</P>
<P>
   Directed by: Thomas Vinterberg &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Screenplay by: Vinterberg, Mogens Rukov &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Starring: Ulrich Thomsen and Henning Moritzen &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 105 minutes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R (strong sexual content and language, including
references to sexual abuse) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Vinterberg's ``The Celebration'' arrives from Denmark
with a baggage of theoretical dogma that's best ignored in favor of
the jagged immediacy its stylistic credo makes possible. If the
dizzying propulsiveness of its hand-held camerawork recalls Lars
Von Trier's ``Breaking the Waves,'' it's because both directors
adhere to an anti-artifice credo they hammered out with Danish New
Wave colleagues. Although their manifesto, Dogma 95, sounds
forbidding, it's more tongue-in-cheek rambunctious than
foot-in-mouth dour.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the group's stripped-down esthetic is well suited to
its story of ugly old secrets erupting at what's supposed to be the
gala 60th birthday celebration of a domineering patriarch in the
elegant country hotel he owns. Vinterberg's deliberate avoidance of
slick illusion-mongering is advanced by a style that suggests a
camcorder running amok as the old man's three grown children barrel
down country roads to converge on the hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Also influencing the climate at the gathering is the fourth,
absent sibling, who committed suicide. The atmosphere is thick with
bumptious overstatement arising from the high anxiety levels of the
uneasy surviving sibs. They are feeling far from festive. Ulrich
Thomsen's eldest, Christian, who owns a restaurant in Paris, is
practically catatonic. Paprika Steen's Helene is spooked by being
put in the same room in which her sister killed herself. And Thomas
Bo Larsen's bullying Michael yells at his wife and crashes around
to conceal his rage at his ongoing status as baby of the family.
</P>
<P>
   At the dinner, the brooding Christian rears up and offers a
shocking toast that has been simmering inside him since the abused
and miserable childhood he shared with his dead twin. When pressed
to apologize, he not only refuses, but deepens his indictment of
his father, whose stoicism is sorely tested and whose smugness is
dented. While one faction tries to smooth things over and avoid
confronting the ugliness, Christian and the others fuel the
insurrection, aided by the long-smoldering resentments of the
kitchen staff.
</P>
<P>
   Just as you think you're in for a Danish ``Discreet Charm of the
Bourgeoisie,'' the last vestiges of playfulness vanish in a jolting
display of racism when Helene's black boyfriend shows up. Then the
intergenerational gloves come off. A few squalid revelations and
jerky camera movements later, the film gives way to natural light,
as if to say that the family has stopped dealing in falsehood and
is at last facing the realities of its history.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to see the technical trademarks of these Danish
directors turning into cliches just as empty as the ones they mean
to sweep away. But on this occasion they are trenchantly wedded to
their subject. And Vinterberg draws vigorous and suitably unruly
performances from his ensemble. Thomsen makes Christian's
bitterness sympathetic, Larsen's aggrieved petulance as the
excluded youngest brother achieves moments of poignance, and,
against all probability, Henning Moritzen's tarnished patriarch
finds a measure of dignity. The mordant, urgent, raw, vital
``Celebration'' is a bare-knuckle powerhouse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
