<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Saturday, Oct. 31:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Politics &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-CLINTON (Undated) _ President Clinton campaigns in New
York for Charles Shumer, the Democrat locked in a tight race with
Senator Al D'Amato. On the trail he talks about Social Security and
urges black preachers to help get out the vote. By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-MASS-WITCH (Salem) _ The race for governor in
Massachusetts has the witches' anti-defamation league in a fury
after Acting Gov. Paul Cellucci accused his challenger, Scott
Harshbarger, of helping witches when he was an attorney general. By
Gustav Niebuhr. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-CALIF (Los Angeles) _ Moderation is the watchword in
the Golden State this year, and Lt. Gov. Gray Davis, a 23-year
veteran of state government widely mocked as the dullest politician
in the state Democratic Party, appears on the verge of a major
victory in the campaign for governor. By Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-INCUMBENT-POWER (Washington) _ More than at any time in
recent memory, this year's U.S. House races are populated with
challengers who have been woefully outspent and who lag far behind
the incumbent. By Leslie Wayne.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-WIVES (Washington) _ Candidates' spouses have appeared
in campaign ads before, where they usually sat silently alongside
their neatly dressed children in family shots. This year, the wives
of many candidates _ Democratic candidates in particular _ are out
in front, with greater prominence and a new purpose. Many have
speaking roles, and almost all talk about their husband's values.
None of the wives featured in this season's commercials come out
and say it: ``Hey, no Clinton problem here,'' but the viewer sees
the point. By Melinda Henneberger.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Other National-General &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GLENN-SHUTTLE (Cape Canaveral, Fla.) _ News from the Cape
and from John Glenn in outer space. By John Noble Wilford.
</P>
<P>
   HALLOWEEN-SCHOOLS (New York) _ Many school districts are
grappling with Halloween controversies. Some say the parties and
parades are taking up a full week and diverting attention from
educational needs. In a handful of cases parents are objecting to
what they call a cult-like fascination. By Maria Newman.
</P>
<P>
   NY-VILLAGE-PARADE (New York) _ The evolution of the Greenwich
Village Halloween parade, and how it reflects changes in the
Village and gay New York. By Randy Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-HARASS (Washington) _ President Clinton fired the U.S.
ambassador to Eritrea last year after two embassy employees
complained he had groped and fondled them, according to a State
Department report. By Philip Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   STARR-STEELE (Washington) _ Julie Hiatt Steele is only a
peripheral figure to a secondary element of the investigation of
President Clinton. But she is still attracting a lot of attention
from Kenneth Starr, who has gone to extraordinary lengths to
investigate a relatively minor figure in the Monica Lewinsky
matter. By Jill Abramson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   G-7-BAILOUT (Washington) _ The world's 7 wealthiest nations sign
on to Clinton's plan for a new program that offers assistance to
nations before they are in crisis. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   PINOCHET-SPAIN (Madrid) _ Spanish High Court rules against
Spanish government prosecutors and says that Spanish courts do have
jurisdiction to go after Former Chilean President Gen. Augusto
Pinochet for actions against Spaniards in Chile and Argentina. By
Marlise Simons.
</P>
<P>
   UN-HEALTH (United Nations) _ The World Health Organization
launches a major anti-malaria campaign, the first big effort by
organization's new head. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   SWEDEN-FIRE (Goteborg) _ Aftermath of disco fire that killed 60
teen-agers at a Macedonian social club. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Undated) _ The United States gross domestic product
rose 3.3 percent in the July-September quarter, considerably higher
than economists had predicted, as healthy consumer spending offset
a continued decline in exports and a lapse in business investment.
President Clinton asserts that the economy is the strongest in a
generation. The latest figure compares with growth of 1.8 percent
in the second quarter and 5.5 percent in the first. By Sylvia
Nasar.
</P>
<P>
   HALLOWEEN-HOTSPOTS (Orlando, Fla.) _ October used to be the slow
season at Universal Studios Florida. But not anymore. For 19 nights
in October, the park has presented its Halloween Horrow Nights,
which feature five haunted houses and zombies and demons that leap
out of the shadows at customers paying as much as $42 each.
Universal, whose Halloween celebration is in its eighth year, did
not invent the concept. Knotts Berry Farm has had a Halloween Haunt
for 26 years, and Disney World also has Halloween events, but they
are more limited. By Edwin McDowell.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At midday, the Dow industrial average was up
161 points, or 1.9 percent, and the Nasdaq index was up 23 points,
or 1 percent. By Robert D. Hershey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   OXFORD-EARNINGS (Undated) _ Oxford Health Plans reported a
narrower third-quarter loss of $47 million, or 58 cents a share.
Three months ago it reported a loss of $507.6 million, which it
described as a turning point. The latest loss was less than
analysts had expected. By Reed Abelson.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ The government will release a
deposition late today detailing direct testimony of Avadia
Tevanian, a senior Apple Computer executive, who is to be the next
trial witness. He is expected to describe Microsoft's efforts to
threaten and bully Apple to abandon Netscape and stop marketing
some of Apple's software to Windows users. By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
