<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABBE-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
 
FBI's FINANCIAL BITE ON GUN OWNERS IS GONE 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By J.R. LABBE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Buried deep within the voluminous, 4,000-page omnibus
appropriations bill passed by Congress this month was a bit of good
news for gun owners.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning Nov. 30, when the National Instant Criminal Background
Check System (also known as NICS) for new gun purchases goes into
effect, the FBI will be prohibited from collecting the threatened
$14 ``user fee'' to pay for its scrutiny of a potential buyer's
facts on file.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of dunning law-abiding citizens for the criminal
background checks (after all, it's decent folk _ not felons _ who
buy guns through licensed dealers), the FBI will fund the program
through a mix of direct congressional appropriations and existing
funds in the Department of Justice.
</P>
<P>
   As it should have been from the get-go. Only the elected
Congress has the authority to assess and retain taxes from the
American people, not some agency eat up with a fantasy about power
and control.
</P>
<P>
   So all you Wal-Mart shoppers who were worried about having to
cough up a $14 nonrefundable fee when purchasing a new deer rifle
after Nov. 30 can rest easy. Those bright yellow signs that warned
about the impending collection of taxes are disappearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``As of Oct. 21, all our stores are in the process of taking
down the signs,'' said Bryan Holmberg, corporate spokesman for
Wal-Mart's gun departments.
</P>
<P>
   Holmberg said Wal-Mart directed its stores to display the signs
starting Aug. 17, in anticipation of what might become the law of
the land. The Senate actually voted in July to prohibit taxing
lawful gun buyers for background checks, but the jury was still out
in the House. Call it erring on the side of caution.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning Oct. 21, the day after Congress approved the
appropriations bill, Wal-Mart stores along with licensed gun
dealers nationwide have been removing the signs.
</P>
<P>
   The next battle lies in stopping the feds from retaining the
names obtained in the instant background checks for as long as 18
months. Once again, the FBI is overstepping its authority. This not
only is contrary to the wording in the budget provision about
destroying such information, but it is a blatant constitutional
violation, as well as a violation of the Brady Act itself.
</P>
<P>
   The Brady Act specifically states that once a firearm
transaction is approved, the system ``shall ... destroy all records
of the system with respect to the call and all records of the
system relating to the person and the transfer.''
</P>
<P>
   Translation: One minute after the computerized system has OK'd a
gun purchase as legal, any record of the sale should be relegated
to the great computer zap file in the sky.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI, for some inexplicable reason, has proposed holding on
to those records for up to 18 months, which is a bald-faced
violation of the Brady Act's prohibition against establishing a
registration system of firearms, firearm owners or firearm
transactions.
</P>
<P>
   Gun owners, of course, think the worst. We've grown exceedingly
suspicious of each new incursion on our civil and privacy rights.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of suspicion, allow me to dispel a crazy rumor that's
circulating in these parts. The story goes that Denver recently
passed a complete gun ban, and sportsmen and women traveling
through the Denver International Airport are having their firearms
confiscated upon arrival. By the time they can fight such action in
court, the guns are being destroyed and the visitors are given
vouchers for the replacement of their guns.
</P>
<P>
   Nonsense, says everyone from the National Rifle Association to
the public affairs office of the airport. The Denver City Council
did pass a local ordinance this year that bans certain types of
semi-automatic firearms (and the members of that misguided body can
expect to hear from the NRA next spring when the national
convention convenes there), but airport personnel have nothing to
do with enforcement of that ordinance. Shucks, the airport isn't
even in the city limits.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's really off the wall,'' said Chuck Cannon, director of
public affairs at Denver International. ``Hunting is big business
in Colorado, and we see all kinds of rifles going through here.''
</P>
<P>
   The truth is bad enough, folks. Let's not start making things
up.
</P>
<P>
   (Jill ``J.R.'' Labbe is senior editorial writer and columnist
for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Her e-mail address is
jrlabbe(at)star-telegram.com, and her phone number is (817)
390-7599. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World
Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
