u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-VAMPIRES-BOS &LR;      10-30 0554
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-VAMPIRES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`VAMPIRES' LIMPS OFF INTO THE SUNSET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHN CARPENTER'S VAMPIRES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by: John Carpenter &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Screenplay by: Don Jakoby (novel: John Steakley) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Starring: James Woods, Daniel Baldwin, and Sheryl Lee &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 107 minutes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R (strong violence and gore, language and sexuality) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Garlic and crucifixes can't stop the chomping fangs in ``John
Carpenter's Vampires,'' but a lame script and flat direction drive
stakes through its heart. Carpenter needn't have bothered to append
his name to the title. Nobody else is likely to be tempted to lay
claim to this misfire.
</P>
<P>
   It has the intellectual firepower of ``From Dusk Till Dawn,''
but not the laughs, although at first it teases us with a promise
of wry humor as James Woods and his band of vampire fighters pile
out of a couple of vehicles near a decrepit hulk of a house and
start unloading gear that suggests an impending goth rock concert.
</P>
<P>
   But no. They're only dressed like rockers. They're really a SWAT
team, wiping out vampires by day, when the vampires are weakest. To
the hunt they bring a new technique _ steel harpoons shot into the
vampire's chest, attached to a cable, so the harpooned bloodsuckers
can be winched, kicking and screaming, into the daylight, where
they go up in flames. But although the posse decimates the nest,
its leader (Thomas Ian Griffith) escapes. He has a plan. If he can
steal a certain antique crucifix and reverse an exorcism, he and
the other vampires can walk in the sunlight. As one silver-tongued
good guy puts it, ``He'll be unstoppable _ unless we stop him.''
</P>
<P>
   Just when you're beginning to wonder on whose behalf the
anti-vampire commandos are patrolling the back roads of New Mexico,
it's revealed that they're in the employ of the Vatican,
represented by a leering cardinal played by Maximilian Schell, in
what surely is the low point of an otherwise mostly distinguished
career. Woods is better suited to the wipeout mode the film calls
for, although the team leader he plays is slowed down after the
vampire chief descends on the motel where the crew is unwinding
with a squad of hookers and slaughters the lot.
</P>
<P>
   For a film that hurls as many bleeding chunks through the air as
this one does, ``John Carpenter's Vampires'' is remarkably dull.
Not even a campy subplot can inject much life into it. It involves
Sheryl Lee's hooker, who has been bitten but hasn't yet turned, and
Daniel Baldwin's vampire hunter who falls for her, undeterred by
the likelihood of her walking away from him with blood dripping
down her chin and into her cleavage. Such is where the film goes
for drama.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, a vampire movie isn't poetry or rocket science. All you
ask is that it scare you a little, and maybe muster a little style.
But it would take a lot more than Woods's valiant attempt to fill
the screen with attitude to make this anemic specimen stand up and
march.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, it wasn't a bad idea to try and cross the vampire and
Western genres. It worked for Kathryn Bigelow in ``Near Dark.''
Reportedly, Carpenter wanted to marry ``Dracula'' and ``The Wild
Bunch.'' But the gory boredom we get cries out to be thought of as
``The Mild Bunch.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-30-98 1456EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981030.0175 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-30 14:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5914 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-NEWMAN-BOS &LR;      10-30 1061
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-NEWMAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANDY NEWMAN AS EVERYMAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Short people, fat people, yellow people, rednecks, gridiron
stars, dancing bears, and ``Toy Story'' animated cartoon figures.
Randy Newman has sung about them all, during an outrageous _ and
often irreverent _ pop career that will hit a crescendo in the next
few months.
</P>
<P>
   Newman, whose rapier wit has ruffled more than a few feathers in
his day, has a flurry of upcoming projects. Topping the list is a
wildly entertaining four-CD box, ``Guilty: 30 Years of Randy
Newman,'' due Tuesday ($59.98 list price).
</P>
<P>
   There's more. In keeping with his recent career as film
composer, Newman contributes to the soundtrack of the current
``Pleasantville'' and the forthcoming ``A Dog's Life'' and ``Babe:
A Pig in the City,'' for which he wrote a song (``That'll Do'')
sung by Peter Gabriel. Next spring, Newman will release a CD of
original songs, ``Bad Love,'' followed by his first tour since the
mid-'80s. He also expects to stage his pop-opera updating of
``Faust'' next year at the Kennedy Center in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``I seem to be everywhere!'' Newman says with a hearty laugh
from his Los Angeles home. ``It's this little brief window of
opportunity. I prefer this to nothing going on, I can tell you
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Newman, who could be labeled the Mark Twain of piano-pop, is
best appreciated on the new boxed set. It pools his hits ``Short
People'' and ``I Love L.A.'' with older classics such as ``Mama
Told Me Not to Come'' (a hit for Three Dog Night), ``Davy the Fat
Boy,'' ``Miami,'' and his bigotry-smashing ``Rednecks.'' And it
collects his movie music from the films ``Toy Story'' (he wrote its
showpiece track, ``You Have a Friend in Me''), ``The Natural,''
``Awakenings,'' ``The Paper,'' ``Maverick,'' ``James and the Giant
Peach,'' and ``Ragtime,'' which contained his Oscar-nominated song,
``One More Hour.''
</P>
<P>
   The box is a sure crowd pleaser.
</P>
<P>
   ``I generally never go back and listen to stuff,'' says Newman,
now 54, ``but the stuff on this boxed set was better than I
remember it. That was a pleasant surprise, rather than thinking,
`Oh my God, I thought it was good, but it was horrible.' I'm proud
of it. It's an accurate documentation of my last 30 years of
writing. And writing is the only thing I'm really serious about.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, listening to the box, it's hard to believe that the
same singer/pianist could have done such divergent songs, running
the gamut from the bitingly satirical slant of his solo albums to
the consumer-friendly tone of his classical-meets-pop soundtrack
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The music on `Toy Story' brought me into the mainstream,''
Newman says. ``The songs that I've written for movies have been the
most remunerative songs that I've ever written, though they're not
the most artistic. Certainly, `I Love to See You Smile' and `You've
Got a Friend in Me' are just sort of generic lyrically, but they're
also friendly. A lot of people could do them, I think, where there
are some things that I do, like `Davy the Fat Boy' or `God's Song'
or `Miami,' that I don't think a lot of people could do. But I'm
grateful for the balance. It's good to get out of the position of
the third-person-narrative stuff that I do on my own, and do
something straight ahead and friendly.''
</P>
<P>
   Newman calls it a ``vestige from my family'' to be interested in
film scoring. His uncle, Alfred, wrote music for the films ``How
Green Was My Valley,'' ``How the West Was Won,'' ``Airport,'' and
``Wuthering Heights.''
</P>
<P>
   Did Newman get any advice from him?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, he was too busy. All he did was work. But I'd see him in
there working. And when I was a kid, he was onstage and I was able
to see an orchestra (with him) up close at a young age, which is a
good thing for any kid to do. I recommend it.''
</P>
<P>
   Another difference between composing for films and for one's own
albums is the meaning attached to each. ``It's an odd ethic I
have,'' says Newman, ``of putting a lot of time and effort into
something that's not really very important _ that is, movie music
compared to making a record. The movie is not your thing. The movie
is the big thing, and the music isn't the most important part of
the movie. But I care desperately about it when I'm doing it. When
I'm done doing it, I don't care about it at all. I don't look back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can work up to 12 to 14 hours a day on movies _ more than on
my own songs. On my songs, I can't do it for more than four hours a
day because it's too hard, too intense. I can do it for much longer
on movies. And if you're writing for orchestra, the time goes
pretty fast. Your adrenaline is going and you don't notice that
you're sort of wiped out until you stop.''
</P>
<P>
   The new boxed set has one CD devoted to his soundtracks, two to
his studio recordings (which include appearances by members of the
Eagles and Fleetwood Mac, notably on ``I Love L.A.''), and one to
``Odds and Ends,'' referring to previously unreleased tunes and
live tracks. The funniest of these is ``Golden Gridiron Boy,'' his
first original record, dating to 1961. Sings Newman of the football
hero who is stealing his girlfriend: ``All the girls run after
him/And my girl is in front of them all .../With every score I lose
more ground/I'm too small to make the team/I can only play in the
band.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a bobby-socks-style pop tune (contrasted with the more
meditative musings of his later, documentary-type songs) and was
produced by former teen idol Pat Boone. The latter was actually a
patient of Newman's doctor father; hence the connection.
</P>
<P>
   Newman's early nerd tendencies were thus well established. They
can also be seen in other odds and ends like the piano ballad
``Tickle Me'' (``Why don't you tickle me?/Gee whiz, that would be a
good idea'') and ``My Little Buttercup.''
</P>
<P>
   But Newman's forte later became his double-edged takes on the
human condition _ a role that he continues to play well. His next
album of original songs, ``Bad Love,'' will even include a song
about aging rock stars, entitled ``I'm Dead, But I Don't Know It.''
Sample lyric: ``I have nothing left to say/But I'm going to say it
anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Adds Newman: ``It's for all of us old farts who won't leave the
stage.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Twain couldn't have put it any better.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
