<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-RANCID-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUNKERS STAY TRUE TO ETHOS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLIVAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Attitude counts.
</P>
<P>
   Here's guitarist-singer Lars Frederiksen on what he would do for
the three other guys in his punk rock group, Rancid. ``I'd lie,
cheat, steal, and kill for any (person) in my band,'' he declares,
on the phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a real close band,'' adds singer-guitarist Tim
Armstrong. ``How would you like to travel around the world with
your closest homeboys? It's so natural out here.''
</P>
<P>
   The men in the Berkeley, Calif.-based Rancid are road dogs. They
are in the midst of their 33d tour; they've played over 1,000 shows
in five years. They stop at the Palladium in Worcester tomorrow
night.
</P>
<P>
   What about their attitude toward fans, perhaps the most
important aspect of all?
</P>
<P>
   This past summer, Frederiksen was sitting in a ramshackle
backstage area at the multi-band Vans Warped tour in Northampton.
Asked to define the ethos of the tour, Frederiksen kept repeating,
almost as a mantra, ``No rock stars.''
</P>
<P>
   For years, status quo has been the star on a pedestal and the
lucky fans who are allowed to bask in the star's shadow. Punk rock
broke down that divide, briefly, during the mid- to late 1970s,
declaring everyone part of the same squalid mess. Then, the divide
formed again. Rancid, one of today's most prominent neo-punk bands,
does its best to revisit the punk vibe of 1976 on contemporary
terms. It doesn't really matter that the four guys _ including
bassist-singer Matt Freeman and drummer Brett Reed _ were children
when punk first happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been turned off by bands with this imperious
attitude,'' says Armstrong. ``Like, `We're better than anyone
else.' That's a weird rock-star kind of thing. I actually get
uncomfortable if I don't feel like I'm on the same level as people
who come to see us play.''
</P>
<P>
   Rancid, adds Frederiksen, knows the world owes it nothing. ``If
you're some kid that's been handed everything to you in life, of
course, you're going to expect everything,'' he says. ``But this
all happened by accident, and that's why you've got to take it with
a grain of salt, stay humble, and treat people with respect. I
mean, all of us come from single-parent families, broken homes, and
it installs a work ethic. We all grew up in minority neighborhoods,
melting pots. You see people as human beings. ... When you do get
something in your life, you treat it with a little bit more
respect.''
</P>
<P>
   Rancid grabbed a place in the punk pantheon with its ``Let's
Go'' album from 1994. The band turned the corner toward what
someone else might call stardom two years ago by selling nearly a
million copies of ``... And Out Come the Wolves,'' bolstered by the
songs ``Ruby Soho'' and ``Time Bomb.'' Its latest, ``Life Won't
Wait,'' was released in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   All of this is done on the feisty indie label Epitaph, which
lacks the clout of the major labels. Frederiksen takes pride in the
underdog status. ``I mean you can be on a major label,'' he says,
``and become some commodity like Janet Jackson. A CEO, what does a
CEO know about music? He knows numbers, figures, and money. He
doesn't know about the artists having to be in a van, traveling
across the country, making your T-shirts. That's the thing about
punk rock.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Epitaph main man Brett Gurewitz does know about these
things from his days in the band Bad Religion. Frederiksen says,
``He knows about writing songs, making records, turning the knobs
to get the sound right, putting the shrink wrap on.''
</P>
<P>
   Rancid formed in 1991. Armstrong and Freeman came from Operation
Ivy; Reed joined and made it a three-piece; Frederiksen, formerly
of Slip and off a stint in a revived UK Subs, was the last to join,
in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The band has always mixed punk, ska, reggae, and roots rock _
nothing about any of the genres feels forced or false to them.
``(It's) music we've been listening to since we were kids,'' says
Frederiksen. ``It all came from the street. There was nothing nice
about it. It was real, honest, had integrity. So, it was kind of
obvious that you can interwine all of it.''
</P>
<P>
   In this way, Rancid is like many of its California punk-bred
peers. But never too far away is the aura of the early Clash,
England's original punk rock avatars. There's the hard and rough
sound; the stylistic mix; the working-class, left-wing politics;
the sense of band-as-gang. They even echo the Clash's
``Sandinista!'' cry on the rockabilly-styled ``Lady Liberty.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We never get bent out of shape when people compare us to the
Clash,'' says Armstrong. ``'Cause, you know, if somebody says, `You
guys sound a lot like the Smashing Pumpkins,' that would be
horrific.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Armstrong does note that Rancid plays faster than the Clash,
mixes more reggae and ska into its stew. But how's this for
serendipity? Armstrong has signed former Clash singer-guitarist Joe
Strummer to his Hell Cat label, a joint venture between Armstrong
and Epitaph's Gurewitz.
</P>
<P>
   Rancid's ``Life Won't Wait,'' recorded on the West Coast, New
York, New Orleans, and Jamaica, showcases a band that has seen the
world, not just its neighborhood. ``I don't live in the exact same
environment anymore,'' says Armstrong, the principal songwriter.
``It would be kind of redundant to keep singing the same thing over
and over again. That would be weird.'' Songs on ``Life Won't Wait''
address class struggle and strife (invoking Bosnia and other
places), black lung disease, the futility of the junkie life. The
Mighty Mighty Bosstones' Dicky Barrett shows up to bark on ``Cash,
Culture &AMP; Violence,'' and some of the Specials join in on
``Hooligans.'' Reggae singer Buju Banton joins on the title track.
There is a righteous charge to most everything Rancid touches, an
us-against-them battle cry, a sense of serious fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Music,'' says Frederiksen, ``is something powerful. It's not
something you lock yourself into, like a 4-by-4 cell, and say `I
can't go out of this.' From the very start, Rancid, first of all,
is built on friendship, and, No. 2, we're fans of music _ not just
punk, not just reggae, not just soul. ... Whether the radio is
playing our songs or MTV is playing our videos _ I mean we never
went for that. That happened and it snowballed. You got four kids
from Nowheresville, USA, and you got all this thrown on your lap.''
</P>
<P>
   They may have made a few mistakes along the way, Frederiksen
says, but the band treats them as learning experiences. ``We've
never stepped on anyone's toes,'' he says. ``We have fun. We work.
The one thing I think in common with all our records, and the way
we operate is, just treat people with respect and be true to
ourselves. You'll never fail doing that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
