<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-ROCK-NOTES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUND OF CARDIGANS EVOLVES INTO `TRIP-HOP' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLIVAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Remember the Cardigans and their sexy Swedish singer Nina
Persson, the woman who incessantly cooed ``Love me, love me, say
that you need me'' in the sugary pop tart single ``Lovefool?''
</P>
<P>
   That was the Cardigans of 1996 and '97 and ``Lovefool'' was the
mega-hit from their third album, the platinum-plus ``First Band on
the Moon.'' That album also marked their US debut. This year's
Cardigans, who play the Paradise tomorrow in their first US concert
of the year, is a slightly different sounding outfit.
</P>
<P>
   The last ``album was cute and nice,'' says guitarist Peter
Svensson from Sweden. ``We tried to make something jolly and happy
because (before) people thought we were too pretentious. Now, we're
older and we can allow ourselves to be a bit serious again. Last
time, we had the tongue-in-cheek thing to hide behind.'' (Keep in
mind, ``Lovefool'' was playfully iroinc, too.)
</P>
<P>
   The Cardigans' ``Gran Turismo'' CD comes out Tuesday. Svensson
says Persson wrote all the lyrics this time _ up from half _ and he
says the album title suggests the theme. ``It's the situation where
you're living your life, but you're not really part of it. You
spend so much time figuring it out you can't enjoy it. Like on
`Starter,' (it's about) how you're always reinventing yourself,
seeing a new girlfriend, buying a new car, moving to a new
apartment, you try to make yourself happy and in the end, you
realize ... you're like a tourist in your own world.''
</P>
<P>
   The 6-year-old quintet's sound has evolved from '60s-infused,
kitsch-tinted pop to what might be called trip-hop/pop. Svensson,
however, is wary of the trip-hop term, because, he says, ``I think
trip-hop is more about atmosphere and beats, and this is still more
about simple songs with an electronic feeling. More like Depeche
Mode, more about melody. They're more singer-songwriter type
songs.''
</P>
<P>
   Live, Svensson says, ``we're a bit heaviver and rougher. This
time, we're going to use some electronics and backup tapes and
drums. It's still the band playing; this just adds an electronic
element. Nina's been growing into this thing. It's making the
situation better 'cause she's singing her own words.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Built to Spill &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Built to Spill is the brainchild of Boise-spawned
guitarist-singer-songwriter Doug Martsch and is an ever-evolving
entity. Mostly, though, starting in 1993, it's been a craftsman's
studio project. Built to Spill was responsible for one of last
year's great unheard masterpieces, ``Perfect From Now On,'' a
spectacular splash of ebb-and-flow psychedelia.
</P>
<P>
   This year, BTS is a flesh-and-blood band and Martsch says, ``I
think it makes for more interesting music, the things that are more
interesting are stumbled upon, not the things that come out of one
person's head. (It's what) will happen when people are
collaborating and improvising _ the combinations of rhythms and
notes.''
</P>
<P>
   The upcoming (January) release ``Keep It a Secret,'' is more
structured and pop-centered. ``Any time we've made records,'' says
Martsch, ``they come out sounding different for different reasons.
There's not much of a vision; it's just pieces of ideas that just
sound the way they do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a band now,'' Martsch, referencing bassist Brett Nelson
and drummer Scott Ploug. ``It used to be a rotating lineup with me
as the only constant. The only thing I was shooting for was to make
it not like the last record. When you work on six minute songs it
takes ten times longer than a three-minute song. A lot of this (new
album) was written out of us (forging) bits and pieces out of hours
of jamming, picking out what sounds cool. I stumble across things.
The ones that stick in my head are the ones we end up using. I
never think about writing a certain kind of song.''
</P>
<P>
   As to any accolades about being an alt-rock guitar hero, Martsch
offers this: ``Just 'cause I play a lot of guitar solos, people
might think I'm good at it. I'm pretty llimited in terms of
ability, but I try to make up for it with ... whatever ... the
unexpectedness. It's daunting.
</P>
<P>
   Can they recreate the expansive sonic tapestry in concert? ``Not
really,'' says Martsch. ``We just do cover versions of our songs.
It's way louder than when anyone ever listens to the records. I
like it better, actually.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
