<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-PARADISE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ISLAND ADVENTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL PRAGER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SERPENT IN PARADISE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Dea Birkett &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Anchor Books, 296 pp., $23.95 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pitcairn Island holds a place in the collective imagination
wholly out of proportion to its place on Earth. In the expanse of
the Pacific Ocean, better than 63 million square miles, Pitcairn is
a rock holding less than two of them.
</P>
<P>
   But because of location (3,000 miles from anywhere) and history
(it was chosen as haven and last home by Fletcher Christian and
nine other mutineers of the Bounty), it is a destination of desire
for countless dreamers who apply for admission each year. Almost
all of them are turned away.
</P>
<P>
   British writer Dea Birkett, an adventurer with an easy
storytelling style, is one of the few who got in. For her, living
on Pitcairn was less a dream than an idea formed the day she saw
``The Bounty,'' the most recent of five films inspired by the
high-seas takeover of the British ship commanded by Captain William
Bligh in 1789. As its final credits rolled, she read on screen that
the descendants of the mutineers still lived on the island. From
that flickering beginning developed a quest lasting almost two
years, during which she researched, and networked, and persisted.
</P>
<P>
   Pitcairn is nothing if not difficult to reach, and that owes
only partially to its isolation. Approvals are required not only
from the island's appointed governor (who lives 3,000 miles away in
New Zealand and has never seen the place) but from the islanders,
whose approval is far from pro forma.
</P>
<P>
   But the location is formidable, too. There are only three
scheduled port calls a year, by a supply ship from New Zealand.
Birkett's trip to the South Pacific was by way of Houston, where
she met a Swedish chemical carrier bound for New Zealand via the
Panama Canal. Its route passed within 30 miles of Pitcairn, and it
would trade passage for some redecorating _ quite unlike the
circumstances of the first Westerners' arrival.
</P>
<P>
   Christian and company landed Jan. 21, 1790, seeking to escape
the gallows. Hunted by the British Navy, they needed a spot where
they could not only survive but disappear. Master's mate Christian
had found Pitcairn in Bligh's meticulous ship's log, something his
pursuers would not be able to do, since their maps had mischarted
the island.
</P>
<P>
   When Birkett arrived, there were 12 men and 26 women. They
seemed to welcome her, and she quickly became a part of, or party
to, generations-old disputes and falsehoods, such as the one about
drinking. Islanders are Seventh-Day Adventists, whose creed
proscribes smoking, card playing, and drinking. The first couple of
times Birkett was asked, conspiratorially, if she drank, she said
no, because she thought she was supposed to; it certainly was the
answer her observant hostess, Irma Christian, would want to hear.
But the third time she said yes, and was invited to a canasta game
where cold Carlsbergs were offered up.
</P>
<P>
   Islanders grow a lot of their food _ in addition to their
gardens, practically every tree belongs to someone _ and the rest
they get from trading with ships such as the one Birkett arrived
on. They trade their handicrafts, such as baskets and carved
sharks, in exchange for, say, frozen fried chicken pieces.
</P>
<P>
   As part of her rent, Birkett did all the cooking for the house,
and she became particularly adept at baking without eggs, because
although Irma had three dozen on hand, she didn't like to use them.
One day, though, Birkett decided to splurge on a cake that required
just two. When she discovered that all but a half dozen had gone
bad, she decided to salvage what she could and make omelettes. Upon
returning home, Irma was aghast. Having rotten eggs, it seemed, was
preferable to having none.
</P>
<P>
   Birkett relates her stories engagingly, albeit with an uneven
knack for allusion. When she describes Jenny, an islander, as being
``unnaturally white with hair the color of a pair of tights from
the 1950s,'' it adds little. But she fares far better in her very
next line when she says, ``If a color photograph were taken of
Jenny, it would appear to be black and white.''
</P>
<P>
   Birkett lasted just a few months on the island. She tried to fit
in but found that while she could learn many island skills, she
couldn't accept the core value of putting community before self,
which caused a growing estrangement. During an expedition to gather
breadfruit _ in which .22 rifles are used to dislodge them from
their high perches _ she even began doubting whether she was safe,
and decided to take the next ship out.
</P>
<P>
   Most readers, I suspect, will be glad she made the trip, and
that she lived to tell about it. She makes many of the 38 islanders
come alive, about as well as an outsider could, and by sharing her
fears and relating her foibles, she herself becomes a sympathetic
heroine.
</P>
<P>
   In her epilogue, Birkett rues having gone: ``Dreams should be
nurtured and elaborated on,'' she says, ``they should never be
visited.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
