<SLUG> BC-LOTUS-NOTES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COST CLAIMS BOOST A LOTUS RIVAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Executives at Lotus Development Corp. are fuming at new research
reports claiming their flagship Notes groupware product is much
more costly than a competing product from archrival Microsoft Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The reports by two separate research firms are the latest bit of
unwelcome news for Lotus. The IBM Corp. subsidiary invented
groupware _ software used to coordinate the activities of many
people in large businesses and organizations. And Lotus Notes has
long dominated the groupware market. But a spate of reports this
year has shown that Microsoft's competing product Exchange is now a
serious threat.
</P>
<P>
   A recent survey by International Data Corp. found 21.9 million
Notes users as of mid-1998, compared to 15 million Exchange users.
But the same survey revealed that Exchange outsold Notes in the
first half of the year, the first time this has happened.
</P>
<P>
   Now two research firms are saying that Exchange is often cheaper
to buy and operate than Notes.
</P>
<P>
   The most dramatic data came from the Radicati Group of Palo
Alto, Calif. In a survey of 110 large corporations, Radicati found
that at companies where workers used Notes, the average yearly cost
per user for the software was $166.66. But for companies using
Exchange, the cost fell to $64.93.
</P>
<P>
   Lotus spokesman Paul Davis says the comparison is unfair. He
said the firms that used Exchange are on average much larger than
those using Notes, thus lowering their per-user cost. In addition,
Exchange users generally concentrate on simple electronic mail
messaging, while Notes is often used for more demanding and complex
tasks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not a direct apples-to-apples comparison, as far as the
size of companies that were surveyed and the kinds of
applications,'' said Davis.
</P>
<P>
   But Sara Radicati defended her company's research. In fact, she
agreed with Lotus officials that Notes is a more advanced product
than Exchange, and that this largely explained the cost difference.
</P>
<P>
   Radicati said that instead of trying to compete with Exchange as
an e-mail product, Lotus should emphasize Notes' more advanced
features. ``They keep wanting to position Notes as a messaging
product. It does more than that,'' Radicati said. ``They're really
doing themselves a needless disservice with all of this.''
</P>
<P>
   Lotus also sniped at a report from another Palo Alto think tank,
Creative Networks Inc. In a study commissioned by Microsoft,
Creative Networks found that companies that installed Exchange
spend $109.86 less per worker in the first year of use than
companies that installed Notes.
</P>
<P>
   ``That study was funded by Microsoft, so nothing more to say
there,'' said Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Lotus officials said that the Creative Networks study was
fairer than Radicati's because it compared companies of roughly
similar size. And director of Notes marketing Ken Bisconti said
that a close reading of the two studies actually shows that Notes
and Exchange cost about the same if they are &UR;  &LR;  compared feature by
feature.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Malcolm, a group product manager for Microsoft Exchange,
hailed the studies as proof that Exchange is a superior value.
``What these studies do is they help to shed some light on why
customers are overwhelmingly choosing Exchange Server over Lotus
Notes,'' Malcolm said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
