<HEADER>
A5928 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      10-30 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUNTERS ARE A DYING BREED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; When Ray Bergiel of Plymouth, &UR;  &LR; Mass., takes to the woods in
the next few weeks in pursuit of his prized whitetail deer, his
prospects for success should be a bit brighter than in past years.
At least according to the numbers.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts and Maine, two of the states where Bergiel
hunts deer every fall, the trends are going his way: more deer,
fewer hunters, higher hunter success rate.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, national figures also show that while the deer herd is
growing, sometimes to annoyingly large numbers in suburban
settings, the number of hunters is on the decline, now around 16
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a change in values,'' says Bergiel, 50, who learned
hunting from his father, now 75. ``Kids today just don't see
hunting as a way of life.''
</P>
<P>
   This state has an archery season in the month of November and a
shotgun season from Nov. 30 to Dec. 13 (Dec. 5 on the Cape and
Martha's Vineyard). But the Interstate 495 beltway, which has a
large and growing deer population (up to 15 percent growth yearly),
has been developing residentially, necessitating firearms bans near
roads and houses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The winters are relatively mild in southeastern Massachusetts;
there is less hunting and predation,'' says John McDonald, director
of the Deer Project for the state's Division of Fisheries and
Wildlife. ``And people are growing lots of nutritional food for the
deer in their backyards. They love those nice shrubs.''
</P>
<P>
   The number of deer hit by cars is just one indication, says
McDonald, of the growing clash between the natural world and
development. While statewide numbers show the herd growing 6-8
percent annually, from the I-495 belt south, the growth rate is
double. In the last decade, the growth has resulted in as many as
5,000 additional deer in a statewide total of 80,000-90,000, or a
density of 16-20 deer per square mile.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't think that's out of control,'' says McDonald. ``We've
doubled the number of antlerless permits to control herd growth,
and people can tolerate the current density.''
</P>
<P>
   Except, that is, for those on Nantucket, where the deer density
on the 50-square-mile island grew to 50-60 per square mile. Aside
from the nuisance factor, the growing herd, as carriers of the Lyme
tick, were a threat to residents, who voted overwhelmingly two
years ago to expand the deer hunt on the island.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, Bergiel and his hunting friends had competition
from around 75,000 other hunters, who could expect around 10
percent sucess rate. Last year only 65,000 Massachusetts hunters
took to the woods, and the success rate, according to McDonald,
rose to 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Why such a decline in the face of more quarry? ``The World War
II generation has pretty much stopped hunting, and the baby boomers
are beginning to drop out,'' says McDonald. ``And there are fewer
and fewer 17-year-olders coming into hunting.''
</P>
<P>
   A case in point is Bergiel's 20-year-old son, who is in college.
Though he grew up sharing many shooting sports with Ray, he has
never wanted to hunt. ``I didn't want to push it on him,'' says
Bergiel. ``There's not a need to hunt today, but I just have a love
of the old ways and past traditions. Today the values have changed.
Kids are more on the soccer fields than in the woods.''
</P>
<P>
   In Maine, the largest New England state with the largest deer
herd, the trend is precisely the same. Fifteen years ago, Maine's
deer herd stood at 160,000. Today it's more than a quarter-million,
according to Jerry Lavine, a state deer biologist from Bangor.
</P>
<P>
   But the numbers of hunters _ both residents and out-of-staters _
are on the decline at a rate of 1,500 per year. ``We're at a rate
now,'' says Lavine, ``where we're losing twice as many older
hunters than we're adding new ones. At one time, we had about
200,000 hunters hunting 160,000 deer. We now have more deer than
hunters.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Maine's 180,000 hunters last year enjoyed a success rate
of 18 percent, and it's growing. Lavine says the goal of his
department is a herd of 300,000 deer, or 10 per square mile, and a
higher harvest. ``Right now, we're underharvesting the herd.''
</P>
<P>
   In the northern reaches of the state, above a line formed by
Greenville, Millinocket, and Rumford, the herd is showing no
increase. Severe winters and loss of winter habitat to logging keep
the herd from growing. But in the rest of Maine, from the farmland
along the major rivers to the suburbs along the coast, deer are
more and more in evidence, as are antifirearms laws. The Maine
season begins tomorrow and runs through Nov. 28.
</P>
<P>
   As the deer herd grows and numbers of hunters decline, Bergiel
and his friends may feel fortunate to reap the benefit of a high
success rate. But like most hunters, they feel that a way of life
is slowly slipping away with their generation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are replacing the older generation, who taught us how to
hunt, but there's no one coming along to fill our place,'' says
Bergiel. He says he enjoys all aspects of the sport: ``I enjoy the
gatherer-server kind of thing. And my friends all look forward to
coming over and having venison at my house because they can't get
it anywhere else.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
