<SLUG> BC-PRIVATE-SCHOOL </SLUG>
 PRIVATIZED SCHOOL DOMINATES BOARD ELECTION  
 (EDs: Stands for EDUCATION-POLL.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JULIAN GUTHRIE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The question of whether a for-profit company
should be allowed to run a struggling public school has become the
hot-button issue in Tuesday's San Francisco school board election.
</P>
<P>
   Both the powerful teachers union and the San Francisco Parents'
Lobby, a small watchdog group, have endorsed candidates solely on
that issue, in the hopes of preventing more takeovers of public
schools.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in San Francisco's recent history, this year
the current board, following the lead of Superintendent Bill Rojas,
allowed the for-profit Edison Project to manage a troubled
elementary school.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, there has been little discussion about what
candidates would do to improve public schools, boost academic
performance of black and Hispanic students, hire qualified teachers
or make sure very student has textbooks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest misfortune of focusing on (Edison) is that it's
dividing us and costing us the political goodwill we need to do big
reforms, like eliminating the achievement gap between ethnic
groups,'' said Dan Kelly, school board vice president and the only
incumbent endorsed by the union and parents' lobby.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the debate over Edison is not what parents are most
concerned about, according to San Francisco PTA president Carol
Kocivar. She said there are traditional issues that must be
addressed before getting to ``whatever happens to be the hot issue
of the day.''
</P>
<P>
   There are three incumbents and nine challengers vying for three
seats on the Board of Education, which manages a $550 million
annual budget and sets policy for more than 60,000 public
schoolchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Incumbents Carlota del Portillo and Kelly are seeking to retain
their seats, along with Frank Chong, who was appointed to the board
by Mayor Willie Brown in August. There are seven seats on the
board.
</P>
<P>
   Mauricio Vela, a longtime community organizer and director of
the Bernal Heights Neighborhood Center, and Eddie Chin, a lawyer
who teaches civics at City College, have emerged as the
front-running challengers. Both ran and lost in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The Parents' Lobby _ which has about 100 members and has
operated off and on since the 1970s _ and the teachers' union
endorsed Vela, Kelly and Chin because of their opposition to the
district's decision to sign a contract with the Edison Project.
</P>
<P>
   The Edison Project began running the school, now called the
Edison Charter Academy, in September. Supporters of the district's
decision say it gives the school a needed infusion of cash,
enthusiasm, new teachers and pedagogy. Critics assail it as a step
toward privatization that undermines public education.
</P>
<P>
   ``Privatization is not the only issue in this race, but it is
the most outrageous and high profile,'' said Marybeth Wallace, a
parent liaison with the child advocacy group, Coleman Advocates,
and a member of the Parents' Lobby.
</P>
<P>
   Del Portillo and Chong say the more important questions, such as
what kids are taught and how to hire and retain qualified teachers,
have been usurped by the politically divisive issue.
</P>
<P>
   Chong, a dean of student affairs at City College who graduated
from University of California at Berkeley and Harvard's Kennedy
School, was not endorsed by the parents lobby or the union because
of what Wallace called his ``foggy'' position on the Edison
Project.
</P>
<P>
   Del Portillo, the current board president who is dean of City
College's Mission campus, was not endorsed because she voted in
favor of handing the school to the Edison Project. Both the parents
lobby and the union said they see her as a rubber stamp to the
superintendent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Edison Project has been made the issue by people who know
how to act up,'' del Portillo said. ``Everyone has bought into
it.''
</P>
<P>
   If re-elected, del Portillo said she would work to reduce class
size in the fourth and fifth grades. She also wants to train
parents to be advocates for their children and focus on helping
Hispanic children do better in school.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all this ballyhoo about Edison, no one is asking how we
improve education for kids in the lowest quartile,'' del Portillo
said. ``One thing we absolutely must do is train parents to become
advocates for their children. When you do that, the whole culture
of the school changes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
