<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-30 15:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5986 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-EFFECT-2TAKES     10-30 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-EFFECT-2TAKES-$ADV1-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON-EFFECT-2TAKES-$ADV1 
 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, NOV. 1) 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ Working his way through a bowling alley in a
working-class suburb, two-term Republican Rep. Steve Chabot is
handing out plastic cups with his likeness.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to talk politics above the din, Chabot is pressed about
his views on a variety of matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is he an NRA guy?'' asks one pro-gun bowler.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is your position on smoking?'' inquires a woman sitting
with her girlfriends and puffing on a cigarette.
</P>
<P>
   ``Watch my Social Security,'' urges an older bowler.
</P>
<P>
   Only once does the the subject that has consumed Washington and
was supposed to dominate the campaign trail this election year _
the Clinton sex scandal _ come up as the candidate winds his way
through the crowded alley.
</P>
<P>
   While some voters interviewed in this southern Ohio city and
elsewhere in the country said they intend to vote Republican to
register their disgust with the president's behavior, many more say
they have been turned off by what they view as an unhealthy
obsession with the topic among the media and politicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who has been screaming, yelling, ranting raving about
moral behavior in the White House will not get my vote. If that's
all they have to talk about then they are not talking about things
that matter to me,'' said Tina Koczeniak, a 41-year old registered
Republican who was greeted outside her workplace by Chabot's
Democratic opponent, Cincinnati Mayor Roxanne Qualls.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Qualls had complained about the difficulty of
piercing the blanket coverage of the scandal. But lately she said
the situation has turned around and the scandal is barely mentioned
in her rounds of the competitive district.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Chabot sits on the House Judiciary Committee that is
scheduled to hold impeachment hearings after the election he rarely
brings up the subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't particularly want to talk about it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Back in August when Clinton first admitted to his affair with
Monica Lewinsky, Republicans salivated at the prospect of major
gains in the House and Senate. Conservatives were angry and
energized while Democrats were demoralized and appeared likely to
stay home on Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   But after House Republicans released the videotape of the
president's testimony before Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr,
public opinion began to shift as many voters complained they were
being inundated with too many salacious tidbits. Pollsters began to
detect a rising resentment at Clinton's treatment and an indication
that growing number of Democrats might head to the polls to show
their disapproval with the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   Since Congress adjourned in mid-October after voting to commence
an impeachment inquiry, the issue has largely disappeared from
front pages of the newspapers and the top of the nightly news.
</P>
<P>
   And opinion surveys suggest that the scandal will not be a major
factor in the mid-term elections on Tuesday when voters select all
435 House members, 34 senators, and 36 governors.
</P>
<P>
   Most analysts are predicting that the election will turn out the
way it typically does _ the better-financed Republicans will likely
to pick up a modest number of seats in both chambers, as the
out-of-power party traditionally does in a non-presidential
election year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The impeachment inquiry never produced that big national issue
that would lead to a substantial rejection of the president's
party,'' said Thomas Mann, a political analyst at the Brookings
Institution. ``It got trumped by a healthy economy and public
rejection of scandal as relevant to work of the president.''
</P>
<P>
   That has not stopped both parties from trying to exploit the
scandal in the closing days of the campaign as they seek to
energize their most active voters who could swing the outcome in
the closest races.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Republican Party commenced a $10 million
advertising blitz that uses the scandal _ particularly Clinton's
lying about his affair with Lewinsky _ to remind people why they
should not elect Democrats. In one ad an announcer asks, ``And
should we reward not telling the truth? That is the question of
this election. Reward Bill Clinton. Or vote Republican.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Crawford, a spokeswoman for the National Republican
Campaign Committee, said that it would have been unrealistic to
avoid the scandal in talking about this year's election.
</P>
<P>
   ``This scandal is really top of the mind for the public,'' she
said from Washington. ``If you are trying to have a discussion
about politics and you pretend it doesn't exist your message isn't
going to ring true.''
</P>
<P>
   And there certainly are those who remain hostile to the
president, including the man who confronted Chabot last week after
the candidate swept through bingo night at the Resurrection School
on Cincinnati's gritty west side.
</P>
<P>
   Upon leaving, Chabot found his car blocked by another vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   When he asked the driver to move, he retorted, ``When you
impeach the president I will move.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
