<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-30 16:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6045 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-SETTLERS-$ADV1     10-30 1475
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-SETTLERS-$ADV1-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAEL-SETTLERS-$ADV1 
 
 
ISRAELI SETTLERS SAY GIVING LAND TO PALESTINIANS IS ULTIMATE
BLASPHEMY 
 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, NOV. 1) 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DEBORAH HORAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   YITZHAR, West Bank _ Yigal Amitai sees the land of the Bible
when he looks out his kitchen window at this windswept Israeli
settlement. He points with a finger to the sites where the biblical
stories unfolded.
</P>
<P>
   On one rocky mountain, the biblical patriarch Abraham received
revelations from God, he says. In the valley of Shechem, now the
city of Nablus, Abraham's son, Jacob, is buried. Nearby, in Shilo,
the tabernacle once stood.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they establish a Palestinian state, our strategy will be to
destroy it,'' says Amitai, a 32-year-old father of seven. He has a
fuzzy brown beard and wears the knitted scullcap common to
religious settlers here.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will find ways to weaken them, to transfer the Arabs from
here,'' said Amitai. ``I have no problem with this word, transfer.
It's not a bad word. Someone must move, so it has to be them.''
</P>
<P>
   Of all the Israeli settlements on the West Bank, Yitzhar has a
reputation as one of the most extreme.
</P>
<P>
   For the 70 families living in dinky trailers and dingy yellow
houses here the agreement signed at the Wye River conference center
last month was a continuation of the ultimate blasphemy: giving
parts of the land of Israel to the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a crime that I don't forgive _ that they brought an army
of strangers inside Israel,'' said Amitai, sitting in a living room
filled with religious books and children.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's against everything the Bible says to do,'' he said. ``It
will endanger Jews and this is quite against Jewish law. It's a
crime history will not forgive.''
</P>
<P>
   Amitai's words, echoing those of many on the fringes of the
Israeli settler movement, have the Israeli government worried.
</P>
<P>
   Since the agreement was signed, Netanyahu has been bombarded
with banners _ some drenched in blood and riddled with bullets _
calling him a traitor. The scenes are all too reminiscent of the
frenzied protests that preceded the assassination of Prime Minister
Yitzhak Rabin by a right-wing Jew three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Netanyahu, Foreign Minister Ariel Sharon and Defense
Minister Yitzhak Mordechai returned from the Wye negotiations to
find the Shin Bet, the secret service charged with internal
security, recommending extra protection in response to the threats.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say the potential for violence against Palestinians or
against holy places shared by Muslims and Jews may be higher as
settlers feeling increasingly under siege, and defended by an
Israeli army that many of them describe as ``weak,'' take matters
into their own hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``The potential for violence is there,'' said Aviezer Ravitzky,
a professor of Jewish thought at Jerusalem's Hebrew University and
author of ``Messianism, Zionism and Jewish Religious Radicalism.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The extreme religious right believes this agreement is against
divine will,'' said Ravitzky.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that they are pushed to the corner, and they no
longer believe they have any representative in the government now
that Netanyahu has signed onto the peace process, makes it a
dangerous situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Though some experts say the atmosphere today is different than
it was prior to Rabin's assassination, the prospect of giving up
territory, continued Palestinian terrorism both before and after
the agreement and despondency among settlers unsure what the next
political step should be have given rise to desperate acts.
</P>
<P>
   Since August, when two young seminary students from Yitzhar were
murdered by Palestinian gunmen, the tiny mountain settlement has
been a focal point for talk of violence.
</P>
<P>
   Convinced that Palestinian farmers coming near the settlement to
pick olives were secretly casing the place in preparation for an
attack, Yitzhar's settlers have prevented any harvesting.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Hebrew daily Haaretz, when Israeli soldiers
tried to escort Palestinians to their olive groves, a settler
shouted: ``We have snipers in the trees and if any of you has the
nerve to take one step around the bend, he'll get a bullet between
the eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm prepared for one or two Arabs, innocent Arabs, being
punished when they get close to the settlement in order that not
one terrorist gets through,'' Amitai explained. ``If they bother
us, we're not going to just sit quietly and accept it.''
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in the West Bank, right-wing violence has been on the
rise. In September, a settler from Kiryat Arba was indicted for
shooting into the homes of Palestinians living in a nearby refugee
camp.
</P>
<P>
   In October, an elderly Palestinian farmer was found bludgeoned
to death outside the settlement of Itamar. And in the past few
months, several settlers have been briefly detained after calling
for violence or resistance to peace agreements.
</P>
<P>
   The attention placed on these incidents, particularly when
Palestinians have perpetrated far more violence _ including seven
murders since August_ makes many of these settlers mad.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's crazy the way everyone focuses on a few olive trees when
there's been so much terrorism from Palestinians,'' said Eli
Mendelovitch, a 27-year-old settler from Yitzhar. ``It's out of
proportion, the quantity of effort (the Israeli army) uses to chase
a few Jews who have Jewish pride instead of going after the
terrorists.''
</P>
<P>
   The reason, say observers, is that anger peaked at the time of
the Rabin assassination in the wake of the first deal to hand West
Bank land to the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Today, they say, that nasty atmosphere no longer prevails.
Demonstrations are calmer and the slanderous pictures _ of Rabin in
Arab headdress or Nazi uniform _ have not been used against
Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, many settlers say they don't feel quite the sense of
political isolation or anger that they felt when Rabin's left-wing
government seemed bent on portraying them as a lonely minority
whose beliefs were wrecking the nation's chance for peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the Rabin government, there was a feeling of deep
personal distress,'' said Rabbi Shimon Klein. The rabbi heads the
Jewish seminary of BeitEl, a 5,000-strong settlement of religious
nationalists, most of whom moved to this hilltop because of its
biblical significance.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told the settlers to go spin like propellers, said we were
only 3 percent of the nation, when we have much more support than
that,'' Klein said. ``Netanyahu doesn't ridicule us.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Israel's president, Ezer Weizman, reminded Israelis
that ``there are democratic ways to express opposition to the
agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   And in recent days, several settler leaders have appealed for
calm and lashed out in particular against the extremist elements
among them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fringe elements are causing so much tension with threats
to the (settler leadership),'' said Yehudit Tayar, a settler
spokeswoman. She referred to threats received by more moderate
settler leaders, citing one in which a bullet was left on the
windshield of a car.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of people who are very level-headed and just
want to raise a family,'' she said. ``It's unacceptable that we
have people who are trying to destroy who we are and what we're
doing.''
</P>
<P>
   But even Arutz 7, the settlers' mainstream radio station, has
been using sharp rhetoric similar to the pronouncements used when
the original peace deal arrived five years ago to denounce this
latest agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The current withdrawal agreement ... is a degradation of our
national pride, is against Jewish law and is in violation of
several biblical prohibitions,'' said one statement signed by
several settler rabbis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is (therefore) forbidden to cooperate with this terrible
agreement,'' the statement, published at Arutz 7's web site, said.
</P>
<P>
   The atmosphere is so charged that a majority of Israelis say
incitement against their leaders is on the rise. Many fear they may
be killed.
</P>
<P>
   According to a Gallup poll of 566 adult Israelis, 81 percent
think there is incitement against Netanyahu, 60 percent think there
is a possibility of political assassination and 63 percent think
Rabin's murder expressed broader political and ideological views
shared by other people.
</P>
<P>
   In Yitzhar, the settlers say only that they will protest, pray
and work to strengthen the settlement by bringing in new families.
But the air is still charged with anger and a sense of foreboding.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope (Netanyahu) will find some miraculous way to escape
from this agreement,'' said Amitai. ``I don't have an alternative.
But giving guns to the enemy is not the answer. It's a one-way
ticket to war.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Horan is a free-lance journalist based in Jerusalem. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
