<P>
   ELECTION-IMPEACH (Washington) _ Any way it goes, Tuesday's
congressional election will have a major impact on the impeachment
inquiry of President Clinton. Big Republican gains will embolden
GOP lawmakers in their conduct of the hearings. If the Democrats do
well, the process will be brief. By DAN FREEDMAN and JUDY HOLLAND.
(Already filed in the ``p,'' or POLITICAL, category.)
</P>
<P>
   HOT-RACES _ Many hot races to watch Tuesday will determine
things other than the future of Bill Clinton. They will also show
how seven scions of the nation's most prominent political families
fare, how six long-serving incumbents do and whether four women who
won Senate seats in 1992 will return to Capitol Hill to legislate
another day. By STEWART M. POWELL. (Will also be filed in the
``p,'' or POLITICAL, category.)
</P>
<P>
   TELECOM-MERGER (Washington) _ AT&AMP;T is betting heavily on
transforming TCI, the nation's No. 2 cable TV provider, into a
telecommunications giant that will break open local phone
monopolies. But many consumer groups and firms with interests in
local and long distance services, Internet access and direct
satellite broadcast are asking the government to stop the AT&AMP;T-TCI
merger. By ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-EFFECT (Cincinnati) _ Working his way through a bowling
alley, Rep. Steve Chabot is trying to talk politics above the din
of balls crashing into pins. But the two-term congressman, who
faces a tough re-election fight against Democratic Mayor Roxanne
Qualls, is only asked once about the subject that has consumed
Washington for much of the year, the sex scandal involving
President Clinton. By BENNETT ROTH. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   GOP-SOUTH (Undated) _ The Republican Party's Sherman-like march
across the South appears to have slowed, and Democrats who have
been on the run for much of the decade see a chance to stand their
ground. By JOHN C. HENRY. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   PRIEST-JUDGE (Undated) _ Convicted pedophile priest Gilbert
Gauthe has been under the protective wing of Henry Politz, the
chief judge of the 5th U.S. Circuit Court for more than 12 years.
By Gauthe's own account, Politz is his ``legal and moral''
counselor. By Politz's account, he has simply assisted a younger
man whose grandfather befriended Politz's widowed mother. Some
believe the assistance has gone too far. By EVAN MOORE.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-MURDER (Houston) _ Every day for four years the Houston
family of a John Gary Monroe, a camper slain at Big Bend National
Park, have prayed that the killer would be captured. But after an
initial promising lead failed to pan out, authorities admit they
are no closer to solving the case than they were four years ago. By
ALLAN TURNER.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SETTLER-VIOLENCE (Yizhar, West Bank) _ A visit to the eye of the
storm, a West Bank Jewish settlement where anger and a sense of
political isolation are running at a fever pitch against the
Israeli-Palestinian agreement. By DEBORAH HORAN.
</P>
<P>
   BOLIVIA-PRISONS (Cochabamba, Bolivia) _ For thousands of
Bolivians, prison is a family affair. Down-and-out wives and
children of Bolivian convicts have moved into prisons, where they
often spend years behind bars in order to survive hard economic
times. By JOHN OTIS.
</P>
<P>
   Editors: These stories for Sunday were filed earlier this week:
</P>
<P>
   COURT-IMMIGRATION (Washington) _ After a decade-long immigration
battle, the Supreme Court on Wednesday will hear Justice Department
arguments that a group of Palestinian activists with ties to a
terrorist organization should be deported. We look at the issues
raised. By MARK HELM. (Filed Thursday in the ``w'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Independence, Mo.) _ If office seekers behind
in the polls are looking for a shrine to election-year miracles,
they will find it here at 219 North Delaware Street. This is where
Harry Truman lived, and his surprise victory over Thomas Dewey set
the standard for projected losers who become ultimate winners. By
ROBERT E. THOMPSON. (Filed Wednesday in the ``k'' category.)
</P>
