<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOUTS-RELIGION-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EACH YEAR, THOUSANDS OF BOYS WIN AWARDS BASED ON THEIR RELIGION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEYVILLE, Texas _ Alex Bustillos loves camping, hiking, tying
knots and doing other things good Scouts do.
</P>
<P>
   He also takes his religion, Judaism, seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worked hard to get this,'' said Alex, proudly showing a
gold-colored Aleph badge, the Jewish religion award for Webelo
Scouts.
</P>
<P>
   He is one of thousands of Scouts _ Protestants, Catholics,
Mormons, Muslims, Hindus, Buddhists, Jews or Zoroastrians _ who win
awards through their knowledge and practice of their religious
faith.
</P>
<P>
   Faith in a higher power is a central _ and sometimes
controversial _ aspect of Scouting. Some atheists and agnostics
barred from participating in Boy Scouts have claimed
discrimination. But courts so far have backed the Boy Scouts'
insistence that members profess an allegiance to a supreme being.
</P>
<P>
   The best-known religion awards are called ``God and Me,'' ``God
and Country,'' ``God and Family'' and ``God and Church.'' But there
are many other names given to the awards by religious groups.
</P>
<P>
   Alex's award for a Webelo Scout, for example, is the ``Aleph,''
after the first letter of the Hebrew alphabet. Members of the
Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints (Mormons) receive a
``Faith in God'' medal, and Bahais earn ``Unity of Mankind''
religion awards.
</P>
<P>
   Alex, 9, was the only Jewish Scout among several Baptists,
Methodists and Lutherans who recently received religion medals in
ceremonies at First United Methodist Church of Hurst, a Fort Worth
suburb.
</P>
<P>
   To earn his award, he had to prove he helped others; give a talk
to his adviser about Bible heroes, including Noah and Abraham;
recite Hebrew blessings; memorize five of the 10 Commandments; and
explain the symbolism of objects used in Jewish holidays.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Spencer of Arlington, a member of the religious relations
committee of the Longhorn Council, which oversees 35,000 Scouts in
the regioin, says the awards don't come directly from Scouting
groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, the religious organizations provide the awards, and
we allow them to be worn on the Scout uniform,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Spencer, a Catholic, leads Boy Scout Troop 5, sponsored by the
Kiwanis Club of Arlington, and he has helped boys of various faiths
earn religion awards.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of my Scouts just earned his Bismillah award for the
Islamic faith,'' said Spencer. ``Another of my boys, who is a
Buddhist, won the Metta award.''
</P>
<P>
   Emphasis on a supreme being is an integral part of Scouting,
said Gregg Shields, a national spokesman for the Irving-based Boy
Scouts of America Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``The very first line of the Scout oath is `On my honor I will
do my best to do my duty to God ...,' '' said Shields. ``It comes
before duty to country, duty to others and duty to self.''
</P>
<P>
   But the emphasis on God has come under fire. Some atheists and
agnostics have filed suits claiming the Boy Scouts are a public
organization that discriminates on the basis of religion.
</P>
<P>
   A lower court in California ruled earlier this year that twin
brothers could not be excluded from the organization because they
didn't believe in God. But the case was appealed and the California
Supreme Court ruled that the Boy Scouts had a right to set
standards of membership.
</P>
<P>
   Also, a 1993 ruling by the U.S. Supreme Court said the Scouts
had the right to exclude a suburban Chicago youth who said he was
an agnostic.
</P>
<P>
   Margaret Downey, founder and president of the
Anti-Discrimination Support Network in Pennsylvania, said the
Scouts' religious policies will continue to be challenged.
</P>
<P>
   She joined the fray in 1992 when her son, Matthew, then 13, was
barred from a West Chester, Pa., Scout troop because he refused to
sign a statement saying he believed in God.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Scouts should come into the 20th century,'' Downey
said. ``They should be ashamed that they are spreading prejudice
and discrimination.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Timothy Gorski, an Arlington physician who is leader of the
North Texas Church of Free Thought for atheists and agnostics, says
the Boy Scouts are a ``stealth'' religious organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Scouts want to be a religious group, they should put up
a cross and declare that they are religious,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gorski has urged the United Way of Metropolitan Tarrant County
to stop giving financial support to Boy Scouts because of its
insistence that members believe in a supreme being.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Clifton, executive director of the Longhorn Council, said
one of the main benefits of the religion awards is promoting
respect for others' beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   Scouting officials depend on churches, synagogues and other
religious organizations to designate the achievements needed to
qualify for the awards, Clifton noted.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Bustillos, for example, worked with Linda Hoffman, his
Sunday School teacher at Congregation Beth-El, a Reform synagogue
in Fort Worth, to earn his Aleph medal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is an important program,'' said Hoffman. ``Even
though nobody else in his den had a clue about what being Jewish
was, they learned a lot from him.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
