<HEADLINE>
DAVIS STILL HOLDS LEAD IN CALIFORNIA RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Filed in ``a'' and ``p'' category)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ Lt. Gov. Gray Davis retains his lead over
his Republican opponent in the race to become governor of
California, according to a new survey out Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The survey of 809 likely voters shows Davis leading Attorney
General Dan Lungren 50 percent to 43 percent. Although the poll
indicates Lungren leads among voters in the Central Valley, Davis
continues to command support among women voters and self-described
independents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gray's got it,'' said Del Ali, senior vice president of
Mason-Dixon Political/Media Research of Columbia, Md., which
conducted the survey for the San Francisco Examiner from Monday
through Wednesday. ``The key thing here is that there is absolutely
no momentum on the positive side for Lungren.''
</P>
<P>
   Other polls this week also showed Davis with support among
likely voters in Tuesday's election. A Field Poll released Thursday
gave Davis a 14 percentage-point advantage over Lungren, and the
Los Angeles Times showed Davis 11 points ahead.
</P>
<P>
   But Lungren said his own polls show a much closer race, putting
him only 4 or 5 points behind Davis. The margin is close enough
that the Republican National Committee agreed to send him $400,000
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guarantee they would not send us $400,000 if we were 14
points down or 11 points down,'' Lungren said. ``I have no problem
with the sincerity of people taking these polls. But hopefully you
look at polls as what they really stand for, which are trends. And
the trends ... have been going in our direction since a week ago
Monday.''
</P>
<P>
   The poll showed voter opinion of the two candidates has changed
little over the past two weeks, with Davis slightly more popular
than Lungren.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty-one percent of voters said they had a favorable opinion of
Davis and 45 percent said they viewed Lungren favorably, despite
efforts from both sides to demonize their opponents as too extreme
for California.
</P>
<P>
   The poll has a margin of error of plus or minus 3.5 points. All
those surveyed were registered voters who said they regularly vote
in elections. Seven percent of those surveyed said they were
undecided.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have been buoyed by recent reports showing a
record-high year for absentee voting. The number of Republicans
requesting absentee ballots in the state's five largest counties is
running 16 percent higher than requests from Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Bill Jones predicted this week that 9.4
million Californians would vote in Tuesday's election, and 25
percent of them would vote by mail. In the past, absentee ballots
have favored Republican candidates, but more recent trends show
that people from all parties vote by mail because it is convenient.
</P>
<P>
   Both parties are pushing hard in the final days, with huge mail
and phone bank campaigns. Lungren said he had 89,000 volunteers
spread throughout the state ready to get voters to the polls on
Election Day, and Democrats said they would have 5,000 volunteers
on Tuesday to drive people to the polls.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
