<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
Page 1, Saturday, Oct. 31. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   G-7-BAILOUT (Washington) _ President Clinton and the other major
industrialized nations announced a series of steps Friday to stem
16 months of mounting financial turmoil around the world, giving
new powers to the International Monetary Fund to aid fundamentally
healthy countries threatened by global upheavals. By David E.
Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   PINOCHET-SPAIN (Madrid) _ The Spanish High Court ruled that
Spanish courts do have the jurisdiction to try former Chilean
President Gen. Augusto Pinochet for crimes against humanity,
seemingly opening the door to a raft of other prosecutions of
former Chilean and Argentine strongmen. By Marlise Simons.
</P>
<P>
   VATICAN-INQUISITION (ROME) _ For the first time ever, the
Vatican is conducting its own inquisition of the Inquisition. And
perhaps appropriately, the initial investigation of the Church's
centuries-long effort to root out heretics is being held behind
closed doors. By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   STARR-NEWSLEAKS (Washington) _ A federal judge cited 24
instances of alleged grand jury leaks to the news media in ordering
an investigation of whether prosecutor Kenneth Starr's office
violated secrecy rules, newly unsealed court documents revealed on
Friday. Neal Lewis. (wire summary)
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-INCUMBENT-POWER (Washington) _ More than at any time in
recent memory, this year's U.S. House races are populated with
challengers who have been woefully outspent and who lag far behind
the incumbent. By Leslie Wayne.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-WIVES (Washington) _ Candidates' spouses used to appear
in campaign ads sitting silently alongside their neatly dressed
children. This year, the wives of many candidates _ Democratic
candidates in particular _ are out in front, with greater
prominence and a new purpose. By Melinda Henneberger.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-CALIF (Los Angeles) _ Moderation is the watchword in
the Golden State this year, and Lt. Gov. Gray Davis, a 23-year
veteran of state government widely mocked as the dullest politician
in the state Democratic Party, appears on the verge of a major
victory in the campaign for governor. By Todd S. Purdum. (with
photo)
</P>
<P>
   NY-VILLAGE-PARADE (New York) _ The evolution of New York City's
Greenwich Village Halloween parade, and how it reflects changes in
the Village and gay New York. By Randy Kennedy. (with photo)
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Undated) _ The United States gross domestic product
rose 3.3 percent in the July-September quarter, considerably higher
than economists had predicted, as healthy consumer spending offset
a continued decline in exports and a lapse in business investment.
President Clinton asserted that the economy is the strongest in a
generation. By Sylvia Nasar. (with graphic)
</P>
