<HEADER>
A6144 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GHOST-STORY-2TAKES-HN     10-30 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GHOST-STORY-2TAKES </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GHOST-STORY-2TAKES 
 
AUTHORS TELL TRANSPARENT TALE OF GHOSTLY ENCOUNTERS 

</HEADLINE>
 -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARTY RACINE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ It's transparently clear: Ghosts do exist.
</P>
<P>
   You might agree after experiencing enough voices, apparitions
and unexplained movement to spook Halloween.
</P>
<P>
   The mysteries inhabit another dimension within ``Transparent
Tales: An Attic Full of Texas Ghosts'' (Best of East Texas
Publishers, $24.95) by Allan Turner and Richard Stewart. The book
will be in stores in mid-November.
</P>
<P>
   These are not flights of imagination told around shadowy
campfires or family lore handed down to impressionable children.
Turner and Stewart are Houston Chronicle reporters, and
newspapermen are cool, dispassionate gatherers of fact. From files
amassed over the years they tracked and interviewed ghost-seers and
corroborated their stories as if they were covering a flood or
investigating a public official.
</P>
<P>
   A few, Turner says, admitted they made up stories just to get
into the news.
</P>
<P>
   ``But in a preponderance of cases, Richard and I believe that
these events happened to them,'' Turner says.
</P>
<P>
   Among them were Texas Parks &AMP; Wildlife staffers who heard
footsteps in a historical San Antonio home, a museum librarian in
Angleton who reported that items were moved in an upstairs bedroom,
and an Amarillo social worker who saw ghosts at Texas A&AMP;M
University-West Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Their encounters seem beyond rational explanation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not theologians, we are not philosophers, we are not
parapsychologists,'' Turner says. ``We're reporters. Are `ghosts'
the disembodied spirits of the dear departed? Frankly, I think so,
but I don't know. Some people allude to passages of the Bible, to
demonic presences.
</P>
<P>
   ``They could be sunspots. It could be a 17th-century man
encountering radio waves. In a hundred years there may be a
physical explanation for this stuff. For now, you've got to kind of
say, what's going on here?''
</P>
<P>
   Ghosts often appear when least expected. Many claimants, in
fact, had never believed in the supernatural.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like being struck by lightning,'' Turner says.
</P>
<P>
   Sightings varied geographically.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you say that ghosts exist, then you have to say they exist
everywhere,'' says Turner. ``Whether or not they are perceived is a
matter of individual and cultural predilection. There is not a
house in New Orleans that is not haunted. Same as Galveston, with
the water, the tragedy of the Great Storm. We found Galveston
(Texas) to be very good ghost-hunting ground.''
</P>
<P>
   The reporters found Czech ghosts, Hispanic ghosts,
African-American ghosts. Then there is Turner's hometown of New
Braunfels, Texas, in what he calls the ``German belt.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They are so rational that even if ghosts were to come sit down
on your dining room table, you're going to have a logical
explanation for that. And if you tell your neighbor, they're going
to start talking about you.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did not find any German ghosts.''
</P>
<P>
   So, does Turner believe in ghosts?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm chagrined to admit it, but I would say I believe in ghosts
at this point. Now, I could be mad but probably not.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago Turner and his wife, Sarah, bought a vacation
house in Galveston several blocks from the water in the old West
End. The two-story bungalow was built in 1909 and had wrap-around
porches and leaded-glass windows.
</P>
<P>
   They closed the deal on a Friday. Sarah and daughter Charlotte
were to spend that night at a Girl Scout camp-out, while Turner
would stay in the new house alone.
</P>
<P>
   He awoke at dawn, fully alert, he says. When he ran water in the
bathroom, the old pipes vibrated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm standing back in the hallway with my hands on my hips
thinking, `Oh, no, how much is it going to cost to fix that?' This
went on for maybe 10 seconds, and literally the absolute nanosecond
that the pipe stopped, I heard a middle-aged woman's voice.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Good morning.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Good morning,'' Turner replied, naturally. The voice sounded
as if it were coming from about 10 feet away. It was there, and it
was not there.
</P>
<P>
   He charged over to the windows. It was 6:30 a.m. No one was in
the adjoining yard or on the street.
</P>
<P>
   There is a category of ghostly entities called stay-behinds,
those who so love a place that they just can't bear leaving. Turner
learned that his house was built by a tinsmith, Albert Fedder, and
his wife, Susie. He was in his early 40s, she in her late 30s, and
they had no children.
</P>
<P>
   Albert died in 1943 from a heart attack. Susie continued to live
in the house by herself until 1956, when she was 85.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were to venture to guess,'' says Turner, ``I would say
that the voice I heard was the voice of this lady. She obviously
loved this house; nieces have testified as to how this was just a
joyous place.''
</P>
<P>
   One trigger for ghostly encounters seems to be a change of
ownership of a business or home. Over the next year, weed-trimmer
twine mysteriously appeared in an upstairs suitcase, an antique
clock on the fireplace mantel changed time and double pocket doors
in the hallway moved _ unseen _ without assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Turner found himself trying to communicate.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't know how silly you can be until you're standing in
an empty house talking to the air,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Then the woman's voice returned. Possibly. He was running water
in the bathroom when he detected a whispery ``Bye ... bye.'' But he
has to qualify that; children were making noise in the street;
water was running. Nothing out of the ordinary has happened since.
</P>
<P>
   But there remained a presence. Whenever the house creaked at
night, Turner would turn on the lights.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt completely ridiculous. It's the fear of the unknown,
because you don't know what you're dealing with.''
</P>
<P>
   So he attempted to strike a deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly we have a reality gap here,'' Turner told ``Susie.''
``Please don't scare the kid, and if you don't mind, make your
appearances during daylight hours.''
</P>
<P>
   It was about 10:30 at night when Turner called Stewart to ask if
he wanted to contribute to a ghost book.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' Stewart replied. ``Have I ever told you about Aunt
Alice?''
</P>
<P>
   What he related gave Turner the chills.
</P>
<P>
   In the summer of 1969 Stewart was between his sophomore and
junior years at the University of Houston. He traveled to Spain,
where his father, like many Americans who worked in the oil
industry in Algeria, kept an apartment in Palma de Mallorca, an
island village in the Mediterranean. The flat was in a
Canadian-American enclave at the end of a street.
</P>
<P>
   It was a great place to be 20 years old. But somewhat spooky,
too. Late at night a big wind blew down from the mountains and
rattled open the glass doors of Stewart's bedroom, billowing the
sheer blue inner curtains into his face. So on the third night he
shut the doors and shoved his heavy wooden bed up against them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get in bed, and I'm a big guy. I go to sleep and something's
tickling my nose, and I reach up to get it, and it's fabric; it's
those curtains. I jump out of bed, turn on the light and that bed
has moved three feet with me in it. That scared the bejesus out of
me. I never stayed in that room again.''
</P>
<P>
   He did, however, keep his valuables there in a nightstand
drawer. ``I'd walk past that room and that stuff would be on top of
that table. Never anything missing. I'd say, why did I drag that
out? I'd put it back in the drawer. Then a week or two later it'd
happen again. I never liked that room.''
</P>
<P>
   A number of teen-age girls in the neighborhood liked to play
with a Ouija board, seeking telepathic messages through its
alphabet and other symbols. One night Stewart and the girls were
doing the Ouija and it said ``burn, burn, burn.'' It then spewed
out some nasty things that embarrassed them all.
</P>
<P>
   The next night the girls' mother, a ``seer'' from Calgary,
Canada, and an Englishwoman were in the next apartment trying to
contact spirits. There was no answer until Stewart dropped in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is anybody there?'' they asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes.'' The Ouija spelled out A-L-I-C-E. Stewart's Aunt Alice
had died in a fire two years earlier. They were close; like him,
she had studied journalism at the University of Houston. As Stewart
would later do, his aunt had worked for the Houston Chronicle and
the Bay City Tribune. Ask the spirit its last name, Stewart
suggested. It spelled M-R-A-Z.
</P>
<P>
   ``And these ladies kind of look at this thing, and one of them
grabs a pointer and moves it around and says, `Well, sometimes it
messes up. We'll try it again.' I said, well, no; her last name was
Mraz. It spelled it right.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ouija knew Alice's middle name, Helen, and gave nicknames
his aunt used.
</P>
<P>
   ``It went on from there to be almost like a conversation with
her. I could even think things, and the answer would come that made
sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, this is my mother's sister, not my dad's, and neither of
these women had ever been to Texas. How they would have known that
I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ouija transmitted a warning about ``Nona's blue lady.''
Nona, the Canadian's 7-year-old daughter, often complained that a
woman wearing blue would appear to her at night. ``You were with
someone very evil last night,'' the board told Stewart, presumably
relating to the spirit that had said ``burn, burn, burn.''
</P>
<P>
   About a year after returning from Spain, Stewart recounted the
story at a dinner party. A woman suggested that Aunt Alice and the
blue lady were the same, that as Alice struggled to escape a house
fire, in which she died from smoke inhalation, her psyche split in
half, a good one (Aunt Alice) and a bad one (the blue lady).
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember driving home after that party,'' Stewart says.
``One of those deals where you don't want to look in the mirror
because you're afraid you'll see Aunt Alice in the back seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Or worse, two Aunt Alices.''
</P>
<P>
   Back in his apartment, Stewart for the first time noticed that
his room had the same sheer blue curtains he had in Spain. He went
to sleep and fell into a dream. He dreamed a woman was in his bed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wake up and there is. She's wearing a blue gown. I push on
her, roll onto my back and she's standing at the foot of my bed,
laughing, and it isn't ha-ha-ha; it's this wanton laugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could see her very clearly. There was a good deal of light
coming in from the street. Then she disappeared like a mist. I
jumped and turned on the light.''
</P>
<P>
   He never saw the blue lady again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, 30 years later almost, I can just about persuade myself
that the whole thing in Houston was a dream, except that I could
swear that I woke up and saw her.''
</P>
<P>
   He has no explanation for the Ouija encounter. He and Turner and
Houston Chronicle computer columnist Dwight Silverman _ not the
likeliest trio of occultists _ tried to re-contact Aunt Alice on
the board. They got nowhere, Stewart says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think maybe you have to be 20 years old and it has be with
an Englishwoman and a Canadian woman and it has to be in Spain.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
