<DOCNO> NYT19981030.0209 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-30 16:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6147 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELECTION-IMPEACH-1STL     10-30 1150
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELECTION-IMPEACH-1STLD-2TAKES-$ADV01-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPEACHMENT BECOMES A GALVANIZING ISSUE ON ELECTION DAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Nov. 1)   (EDs: ADDs quotes on Democratic ad blitz, other edits; filed in the
``w'' and ``p'' categories)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN and JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It was being called the ``Seinfeld election,''
something about nothing, a midterm yawner void of any galvanizing
national issue.
</P>
<P>
   But the launching of a last-minute Republican advertising blitz
highlighting the Monica Lewinsky sex scandal changed all that. No
longer a sleeper, this election will set the stage for the
impeachment inquiry of President Clinton, who is accused of lying
and using his power to cover up his affair with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Any way it goes, the congressional election will have a major
impact on the impeachment process. With hearings likely to begin a
few weeks after Tuesday's balloting, leaders of both political
parties say they'll be happy to either gain a few seats or not lose
too many.
</P>
<P>
   Republican gains would embolden GOP lawmakers in their conduct
of impeachment hearings. If the Democrats do well in races for the
House and Senate or lose only a few seats, ``the hearings will be
brief,'' said political scholar Thomas Mann of the Brookings
Institution, an independent Washington-based think tank.
</P>
<P>
   Orchestrated by House Speaker Newt Gingrich, the $10-million
television effort is aimed at 30 districts, many in the South and
rural areas where animosity to Clinton runs high. The goal:
Energize conservatives disappointed by GOP budget compromises two
weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, however, say the backfire potential is so high that
the ads and ensuing news coverage might help bring out their
voters. Late last week, the Democratic National Committee announced
a $1 million ad blitz of its own. The aim is to convince voters
that Republicans are scandal-obsessed while Democrats want to move
forward on issues such as education and reining in managed care
health plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very obvious Republicans have said we can't win on the
issues, therefore let's try to gin up our hard-right, narrow base
with attack ads,'' said DNC national chairman Roy Romer, the
governor of Colorado. ``They're obsessed with investigations. I'm
glad our party is obsessed with education.''
</P>
<P>
   The dueling ad campaigns ``open up a Pandora's box of
uncertainty,'' said Curtis Gans, president of the nonpartisan
Committee for the Study of the American Electorate. Before they
aired, he added, ``we were heading into a low-turnout election.''
Still, Gans estimated turnout in the range of 36-to-38 percent of
eligible voters, down from the 38.8 percent turnout in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   While candidates on the home turf may be talking about abortion,
health care and other issues, the ads put impeachment on the
electoral map as perhaps the closest thing there is to a
galvanizing national issue.
</P>
<P>
   The party controlling the White House always faces an uphill
battle in midterm elections. The last time the president's party
did not loose seats was 1934, just as President Franklin D.
Roosevelt, a Democrat, was launching the New Deal.
</P>
<P>
   All 435 House seats are up, but only 50 to 60 are considered
competitive. Many of those are taking place in 34 districts where
the incumbent is retiring, leaving an open seat. The open seats are
evenly split _ 17 belonged to Republicans and 17 to Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Ninety-four incumbents are in uncontested races. Another 240 are
expected to be re-elected. Republicans now control the House
228-206, with one independent who generally votes.
</P>
<P>
   In June, Democrats appeared gleeful that the 11 seats needed to
retake the House seemed within reach. Now they concede that
scenario is virtually impossible. Democratic Congressional Campaign
Committee executive director Matt Angle predicted ``plus five or
minus five'' for the party's candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Linder, R-Ga., chairman of the National Republican
Congressional Committee, predicted the Republicans would gain
between 10 and 15 seats.
</P>
<P>
   Both parties will watch whether House votes last month for or
against the impeachment inquiry resolutions affect incumbents'
re-election bids.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-four Senate seats are up for grabs. With Republicans in
control 55-45, Democrats are given virtually no chance of retaking
control of the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are unlikely to pick up the five needed to reach 60,
a number that would enable them to defeat Democratic filibusters
that can kill legislation. More probable is that the Republicans
will gain two to three seats in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Gender is less of an issue this year than in 1992, dubbed ``the
year of the woman'' because of strong electoral gains by women.
Sen. Carol Moseley-Braun, D-Ill., elected in 1992, has been
entangled in scandals ever since. She looks to be a goner.
</P>
<P>
   In California, after a tumultuous struggle against Republican
challenger Matt Fong, incumbent Sen. Barbara Boxer is ahead in the
polls. And in Washington state, self-proclaimed ``mom-in-tennis
shoes'' Sen. Patty Murray, another Democrat elected in 1992,
appears to be headed for a slim victory over Republican Rep. Linda
Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Among the other hot races:
</P>
<P>
   _ In Kentucky, the Senate seat vacated by retiring Sen. Wendell
H. Ford, a Democrat, is a tossup between Rep. Scotty Baesler, a
Democrat, and Republican Rep. Jim Bunning.
</P>
<P>
   _ In New York, the mudbath between Republican Sen. Alfonse M.
D'Amato and his Democratic challenger, Rep. Charles E. Schumer,
remains close. Most polls put Schumer slightly ahead.
</P>
<P>
   _ In Wisconsin, it's too close to call between Democratic
incumbent Sen. Russ Feingold, and Republican Rep. Mark Neumann. One
late poll shows Neumann moving ahead.
</P>
<P>
   _ In North Carolina, Republican Sen. Lauch Faircloth is in a
tight race against trial attorney John Edwards. Faircloth's poll
numbers are slipping, making him one of the few vulnerable
incumbent Republicans this November.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Republicans outdistanced Democrats in campaign
fund-raising. Democratic Party national committees raised $106.9
million, a 40 percent increase over the last midterm election in
1994. But they have a debt of $11.1 million, much of it left over
from the 1996 campaign. Their Republican counterparts raised $184.6
million and have a debt of $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans also beat Democrats in the war for ``soft'' money,
contributions for party building and voter turnout that are not
subject to Federal Election Commission limitations. Soft money
mostly winds up financing not-to-subtle party television
commercials that endorse candidates without specifically soliciting
votes.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans took in $93.7 million in soft money, a 144 percent
increase over 1994. Democrats received $78.8 million, an 84 percent
increase.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE ... MORE)
</P>
<P>
   The secret of the GOP's success: Business contributions.
Business interests have given Republicans $262 million, according
to research by the non-partisan Center for Responsive Politics.
Business also gave Democrats $198 million.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the race, the election this year is less about winning
converts than it is about getting out loyal followers and hoping
opponents' supporters take the day off.
</P>
<P>
   Ross Baker, a political science professor at Rutgers University,
compared it to the staunch loyalty of pickup truck drivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not anything that will make a Chevy pickup driver
drive a Ford,'' he said. ``But dealers still have the task of
getting them to dealership to buy their products every few years.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The AFL-CIO is spending $28 million, mostly to elect Democrats.
Some $14 million of that is for an on-the-ground campaign involving
telephone banks, leaflets at factory gates, union meetings and 392
organizers agitating to get organized labor's vote in 75 races.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our sense was that politics had become completely
impersonal,'' said AFL-CIO political director Steven Rosenthal.
``We thought we could personalize it on the ground better than we
could on TV.''
</P>
<P>
   Also within the $28 million is $7 million for television
advertising, most of it geared to issues such as saving Social
Security and reining in managed health care. In 1996, the AFL-CIO
put most of its massive $35 million war chest into television
commercials.
</P>
<P>
   Organized labor also is contributing $35 million to Democratic
candidates. But money alone may not do it for labor. The AFL-CIO
gave $40 million to Democrats in 1994, the year Republicans took
control of Congress in an election widely interpreted as a
rejection of Clinton's first two years in office.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, not only did the Republican voter turnout surge, but
the number of Democrats heading to the polls declined. (Overall in
midterm congressional elections, turnout has declined since 1966,
falling from 48.6 percent that year to 38.8 percent in 1994.)
</P>
<P>
   Republicans and their supporters also are concentrating on
turnout. Linder said the campaign committee committed $5 million to
a get-out-the-vote drive, with $300,000 of that targeted to
absentee balloting in California.
</P>
<P>
   The Christian Coalition is spending $3.1 million to distribute
45 million copies of its ``non-partisan'' voter guide in churches,
advising supporters on candidates' views on issues such as abortion
and school prayer.
</P>
<P>
   The Campaign for Working Families, a conservative political
action committee, is spending about $3 million on more than 200
candidates and on promotions to boost voter turnout.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-30-98 1652EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
