<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-30 17:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6180 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTHORS-WILLIAMS-SPI &LR;      10-30 1400
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHORS-WILLIAMS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW BIOGRAPHY SHEDS LIGHT ON `MR. CIVIL RIGHTS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN MARSHALL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   School children do not memorize his words or sketch his
portrait. Holiday festivities do not honor his birthday with
parades or sermons. That he was once widely known as ``Mr. Civil
Rights'' is largely forgotten now as Thurgood Marshall has quickly
faded behind the curtain of history.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Williams aims to change that. The 44-year-old national
correspondent for The Washington Post has marshaled compelling
evidence that Thurgood Marshall is the most important figure in the
struggle for equal rights in 20th-century America.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall is far less well-known than the Rev. Martin Luther King
Jr. or Malcolm X, who both were assassinated young and soon
canonized, but Marshall's accomplishments, in Williams' view,
outstrip those of the two other historic black leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is important for people to have a sense of heroes and how
they affect social change and shifts in power,'' Williams said in
an interview. ``Marshall is, to my mind, the personification of how
power in race relations and individual rights shifted in the 20th
century.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams argues Marshall's case in his compelling new biography,
``Thurgood Marshall: American Revolutionary'' (Times Books, 404
pages, $27.50). This is a full-blooded account of a remarkable man
with an outsized, multifaceted personality _ a driven crusader,
committed pathfinder, cantankerous dissenter and an unrestrained
raconteur who possessed prodigious appetites for bourbon, women,
tobacco and song.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall may not be the sort of antiseptic leader that seems the
ideal in these times of rigid political and moral correctness. But
there is nothing idealized about Marshall's accomplishments, which
are written into the law of the land as a result of his
barrier-busting work as the point-man attorney for the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People. He won a
phenomenal 29 of the 32 cases he argued before the U.S. Supreme
Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``Separate but equal'' schools were outlawed because of
Marshall's work in the landmark Brown vs. Board of Education case
in 1954 from Kansas. All-white primary elections were outlawed
because of Marshall's work in a 1944 case from Texas. Segregated
facilities in interstate travel were outlawed because of Marshall's
work in a 1946 case from Virginia. Restrictive real estate
covenants against blacks and Jews were outlawed because of
Marshall's work in a 1948 case from Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   All this was accomplished by the time Marshall was 46, and
almost 15 years before he was named the first black justice on the
Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   As a young lawyer in Baltimore, Marshall had hoped to become a
local judge, though no blacks held that position. So being named to
the high court was the capstone of a lifetime's work in law, which
also had seen him become the first black on the U.S. Court of
Appeals and the first black solicitor general, the top attorney
arguing for the government.
</P>
<P>
   But as Williams persuasively illustrates, it was Marshall's work
on the high court that would, ironically, cost him much of his
hard-earned reputation. His ego was so wrapped up in being a
Supreme Court justice that Marshall hung on to the post for 24
years, long after he could render useful service.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall became an embittered and reclusive figure, beset by the
afflictions of old age, given to outlandish public comments,
castigated for his lazy work habits, one of two embattled liberals
on the high court as it took a hard right in the Reagan era.
</P>
<P>
   It was during Marshall's waning days that he sat down with a
young reporter for The Washington Post, who was hoping to write a
profile for the paper's magazine. Williams still can readily recall
how he ``felt like Dorothy going to see the Wizard'' as he trudged
up the Supreme Court's broad marble steps, passed through its
imposing columns, entered its hushed mahogany world where he
expected the justice to check him out.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Marshall embarked immediately on the interview, then
invited the surprised Williams back for another interview.
Interviews continued on a weekly basis for six months, as he came
to know Marshall well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, he was a man in some distress,'' Williams recalled.
``I think Marshall was an emotionally depressed man who felt
forgotten and unappreciated and misunderstood. Often, he would tear
up when he tried to read some paper right in front of his face
because of advancing glaucoma. He also had to go to the bathroom
frequently, where he walked with difficulty, using his cane and
wearing support stockings. Yes, he was definitely an old man.
</P>
<P>
   ``But Marshall remained a wonderful storyteller. At first, I was
reluctant to argue with him because I did not want to piss him off.
But I pretty soon learned that Marshall still loved to debate, as
he always had.''
</P>
<P>
   Marshall was pleased with Williams' profile when it finally was
published, but the reporter's attempt to turn his material into a
book met with a stone wall from the subject as well as his family
and compatriots. Many seemed concerned about what a full-scale
examination of Marshall's life might reveal, perhaps to the
detriment of his legacy.
</P>
<P>
   Williams persisted. He had already honed his book-writing skills
with his best-selling companion volume to the civil rights series
on television, ``Eyes on the Prize.'' But Williams soon found
himself riddled with doubts as he confronted the years of work and
other demands of writing a biography of such a historic figure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The times I thought about quitting were when I considered how
much material there was and how rich a story it was,'' Williams
remembered. ``Then my question was: Can I actually do this? I had
always thought my journalistic skills could get me through things,
but suddenly I found myself set adrift in an ocean of information,
much of it legalistic, and with characters from all the way back to
before the turn of the century.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams' fascinating account of Marshall's life is particularly
strong in portraying his roots, the effects of his middle-class
upbringing in a racially mixed Baltimore neighborhood, and a strong
mother so intent on having her two sons succeed that she pawned her
engagement and wedding rings in order for Thurgood to enroll in law
school at all-black Howard University in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall helped pay for his education by working as a railroad
porter and as a waiter at an all-white country club on Chesapeake
Bay, jobs also held at various times by his father, who only had a
fourth-grade education.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Marshall's rise also owed much to the intervention of fate
and key people at crucial moments in his life. Marshall was a
hell-raising frat boy as an undergraduate until a truck accident
cost him one testicle and imparted new seriousness to his life _
this at a time when he increasingly came under the activist
influence of fellow student Langston Hughes.
</P>
<P>
   ``What captured my mind about Marshall,'' Williams said, ``was
sensing how this character grew. This was not somebody who was
obviously marked a great man from the time he was a baby. He lived
in circumscribed circumstances as a child, and only much later
started to flower.''
</P>
<P>
   Marshall was at the peak of his powers in the 1940s and 1950s, a
relentless force for change as the NAACP's crusading attorney. He
fearlessly carried the cause to hostile Southern towns, despite
frequent threats and attempts at intimidation, including a close
encounter with death in a car where he was surrounded by angry
white men taking him down a dark country lane in Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall's belief in the crucial importance of legal change kept
him motivated, as did his bedrock sense that integration was the
essential ingredient in achieving racial equality.
</P>
<P>
   So when much younger black leaders came to challenge those
assumptions with sit-ins or marches in the streets or cries of
``Black power!'' Marshall was not sympathetic. Until his death in
1993 at the age of 84, Marshall was convinced that his way of
challenging the law was the best way to affect social change.
</P>
<P>
   As Williams emphasized, ``This was an extraordinarily willful
man who had a strong, clear vision of what he wanted done, and he
went after it and he did it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
