<HEADLINE>
STIPE SAYS `UP' SENDING R.E.M. IN NEW DIRECTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GENE STOUT  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   R.E.M.'s new album, ``Up,'' could have been titled ``Upside
Down'' or ``Inside Out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What you're hearing on this record is the sound of a band
mutating faster than it should be,'' lead singer Michael Stipe said
in a phone interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little like going from chrysalis to butterfly, but
skipping a few steps in between.''
</P>
<P>
   Work on ``Up,'' released this week on Warner Bros. Records, was
under way last fall when original drummer Bill Berry suddenly quit
the group that Stipe described as a ``four-cornered powerhouse.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd been a four-piece for longer than most bands. We'd been
together for 17 years. And to have one guy leave really upset the
balance,'' Stipe said.
</P>
<P>
   Berry, who had also served as background singer, songwriter and
occasionally bassist, had his reasons for leaving the group he had
helped found in 1980 in Athens, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   While on tour, Berry had suffered a life-threatening fever in
Germany in 1989 and a brain hemorrhage in Switzerland in 1995.
Unlike the others in the band, Berry didn't like being away from
the comforts of home.
</P>
<P>
   Devastated by his departure, Stipe, bassist Mike Mills and
guitarist Peter Buck, who lives in Seattle with his wife and twin
daughters, nevertheless continued to work on R.E.M.'s 11th studio
album with a disorienting sense of freedom.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were embarking on a very experimental record as a
three-piece for the first time ever, and without one of our core
songwriters and core group members present,'' Stipe said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Initially, it really tore us apart. But it brought us back
together in the end. I don't think we've ever been closer as
working musicians and as friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Known for its uncompromising integrity and lyrical brilliance,
R.E.M. had begun to experiment in the studio months before Berry
announced his retirement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had 40-odd song tracks recorded on demo tapes that had no
drums, that were all done with drum machines and very little
guitar,'' Stipe said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the songs had synthesizers and keyboards and string
patches. So it was an experimental record to begin with,'' Stipe
said. ``It became even more so after Bill left and the dynamic of
our entire working lives completely changed.''
</P>
<P>
   In the studio, Stipe, Buck and Mills played musical chairs,
switching instruments and bringing in various musical guests.
Playing drums were Joey Waronker (of Beck's band) and Barrett
Martin (of Screaming Trees and co-founder with Buck of Seattle
group Tuatara).
</P>
<P>
   Providing a lot of guidance was co-producer Pat McCarthy, who
had engineered 1996's ``New Adventures in Hi-Fi'' and 1994's
``Monster.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What Pat brought to the album is what any great producer
brings to a project,'' Stipe said. ``He was able to provide an
objective outside opinion, yet still be in the creative swirl.''
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy and the group worked on the album for months, recording
in Seattle, San Francisco, New York and Athens, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sonically, Peter and Mike were responding to our last record,
`New Adventures in Hi-Fi,' which was very much a live,
in-the-studio album,'' Stipe said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they felt like they had done the guitar-drum-bass
thing as well as they could. And they kind of naturally went off in
a different direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Stipe regards ``New Adventures in Hi-Fi'' as R.E.M.'s best
album. ``It was very much an album with a rock-group feel, and it's
a record that we're all really proud of,'' Stipe said.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge was to make ``Up,'' which is available in a
limited-edition package including a 48-page booklet, an even better
record.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hold `New Adventures in Hi-Fi' in such high esteem,'' Stipe
said. ``I really wanted to do as good as or better than that
record, and I feel like I accomplished that. I'm very, very proud
of the new record. I think, in a way, the songs are smarter than I
am.''
</P>
<P>
   Stipe packed such songs as ``Lotus,'' ``Hope'' and the album's
first single, ``Daysleeper,'' with power and emotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted the emotions and the feeling of the songs to be as
extreme as possible,'' he said. ``If they were sad songs, I wanted
them to be really sad. And if they were hopeful songs, I wanted
them to make you jump up and grab somebody and shake them. I just
wanted the record to be direct.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, R.E.M. made a rare two-night appearance on ``The Late
Show With David Letterman.'' Last night, MTV aired an hourlong
concert taped last week at New York's Bowery Ballroom.
</P>
<P>
   The group is also scheduled to appear next month on ``Late Night
With Conan O'Brien'' and ``Rosie O'Donnell'' and in January on
``Sesame Street.''
</P>
<P>
   In mid-October, R.E.M. performed with Neil Young at the annual
Bridge School benefit in the Bay area. Stipe, Mills and Buck were
joined by Seattle musicians Scott McCaughey of the Young Fresh
Fellows and the Minus 5 and Ken Stringfellow of the Posies.
</P>
<P>
   McCaughey (who has toured with R.E.M.) and Stringfellow are also
doing promotional shows with the band this week in England and in
early November on the European continent.
</P>
<P>
   But aside from random performances, R.E.M. has decided not to
tour in support of ``Up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``None of us felt like tying ourselves up for a year on the
road,'' Stipe said. ``And it doesn't seem like the most opportune
time to see the band. I don't think we would have had all pistons
firing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
