<DOCNO> NYT19981030.0222 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-30 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6225 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      10-30 1085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROSPERITY MAY CARRY D'AMATO YET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Advance for Sunday)   use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Alfonse D'Amato is the Howard Stern of the US Senate,
a coarse, abrasive, in-your-face New Yawky character whose
behavior, and personality, I find it hard to believe, could survive
the election process in any other state.
</P>
<P>
   For 18 years, the self-proclaimed ``Senator Pothole'' bragged of
his ability to commandeer pork in D.C. and drag it back home. And
in crude, caveman-ish fashion, he did a lot of that. He also has a
habit of surviving close elections, despite a style resembling that
of the most offensive taxi cab operator who ever hijacked an
out-of-towner at La Guardia.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato won by an eyelash six years ago against a docile
Democrat, Robert Abrams, who could not adapt to the kind of
scorched-earth campaign it takes to win in New York. D'Amato is now
swallowing some of the same kind of napalm he is fond of spraying,
and US Representative Charles Schumer, who's been in the House as
long as D'Amato's been in the Senate, has edged ahead in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   I once asked George Mitchell what pleasures he anticipated on
retiring from the Senate: ``Not having to listen to Al D'Amato''
was the first thing off Mitchell's lips. The distinctive voice of
the grim D'Amato can shift from a groan to a wheeze faster than the
drop of an insult. If there were a Junkyard Dog Award for the
Senate's nastiest campaigner, Senator Pothole would have retired
the trophy by now.
</P>
<P>
   But as a scrappy politico willing to go to the wall, over the
wall, through the wall, even if that wall is the wall of good
taste, he has no equal. So Schumer has plowed $13 million into a
yearlong, take-no-prisoners campaign of his own that may still fall
short of toppling the Senate's most abrasive individual.
</P>
<P>
   By trumpeting his push for more federal money for breast cancer,
and his knuckling Swiss banks for $1.25 billion for Holocaust
survivors, D'Amato hoped to submerge his absurdly high negative
ratings. A New York Times/CBS poll gave D'Amato 27 percent
favorablity to 36 percent unfavorability; Schumer's numbers were 22
favorable, 18 unfavorable.
</P>
<P>
   The Bay State handwringers who decried the interruptions and
talking-over-the-other-guy of the Cellucci-Harshbarger debate would
have fainted in front of their TV sets during the last
D'Amato-Schumer slugfest. ``Gentlemen, gentlemen _ this is getting
out of hand,'' said moderator Gabe Pressman, referee of many an
11th-hour Manhattan television set-to.
</P>
<P>
   In a meeting with Jewish voters, D'Amato defamed Schumer with a
Yiddish vulgarism, ``putzhead.'' When word got out, D'Amato first
issued a stammering denial, then was forced to admit the slur, and
his sputtering eventual admission was appropriated into a Schumer
campaign commercial. ``D'Amato _ too many lies for too long,'' or,
``After 18 years, when will the hypocrisy stop?'' are taglines for
Schumer TV spots. And D'Amato played right into that.
</P>
<P>
   The senator also called US Representative Jerrold Nadler ``Jerry
Waddler'' in a demeaning jibe at that Democrat's considerable
girth. These episodes came atop resentment over D'Amato's shameless
exploitation of the Holocaust _ claiming spuriously that Schumer, a
Jew who lost relatives in Nazi death camps, is insensitive to that
cataclysmic event. There are apparently some gambits that even the
jaded New York electorate will not tolerate. And playing games with
the Holocaust seems to be one.
</P>
<P>
   All this cost D'Amato some Jewish votes. D'Amato will win big
upstate, and Schumer will win big in New York City, where about 30
percent of voters live. D'Amato leads among whites, trails among
minorities and the elderly. The popular governor, George Pataki, is
touring with the senator, and D'Amato's negative ads cast Schumer
as a ``Brooklyn liberal Democrat'' with all the anti-New York City
baggage that implies.
</P>
<P>
   The race will be decided in the suburbs. Because New York is
still relatively Clinton-friendly, both the president and Al Gore
were to make last-minute hits for Schumer.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato opposes abortion on demand and gun control. These two
hot-button issues merge with the ghastly sniper assassination in a
Buffalo suburb of Dr. Barnett Slepian, a doctor who provided his
patients with abortions. Slepian was slain in his kitchen on the
night he came home from a Jewish remembrance service for his
father. Democrats think that will hurt -D'Amato.
</P>
<P>
   It's also get-even time for Hillary Clinton. D'Amato chaired
Senate hearings investigating Whitewater, till his radar picked up
the beginning of the backlash in the Empire State. Hillary, now
arguably the most popular Democratic campaigner in the land, made
several campaign trips for Schumer, a leading gun control advocate.
Knocking off D'Amato would give Clinton &AMP; Clinton a warm, fuzzy
feeling election night, no matter what else happens.
</P>
<P>
   But D'Amato is also the Freddy Krueger of the Senate; he won by
a sliver last time out, and it is widely believed in New York that
he gets votes from people who don't like telling pollsters they're
for this abrasive, divisive figure. He'll outspend Schumer down the
stretch. As chairman of the Banking Committee, he had little
difficulty collecting $22 million in ``contributions.''
</P>
<P>
   If he gets knocked off, Texas Senator Phil Gramm inherits the
chairmanship, and along with it, the lion's share of the mother
lode of campaign cash that is funneled to the Banking Committee's
top dog.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudy Giuliani is back in bed with Senator Pothole. In '94,
Rudy said, ``If the D'Amato crew ever get control, ethics will be
smashed'' in New York politics. Now? Rudy's with Al.
</P>
<P>
   New York's economic boom was exaggerated by the explosion of
wealth on Wall Street, and D'Amato bathes in that lingering
economic glow. At dusk last Saturday night near the spruced-up
Times Square, I walked past a gentleman clad in oversize Army
fatigues, combat boots, hair down to his shoulders. He was clearly
under the weather due to some sort of chemical ingestion, because
he held himself partially erect only by keeping one arm stiffly
propped against the fender of a parked car. But he was not so far
gone he could not mumble into the cell phone plastered to his ear.
</P>
<P>
   When even the homeless-looking guys have cell phones, that's
prosperity. If D'Amato survives, he'll have prosperity to thank.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-30-98 1716EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981030.0223 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-30 17:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6228 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT-$ADV01-COX     10-30 0942
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-$ADV01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GATES EMBODIES A MACHIAVELLIAN PRINCE AT MICROSOFT TRIAL
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories for
release Sunday, Nov. 1.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ To comprehend what's taking place at the federal
antitrust trial of Microsoft Corp., it's handy to be up on both the
latest workings of cyberspace and the dowdy universe of antitrust
law. But to get the full flavor of the historic trial, which enters
its third week Monday, you'll need to blend in the politics of the
Italian Renaissance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is necessary for a prince, who wishes to maintain himself,
to learn how not to be good, and to use this knowledge and not use
it, according to the necessities of the case,'' Niccolo Machiavelli
wrote in ``The Prince.''
</P>
<P>
   Fast-forward nearly five centuries and you'll recognize the
business philosophy of software prince Bill Gates. In 23 years,
Gates has parlayed Microsoft's Windows monopoly for personal
computers into a leviathan whose stock is worth $260 billion,
trailing General Electric by only a few billion on the leader
board.
</P>
<P>
   The flood of once-secret documents pouring out of the trial
depicts Gates _ who could retire in his early 40s to a princely
life on just a fraction of the interest on his $58 billion wealth _
as a hands-on boss. ``Bill's blessing,'' as one e-mail that popped
up at the trial puts it, means it's a cinch that a proposed deal
would move forward.
</P>
<P>
   But the slew of electronic messages also reveal a dark edge to
Gates.
</P>
<P>
   There was, for example, the time he ``just exploded'' at
Tele-Communications Inc. Chairman John Malone ``as part of their
scheduled one-on-one meeting, threatening to bury this company, buy
up (rival) cable operators, and do whatever it took to crush At
Home, since we are obviously so anti-Microsoft that it's
criminal.''
</P>
<P>
   That 1996 e-mail from a senior official of At Home, a high-speed
Internet provider partly owned by TCI, was put into evidence to
bolster the federal claim that Microsoft has sought to use its
Windows-based market dominance to pressure its many business
partners to standardize on its own Internet Explorer browser.
</P>
<P>
   In this instance, the Gates tirade had a happy ending: Microsoft
and At Home have since formed a strong working partnership _ one
that calls for Microsoft's Windows CE software to run At Home's
cable set-top boxes. Moreover, that alliance has matured even
though Netscape Communications Corp. chief executive Jim Barksdale,
the government's opening witness at the trial, sits on At Home's
board.
</P>
<P>
   On a broader plane, the episode illuminates how in the
fast-paced, high-tech corporate arena, ``strategic alliances'' form
only to eventually fail when competitive juices start to flow.
Similarly, bitter rivalries are quickly set aide whenever common
opportunities for market shares and profits suddenly appear on the
horizon.
</P>
<P>
   Shifting alliances has been an underlying theme at trial. An
America Online executive testified last week how AOL dumped its
browser deal with Netscape when, as a colleague put it, Microsoft
``made us an offer we couldn't refuse.'' But Microsoft's lawyers
also noted that AOL is now back in bed with Netscape in developing
another deal for so-called instant messaging services, an Internet
text version of a phone conversation.
</P>
<P>
   The overall portrait of Silicon Valley business life that
emerges from the trial perfectly suits the city-states of the
Italian Renaissance _ a time when rulers would often hold out olive
branches to their wary neighbors while hiding daggers behind their
backs.
</P>
<P>
   At the government would have it, Microsoft plunged a digital
dagger into Netscape on Dec. 7, 1995, which was referred to at the
trial by Barksdale as ``our own Pearl Harbor Day.''
</P>
<P>
   On that date, Gates announced that Microsoft was ``hard core''
about the Internet and planned to ``embrace and extend'' it across
all the company's products and platforms, including Windows 95, its
then-new flagship operating system. For openers, Gates said
Internet Explorer would be forever free to all comers.
</P>
<P>
   Netscape stock promptly fell nearly 30 percent. It has yet to
recover. The Justice Department took notice.
</P>
<P>
   The story of the still-raging browser wars is told in
``Competing on Internet Time: Lessons from Netscape and Its Battle
with Microsoft,'' a soon-to-be published book by Massachusetts
Institute of Technology management professor Michael Cusumano and
Harvard Business School's David Yoffie.
</P>
<P>
   ``A classic battle was looming,'' the authors write. ``Netscape
and its 700 or so employees were cast as David against Gates'
Goliath, which had more than 17,000 employees and almost $6 billion
in sales in 1995. ...At the end of 1997, Netscape was forced to
declare a fourth-quarter loss of $88 million and its share of the
browser market had dropped close to 50 percent by the middle of
1998.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Emboldened by their success and wealth, Microsoft's executives
thought they could break the rules with impunity,'' the government
has charged. Gates has misrepresented his own actions, they
maintain, by claiming no recollection of deals that court documents
reveal he in fact closely steered.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft has adopted a ``business culture'' defense in the
trial, arguing that its actions faithfully mirror those taken by
its corporate accusers. But as Machiavelli wrote in his day, and as
Gates may be learning now, a prince must try to win the day in ways
that avoid making gratuitous enemies.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
