<HEADLINE>
A LOSS IN CALIFORNIA COULD HAUNT REPUBLICANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ Republicans often voice a proprietary attitude
about real estate. In the early 1950s, they asked: ``Who lost
China?'' In the late 1990s, in the Taiwan of their dismay, they can
bitterly debate: ``Who lost California?''
</P>
<P>
   GOP gubernatorial candidates are ahead in most big states:
Texas, New York, Florida, Illinois, Ohio, and Michigan. But here in
the biggest state, Dan Lungren is not. He is lagging partly because
of his self-managed campaign and partly because of the skill of his
opponent, Democrat Gray Davis. But his most daunting obstacle is
the public perception of his party as a rich white man's
fraternity.
</P>
<P>
   Lungren is a likable fellow, as the former speaker Tip O'Neill
once admitted. ``You have the qualities I admire in a politician,''
the late House speaker wrote to Lungren in 1983. ``You love your
country, and you love politics.''
</P>
<P>
   In California, 36 percent of voters are registered Republicans,
but 47 percent are Democrats. In an off-year election, the party
needs to do more than jump-start its zealots, especially against
savvy, well-financed Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Fong, the Republican state treasurer, was leading Senator
Barbara Boxer two weeks ago until President Clinton's fund-raising
helped Boxer finance an avalanche of negative ads depicting Fong as
a fan of assault rifles and toxic waste.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of her attacks have gone unanswered,'' exults Democratic
consultant Bill Carrick. ``Matt Fong is the Mike Dukakis of this
campaign. He doesn't fight back.'' At a small rally on the Capitol
Mall here, Senator Fred Thompson of Tennessee praised Fong, who
then read a speech on crime, in which he declared himself against
it. Boxer, who riles Republicans the way Jesse Helms rankles
Democrats, has a 9-point lead in the Field Poll.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are reaping the whirlwind of divisive tactics that
once energized their base but alienated others. Governor Pete
Wilson, the godfather of ``wedge issues,'' pushed ballot questions
against illegal immigration, affirmative action, and bilingual
education, angering Hispanic voters and creating future trouble for
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, a gubernatorial candidate eagerly denounces the
legislative leadership of the other party. When the Los Angeles
Daily News endorsed Lungren for governor, it said, ``He offers a
good counterbalance to the Democrat-controlled state Legislature.
We like the notion of continued checks and balances on state
government.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Lungren rarely mentions state senate president John Burton
of San Francisco or Assembly Speaker Antonio Villaraigosa of Los
Angeles, two of the state's most liberal legislators.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody knows who they are,'' says Mike Schroeder, chairman of
the Republican State Committee. ``We tested their name ID
statewide, and they test below 20 percent. If you attack somebody
like Villaraigosa, whom nobody knows, it sounds like you're beating
up on him because he's Mexican-American.''
</P>
<P>
   Lungren has made Spanish-language commercials wooing Latinos,
but Davis now commands a 70 percent share of Hispanic voters in a
poll. When that chicken comes home to roost, it will sport the
feathers of Pete Wilson, but Lungren himself carries the lethal
Republican virus of nostalgia.
</P>
<P>
   In his last debate with Davis, his opening statement was a
rambling tribute to Ronald Reagan, ``who understood what being an
American was all about.'' Reagan was a hot commodity in 1966, when
he first ran for governor. But the Gipper thrived by focusing on
the future. Lungren's campaign is stuck in the 1970s, lambasting
Davis because he worked for Jerry Brown.
</P>
<P>
   California's vote will have a profound effect on the national
debate among Republicans. Their social-issue, quasi-religious,
ideological squabbles will intensify if Lungren and Fong lose. In
1949, when China fell to the Communist, Republicans leapt on the
issue. In the winter nights of 1999, they will be leaping on each
other.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Martin F. Nolan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
