<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-30 17:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6270 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANIMALS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      10-30 0633
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANIMALS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEA MONSTERS LIVE! 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By VICKI CROKE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not to scare you on Halloween or anything, but there is such a
thing as a sea monster.
</P>
<P>
   It is elusive, powerful, and huge. It is menacingly muscled.
With eyes as big as hubcaps, sinewy tentacles carrying toothed
suckers (the better to grasp you with, my dear), eight writhing
arms, and a strong birdlike beak (located between its arms, no
less) that cuts flesh into chunks. And there is no head where a
head should be. (Talk about brain food: Everything this monster
eats passes through its brain on the way to its stomach.)
</P>
<P>
   You wouldn't want to meet this beast in a dark alley of the
ocean _ unless you were part of a team of curious scientists.
</P>
<P>
   The sea monster we're talking about is Architeuthis
(ark-ih-TOOTH-is), the giant squid. This is the animal that danced
in the nightmares of sailors for centuries, the elusive quarry of
marine biologists who hope to study them, and the subject of marine
artist and writer Richard Ellis's latest book, ``The Search for the
Giant Squid: An Authoritative Look at the Biology and Mythology of
the World's Most Elusive Sea Creature'' (Lyons Press, $35).
</P>
<P>
   From the 200 or so specimens that have landed in fishermen's
nets or washed ashore, we know that these creatures are indeed
monstrous: The largest ever recorded was found in 1887 on the coast
of New Zealand. It was 57 feet long from the top of its mantle to
its tentacle tips. Its archenemy, the sperm whale, reaches a length
of 60 feet. It is believed that giant squid could grow larger than
that.
</P>
<P>
   But we don't know.  &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Though they show up regularly in fiction (Jules Verne's
``20,000 Leagues Under the Sea,'' for one), there hasn't been one
confirmed sighting or photograph of a living, healthy giant squid.
That means no one has really seen them tossing a tentacle or two
over the prow of a boat to snack on seagoers. They may come to the
surface of the water only when they're really not feeling well. All
the ones seen onshore are dead, and the ones hauled up in nets are
dead or dying.
</P>
<P>
   The less we know, of course, the scarier they seem. And
zoologists are trying to do something about that.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Stone, the director of conservation for the New England
Aquarium, was part of a prestigious team of scientists with
sponsorship from National Geographic Television, the Smithsonian
Institution, and the New England Aquarium that prowled the waters
off the South Island of New Zealand in January and February 1997.
They brought high-tech equipment to gain a glimpse of deep-sea
life, which they hoped would include giant squid. We know that
sperm whales feed on giant squid (the evidence being large numbers
of indigestible squid beaks left in sperm whale bellies). And so
this group even attached a ``critter-cam'' to a sperm whale in
hopes of catching a giant squid on tape. ``We saw some really neat
stuff,'' Stone reports, ``but we knew the chances of seeing a giant
squid were slim.'' And indeed, no squid made the tapes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like being dropped into the middle of an Indian jungle
because you want to see a tiger,'' author Ellis says; it wouldn't
be fair to conclude after a few minutes, ``Well, there are no
tigers in India.''
</P>
<P>
   The hunt for the living giant squid will take more time. But
people will keep trying. Ellis describes the quest as ``the
ultimate zoological quest'' for the ``quintessential monster.''
</P>
<P>
   But as we all know from movies, monsters never show up when
scientists want them to. And considering that one washed ashore on
Plum Island, near Newburyport, in 1980, those of us who swim around
here should hope they don't show up when they're unwanted, either.
</P>
<P>
   Happy Halloween.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
