 (l and f coding)  
 IT'S SHOW TIME FOR 1999s  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN R. WHITE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New England International Auto Show begins Saturday,
signaling the beginning of the New Year _ that may be Jan. 1 for
most people, but in the auto business, a new year begins with the
unveiling of the new models. So, happy 1999, everybody.
</P>
<P>
   The festivities actually got under way Friday with previews of
new models for the New England Motor Press and last night's
Massachusetts State Automobile Dealers Association celebration.
</P>
<P>
   Acura led off at 11 a.m. with its vice president of marketing,
Jeff Conrad, pulling the cover off the 1999 3.5RL, the flagship of
the luxury line. Next came Joel Manby, president of Saab Cars USA,
to unveil the new 9-5 Saab station wagon, a radical departure for
the Swedish maker that has previously offered spacious hatchbacks
which did about what wagons do. Then it was Saturn's turn _ Don
Hudler, Saturn president, introduced the new three-door coupe.
</P>
<P>
   The annual New England Motor Press Association lunch was up
next, with Mark Hutchins, president of Ford's Lincoln Mercury
division, offering the keynote address outlining a look at the
challenges ahead in the auto market, LM's hopes for the new LS
model, and the reasoning behind its corporate shift to California _
to create a truly American car, he said, a combination of
California imagination and New England practicality. A couple of
awards highlighted the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   NEMPA presented its Charles Dole High Road Award to Ken Gross,
an automotive journalist whose work appears in national magazines
and who is currently director of the Peterson Auto Museum. The
award, named for retired Christian Science Monitor journalist
Charles Dole _ its first recipient _ recognizes career
professionals in auto journalism or the automotive industry who
have set an example of high ideals, integrity, and professionalism.
</P>
<P>
   MSADA also cited one of its own, Quincy, Mass., dealer Dan
Quirk, winner of Time magazine's Quality Award for Massachusetts; a
national winner is to be chosen from among the state winners. The
Quirk family operates dealerships selling Ford, Chevrolet, Nissan,
Mazda, Mitsubishi, and Volkswagen vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   In the afternoon, Karen Makris, Mercedes-Benz product manager,
offered a look at the new C230 Kompressor, a supercharged
performance model. Ed Hightower of BMW introduced that company's 5
Series Sport Wagon; Chrysler unveiled its new Jeep Grand Cherokee
for 1999, and Volvo's Jim Borsch wound up the afternoon with a
presentation of Volvo's 1999 S80.
</P>
<P>
   That's a short list of the newest, but everything is new at the
show _ if not totally new, at least freshened for the new year. To
keep things interesting, there are concept cars from a variety of
manufacturers and this year automobiles sculpted in sand.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
