<HEADLINE>
CRITICS OF MEGA-MERGER OF AT&AMP;T AND TCI COMPLAIN TO THE FCC 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Nov. 1)   (EDS: Filed in ``w'' and ``f'' categories.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ AT&AMP;T Corp., the nation's largest long distance
carrier, is betting heavily on transforming cable TV from an
entertainment-oriented medium into a telecommunications pipeline
that will penetrate local phone market monopolies.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T says its pending $48 billion merger with TCI Corp., the
nation's No. 2 cable TV provider, will allow consumers one-stop
shopping _ local and long distance telephone services, Internet
access, e-mail, high speed data transmission _ all through cable TV
hookups and all itemized on one monthly bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this local phone capability offers the consumer is a
choice of local phone companies, a choice of local services, and a
choice of local prices,'' said C. Michael Armstrong, AT&AMP;T's CEO and
chairman.
</P>
<P>
   But Armstrong's vision isn't shared by consumer advocacy groups
and an array of telecommunications companies with interests as
diverse as local and long distance service, Internet access, direct
broadcast and wireless communications.
</P>
<P>
   They asked the Federal Communications Commission last week to
stop the merger unless AT&AMP;T is required to give competitors equal
access to TCI's cables that connect to about 14 million U.S.
households.
</P>
<P>
   Among those filing formal petitions challenging the merger were
AOL Inc., Ameritech, the Consumer Federation of America, Echostar
Communications Corp., GTE Corp., the Independent Cable and
Telecommunications Association, Mindspring Enterprises Inc., SBC
Communications Inc., Sprint Corp., the Wireless Communications
Association International, US West, and MCI Worldcom Inc.
</P>
<P>
   GTE assaulted the merger for being ``brazenly
anti-competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   US West officials said the union ``poses grave risks to
competition in a number of markets.'' The merger would result in a
giant ``with combined revenues of nearly $60 billion and with
leading positions in fields spanning virtually the entire
communications industry.''
</P>
<P>
   AOL, the nation's largest online service, said consumers
potentially could benefit but warned that competition might suffer
unless the FCC steps in.
</P>
<P>
   Echostar, a direct broadcast satellite distributor and a cable
TV competitor, said AT&AMP;T's exclusive control over what runs over
TCI's cables ``would be a sufficiently serious anti-competitive
concern standing alone.''
</P>
<P>
   The Consumer Federation of America charged that, despite AT&AMP;T's
assurances to the contrary, ``consumers will certainly face
spiralling cable TV rates and discriminatory practices restricting
customer choice and competition in telephone, video, Internet and
other advanced services.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the complaints focus on the fact that cable TV providers
and telephone companies face different levels of federal
regulation.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, two wires carrying commercial services enter most
American homes _ the phone line and the cable TV line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paradoxically,'' GTE said, the phone wire ``is subject to a
host of regulatory requirements that open their lines for consumers
and competitors while the cable broadband line is under no such
constraints.''
</P>
<P>
   The disparity in regulations is apparent in Internet services.
</P>
<P>
   The FCC requires that phone companies, or common carriers, allow
consumers to have access to any Internet provider they choose. This
allows the 25 million U.S. Internet subscribers with telephone
connections to select from among numerous providers.
</P>
<P>
   Cable TV operators aren't subject to that FCC requirement. As a
result, an estimated 300,000 consumers who gain access to the
Internet through cable TV hook-ups are forced to use their cable
company's preferred Internet provider _ usually Time Warner's Road
Runner or At Home, which is partly owned by TCI.
</P>
<P>
   Ameritech called on the FCC to ``promote a level regulatory
playing field and dismantle regulatory distinctions based on
technology and industry segments.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, MCI said ``there should be no regulatory distinction
between telecommunications services provided over cable facilities
versus the traditional telephony structure.''
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T officials argue that the merger will bring competition to
local phone markets, which are dominated by the so-called Baby
bells such as SBC, US West, Ameritech, Bell South and Bell
Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong argued that the Baby Bells and their new corporate
alliances pose a serious threat to competition that increases the
rationale for AT&AMP;T's purchase of TCI.
</P>
<P>
   ``The proposed mergers between Bell Atlantic and GTE, and SBC
and Ameritech threaten to create a Ma Bell East and a Ma Bell West
controlling more than a third of all homes in America _ 55 million
phone lines,'' Armstrong said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their version of our communications future is very different.
It's built not on consumer choice but on extending their local
monopoly,'' Armstrong said.
</P>
<P>
   Boyd Peterson, a telecommunications analyst with the Yankee
Group _ a Boston-based consulting firm _ believes the merger
ultimately will be approved because it promises competition in
local phone markets, a major reason Congress deregulated the
telecommunications industry in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``The deal gives credence to the concept of using cable for some
of the services that were traditionally offered by the monopolies,
namely voice communication and Internet access,'' said Peterson.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed merger must be approved by the FCC, and a decision
is expected by next spring. In addition, the Justice Department is
examining the merger for anti-trust implications.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
