<SLUG> BC-MORTGAGE-REITS-$ADV01-NYT </SLUG>
  
 FOR REITs, A FUTURE ACCORDING TO DARWIN  
(For release Sunday, Nov. 1) 
(af) 
 By CHARLES V. BAGLI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since the mid-'90s, Wall Street has had two main ways to invest
in real estate: mortgage-backed securities for big institutional
investors and real estate investment trusts for retail investors.
Now, the mortgage-backed market is paralyzed, as is much of the
world of bond investing. What about REITs?
</P>
<P>
   For three years, these companies poured the money of
enthusiastic investors into hotels, office buildings and shopping
malls. Their market capitalization jumped from $44.3 billion in
1994 to $140.5 billion in September.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the 174 so-called equity REITs _ which buy properties,
not mortgages _ showed growth rates approaching 20 percent and
traded at 20 times earnings.
</P>
<P>
   But with investors concerned that the real estate market may
have peaked, REIT stocks have fallen on average about 21 percent so
far this year. Shares of trusts that buy hotels have declined 50
percent; those that buy office buildings are down nearly 25
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The days of go-go growth for REITs are gone,'' said Thomas J.
Barrick, chairman of Colony Capital, a real estate investment fund
based in Los Angeles. ``REIT's will go on, but you're going to have
unbelievable consolidation. You'll go from 170 REITs to 10, all
first-class operations.''
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts say REIT stocks will come to be regarded more like
utility stocks, growing slowly and throwing off ample dividends.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Whyte, a Morgan Stanley Dean Witter analyst, calls REITs
``fabulous utility substitutes.''
</P>
<P>
   The capital markets' big role in real estate during the '90s, he
said, has imposed a new discipline on the industry, cutting off
financing for development deals that might have led to oversupply.
</P>
<P>
   So rents should continue to rise, driving up the REITs cash
flows, Whyte said. He expects real estate stocks to generate
earnings growth of 6.5 percent to 7 percent annually, as well as to
pay, on average, a 6.8 percent dividend _ much better than the 3.7
percent average yield on utility stocks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
