<SLUG> BC-MALARIA31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MOVEMENTS AGAINST MALARIA BEGIN TO STIR
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The World Health Organization (WHO), the World Bank
and two United Nations agencies unveiled a ``Roll Back Malaria''
campaign Friday aimed at getting control of the rapidly spreading
disease.
</P>
<P>
   One of humanity's deadliest and stubbornest scourges, malaria
kills an estimated 2.7 million people a year, nearly half of them
small children and pregnant women.
</P>
<P>
   Yet efforts to control it have failed, and in recent years the
spread has accelerated. In the African nation of Senegal, deaths
have increased sevenfold in just five years, for example.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of WHO, the World Bank, the U.N. Development Program
and UNICEF, the U.N. fund for children, said the new campaign would
concentrate on strengthening the ability of local public health
agencies and nongovernmental organizations to respond to outbreaks
of the disease.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Gro Harlem Brundtland, newly elected director general of the
World Health Assembly and former prime minister of Norway, said
human suffering and economic burden of malaria are
``unacceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to using satellite mapping and climate data to
pinpoint the presence of malaria, the initiative will increase
funding for research and support of community-level public health
agencies.
</P>
<P>
   UNICEF officials said the fund will increase the use of
pesticide-soaked mosquito nets. Research funded by WHO and the U.S.
Agency for International Development demonstrated that this simple
and inexpensive measure can significantly reduce the incidence of
the disease among children.
</P>
<P>
   The latest attempt to confront malaria comes at a time when
other groups, ranging from a civic club in Normal, Ill., to the
National Naval Medical Center in Bethesda, Md., have also begun to
take action the disease.
</P>
<P>
   Drake Zimmerman, a member of the Normal Rotary Club, is pushing
a plan to get individual Rotary clubs to buy and distribute the
mosquito nets. He said other Rotary members in Switzerland and
Australia have independently started similar campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Rotary clubs were a driving force behind the global campaign to
eradicate polio, a project for which Rotary International has
raised hundreds of millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman thinks mass purchasing and other private sector
approaches could cut the cost of nets and biodegradable pyrethroid
insecticides in half. He has set up an Internet site
(http://www.bednet.org) to promote the idea.
</P>
<P>
   But the nets keep the female Anopheles mosquito and the
plasmodium parasite she carries away from only some potential
malaria victims, and the research indicated the resulting reduction
in deaths ranged as low as only 25 percent in some areas.
</P>
<P>
   A possibly more effective, but so far elusive, measure would
involve immunization. Efforts to develop a vaccine received a shot
in the arm Oct. 16 when a team of Navy doctors in Bethesda reported
that by injecting malaria genes into human volunteers, they
stimulated strong immune responses.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers reported in the journal Science that the gene
they stripped from plasmodium caused no serious side effects among
the 20 volunteers, while stimulating them to develop more
antibodies against the disease than a natural infection would have.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to antibodies, the naked DNA vaccine stimulated the
second half of the immune response system, spurring the development
of ``killer T-cells'' capable of destroying infected cells.
</P>
<P>
   Trials to determine if persons given the vaccine are resistant
when exposed to the malaria parasite have yet to be attempted.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
