<SLUG> BC-MOM-GRANDMOTHER-2TAKES-$ADV1-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOM-GRANDMOTHER-2TAKES-$ADV1
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  EDITORS: Photos available on New York Times photo service 
 
 
LABOR OF LOVE: 53-YEAR-OLD WOMAN SERVES AS SURROGATE, DELIVERS
DAUGHTER'S TWINS 
 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, NOV. 1) 
 
By JEANNIE KEVER 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ In family lore, it already has become known as simply
``the story.''
</P>
<P>
   As in, the story of how 53-year-old Joan Stein served as a
surrogate mother for her daughter and son-in-law, delivering the
couple's twins _ her own grandchildren _ in late September at St.
Luke's Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not particularly conventional,'' Stein says.
</P>
<P>
   Her daughter, Jayme Morgan, agrees. ``She's unusual.''
</P>
<P>
   Enter Ella Rose Morgan and Sax Avery Morgan as evidence.
</P>
<P>
   For Stein, it was a way to pass the torch of motherhood to her
only daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have really enjoyed my children. That's it,'' she says.
``And I just wanted her to enjoy the same opportunity. I never
thought about grandchildren. I don't work. I was in pretty good
shape and ... it didn't seem that hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, Avrum Stein, was supportive, although as a
physician he first had to be convinced that such a late-in-life
pregnancy wouldn't be too risky for his wife of more than 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   That accomplished, the couples embarked upon an
intergenerational adventure unconventional even in the high-tech
world of baby making.
</P>
<P>
   None of them ever dreamed it would come to this, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Jayme, the oldest of Joan and Avrum Stein's three children, had
the most traditional of expectations when she married Scott Morgan,
an executive with his family's Houston-based real estate
development company, the Morgan Group, in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   They enjoyed two carefree years before deciding to start a
family.
</P>
<P>
   Six months passed, and she wasn't pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   And so the Morgans entered America's infertility pipeline,
officially joining the estimated 15 percent to 20 percent of
married couples unable to conceive a child without medical
intervention.
</P>
<P>
   This new life centered around powerful, mood-altering hormones
and invasive surgeries.
</P>
<P>
   Hope and disappointment. Big money.
</P>
<P>
   As with most couples seeking treatment for infertility, the
Morgans' health insurance didn't cover the cost. Scott Morgan
estimates that they spent about $200,000 on their baby quest.
</P>
<P>
   Infertility treatments range from drugs to boost ovulation or
treat an underlying infection or hormone deficiency to a number of
high-tech procedures. The American Society for Reproductive
Medicine estimates that Americans spent $197.7 million on in vitro
fertilization in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   In vitro is the original assisted reproductive technology, now
20 years old, and is used to create ``test tube babies'' by
stimulating the woman's ovaries to produce multiple eggs, which are
then removed and combined with the man's sperm to create embryos.
</P>
<P>
   The embryos are transferred back into the woman in the hope that
they will attach to her uterus, resulting in pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   Scott and Jayme Morgan were young and healthy, and doctors
deemed them good candidates for in vitro fertilization. Over the
next few years, they enrolled in a variety of infertility programs
in Houston and elsewhere, trying in vitro eight times.
</P>
<P>
   Three times, the pregnancy test came back positive.
</P>
<P>
   Each time, it was an ectopic pregnancy, with the embryo lodged
in the fallopian tube rather than descending into the uterus.
</P>
<P>
   Jayme Morgan, 29, says it was never clear exactly why she
couldn't sustain a pregnancy; she eventually underwent several
surgeries to increase her odds of success.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing worked.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors suggested using donor eggs. The Morgans resisted, saying
they were willing to have a child who wasn't genetically linked to
each of them but were not convinced that they wouldn't succeed on
their own terms.
</P>
<P>
   They also considered adoption but ranked it as a last resort.
</P>
<P>
   Through each disappointment they kept going.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a mindset,'' Jayme Morgan says. ``We had a goal.
We knew the only way to get there was to be aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   With every failure, they allowed themselves a one-day ``pity
party'' _ he would stay home from work, she would rage and cry.
</P>
<P>
   Then they'd start another round of hormone shots.
</P>
<P>
   Having children, 30-year-old Scott Morgan says, ``wasn't an
option, it was a requirement. Family is everything to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Joan Stein, a trim, healthy woman who has always been athletic,
first broached the idea of serving as a surrogate several years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Morgans declined.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought, `Wouldn't that be incredible?' But ... no way,''
Jayme Morgan says.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't worth it to us to risk her (health),'' Scott Morgan
adds.
</P>
<P>
   But as the months passed, they did begin to think about hiring a
surrogate to carry their child.
</P>
<P>
   There are no generally accepted statistics on the use of
surrogate mothers _ having another woman carry a child, either by
conceiving it or by having an embryo implanted in her uterus. In
1995, the most recent year for which statistics are available, 65
babies were born in the United States to surrogate mothers through
in vitro fertilization, according to the American Society for
Reproductive Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Many surrogate arrangements involve relatives or close friends
of the infertile couple, but the practice of hiring strangers to
serve as surrogates has grown in the past decade. Commercial
agencies have sprung up to match would-be parents with potential
surrogates.
</P>
<P>
   By the summer of 1997, the Morgans were ready to consider it.
They spent the summer in San Diego, where Scott Morgan was involved
in a business deal, and discussed the idea with a doctor there.
</P>
<P>
   Surrogacy is legal in all states, but case law in California
already had established a precedent favoring the rights of genetic
parents over the birth mother. That lessened the fear that a
surrogate mother would back out of the deal and try to keep the
baby.
</P>
<P>
   The doctor referred them to an agency, and they began to sift
through lists of potential surrogates.
</P>
<P>
   None seemed right. Many were in their late 30s or early 40s, and
some were overweight or had other health problems. The Morgans
worried about having no control over the surrogate's diet and
lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   Last October, Stein noticed an article in The New York Times
about women older than 50 giving birth, and once again mentioned
the idea of serving as a surrogate.
</P>
<P>
   Not so long ago, it would have been unthinkable. Women in their
50s rarely had babies, and certainly not by high-tech means. That
began to change as older women urged infertility clinics to push
the boundaries, proving that even postmenopausal women could
sustain a healthy pregnancy using donor eggs and hormone
injections. The idea gained notoriety last year, when doctors
announced that a 63-year-old Southern California woman had given
birth to a healthy daughter in November 1996.
</P>
<P>
   If few women older than 50 give birth, it is even less common
for a woman older 50 to serve as a surrogate. ``You're getting into
a really low number,'' says Heather Kowalski of the American
Society for Reproductive Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But it's not unprecedented for a woman to carry her own
grandchildren. The first case in the United States occurred in
1991, when a 42-year-old librarian in South Dakota gave birth to
twins produced from her daughter's eggs, fertilized with sperm from
the daughter's husband.
</P>
<P>
   The Morgan family contacted the Pacific Fertility Center in San
Francisco, which was mentioned in the article, to see if it was
plausible.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors there accepted Stein as a patient but also suggested a
ninth attempt at helping Jayme Morgan get pregnant through in vitro
fertilization.
</P>
<P>
   When the time came, they implanted embryos created from Jayme
Morgan's eggs and Scott Morgan's sperm in both women.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan's pregnancy test came back negative. Stein's test was
positive.
</P>
<P>
   At age 52, she was pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   The younger couple had always been open about their frustrating
attempts to have a baby, but Joan and Avrum Stein were more
circumspect.
</P>
<P>
   ``At 52, you wonder how you're going to tell your mother you're
pregnant ... with your grandchildren,'' says Joan Stein, who
celebrated a birthday before the babies' birth.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Avrum Stein, a pathologist, says he told
``virtually no one, because I didn't want to explain it.''
</P>
<P>
   But as the pregnancy progressed, they took the quizzical looks
of strangers in stride. The reaction from most people ``has been
fabulous,'' Joan Stein says.
</P>
<P>
   Their two sons, neither of whom lives in Houston, were
supportive, knowing the lengths to which their sister had gone in
her efforts to have a child.
</P>
<P>
   Joan Stein's parents, who also live out of town, took the news
with aplomb, although both worried about the physical toll,
fretting through frequent telephone calls to check up on their
daughter's health.
</P>
<P>
   Stein, who hadn't yet entered menopause, endured 10 weeks of
hormone therapy before and during the first weeks of pregnancy to
prepare her body, until the placenta had formed and was ready to
take over supporting the twins.
</P>
<P>
   She continued to work out for the first five months, despite
nausea during the first trimester. The last three months were
marked by indigestion, but she insists that ``it was absolutely the
easiest pregnancy. I really wasn't limited.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Robert Carpenter, the Houston obstetrician who cared for
Joan during the pregnancy and delivered the babies, said, ``Joan
had as nice a pregnancy as you could ever want, both for her age
and for twins.'' She was his first patient to serve as a surrogate
for her own daughter, and Carpenter says he expects the situation
to remain rare.
</P>
<P>
   But Stein's age didn't make her unique.
</P>
<P>
   Carpenter has delivered babies for a number of women in their
50s, including a 51-year-old and a 52-year-old earlier this year.
Like Stein, they became pregnant through in vitro fertilization,
using donor eggs. But most of his fiftysomething patients have
gotten pregnant naturally, including a 54-year-old woman who was
pregnant for the 17th time.
</P>
<P>
   Carpenter grew close to both couples during the pregnancy,
coming to view Stein's decision as an act of love and generosity.
</P>
<P>
   Their story, he says, is important not only because of what it
says about modern science but also because of its message about
family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she's a very neat and special person,'' he says. ``It
took a lot of sacrifice for her and her husband to choose to do
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Stein gained 12 pounds during the pregnancy, trying to eat only
nutritious foods. ``I probably ate better than I have in years and
years,'' she says. ``It's a heavy responsibility. It's one thing
when you're pregnant with your own children, but ...''
</P>
<P>
   The low point came last summer, when her oldest son got married.
She isn't exactly the pink polka dot type, so shopping for a
mother-of-the-groom dress in a maternity shop wasn't a lot of fun.
Still, she and her husband figure it gave the wedding guests a hot
topic of conversation.
</P>
<P>
   And if they occasionally would have preferred to avoid the
curiosity _ they report with a mix of bemusement and exasperation
that Joan Stein's mother insisted on telling ``the story'' to
everyone they met at the wedding _ they also saw it as a natural
extension of family love.
</P>
<P>
   The Morgans accompanied Stein to most of her doctor's
appointments, sharing the excitement of learning their children's
gender _ they are fraternal twins, one boy and one girl _ and
watching them squirm during ultrasound examinations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was fun, and it went really fast,'' Jayme Morgan says of
the pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   In August, she and her husband even moved into her parents'
River Oaks home while waiting for their own to be remodeled.
They've promised to move out before the babies' first birthday.
</P>
<P>
   The Morgans were declared the legal parents before the birth,
allowing their names to be placed on the birth certificates
immediately. The Steins' health insurance covered the delivery; the
babies were covered by their parents' insurance after the birth.
</P>
<P>
   Together, the four planned the delivery room protocol, devising
a way for the Morgans to participate without compromising Joan
Stein's privacy. ``After all, he's still my son-in-law.''
</P>
<P>
   But when it was time for the delivery _ Wednesday, Sept. 23,
about 3 { weeks before Stein's due date _ she began having chest
pains and the babies developed signs of distress. They were born by
emergency Caesarean section; everyone recovered nicely.
</P>
<P>
   Ella weighed 3 pounds, 5 ounces; Sax weighed 5 pounds,1 ounce.
They spent nine days at Texas Children's Hospital in Houston,
demonstrating their individual personalities almost immediately:
Ella is calm and easygoing; Sax is demanding and temperamental,
``the devil child,'' say his parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``But no complaints,'' Scott Morgan quickly adds.
</P>
<P>
   Stein, meanwhile, went home after three nights in the hospital.
Hours later, she was eating a steak dinner at a local restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Within a few weeks, she was thinner than she had been before the
pregnancy, telling everyone that she felt great.
</P>
<P>
   And getting quite a kick out of the reactions she encountered as
the news spread.
</P>
<P>
   ``People would say, `Are you going on Oprah?' ''
</P>
<P>
   They'd joke that they're holding out for Jerry Springer.
</P>
<P>
   Now between endless feedings and diaper changes and hastily
snatched sleep, Scott and Jayme Morgan reflect on the long road
that brought them to parenthood.
</P>
<P>
   Each round of in vitro fertilization was ``this little piece of
hope,'' Jayme Morgan says, and hope has been rewarded.
</P>
<P>
   Stein insists she has had no trouble separating her roles as
surrogate and grandmother.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like I don't like them,'' she says of the twins. But
then again, it feels good to relax downstairs, listening to the
twins wailing overhead and knowing that her daughter and son-in-law
are rushing around with bottles and diapers, feeding and burping.
</P>
<P>
   ``People ask me, `Are you going to nurse them?' No. I nursed my
own children. These aren't mine,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   The Morgans say they will tell the twins the circumstances of
their birth as soon as they're old enough to understand.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's such an incredible way of getting here,'' Jayme Morgan
says. ``We'll just tell them, `We wanted you so badly, and this is
how we could get you.' '' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
