<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-30 17:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6330 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTOS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      10-30 1202
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN OK GALANT AND SOME SERIOUS TRAINING WHEELS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN R. WHITE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is Saturday, a day usually reserved for the mundane chores of
a single householder _ laundry, errands, etc. _ but I am heading to
school instead. At an airport. Not to learn how to fly but to get a
lesson in the technique of taming teenage testosterone on the
highway.
</P>
<P>
   This is a course dedicated to teaching inexperienced
16-year-olds the basics for survival behind the wheeel _ probably a
lot riskier than flying.
</P>
<P>
   The car chosen for the excursion is a Mitsubishi Galant ES, a
car with good looks and no other particular distinction, unless a
list price less than $18,000 is your idea of distinction. The
Galant is a family of automobiles, starting with the under-$17,000,
four-cylinder DE fairly well equipped, and graduating to the
$24,250 (plus $435 delivery) LS.
</P>
<P>
   The marque has been through a counter evolution of sorts, having
once been a techno-wonder with infinitely adjustable electronic
suspension guaranteed to induce mal de mer devolving to, depending
on price and engine, either a tame little inoffensive car or a
zippy little bit of fun. This ES is in the inoffensive class, doing
nothing particularly well but certainly nothing badly.
</P>
<P>
   The trip today is a roughly 50-mile jaunt to an airport at
Concord, N.H., starting with a pleasant stretch of winding road
past some still blazing patches of autumn color, through some
construction, onto interstate and finally into city traffic.
Approaching the airport, arrows mark the way to the Stevens
Advanced Driver Training School, Sandy Stevens proprietor,
currently in session for newly-minted young drivers _ drivers who
haven't really mastered elementary driving yet.
</P>
<P>
   The ultimate arrow points to a hole in the fence around the
perimeter of the airport; there is no gate, no driveway, merely an
opening _ and of course there is the curbing to climb. In the
distance, I see the familiar white Tauruses of the Stevens School;
between me and them is an overgrown field. This is a small sedan,
not a sport/utility!
</P>
<P>
   I ease over the curb _ nothing scrapes _ and head into the tall
grass, hoping. I hear the sound of water underneath, then realize
it is merely grass rushing against the undercarriage as we bump
along together, the Mitubishi and I. Bud Stanley of the driving
school greets me, explains the drill.
</P>
<P>
   It is basic brake-and-steer instruction, frst with antilock
brakes, then without. It is necessary to teach the use of ABS,
Stanley says, but because so many youngsters drive older cars
without it, it is also necessary to give a grounding in what is
called threshhold braking _ how to do what ABS does for you.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens is set up on an unused runway; far away, aircraft drone
on and off a working runway. ``Forget school parking lots, will
you?'' Stevens tells me. There isn't room enough, he says, to
ensure safe operation. There are plenty of underused airport
runways around within easy reach of high schools, Stevens says.
``If there's enough room to land an airplane safely, you know it's
safe enough for driver training.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevens has a trailer equipped as a classroom _ TV monitor,
overhead projector and all _ parked at the side of the runway. His
students have already done the classroom portion and are driving.
Some parents are participating, too.
</P>
<P>
   I climb into the back seat of a Taurus; up front Stanley is
coaching Paul, 16, through an exercise I last saw Stevens use in a
police training course. Paul heads the car down a cone-marked lane
at 45 miles per hour toward a solid wall of cones. At either end is
a light and a gate _ an open space. When a light is triggered, Paul
must brake, turn toward the gate nearest the light, go through the
gate, turn the opposite way, then turn again to pass through
another gate in line with the original course on the other side of
the cone barrier. With ABS, it's fairly easy _ as long as you brake
before you turn with the ABS. But this time it's with the ABS
turned off.
</P>
<P>
   Paul isn't very smooth first pass, but makes it _ he would not
have crashed. At 50, it's harder, but Paul is thinking, executes
fairly well. At 55, momentum is multiplied, the exercise more
difficult, more ... exciting. Later, I watch as Paul's father, an
experienced driver, brakes sqealing, tires smoking, blows through
the barrier sending cones flying. ``What do you bet the kid asks to
drive home?'' somebody says.
</P>
<P>
   This training session is a joint operation of Stevens, a New
Hampshire-based driver trainer of long experience and solid
credentials, and Co-operative Insurance, a small underwriter in
Vermont and New Hampshire. Co-op is new to the car insurance
business, having dealt mainly in farm insurance; Harold F. Burke, a
special investigator for the company and a booster of the program,
fills me in. Co-op, he says, takes a different view from the
conventional _ why charge the inexperienced driver high premiums,
in effect charging him for what he hasn't done yet? Why not train
the inexperienced to reduce risk and consequences?
</P>
<P>
   Co-op figures it costs $250 per day per driver in the course and
will pay approximately half the cost for the teen applicant. Having
completed the training, the teen is then qualified for a discounted
premium on his auto insurance _ that alone pays for his share of
the training. So far, about 140 youngsters have successfully
completed the course.
</P>
<P>
   The company saves even when accidents occur, Burke said. The
average cost of a young driver's first accident is around $4,000.
Young drivers with advanced training sometimes have accidents, too,
but the cost averages around $800, according to company figures.
</P>
<P>
   The session is over and it's back into the Galant and through
the tall grass once more. The 2.351-liter four-banger is somewhat
restrained by the automatic transmission, a smooth four-speed;
acceleration isn't great. The brakes are good. Handling is so-so,
not great, not bad.
</P>
<P>
   It's bottom-of-the-line, perhaps, but not bottom-feeder _ it's
fairly well-equipped. To speak of back-seat room in this car is to
gild the lily _ there isn't much head or knee space and the rear
doors are quite narrow at the bottom making entry/exit tight. Radio
controls are mixed _ too many too-small bits on the control panel.
One of the two cupholders up front is obscured by the armrest that
doubles as lid for a small but deep bin. Fuel mileage is very good
_ 26.66 miles per gallon overall for 560 miles measured.
</P>
<P>
   So why is it important to brake first with ABS, then turn?
Because, as Stanley demonstrated so well with yours truly hanging
on in the passenger seat, with ABS you can brake and turn. But, if
you turn first, as weight shifts when you brake, all the force is
directed to the outside front wheel. Now the ABS is reading the
other three lightly loaded wheels as about to lock up _ so the
brakes on those wheels are off more than on. The brunt of the
braking effort is borne by that lone front wheel, thus stopping
distance is significantly lengthened.
</P>
<P>
   Technology is no substitute for knowledge.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
