<HEADER>
A6332 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-PROFILE-LIVERMORE     10-30 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-PROFILE-LIVERMORE-ART-$ADV01-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN IRON WILL, CLOAKED IN VELVET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., N.C.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(For release Sunday, Nov. 1) 
(af) 
 By JOHN MARKOFF   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOUNTAIN VIEW, Calif. _ In her first year at Stanford
University's business school, Ann Livermore submitted the winning
plan to manage the student snack bar. Soon she was persuading
corporate recruiters to buy doughnuts from her to serve at
presentations. The companies thought nothing of paying 50 cents for
doughnuts that cost her a nickel.
</P>
<P>
   Following tradition, she was allowed to keep her profits.
Breaking tradition, she made a small fortune _ enough, in fact, to
pay for her entire MBA education. The next year, the administration
took the business back for itself.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Livermore has always set her sights high, and now she is
suddenly in a position to scale the peaks of one of the most
male-dominated industries in America. Two weeks ago, she was named
to head the new Enterprise Computing Solutions organization at the
Hewlett-Packard Co., the world's second-largest computer maker.
</P>
<P>
   The promotion thrust her into the company of America's most
powerful women executives. Enterprise Computing Solutions, which
markets all of Hewlett-Packard's computers except for desktops, has
44,000 employees and estimated annual sales of $15 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only a handful of women, including Carly Fiorina at Lucent,
Jill Barad at Mattel, Andrea Jung at Avon and Lois Juliber at
Colgate, have assumed operating roles of this size, scale and
complexity,'' said Caroline W. Nahas, managing director for
Southern California of Korn Ferry International, the executive
search firm. ``It's a significant announcement.''
</P>
<P>
   Her new job has made her a contender to succeed Lewis E. Platt,
Hewlett's chief executive, when he reaches the company's retirement
age of 60 three years from now. But Mrs. Livermore, who is 40,
played down the significance of her sudden proximity to the throne.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, what I'm worrying about is how I'm going to learn
17,000 new names,'' she said with a laugh. Turning serious, she
added, ``I have never in my HP career thought about what my next
job is going to be.''
</P>
<P>
   That may not be spin. The secret of her success seems to be the
intensity of purpose she gives to whatever task is at hand. Until
she got her new assignment, she was vice president and general
manager of the company's software and services group, which handles
everything from Internet commerce and consulting to telephone
support.
</P>
<P>
   There, she set a goal for her businesses to grow at twice the
industry average. And for each of the last four years, they
expanded by 20 percent or more, meeting or exceeding her target.
</P>
<P>
   She has also earned a reputation as an iron-willed manager, and
considers herself a disciple of Jim Arthur, a now-retired
Hewlett-Packard executive whose intimidating manner has made him
something of a company legend.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Mrs. Livermore has a gracious manner that has made her one
of the most popular bosses at Hewlett-Packard. She remembers a
colleague once telling her that she was ``one of the few people who
can tell you to go to hell and you'd look forward to the ride.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether she is really material for the top job remains an open
question, of course. A 16-year veteran at Hewlett-Packard, she is
not a technology buff. Even so, those who work with her say she is
a quick study on almost any topic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ann can take a complex business situation and really
understand the implications,'' said Joe Beyers, a Hewlett-Packard
executive who worked for her in starting several Internet
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   She views customer satisfaction as the key to growth. She breaks
down the concept into three components, to which she gives equal
weight: customers' pure satisfaction with a product; the likelihood
that they will buy it again, and the likelihood that they will
recommend it to someone else.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Livermore _ nee Martinelli _ grew up in Greensboro, N.C.
When she was 8 or 9, her father, an insurance company executive,
showed her some ``big old IBM mainframes'' in his office and
explained how they worked. She was so taken with them that she
became a volunteer key punch operator, entering data for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time I didn't realize I was cheap labor,'' she said.
``But I'd sit down with pages and pages of stuff that had to be
key-punched, thinking that this was the greatest thing in the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it wasn't love of computers that brought her to Silicon
Valley. As a senior at the University of North Carolina at Chapel
Hill, she made trips to both Harvard and Stanford to decide where
to go to graduate school. It was no contest.
</P>
<P>
   ``In March, I visited Harvard and it was wet, cold, snowy,
ugly,'' she said. ``I came to Stanford and people were sitting out
by the swimming pool looking at their accounting books.''
</P>
<P>
   Even before her recent promotion, her stature had grown. Last
year, she became a member of the board of United Parcel Service.
</P>
<P>
   She likes nothing more than spending the day alone with her
husband, Tom, an executive at a Bay Area packaging company, and
their 9-year-old daughter, Emily. An avid skier and a fledgling
golfer, she says she can still unplug more completely than some of
her associates when she is away from work. More than most
companies, Hewlett-Packard operates on voice mail _ but she says it
hasn't taken over her life.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm on vacation,'' she says, ``I don't listen to
voice-mail messages.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
