<SLUG> BC-PEACOAT-FASHION-$ADV01-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AHOY, CHIC PEACOATS: NOT FOR SAILORS ONLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Nov. 1) 
(bl) 
 By DAVID COLMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When the peacoat first appeared on the backs of mod
Londoners in the early 1960s, it was an integral part of the
biggest fashion revolution of the decade. Reaching only to
mid-thigh, its brief shape was in keeping with what Vespa-riding
Italians had ordained to be the new length for outerwear.
</P>
<P>
   The warm, woolen navy coat, which rightfully belonged to
sailors, became a favorite among style makers, who found that it
had a perverse chic, a working-class inelegance. And it shielded
them from the cold when few of their other plastic, mini,
see-through clothes could.
</P>
<P>
   The peacoat's macho appeal was forever compromised when a young
designer named Calvin Klein introduced a far more stylish model, in
white, which appeared on his first Vogue magazine cover. Almost 30
years later, the peacoat is once again checking (that's selling
well, in retail lingo). While its short style has a perennial
appeal, the sporty length is particularly suited to men who want a
single overcoat that looks equally appropriate with business or
casual clothes.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the peacoat's universal appeal, it has been hard in
recent years to find one at anywhere other than an Army-Navy
surplus store.
</P>
<P>
   This year, a variety of designer versions have dropped anchor.
Polo Ralph Lauren on Madison Avenue has an archetypal peacoat, in
rigid wool, roomy enough for a brawny deckhand and with an anchor
etched onto each plastic button, for $297.50.
</P>
<P>
   Marc Jacobs in Soho did one in a cashmere and mink blend for
$1,800. (Stevedores, take note: the mink is said to help waterproof
the fabric.)
</P>
<P>
   At Bergdorf Goodman, there are traditionally cut peacoats from
Michael Kors in navy cashmere, for $1,295, and peacoats in black or
camel wool by the young designer Matt Nye, for $995.
</P>
<P>
   At Saks Fifth Avenue, there are two versions from Dolce &AMP;
Gabbana _ a nubby royal blue wool, for $895, and a gray blanket
wool from the designers' D &AMP; G line, for $695. But both of these
designs pose a potential rub. Cut close to the body, for a manly,
military look, they afford little leeway for anything more than a
sweater underneath. A suit jacket would be a problem. Any peacoat
that is meant to double as an overcoat should be tried on with a
jacket and without.
</P>
<P>
   The peacoat master, Klein, is offering one this season that
strays from the classic. Cut slightly larger, the coat, which costs
$895, provides a neat fit when worn with a blazer underneath, but
with anything less, it takes on a slightly slouchy, trench-coatish
silhouette. While the coat, made of a wool blend, may be too
lightweight for the bounding main, it's OK for braving a sea of
cabs.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-30-98 1800EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
