<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-30 18:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6345 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOT-RACES-$ADV01-HNS &LR;      10-30 1205
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOT-RACES-$ADV01-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOT RACES TO WATCH ON TUESDAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Nov. 1.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The hot races to watch on Tuesday will determine
the fortunes of seven scions of the nation's most prominent
political families, six long-serving incumbents and four women who
won Senate seats in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   The hottest race of all, of course, will affect the fate of a
politician who isn't even on the ballot. The aggregate results of
the contests for 34 Senate seats and many of the 435 House seats
will influence the breadth and timetable of the House impeachment
inquiry into President Clinton's sex and cover-up scandal.
</P>
<P>
   But the nation's political future also depends on which party
controls the 50 statehouses. Republicans hope to expand their
domination beyond the 32 governorships they already hold _
including those in 8 of the nation's 10 most populous states. Of
the 36 governorships up for grabs, 24 are already in GOP hands.
</P>
<P>
   The two sons of former President George Bush are heading into
their gubernatorial races with commanding leads, according to
pre-election polls.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush is expected to trounce Democratic
challenger Garry Mauro with important help from Hispanic voters.
His victory could propel the former part-owner of the Texas Rangers
baseball team into the Republican presidential nomination in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   His brother, Miami businessman Jeb Bush, appears to be staging a
comeback from his 1994 defeat in Florida at the hands of Democratic
Gov. Lawton Chiles. In this year's contest, Bush is ahead of Lt.
Gov. Buddy McKay by about 10 points in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   In Ohio, a fourth-generation representative of the politically
prominent Taft family _ Ohio Secretary of State Bob Taft _ appears
headed for victory in his race against Democrat Lee Fisher, a
former state attorney general, for governor.
</P>
<P>
   Taft's father and grandfather represented Ohio in the Senate.
His great-grandfather was President William Howard Taft, who also
served as chief justice of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In Minnesota, name recognition is helping Democratic Attorney
General Hubert H. Humphrey Jr., son of former Vice President Hubert
Humphrey, in his tight race against Republican Norm Coleman.
</P>
<P>
   Second-term Democratic Gov. Evan Bayh is running far ahead of
Republican rival Paul Helmke in his bid to represent Indiana in the
Senate. Bayh's father Birch Bayh served in the Senate for 18 years
until Dan Quayle beat him in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   In New Hampshire, Republican Sen. Judd Gregg, son of former
Republican Gov. Hugh Gregg, a kingmaker in New Hampshire
presidential primaries, holds a 40-point lead over a little known
Democratic challenger, civil engineer George Condoemetraky.
</P>
<P>
   In Rhode Island, Democratic Rep. Patrick Kennedy, youngest son
of Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, faces three unknown challengers in his
all-but-certain bid for a third two-year term.
</P>
<P>
   Other well publicized governorship races have nothing to do with
political dynasties.
</P>
<P>
   In California, where the stakes are formidable, Democratic Lt.
Gov. Gray Davis is leading Republican Attorney General Dan Lungren
in a bid to succeed two-term GOP Gov. Pete Wilson. With the state
legislature in Democratic hands, a Davis victory would assure
Democrats a sweet prize _ domination in redrawing boundaries of the
state's 52 House districts for the 2002 election. The state
controls 20 percent of the electoral votes needed to win the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   And in Michigan, second-term Gov. John Engler is well ahead of
his challenger, Democrat Geoffrey Fieger, a lawyer for Dr. Jack
Kevorkian, the practitioner of doctor-assisted suicide. Fieger has
committed a series of gaffes that have contributed to Engler's
32-point lead in the latest survey. In one news conference, Fieger
offered _ and then withdrew _ a proposal for a $450 million state
tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual development for a midterm election, the Texas
lieutenant governor's race is taking on added significance.
Politicians are watching it closely because of the possibility that
George W. Bush will run for president in 2000. In the second-spot
battle, Democratic state comptroller John Sharp is running
neck-and-neck with Republican agriculture commissioner Rick Perry.
</P>
<P>
   Six political veterans face challenges of varying intensity.
</P>
<P>
   Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y., who has served in the Senate for 18
years, faces a stiff challenge from Rep. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y.,
an 18-year veteran of the House. D'Amato's hopes for a fourth
Senate term may turn on voters' reaction to D'Amato's denigration
of Schumer as a ``putz head,'' which is Yiddish for penis and in
American slang means fool or jerk.
</P>
<P>
   With 32 years of service in the Senate, Fritz Hollings, D-S.C.,
is locked in a tight race for re-election against Republican Bob
Inglis, a third-term congressman.
</P>
<P>
   Three longtime House members are fighting for political survival
as well.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. George Brown, D-Calif., a 34-year veteran, is seeking an
18th term in a tough race against Republican businessman Elia
Pirozzi.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, Democratic Rep. Charlie Stenholm, a 20-year House
veteran, is struggling for an 11th term against Republican San
Angelo Mayor Ruddy Izzard. Stenholm is hoping his support for the
GOP's wide-ranging impeachment inquiry will help offset Texas
Republicans' generous financial support for Izzard.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Lane Evans, D-Ill., who has served in the House for 16
years with strong support from organized labor, is trying to hold
off a stiff challenge by Republican Mark Baker, a former television
anchorman.
</P>
<P>
   Wisconsin Gov. Tommy Thompson, who has occupied the state house
for 12 years, appears headed for a fourth term despite the
challenge of Republican Ed Garvey. Thompson, listed by GOP
presidential nominee Bob Dole as a possible vice presidential
running mate in 1996, could play a key role in the presidential
sweepstakes in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's outcome also will determine whether the stunning 1992
``year of the women'' Senate victories by Democratic Sens. Barbara
Boxer of California, Patty Murray of Washington and Carol
Moseley-Braun of Illinois will be repeated. Sen. Barbara Mikulski,
D-Md., who won her second term in 1992, is expected to win another
one this year.
</P>
<P>
   Polls show Boxer pulling slightly ahead of California Republican
state Treasurer Matt Fong and Murray leading her GOP challenger,
second-term Rep. Linda Smith.
</P>
<P>
   But Moseley-Braun, the first African-American woman to serve in
the Senate, is lagging behind millionaire Republican state Sen.
Peter Fitzgerald, whose attacks on her ethics have forced her to
air an apology. ``I know I've made some mistakes and disappointed
some people,'' Moseley-Braun says in a campaign ad. ``But I want
you to know that I've always tried to do what's best for
Illinois.''
</P>
<P>
   In yet another hot race, Rep. Loretta Sanchez, D-Calif., is well
ahead in fighting off a comeback effort by former 11-term Rep. Bob
Dornan, the fiery California Republican who waged a bitter 15-month
campaign to deny Sanchez her 1996 victory by disputing the legality
of some ballots. The House ultimately rejected his claim.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
