<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-30 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6352 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOBACCO-MONEY-HNS &LR;      10-30 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-MONEY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG MONEY POURS INTO CALIFORNIA ELECTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Filed in ``a'' and ``p'' category)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CHUCK FINNIE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ More than $34 million poured into California
political compaigns in the last week, with a tobacco industry
effort to stamp out a cigarette tax leading the way, an analysis of
campaign finance reports shows.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Morris Cos. Inc. contributed almost $6 million from Oct.
20-28 to the effort to defeat Proposition 10 _ making it the
biggest giver in the campaign's final days, the analysis by the San
Francisco Examiner showed.
</P>
<P>
   More than $4.7 million went to both sides in the other
high-stakes state measure on Tuesday's ballot, Proposition 5, which
would allow expanded gambling at Indian reservations.
</P>
<P>
   And more than $10 million was reported to campaigns for state
office and the state propositions on a single day _ Oct. 21.
</P>
<P>
   The analysis was based on records filed in the secretary of
state's office of contributions of $1,000 or more made after Oct.
19, the end of the last campaign finance reporting period.
</P>
<P>
   The infusion of money drives the escalating advertising wars in
the days leading up to Tuesday's election and has renewed debate
over the need for campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   The real action was in the ballot measures, where big tobacco is
trying to turn voters against what started as a popular move to
fund childhood development and anti-smoking programs through a new
50-cent-per-pack cigarette tax.
</P>
<P>
   And, in what is expected to be the most expensive ballot measure
in state history, Indian tribes are going toe-to-toe with Nevada
casinos and organized labor over allowing expanded gambling on the
reservations.
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco giants, led by Philip Morris, contributed $7.6 million
over the eight days, records show.
</P>
<P>
   During the last two weeks of a campaign, contributions of $1,000
or more must be reported to the state. Candidates for federal
office aren't covered by the state law.
</P>
<P>
   The contributions by the tobacco companies to defeat the
cigarette tax made the No on Proposition 10 campaign the biggest
recipient of late money.
</P>
<P>
   A representative for the anti-Proposition 10 campaign said the
money would fund ads to encourage voters to decide the measure on
its merits, rather than as a referendum on an unpopular tobacco
industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been encouraging voters to carefully read this
initiative, and the ads simply point out the obvious flaws with
this big government program,'' said Matt Taggart, spokesman for the
No on Proposition 10 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``The devil is in the details, and if it passes, ultimately
voters will be left with more encumbered spending, a bloated,
shadow bureaucracy and no accountability.''
</P>
<P>
   Proposition 10 would create state and county commissions to
decide how to divvy up an estimated $750 million annually from the
new levy on smokers.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Roos, the former Democratic assemblyman from Los Angeles
heading the pro-Proposition 10 campaign, said the cigarette makers
were putting in cash late in the campaign in hope of avoiding
detection.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted to hide the true source of the money,'' Roos said.
``They know the business they are in and they know people have
caught on to the fact that every year 300,000 people die because of
their product. They know that people don't like them.''
</P>
<P>
   Proposition 5, the measure to loosen regulations on
reservation-based casinos, received more than $3.2 million in
contributions, disclosure reports show. The measure's financial
supporters are mainly California tribes.
</P>
<P>
   Money also has been pouring into the governor's race, in which
Democrat Gray Davis and Republican Dan Lungren are expected to
spend a combined $50 million _ a record. The Davis campaign
reported $2.2 million in late contributions, and the Lungren camp,
$2.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``For whatever reason, people have decided to contribute,'' said
Michael Bustamante, the Davis campaign spokesman. ``People like a
winner. It is hedge-your-bet time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We met our budget and we have significantly curtailed our
fund-raising activity, but money keeps coming in,'' Bustamante
said.
</P>
<P>
   Lungren campaign representatives didn't return telephone
messages seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   The secretary of state recorded 3,156 separate contribution
reports from candidates and campaigns between Oct. 20 and
Wednesday. No reporting was recorded Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Recipients reported taking in an average $4.3 million per day as
the election drew near _ including a single $5.9 million donation
from Philip Morris to the No on Proposition 10 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Voters passed a ballot measure in 1996 imposing severe limits on
contributions to candidates for state office and ballot measure
campaigns. But a court threw it out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The strategy behind late contributions is (to allow campaigns)
to do last-minute damage attacks without the opportunity for a
response. That is the real modus operandi,'' said H. Eric Shockman,
a professor of government at the University of Southern California.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-30-98 1806EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981030.0259 </DOCNO>
