<HEADER>
A6384 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOLIVIA-PRISONS-$ADV1     10-30 1377
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOLIVIA-PRISONS-$ADV1-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOLIVIA-PRISONS-$ADV1 
 
BOLIVIA TO END PRISON ARRANGEMENT ALLOWING CONVICTS' WIVES,
CHILDREN TO MOVE INTO JAILS 
 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, NOV. 1) 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN OTIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COCHABAMBA, Bolivia _ Instead of marching off to choir practice
or to the mall like other junior high students, 13-year-old Marysol
Rojas has a different after-school agenda: She goes to jail.
</P>
<P>
   She's no criminal. Yet every afternoon, Marysol checks into her
father's tiny cell at San Sebastian prison in the central Bolivian
city of Cochabamba.
</P>
<P>
   There, amid the shouting, drinking and carousing of 450 inmates,
she curls up on the cement floor and tries to concentrate on her
homework.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first came here, I didn't like it at all. It was full
of scoundrels,'' said Marysol, who has lived in the prison for four
years. ``But now I'm getting used to it.''
</P>
<P>
   In Bolivia, prison is a family affair. Thousands of down-and-out
wives and children of Bolivian convicts have moved into the jails,
often spending years behind bars in order to survive difficult
economic times.
</P>
<P>
   Some prison experts cautiously endorse this unique,
hard-time/time-share arrangement because they say it helps to keep
families together and improves inmate behavior.
</P>
<P>
   But Bolivian officials contend that drug traffickers,
pickpockets and sex offenders are dangerous role models.
</P>
<P>
   After the murder of an 11-year-old girl in a prison in January,
Bolivian President Hugo Banzer announced plans to remove all
children from the jails by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jail is not a home,'' said Mario Prada, a spokesman for first
lady Yolanda Banzer, who is leading the prison-reform campaign.
``It's not the place for a child.''
</P>
<P>
   Compared with U.S. prisons, Latin American jails are loosely
regulated. Prisoners have more freedoms and conjugal visits are
routine. In women's jails, infants usually are allowed to stay with
their mothers.
</P>
<P>
   Bolivia, however, is the only country that has allowed large
numbers of women and children to move into its jails, according to
Joanne Mariner, a prison expert with Human Rights Watch in New York
who has toured Bolivian penitentiaries.
</P>
<P>
   Several factors led to this unofficial policy. For one thing,
the Bolivian government largely ignores the prisons. Inmates must
fend for themselves, pay rent for their tiny jail cells and even
buy their own food. Thus, family support is a lifeline.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good thing about (Bolivian) prisons is that they allow
more family contact. But the flip side is that the prisoners are
dependent on their families for a lot of basic requirements,''
Mariner said.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem was a surge in the prison population after the
passage of a draconian anti-drug law in 1988 that mandates the
immediate detention of Bolivians suspected of drug smuggling.
</P>
<P>
   In such cases, guilt is assumed. Those detained must prove their
innocence in Bolivia's slow, often corrupt judicial system.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, 175 new prisoners entered San Sebastian prison,
compared with just eight in 1987, according to the Andean
Information Network, an independent research group that has
published a survey on Bolivian prisons.
</P>
<P>
   About 430 of San Sebastian's 450 inmates are charged with drug
trafficking. Most are small-timers, peasants who were nabbed while
trying to earn extra money by transporting a few pounds of coca
paste, which is used to make cocaine. Bolivia is the world's second
largest producer of cocaine, behind Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   With the main income earner of the house behind bars, family
members often have trouble finding work and making rent payments.
</P>
<P>
   Many simply move into the jails. For some children, jail is the
only alternative because state-run orphanages are overcrowded.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you hear that kids are living in the jails, you might
think: `Oh my God, that's horrible!' But when you look at the
options, it might not be the worst thing,'' said Lee Cridland, of
the Andean Information Network.
</P>
<P>
   At San Sebastian prison, which is home to 175 children, freshly
showered youngsters wearing blue and white uniforms and backpacks
file through the main gate each morning, past rifle-toting guards,
and walk to school.
</P>
<P>
   Wives often leave for jobs in Cochabamba or help their husbands
build furniture in the jail's woodshop for sale to the public.
Preschool children go next door to a day-care center. Nearly
everyone is back inside the walls by 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent afternoon, a shirtless inmate brushed his teeth
while holding his infant son on his shoulders in the crowded prison
courtyard. Others played volleyball or snacked on chicken and fried
bananas sold at rickety wooden food stands.
</P>
<P>
   It all gives San Sebastian the feel of an open-air market rather
than a penitentiary.
</P>
<P>
   Rene Ochoa, who was jailed for drug trafficking, said that this
tranquil, Sunday-picnic atmosphere lifts his spirits.
</P>
<P>
   ``You feel the support of your family,'' Ochoa said, as he
sipped a soft drink on the second-floor balcony of the jail. ``We
try not to talk about (prison). We try to be happy.''
</P>
<P>
   At one point last year, about 2,200 children lived in Bolivia's
jails. Most are younger than 10. Adolescents are encouraged to move
out to reduce the threat of sexual assaults.
</P>
<P>
   Rose Marie de Acha of the Bolivian Information Center, a private
think tank in Cochabamba, contends that the policy has improved the
behavior of inmates.
</P>
<P>
   Some prisoners argue that it may actually be safer for kids to
live in jail because parents can keep an eye on them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all feel responsible for the safety of the children,'' said
Oligario Vega, an inmate at San Pedro jail in the capital city of
La Paz.
</P>
<P>
   Still, no one believes that it's an ideal arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's so humanizing, then other countries would put the
policy into practice,'' Prada said.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1994 survey at San Sebastian jail by the Andean Information
Network, nearly half of the families interviewed said they would
prefer their children to live elsewhere because they had developed
a more aggressive behavior or felt jail was a dangerous
environment.
</P>
<P>
   The Bolivian government finally took notice after an 11-year-old
girl was raped and smothered to death by a deranged inmate in a La
Paz prison in January.
</P>
<P>
   The story was covered extensively by the Bolivian media, and
first lady Yolanda Banzer organized a publicity campaign dubbed:
``Don't imprison my childhood.''
</P>
<P>
   The outrage led to a new law that states that all women and
children must leave the jails by Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   They will be sent to live with other family members or to
government shelters set up especially for them, said Jose Orias,
director-general of Bolivia's penal system.
</P>
<P>
   The forced evictions began earlier this year and sparked a
series of protests in the jails due to fears that some children
will end up on the streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Family means everything,'' said 14-year-old Ximena Medran,
whose father has been jailed in San Sebastian for a year. ``I
wouldn't want to be separated from my father. Everyone should be
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Mariner, of Human Rights Watch, an independent human-rights
organization, said one justification for removing children is the
lack of prison classifications. There are no minimum security
facilities in Bolivia, thus the children must share space with all
kinds of criminals.
</P>
<P>
   But because prisoners have long been dependent on their
families, under the new policy the government will have to provide
much more support for inmates, Mariner said.
</P>
<P>
   Others say the move is part of a larger government plan to turn
the prisons into harsh symbols of punishment in order to deter
would-be criminals.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are trying to reform the jails along the lines of the
North American model without taking into account Bolivian
realities,'' said Isabelle Roger, who runs the day-care center next
to San Sebastian prison.
</P>
<P>
   Orias retorts that if inmates are so concerned about their
families, they should have stayed out of trouble in the first
place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, the prisoner should think about that issue
before committing a crime,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   John Otis is a free-lance journalist. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
