A6399 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CSIBLEY-COLUMN01-COX     10-30 0569
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CSIBLEY-COLUMN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: It's `Heaven Bound' time at Big Bethel
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL NOVEMBER 1: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Celestine Sibley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Heaven Bound,'' the classic story of erring human beings'
struggle to reach the Pearly Gates, will be presented for the 800th
time at Big Bethel AME Church on Nov. 13 and 14 in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   I have seen this folk story almost every November since I came
to Atlanta _ first at the suggestion of former Atlanta Constitution
editor Ralph McGill _ and I have tried not to miss it ever.
</P>
<P>
   It is one of the colorful and moving events on Atlanta's
calendar, and this year I have been given an assignment. As the
first honorary recipient of angel wings at the conclusion of the
performance a couple of years ago, I have been assigned to present
wings this year to the second honorary recipient, U.S. Rep. John
Lewis (D-Ga.).
</P>
<P>
   Congressman Lewis has been called a saint a few times lately,
principally because of his support of President Clinton, but this
will be the first concrete proof that members of his race also
regard him as saintly.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, I expect the performance of colorfully clad sinners
trying to make it to heaven and the singing of a really spectacular
choir will be pretty much the same as it was in 1930 when it was
started to raise funds to rebuild Big Bethel after it was destroyed
by fire.
</P>
<P>
   Gregory Coleman, an Atlanta lawyer and a lifetime member of the
cast, told me that Mills B. Lane, who headed the Citizens &AMP;
Southern Bank, later NationsBank, suggested a benefit performance
of some kind to raise money for rebuilding the church. He admired
the singing of the choir and suggested a concert, but two Sunday
school teachers were already at work on the allegory that became
``Heaven Bound.''
</P>
<P>
   They have been a remarkably durable group of performers. One of
the original cast is Esther McDonald, who except for one time, has
been in all the performances of ``Heaven Bound'' since 1930. She
joined Big Bethel in 1909. Cora Wofford, who joined the cast in
1936 as a saint, died this year.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Coleman's book, ``We're Heaven Bound,'' about the history of
the performance, published in 1992 by the University of Georgia
Press, is about to make its appearance in paperback. It is loaded
with pictures and is a treasure for all Atlantans.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the author is working on a book about the history of
the church, which is colorful itself. It was started in 1855 by
white Methodists who admitted slave members. L.P. Grant, the
engineer who designed the defenses of Atlanta for the Civil War,
contributed land down on Jenkins Street, now called Auditorium Way
because it is next-door to the old municipal auditorium.
</P>
<P>
   When the white members withdrew, turning the church over to
slaves, it was still mandatory that a white attend all services.
Once, Mr. Coleman tells me, the congregation met without a white in
attendance and a nursemaid, determined to meet the legal
requirement of the day, went and brought a white baby to sit
through the service.
</P>
<P>
   During the occupation of Atlanta by Gen. William Sherman's
forces, the little church served as a hospital for smallpox
sufferers.
</P>
<P>
   The performance starts at 7 p.m. and, as always, is in the
church sanctuary at 220 Auburn Ave. N.E.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-30-98 1822EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
