<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-30 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6400 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CUSTOM-SUITS-COX     10-30 0391
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUSTOM-SUITS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Definition of `tailor-made' suits debatable, but concept
catching on
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL NOVEMBER 1: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's a war of words waging wherever better menswear is being
sold.
</P>
<P>
   All over Atlanta there are marketers arguing over the definition
of a custom-made suit. The debate's combative because of the money
involved: Whereas better ``off-the-rack'' suits cost a few hundred
dollars, suits that carry the ``custom-made'' designation sell for
a base price of about $1,500.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people who say they make custom clothing don't even know
what `custom' means,'' contends Edgar Pomeroy, Atlanta's famous
merchant of customized suits.
</P>
<P>
   Pomeroy has detractors _ other suit-makers, mainly _ who say his
suits don't fit under the heading of ``custom-made'' either. He
refers to his $1,800-and-up suits as ``bespoke,'' and says the term
means, ``made by hand, for an individual, with (a series of)
fittings.''
</P>
<P>
   But R. Mauryce Vick, who coordinates custom suit services for
Alexxandro's Authentic Tailors, a division of Guffey's stores in
Buckhead and Marietta, says ``bespoke'' is a term that people use
far too loosely and one that should be thrown out of the menswear
vernacular.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bespoke simply means `too good to be described,''' Vick says.
``And nobody makes anything that's that good anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Between the competing commercial interests of clothiers such as
Pomeroy and Vick stand the growing number of men willing to pay
more _ much more _ for suits tailored to their specific proportions
and tastes. Vick says some of these men are being bamboozled by
clothiers who play on the public's ignorance of what a custom-made
suit entails.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you walk into a shop, and they take your measurements and
send those measurements off to some plant to make the suit, it's
not a custom-made suit,'' Vick explained. ``That's a
made-to-mmeasure suit made, custom suits provide unique degrees of
satisfaction. It's that added appeal _ the prestige factor _ that
leads clothiers to believe that custom suit sales will increase.
</P>
<P>
   Said Vick: ``I get excited about it because I know, without a
doubt, that it's going mainstream.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
