<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sopping has never sounded so good
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL NOVEMBER 1: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Jim Auchmutey
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   History remembers Ross Barnett as the Mississippi governor who
stood in the way of desegregation at University of Mississippi in
1962. The folksy old cuss once suggested a less controversial
remembrance for himself:
</P>
<P>
   When I die, you can bury me deep.
</P>
<P>
   Put a jug of molasses at my feet,
</P>
<P>
   With nine biscuits in each hand,
</P>
<P>
   I'll sop my way to the Promised Land.
</P>
<P>
   Sopping, like politics, isn't as easy as it sounds. Experienced
soppers strive for the simultaneous sensation of butter, syrup and
biscuit melting in the mouth. They accomplish this by letting the
butter sit out to soften, then swirling it with slightly warmed
syrup, through which they dredge hot biscuits. Sorghum syrup is
said to taste better if you pronounce it ``sarg'm surp,'' as
old-timers do, which is the way it naturally comes out when your
mouth is full of syrup.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some other ways to use sorghum.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Sorghum Apple Stack Cake
</P>
<P>
   Makes 1 cake, up to 10 layers, serving 16 Preparation time: 40
minutes Cooking time: 2 hours
</P>
<P>
   This may be the most famous Appalachian dessert. Stack cakes are
assembled from layer upon layer of thin, biscuitlike cakes mortared
together with apple filling. Joseph Dabney, author of a new book on
mountain cooking, ``Smokehouse Ham, Spoon Bread &AMP; Scuppernong
Wine'' (Cumberland House), tells a story about stack cakes: At
old-time weddings, neighbors would bring layers to make a cake, and
a bride could measure her popularity by how tall the cake was. This
version has 10 layers, so she must be very popular.
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup butter
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1cup sorghum
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup cream
</P>
<P>
   2eggs, well-beaten
</P>
<P>
   6cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   and cover bottom of skillet equally. Bake for 12 minutes. Loosen
cake layer with spatula and place on a dinner plate, then spread
with a thin layer of hot apple filling (recipe below). Continue
baking layers and stacking them with apple filling. Do not cover
the top layer. Cover with plastic wrap and let set overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Dried Apple Filling
</P>
<P>
   Makes 7 1/2 cups Preparation time: 10 minutes Cooking time: 1
hour
</P>
<P>
   1pound dried apples
</P>
<P>
   6cups water
</P>
<P>
   1cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon ground nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   2teaspoons ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon ground cloves
</P>
<P>
   Cover apples with water and simmer until tender (about 1 hour).
Mash apples into small chunks; add sugar and spices and mix well.
Spread about 1/2 cup of hot apple mixture on each cake layer.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 439 calories, 7 grams protein, 10 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 20), 84 grams carbohydrates, 52
milligrams cholesterol, 360 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   VEGETABLE
</P>
<P>
   Vegetable Stir-Fry
</P>
<P>
   Makes 2 cups Preparation Time: 15 minutes Cooking time: 10
minutes
</P>
<P>
   There's a scene in ``To Kill a Mockingbird'' where Scout can't
believe how a poor boy dumps syrup over everything on his dinner
plate. This recipe doesn't go that far. But Southern cooks have
long used syrup as a glaze or as a sweetening agent for certain
vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   3medium carrots, pared and sliced diagonally
</P>
<P>
   1green pepper, cut in strips
</P>
<P>
   2ribs celery, sliced
</P>
<P>
   diagonally
</P>
<P>
   1/4pound fresh green beans,
</P>
<P>
   cut in 2-inch strips
</P>
<P>
   3green onions, white part only, sliced diagonally
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4teaspoon pepper
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons sorghum
</P>
<P>
   Melt butter in large skillet over high heat. Add carrots, green
pepper, celery, beans and onion and sprinkle with salt and pepper.
Cook, stirring constantly, for 5 minutes. Add sorghum and stir 1
minute more. Serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 101 calories, 2 grams protein, 6 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 54), 12 grams carbohydrates, 16 milligrams
cholesterol, 387 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   SIDE DISH
</P>
<P>
   Baked Beans
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings Preparation time: 20 minutes Cooking time: 35
minutes
</P>
<P>
   4slices bacon
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons reserved bacon fat
</P>
<P>
   1/3cup diced celery
</P>
<P>
   1small onion, diced
</P>
<P>
   3tablespoons chopped
</P>
<P>
   green pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/4teaspoon garlic powder
</P>
<P>
   21-pound cans pork and beans
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup ketchup
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup sorghum
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon prepared
</P>
<P>
   mustard
</P>
<P>
   1/4teaspoon liquid smoke, optional
</P>
<P>
   l
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 400 degrees. Fry bacon and remove from grease,
leaving 2 tablespoons grease in skillet. Add celery, onion and
green pepper and saute until tender. Add garlic powder, pork and
beans, ketchup, sorghum, mustard and liquid smoke; mix well. Pour
into lightly greased 1 1/2-quart casserole dish. Cover; bake for 25
minutes or until heated. _ From the Sweet Sorghum Growers
Association.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 219 calories, 8 grams protein, 7 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 31), 31 grams carbohydrates, 14 milligrams
cholesterol, 734 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Election Day Gingerbread Cookies
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 dozen 2-inch cookies Preparation time: 15 minutes
Cooking time: 18 minutes per sheet
</P>
<P>
   Clarise Shepherd of Jamestown, Tenn., grew up in a large
Appalachian family and remembers what an event it was every fall
when the first sorghum syrup was made. ``We knew there would be
gingerbread soon in the kitchen,'' she says. The name of her
recipe? Farm wives used to make gingerbread to sell at the polls on
Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   3/4cup shortening
</P>
<P>
   2cups dark brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   2/3cup sorghum
</P>
<P>
   2/3cup boiling water
</P>
<P>
   4cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon ground ginger
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   2teaspoons baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2teaspoons baking powder
</P>
<P>
   2teaspoons ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon ground nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon ground cloves
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon dry mustard
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon ground mace
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 325 degrees. In a large bowl, cream the
shortening and dark brown sugar. Mix sorghum and boiling water and
add to creamed mixture. Add flour, ginger, salt, soda, baking
powder, cinnamon, nutmeg, cloves, mustard and mace to the liquid
and mix well. The batter will be sticky. Add additional flour and
knead lightly until the stickiness is gone and dough can be handled
easily by hand. Form each tablespoonful into a biscuit shape. Place
on lightly greased cookie sheets and bake for about 18 minutes. Do
not flatten the dough on the cookie sheet, and they will hold their
form.
</P>
<P>
   Cool on a wire rack and store in an airtight container. Cooking
softens them, and a slice of bread placed with them keeps them
soft.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 103 calories, 1 gram protein, 3 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 30), 17 grams carbohydrates, no cholesterol, 108
milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
