<HEADER>
A6402 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TASTE-COX     10-30 1248
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TASTE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Mennonites of Tennessee, known for old-time religion, are
making some old-time sorghum syrup, too
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL NOVEMBER 1: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Jim Auchmutey
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MUDDY POND, Tenn._When the Mennonites moved into this rocky
corner of the Cumberland Plateau, so many people drove out to look
that a neighbor posted a sign christening their gravel road the
Muddy Pond Interstate. It was 1965, and the newcomers seemed rather
peculiar to the local crew cuts and beehives. The women wore
bonnets like pioneers. The men wore beards that looked as thickety
as the mountain underbrush.
</P>
<P>
   ``They must have thought we were hippies,'' laughs John
Guenther, the head of the first family to arrive.
</P>
<P>
   The weekend tourists are still coming today, but for a different
reason: They want to sop, not gawk. The Mennonites, known for their
old-time religion, are practicing some old-time cooking as well,
making sorghum syrup the way highland Southerners have been doing
for generations.
</P>
<P>
   On a warm autumn Saturday, a couple of dozen customers sit under
the shade of an oak tree and watch as the grinding wheel turns. Two
horses, harnessed to a long, weathered log, plod in a wide circle
around a man who stands on a platform feeding stalks of cane into a
press. A stream of green liquid gushes out the other end of the
machinery, through a burlap filter and into a barrel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would you mind if I took a stalk?'' asks one of the
spectators, Clarise Shepherd of nearby Jamestown. ``I'd like to
take some back to my granddaughter. I don't think she's ever seen
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of us these days probably haven't seen sorghum. For decades
now, refined white sugar has been America's sweetener _ as
universal as salt and pepper. It wasn't always that way. Before
granulated sugar became widely available around the turn of the
century, it was too expensive for most people. Americans relied on
other, more distinctive sweeteners such as molasses, honey and
maple syrup. In the South, people made their own syrups from
sorghum and sugar cane and used them to sop biscuits and flavor
everything from cakes to collard greens.
</P>
<P>
   There is something of a divide in this region when it comes to
syrups. In the lower South _ especially the sugar country of
Louisiana _ people swear by cane syrup. The South Georgia town of
Cairo, home of the Roddenberry syrup factory, is so identified with
cane that the local high school team is called the Syrup-makers.
</P>
<P>
   In the hills and mountains of the upland South, on the other
hand, syrup has traditionally been made from sorghum, a grass that
grows in spearlike stalks reaching as high as 15 feet. Sweet
sorghum (not to be confused with a variety widely grown for fodder
in the Midwest) is cultivated for syrup on small farms from
Virginia to Kansas, with the greatest acreage in Kentucky and
Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the acreage is all that great. While cane syrup has
held its own, sorghum has dwindled. When the Georgia mountain town
of Blairsville held its first sorghum festival 28 years ago, there
were perhaps 30 syrup mills in the area. Now there are fewer than a
third that number.
</P>
<P>
   Changing tastes are one reason. For palates raised on white
sugar and maple-flavored pancake syrups, sorghum can have an
unpleasant off-flavor _ a little grassy, sometimes downright
bitter. It's not unusual for the schoolchildren who tour the Muddy
Pond sorghum mill to crinkle their noses when they sample the amber
syrup.
</P>
<P>
   John Guenther never turned up his nose at sorghum. The leader of
the Muddy Pond Mennonite community grew up on the Canadian plains
of Saskatchewan in a poor family that ate blackstrap molasses, the
harshest-tasting syrup. When he moved away and tried sorghum for
the first time, it seemed sweet by comparison. Settling in
Tennessee as a young man, he thought sorghum would be a fine thing
to build a farming village around.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know if we could make it at first,'' he says. Not
only did he burn his first batch of syrup, but he had trouble
communicating with the local folk. Guenther was raised in a
German-speaking family and still has a curious Canadian-Teutonic
accent. Tennesseans sounded just as funny to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't understand them,'' he says. ``I'd go down to the
store, and they'd be telling these jokes, and I'd come back home
crying, thinking they were laughing at me. But these people have
really accepted us. These hillbillies around here are all right.''
</P>
<P>
   Guenther certainly acts like one of the boys now. During sorghum
season, from Labor Day through the end of October, you can usually
find him holding forth among the visitors at the mill, a perpetual
look of amusement on his face. At 58, he has a long, gray-flecked
beard that falls into twin forks, like Yosemite Sam's, and wears a
pair of overalls that seem to have putty-colored dirt woven into
the fabric. He is the patriarch of an extended family of 25 that
works and lives together on 740 acres of farmland.
</P>
<P>
   The Guenthers started out as old-order Mennonites, members of a
back-to-the-roots Protestant church that practices nonconformity to
the point of eschewing modern technology. They cleared their land
at Muddy Pond with horses and crosscut saws, and for years refused
to drive or use electricity.
</P>
<P>
   But they have made allowances. Guenther gave in and bought a
couple of used pickup trucks. And though there's still no
electricity in his house, he couldn't get by without it at the
sorghum mill.
</P>
<P>
   The syrup-making process starts in the fields where the sorghum
is cut by hand and left to dry two or three days. Most of the juice
is extracted on site with portable presses run off tractor engines.
But they always save some cane to crush the old-fashioned way, with
horses, for the tourists. The juice is then piped into the mill, a
shedlike structure with screened windows and clouds of sweet steam
that make it hard to see from one end to the other. The sap pours
into a 20-foot-long pan where it boils for 20 or 30 minutes, as men
stand over the sides skimming green scum off the top. The juice
loses perhaps 90 percent of its volume to evaporation before
emerging, thick and golden, from a tap where bonneted women fill
jugs and jars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm taking this to my mother,'' says one customer, Arthur Hart
of Chattanooga, as he walks out with a freshly filled quart jar
that feels as warm as a napping cat. ``I want a stack cake for my
birthday, and she can't make it without sorghum.''
</P>
<P>
   The Guenthers don't sell stack cakes, but they sell just about
everything else made with sorghum, from fudge to gingerbread. The
chief baker is John's wife, Emma, a no-nonsense woman with a flat
Indiana accent who doesn't see eye to eye with her husband on
technology. She dislikes it so much that when visitors aim a camera
in her direction, she sometimes shoos them away like yellow
jackets. In fact, she wishes her husband had never bought a pickup
or a tractor. She's a horse-and-buggy Mennonite, even in the
kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing about this cool weather is that I can cook on
my wood stove,'' she says. ``I always feel like it's Sunday morning
when I can use my wood stove.''
</P>
<P>
   She does all this wonderful baking on a wood stove?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' she says, after a moment's hesitation, ``I actually do
my baking on a gas stove.''
</P>
<P>
   Sin never tasted so sweet.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
