<HEADLINE>
AIR FORCES SQUARE OFF IN `DEFENDER CHALLENGE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SIG CHRISTENSON  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Some of the world's top troops gather here Sunday
for what one general described as the ``Pro Bowl'' of
anti-terrorist and security forces competitions.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of tackling runners or throwing footballs, the nearly
200 uniformed personnel from the United States, Great Britain and
Canada _ battling for top honors at ``Defender Challenge '98'' _
will compete with rifles, machine guns and grenade launchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the one time each year that the `best of the best' of
security forces compete against each other in the craft and tools
of our trade,'' said Brig. Gen. Richard A. Coleman, commander of
the Air Force Security Forces Center, based at Lackland Air Force
Base.
</P>
<P>
   The contest, which ends Nov. 7, is being held at Lackland and
Camp Bullis for the first time. It follows the center's move to San
Antonio last year.
</P>
<P>
   Previously named ``Peacekeeper Challenge'' and held at Kirtland
Air Force Base in Albuquerque, N.M., the contest is rooted in a
1952 marksmanship competition sponsored by the old Strategic Air
Command.
</P>
<P>
   It went international in 1981, when the Royal Air Force joined a
dozen other teams at Kirtland. Since then the contest has focused
on likely terrorist and enemy scenarios, and this year has been
given a new name, Defender Challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's based on fire team tactics with heavy emphasis on
physical fitness, weapons application and patrolling which requires
demanding teamwork,'' Coleman said.
</P>
<P>
   The base defense and anti-terrorism tactics are ``overall
security measures that one could be expected to be called on to
perform anywhere in the world to defend Air Force resources,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman likened the event to the NFL's Pro Bowl, held each
January in Hawaii, saying Defender Challenge is ``the place where
the Security Forces display their best.''
</P>
<P>
   Even before the 168 team members arrived here Friday, they
endured competition within their commands, much as Olympians do,
Security Forces Center spokesman Denton Lankford said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call this the `Olympics' of security forces competition,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Security force teams from 12 Air Force commands, the Royal Air
Force Regiment and Canadian Forces Air Command will square off
starting Monday at Lackland and nearby Camp Bullis, where the Air
Force maintains a $20 million anti-terrorist training facility.
</P>
<P>
   Rifles with infrared sights, grenade launchers and an iron
constitution are key elements of the contest, which kicks off
Monday. Team members will thread their way through a 1.1-mile
obstacle course over hilly terrain. Among the 21 obstacles they
must negotiate are a row of X-shaped logs dubbed ``the tough nut''
and a trench covered by mesh and barb wire.
</P>
<P>
   A new computer-driven handgun course filled with pop-up steel
targets is part of the handgun competition, as is a first-ever
nighttime M-16 rifle marksmanship course.
</P>
<P>
   Capping the event is the ``chief's challenge,'' a showdown where
one team member from each unit works Lackland's ``confidence
course.''
</P>
<P>
   Teams and individuals will be honored with gold, silver and
bronze medals in each event, but they will not be ranked in terms
of their overall performance or given a cumulative score.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-30-98 1823EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981030.0273 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-30 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6406 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-LMAY31-COX     10-30 0553
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-LMAY31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fringed gentian
 &HT;    By Lee May
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   McCaysville, Ga._Call it a walk on the wild side.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Patrick, a botanist with the state Department of Natural
Resources' Georgia Natural Heritage Program, had come to help me
find out what grows on this land. I had invited him to visit
because so many of the plants are new to me _ and because I wanted
to know if any were among the state's rare or endangered ones.
</P>
<P>
   Looking through ``Protected Plants of Georgia,'' the fascinating
book published in 1995 by the department (Patrick is one of the
authors), I noted several that had been seen in Fannin County,
including two sedges (Blue Ridge purple and Fraser), both of which
were designated as threatened. Also threatened was the small
whorled pogonia, a perennial herb.
</P>
<P>
   Cited as endangered was goldenseal, while pink and yellow
lady-slippers were listed as unusual.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with the book, I had searched for any of these plants _
and others that might have shown up from other counties (entirely
possible, as they cannot read and thus do not know where their
official homes are).
</P>
<P>
   Since winter, the only listed plant I'd found was pink
lady-slipper, which grows near the cabin in a shaded area under
pines and hardwoods, amid drifts of ground cedar.
</P>
<P>
   However, I'd seen much that I didn't recognize _ protected or
not. I needed help.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick gave me a lot, including a simple way of telling a red
oak from a white one: ``The leaves. Red oaks' lobes are pointed;
white oaks' are rounded.'' This I learned on a chilly October
morning as we stood on the back porch, where we were almost at eye
level with the tops of several oaks.
</P>
<P>
   We headed for the woods and hit the ground rushing, as a shower
was blowing in; as it turned out, the welcome rain just released
the woods' wonderful fragrances, leaving us unsoaked under
leaf-thick trees.
</P>
<P>
   Good water and good plants are inextricably linked, Patrick
noted, explaining that springs, for example, ``need vegetation to
protect water quality'' _ a view reflected in broad-based
endorsements of Amendment 1 in Tuesday's vote on funding
acquisition of wild lands.
</P>
<P>
   What delightful discoveries on my wild land. Patiently, Patrick,
who must have seen plants like mine a million times, explained what
they were, when they bloom, their habits, sometimes, their lore.
</P>
<P>
   Ground cedar puts up spores, which, Patrick said, are so
flammable that photographers many years ago put matches to them to
light subjects.
</P>
<P>
   We saw sweet goldenrod, aster, sassafras, hearts-a-bustin',
trailing arbutus, Christmas fern, New York fern (tapered at top and
bottom, it, like Big Applers, ``burns its candle at both ends''),
trillium, rattlesnake plantain, broom sedge (Big Momma used it to
make brooms) _ and so much more.
</P>
<P>
   We saw no endangered plants on my land, not even any rare ones.
But they're all special to me.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick did say fringed gentian, an herb producing lovely blue
flowers, has been seen in two neighboring counties, Union and
Towns. I hope to see these threatened plants, hope too that they
decide to move onto my land. Meanwhile, Patrick lent me pictures.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: leemay(at)bellsouth.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
