<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-30 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6407 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LAMPS-COX     10-30 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAMPS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Watt's new
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The next time you switch on a lamp, take a good look at the
piece.
</P>
<P>
   Is the base that same old ginger jar or brass cylinder you
bought years ago? Is it topped by your basic ribbed white shade _
maybe minus the cellophane wrapper your mother insisted on keeping
to cut down on the dust?
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people tend to forget the importance of lighting as they
decorate,'' said Sid Fleishman of Ohio-based Kichler Lighting
Group. ``They'll start with the larger furniture pieces, then the
auxiliary pieces, then the carpet, wallpaper, etc., and finally the
lighting. But you want to know how important lighting is? Turn off
all the lights in your home one evening, and you'll see.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, consumers are seeing the light _ enough to provide
a burgeoning market for lamp designers, who are creating shades and
bases for every taste. Artists are also drawing on a seemingly
endless variety of materials to create one-of-a-kind lamps for a
generation of buyers demanding something unique among the
mass-produced. Even mainstream lighting manufacturers are
recognizing that consumers are willing to pay more for a lamp that
makes a statement _ not just light.
</P>
<P>
   Lamps made from costume jewelry. Lamps made from junk parts.
Lamps made from natural materials. Lamps made from pieces of old
lamps.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many small companies out there pushing the
boundaries for what a lamp can be,'' said Ben Goldstone of Fire
Farm, an Oakland, Calif., lighting manufacturer. ``No longer is
something that blasts this huge amount of wattage quite right in
the home. For our parents, furniture was furniture, but for this
new generation with disposable incomes, there are so many options
that are so much more playful in terms of shape, color and
proportions.''
</P>
<P>
   Sales of table lamps, which totaled $365 million last year, are
projected to increase 5 percent in 1998, in large part because of
design trends, according to the American Lighting Association.
</P>
<P>
   In the five years since opening Eclectic Electric, an Atlanta
lighting gallery on Highland Avenue, Kim Smith has seen the
evolution in the way consumers are embracing lighting as art.
``It's gotten crazy,'' said Smith, who represents some 100 artists
throughout the country. ``There are so many artists doing custom
work.''
</P>
<P>
   Max Birnkammer, for example, crafts lamps with metal bases and
rice paper shades in 20 colors from which buyers can take their
pick. Allowing buyers to customize their lamps makes them more
special than selecting ones off the department store shelf,
especially for those who can't afford to pay thousands for a piece
of lamp art.
</P>
<P>
   The demand for many artists' lamps has grown so large that
designers _ resisting the urge to sign on with a manufacturer _ are
creating limited editions of their work.
</P>
<P>
   It's a move New York artist Dez Ryan made last year. After 10
years of creating one-of-a-kind pieces from the parts of old lamps,
she began making collections from which consumers can order.
</P>
<P>
   ``For years, I would haunt the flea markets and junk shops to
collect old lamps, which I would then cannibalize, reconfigure and
reassemble into sculptural things,'' said Ryan, who previously
worked as a sculptor and art historian.
</P>
<P>
   She describes her pieces, which combine handblown glass orbs and
handsewn silk shades, as ``elegantly eccentric,'' for a look that's
part funk, part Grandma's attic. ``They're sort of 'Queen Victoria
meets Buster Keaton,' though someone said they're more like 'Dr.
Seuss meets Versace,''' Ryan said. ``My intention is for them to be
sophisticated but with a sense of humor.''
</P>
<P>
   Her latest creations, introduced at Atlanta International Gift &AMP;
Home Furnishings Market in July, include a collection dubbed ``Rare
Birds'' _ seven lamps with curvaceous shades in lacy velvets, sheer
chiffons and shimmery jacquards topping bases of smoked glass orbs
and ribbed necks.
</P>
<P>
   ``By rearranging the classic forms and embellishing them . . .
I'm aiming to breathe new life into an old form,'' Ryan said.
</P>
<P>
   The thing she likes best about her work is that while it looks
eccentric, it blends with traditional settings. ``That's kind of
the magic, in that it's not 'the trendy,' '' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Even large manufacturers have gotten the message that consumers
want something a little different.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are looking at lamps now more as collectible items,''
said Bob Davis of Miami-based Van Teal lighting. ``We say our
products are similar to the earrings and necklace on a beautiful
woman in a simple black dress. Until you have the accessories, the
decor is incomplete.''
</P>
<P>
   At the fall International Home Furnishings Market in High Point,
N.C., Van Teal emphasized color, with high-gloss, automotive-type
finishes covering tripod bases in metallic reds, blues and yellows.
</P>
<P>
   Others played off the Old World look with heavy ironwork, the
Arts and Crafts period with Mission styling, retro influences with
glass-beaded shades and Asian motifs with mosaics.
</P>
<P>
   For Fire Farm, Elizabeth Meredith designed a new ``Heaven and
Earth'' lamp that features a silk-paneled shade floating over a
metal base pan holding river rocks. Another of the company's lines,
``Puck,'' offers consumers the option of picking and choosing among
several colors of ``slipcover shades,'' including beige, sage
green, coral, yellow and lavender.
</P>
<P>
   David Landis, a New York designer, went for the oversized look
with ``classic retro'' lamps _ brass and cast zinc bases, topped by
tall white shades. ``I'm going after more of the mainstream market
with larger pieces that make a statement,'' he said. ``You can get
a stylish lamp for less than you used to at places like Pottery
Barn and Crate &AMP; Barrel. I think that just shows that Americans, as
a whole, are getting a little more design conscious.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
