<HEADER>
A6409 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-BIBLESTUDY-C     10-30 1643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-BIBLESTUDY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Laity embracing long-term Bible study
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The two factions are clearly divided: One supports a monarchy as
a unifying presence; the other sees royalty as outmoded,
unnecessary and a drain on the public treasury.
</P>
<P>
   The debate is not about the Great Britain of today but the
Israelites of the Hebrew Bible. And the discussion is taking place
in a classroom at a Snellville church.
</P>
<P>
   A dozen people meet here at St. Matthew's Episcopal Church for
two hours every Sunday night for an intensive study known as
Education for Ministry, or EFM. Conversation ranges from the
esoteric to the practical, with illustrations thrown in from opera,
film and politics. In between classes, there is homework to do.
</P>
<P>
   John Bennett, 55, a Georgia Department of Labor job counselor
and member of St. Edward's Episcopal Church in Lawrenceville,
recently finished the four-year program. ``It was a lot of work,''
he said, ``but I do miss the structure of the weekly
get-together.''
</P>
<P>
   Long-term studies such as EFM are sweeping mainline Protestant
churches, drawing lay people into the ancient prophets and obscure
genealogies of the Scriptures and adding context to the most
familiar Bible stories. Housewives and doctors, stockbrokers and
maintenance workers faithfully spend time every day reading the
Bible and supplementary material to prepare for class discussion.
Hauling their books, workbooks and multicolored highlighters, they
trek off to class once a week to test their theories and
perceptions on their classmates.
</P>
<P>
   Some churches have several groups at different levels going on
at once. At Atlanta's Cascade United Methodist Church, a dozen
groups are studying levels 1, 2 or 3 of the Disciple program from
the United Methodist publishing house. Each Wednesday, the church's
staff has its own group study, now in its second year. The Rev.
Walter Kimbrough, the church's senior minister, participates as a
student.
</P>
<P>
   'Hunger' for study
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very important for us to be intently involved in Bible
study because the people of God shouldn't be biblically
illiterate,'' said Kimbrough.
</P>
<P>
   Both EFM and Disciple have spread beyond their own
denominations. At least 14 different denominations, from Adventists
to United Church of Christ, have congregations sponsoring Disciple
study groups, said Madge Yoke, the Nashville-based office
coordinator for the program. Presbyterians, Catholics and Lutherans
are enrolled in EFM groups alongside Episcopalians in metro area
churches.
</P>
<P>
   The reception has surprised the studies' founders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I must say we were really caught off guard by the overwhelming
willingness of people to commit,'' said United Methodist Bishop
Richard Wilke, author with his wife, Julie, of workbooks for the
Disciple Bible study, the largest of the programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our dream was very small,'' Wilke said. ``Our dream was in
nine months to read most of the Bible and to try to get a few
thousand people to do that. That was the extent of our dream.''
</P>
<P>
   More than half a million people have completed at least a year
of the study since its inception in 1986. People who finished the
first book demanded more. Two subsequent studies are now available,
with another on the way.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Winters, the now-retired University of the South
professor who wrote the EFM material, was asked by the theology
school's computer department what the maximum enrollment would be.
``I took a wild guess and said 1,000,'' he said. Twenty-three years
later, more than 40,000 people have participated, 13,000 have
finished the full four-year program, and more than 7,000 are
currently enrolled.
</P>
<P>
   Both Wilke and Winters said they had sensed a ``hunger'' for
study among the laity of their denominations but failed to see how
deep and wide it reached.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm convinced the main ministry of the church is the ministry
of the laity to the world,'' said Winters, who now lives in
Asheville, N.C. ``To have lay people do their ministry, I thought
they needed to be educated and trained. We train people to be
ministers with a great deal of Scripture and theology to prepare
them to make ethical decisions. But it seems to me the lay people
have to make more difficult ethical decisions than clergy face.''
</P>
<P>
   Education of the laity makes for stronger leadership in the
churches, said Wilke, bishop-in-residence at Southwestern College
in Winfield, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had people hesitant to teach adult Sunday school or work
with the youth or even teach the children because they felt they
were not adequately prepared,'' he said. ``Our enemy was ignorance
of the Scripture, and so our goal was to ground people in the
Scripture.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilke and Winters also said their programs are intended to give
people a new way of looking at their life and the culture in which
they live. The Disciple program, as Wilke puts it, should result in
``not merely information, but transformation.''
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Kemph, a member of Mount Bethel United Methodist Church in
Marietta, has taken Disciple 1, 2 and 3 and repeated 1 ``as a
refresher'' at North Springs United Methodist Church in north
Fulton County.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was an adult Sunday school teacher and as a kid and a teen
had been really active,'' she said. ``I went to church a lot, but I
had never spent a lot of time studying on my own. I enjoyed the
challenge of making sure I could do my reading every week, and the
discussions that come out of the reading are invaluable.''
</P>
<P>
   Her study has given her more confidence in her own beliefs, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It made me challenge authority, or people who really believe
they're authorities and don't like to be questioned,'' she said.
``A lot of times, people are just regurgitating what people told
them..''
</P>
<P>
   Now, she said, ``in Sunday school classes or even if I hear
something on the radio or on television, when people are trying to
manipulate the Scripture, grab something out and try to make it say
what they want it to say, I immediately go to my own Bible and see
what's before it and what's after it. That's not something I would
have done before.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides the Disciple studies, Kemph has taken two years of
supplemental work under the Rev. Bob Winstead of North Springs
United Methodist. Winstead compiled a church history study, based
on the Disciple format, when he found people still wanting more
after exhausting the Disciple material.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most churchgoing folk don't have a sense of the biblical
timeline,'' said Winstead. ``What I'm trying to do is help them lay
it all out on the table and try to make some sense of it.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he encourages each class to ask three questions about
every text they study: ``What? So what? and Now what?''_ or What
does it say? What does it mean? And, how does it apply today?
</P>
<P>
   Winstead's average Sunday congregation is 150 to 300 people.
Since the church has more than 150 people who have had at least a
year of Disciple training, that means half the regular churchgoers
have been exposed to the study, he said. ``In a biblically informed
congregation, I can use images and stories and references much
freer, making connections and expecting the congregation to follow
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Communal experience
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the study itself, many long-term study participants say
they are profoundly changed by the communal experience of
small-group Bible study.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting story after story about someone getting cancer,
maybe a mother dies, a baby is born, life moves on, and here are
people studying together,'' said Wilke. ``It becomes a biblical
fellowship. These people become very close. We were surprised by
the power of the bonding. We shouldn't have been. (Jesus) says when
two or three of you are gathered, I will be there.''
</P>
<P>
   Russell Killebrew, 45, a member of St. Matthew's in Snellville,
was involved in EFM when his wife died of breast cancer in May.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dynamics of being part of a small group, the mutual
support has been tremendous,'' he said. ``Having this group of
folks to get with every week has been a big help.''
</P>
<P>
   Killebrew's classmates include computer programmer Wally Watson,
54, and Centers for Disease Control and Prevention scientist Rob
Merritt, 34.
</P>
<P>
   Watson said she and her husband, Bob, 53, a sales
representative, decided to take the class together.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I've sort of struggled with a lot of people I know
taking the Bible very literally,'' she said. ``I never have. And
I've struggled with some guilt _ was I strange or unusual for not
having a literal interpretation?''
</P>
<P>
   Learning how and when the Bible was written, ``it's making sense
to me,'' she said. ``My faith is being reinforced.''
</P>
<P>
   Merritt said he entered the program ``to discover what my
ministry is in the church community and the community at large.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoy people with different perspectives,'' he said. ``We
get a diversity of ideas and experiences that contribute to the
discussion. It's quite different than just reading something for
yourself, but it's not spoon-fed.''
</P>
<P>
   On a recent Sunday night, with books, Bibles and pens spread out
around them, they and their classmates reviewed the stories of
Samuel and Saul from the Old Testament with the Rev. Jim Johnson,
St. Matthew's rector, then went on to discuss the technique of
``theological reflection,'' a major component of EFM. They will
practice looking at major and minor events of their lives through
the Scripture, the tradition of the church and their own beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole point is to help you see how your life intersects
with God,'' Johnson said. ``This is education for ministry. This is
getting y'all ready to go out there and do something. It's where
the rubber hits the road in this class.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
