<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-VOLUNTEER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    6 ways to give
 &HT;    By Derrick Henry
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although Thanksgiving is nearly a month away, it's already that
time of year to start thinking about helping others.
</P>
<P>
   Who among us doesn't find satisfaction in feeding the homeless
and hungry a lavish Thanksgiving meal or providing Christmas
presents for a needy child?
</P>
<P>
   Many people, focused on family and career, find this time of
year a perfect time to reach out to others in need.
</P>
<P>
   For Connie Sabo of north Fulton County, the holidays would not
be complete without involving the entire family in Operation
Christmas Child, a project that provides gifts to needy children
throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's never too early to teach your kids about compassion,''
says Sabo, who has been involved with the project for five years
with her husband, Frank, and daughters Chelsea, 13, and Taylor, 9.
</P>
<P>
   ``We love the theme of kids helping kids. One of the things we
are trying to do as a family is to get away from the old traditions
of getting to traditions of giving. We want to emphasize values.''
</P>
<P>
   For some organizations, the volunteer onrush during the holidays
can be overwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   ``We use about 25,000 volunteers a year, and more than half of
those come between October and December,'' says Kathleen Kelly,
volunteer program co-manager for the Atlanta Community Food Bank.
</P>
<P>
   While Thanksgiving or Christmas may seem a long way off,
volunteer opportunities with many popular organizations are already
filled or nearing capacity. For example, the Atlanta Union Mission
already has enough volunteers to handle its Thanksgiving Day
programs.
</P>
<P>
   The message is clear: If it's something you really want to do,
register now before it's too late.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at nonprofit organizations also point out that
problems like hunger and homelessness don't disappear after one big
party or meal. They suggest volunteers pledge their services for
other times of the year as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``People aren't just hungry at Christmas,'' says Mack Barnes of
the Feed the Hungry Foundation in Marietta.
</P>
<P>
   And sometimes it's helpful to think small. While the projects
detailed below need large numbers of volunteers, many small
agencies often have difficulty finding people willing to help.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
