u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WHOLELIFE-EXPO-COX     10-30 0574
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHOLELIFE-EXPO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Spiritual journey tied to service
 &HT;    By Derrick Henry
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Helping others is as important as helping ourselves. That's one
of the messages that will be delivered by several of the nationally
known lecturers and authors at this weekend's Whole Life Expo in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``At a certain point, the search for self-awareness can become
self-preoccupation,'' says Marianne Williamson, author of ``The
Healing of America'' and a leading advocate for social conscience
in the spiritual movement. ``Ultimately, a spiritual journey that
does not include service to the outer world disintegrates into
narcissism and self-indulgence.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Millman, in his new book ``Everyday Enlightenment,'' details
12 ``gateways'' to enlightenment, the last of which is Serve Your
World. ``Service is very selfish,'' he says. ``We cannot uplift
someone else without uplifting ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Millman is certain that material success doesn't provide
happiness. ``There must be more to life than having everything,''
he says, quoting noted children's author and illustrator Maurice
Sendak.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, ``if you are working for money, power, prestige,
celebrity or a bigger car, then you are in trouble,'' says Bernie
Siegel.
</P>
<P>
   Siegel, a retired surgeon whose books on humanizing medical care
are full of inspirational stories of how people have dealt with and
overcome life-threatening illnesses, has become a household name in
the self-help field. His new book, ``Prescriptions for Living,''
expands his principles to embrace the physically healthy.
</P>
<P>
   When you are ``giving unconditional love from your heart, you
improve your health,'' Siegel says. ``That's why volunteers live
longer, healthier lives. They are giving a gift to themselves as
well as those around them.''
</P>
<P>
   Siegel thinks it's important to find a cause that you believe in
and a task that gives you satisfaction. ``If you are doing
something where you lose track of time, when your aches and pains
and illnesses and worries disappear,'' Siegel says, ``then you know
you are on the right track.''
</P>
<P>
   And Millman thinks a little bit of service is ``better than a
lot of nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Start where you are,'' he says. ``Say a few kind words to
someone at the supermarket or pay the toll for the car behind
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Helping others is of such critical importance to , will have its
first major conference Nov. 20-22 in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Williamson's hope is to create ``a new politics, a positive
politics, centered around people helping people.''
</P>
<P>
   Self-help lecturers make service 'a way of life'
</P>
<P>
   DAN MILLMAN Born:Resides:Accomplishments: in 1964, representing
the U.S. Gymnastics Federation. Coached the Stanford University
gymnastics team 1968-72. A movie is in development based on his
best-seller ``Way of the Peaceful Warrior'' (H.J. Kramer, $12,
1980), a semi-autobiographical book that focuses on a meeting with
an old man at a gas station.
</P>
<P>
   Latest book:Excerpt:Web site:Whole Life Expo Topic:.
