<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-30 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6422 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELECTION-$ADV01-COX     10-30 1502
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELECTION-$ADV01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WITH 'CLINTON FACTOR' AN UNKNOWN, PARTIES LAUNCH A FINAL DRIVE
 &HT;    720&AMP;adds. For release Sunday, Nov. 1.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The heart of an election is mostly invisible,
millions of people making millions of decisions for untold _ and
unpolled _ reasons. Tuesday's voting will be no exception.
</P>
<P>
   But the mood of the American electorate, unusually puzzling in
this fall of peace, prosperity, space heroism and scandal, has both
political parties retreating to what they know best: demonizing
each other and their leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes are high: all 435 seats in the House of
Representatives, 34 seats in the U.S. Senate, 36 governorships, and
more than 6,000 seats in state legislatures.
</P>
<P>
   The election is local, with results in many races, hinging on a
highway, a waste site or a school bond. But it is also national,
portending the future of Social Security, health care, the
environment, education _ and, perhaps, the outcome of the
impeachment inquiry against President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the voting's importance, expectations are that only
about 36 percent of the electorate will participate. But with the
impeachment investigation ``hovering over this election like a
five-ton elephant,'' in the words of Curtis Gans, a leading scholar
of voting behavior, experts are shying away from hard predictions.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the uncertainty, both parties and their interest
group allies are waging mammoth television advertising campaigns
designed to rally their most faithful supporters.
</P>
<P>
   They are airing unprecedented numbers of generic ``issue'' ads
that are not regulated by federal election law. The number of
negative ads is up as well, with 6 out of every 10 TV ads attacking
the sponsor's opponent in one 30-state study by media expert
Kathleen Hall Jamieson.
</P>
<P>
   For voters immune to the ads, the parties and interest groups
are waging ambitious get-out-the-vote drives by mail and telephone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both parties are running scared,'' said William Schneider, a
political analyst for the Cable News Network (CNN) and the American
Enterprise Institute, a business-oriented research center in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Only weeks ago, as the Monica Lewinsky sex scandal engulfed the
president, it appeared the Republicans would add dozens of seats to
their 21-seat majority in the House, win the five seats necessary
to have a filibuster-proof Senate majority of 60, and expand their
majority of 33 governorships.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the effects of Clinton's self-made problems, the
Republicans had history on their side. The average number of House
seats gained by the party in its sixth year of controlling the
White House is 43, and the average number of Senate seats gained is
eight.
</P>
<P>
   But the GOP failed to recognize that the American people
rendered their judgment on Clinton long before the midterm election
heated up. Since the Lewinsky scandal broke last winter, more than
six out of 10 Americans have approved of the job Clinton is doing
as president. Throughout this fall, a solid majority has opposed
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   And before Congress adjourned in October for electioneering, the
GOP leadership caved in to Clinton on social spending and added
pork-barrel giveaways to the budget, angering some conservatives
enough to threaten war on their own party once the election is
over.
</P>
<P>
   Then Clinton, already having claimed credit for the first budget
surplus in 29 years, brokered a Middle East peace agreement,
producing statesmanlike images that were broadcast worldwide for
days. And within a week he was in Florida, basking in the televised
nostalgic, can-do glory of Democrat John Glenn's historic return to
space.
</P>
<P>
   ``Republicans had a bad month,'' former Bush White House
pollster Robert Teeter noted in the release of this week's Wall
Street Journal/NBC News poll, which indicated that Democratic
congressional candidates have rebounded and are even with
Republicans in the final stretch of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Now, any Republican dreams of a mandate-sized gain in the House
and a filibuster-proof Senate have all but vanished. The best guess
among experts is that the GOP will gain 10 or fewer House seats and
two or three Senate seats.
</P>
<P>
   Anything less than the historic gains by the party out of the
White House will be ``a tremendous victory'' for Democrats, claims
Gov. Roy Romer of Colorado, the general chairman of the Democratic
National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The GOP, which currently holds 33 governorships, is close to
equaling its previous record of 34 governorships, in 1921-22, with
the most important addition likely to be Jeb Bush in Florida. With
his brother, George W., cruising to re-election in Texas, the GOP
would control the two pillars of a White House strategy for 2000: a
combined total of 57 electoral votes, more than a fifth of those
needed to win the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   But the GOP is likely to suffer a tremendous loss in California,
where Democratic Lt. Gov. Gray Davis is poised to end 16 years of
Republican control of the governor's office and GOP hopes of
controlling the redistricting of the state's congressional
districts, now totaling 52.
</P>
<P>
   To ensure even modest gains in Congress, the GOP has launched a
$10 million TV campaign in the final days of the election to keep
their core supporters outraged over Clinton's misconduct with
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   It's a risky strategy. Democrats have responded with a $1
million campaign portraying Republicans as ``obsessed'' with
Clinton's sexual conduct. The ads feature their favorite campaign
whipping boy, House Speaker Newt Gingrich of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen an increase in the intensity of Democrats,'' said
Ed Goeas, a Republican pollster who is involved in nearly 100 races
around the country. But loyal Republicans, especially religious
conservatives, have energized for months, he added, and
``Republicans in Congress as a check on Bill Clinton is a good
message.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is not on the ballot anywhere, of course. And the
last-minute GOP ad campaign is not an attempt to nationalize the
election about him, the way the GOP did in 1994. The ads are airing
in only a handful of House districts with close races.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic Party's strength is not in the ``air war,''
however, where the GOP is outspending it by $20 million in the
final two weeks alone. Democrats are depending on organized labor
to wage a $14 million ``ground war'' of mail and telephone banks to
get out the vote in 40 House races, 10 Senate contests and 12
gubernatorial elections.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats also expect to gain from get-out-the-vote pushes with
African Americans, the party's most loyal constituency. The
president and First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton planned final
weekend events to rally black voters in Illinois, where Democratic
Sen. Carol Moseley-Braun is trailing badly, and in Maryland, where
Democratic Gov. Paris Glendening has a razor-thin lead.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   However, there is only ``a modest interest'' in the election
among African Americans, said David Bositis, the chief researcher
at the Joint Center for Political and Economic Studies, a public
policy organization specializing in issues of importance to blacks.
</P>
<P>
   Both parties have targeted Hispanics, an increasingly important
voting bloc. Democrats are pursing Latinos in California, trying to
capitalize on the lingering anger over anti-immigrant initiatives
championed by outgoing Republican Gov. Pete Wilson. But they have
ceded the Latino vote in Texas and Florida to the Bush brothers.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP also is banking on voters reached by the 45 million
voter guides the Christian Coalition planned to distribute in
churches throughout the country this Sunday, the organization's
most ambitious election-year effort ever. The guides compare the
voting records of candidates on issues central to the beliefs of
conservative Christians: abortion, homosexuality and vouchers for
religious schools.
</P>
<P>
   But two favorites of the Christian Coalition are in political
trouble: Gov. Fob James of Alabama and Gov. David Beasley of South
Carolina face serious challenges from Democrats in the South, a
region that otherwise seems on the verge of a complete political
realignment to the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   For all the efforts of both parties, though, a survey last week
for Project Vote Smart, a nonprofit organization that maintains
databases on political candidates, found that 31 percent of
American voters do not trust any level of government to make the
best decisions for the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is, unfortunately, a sad reflection on the nature of how
candidates campaign for office,'' said Richard Kimball, the
organization's president. ``After months of negative and often
useless campaigns, voters can't help but feel their elected
officials are not to be trusted.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
