<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PEROT PETITION DRIVE SETS SIGHTS ON DEC. 7 DELIVERY
 &HT;    EDS: UNBUDGETED
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The resurfacing of the Monica Lewinsky affair as a
campaign issue just before Tuesday's elections may have energized a
drive launched by Texas businessman Ross Perot to collect petitions
seeking President Clinton's resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Backers of the petition drive were regrouping this weekend, as
CNN's Larry King Live was rebroadcasting Saturday an appearance by
Perot from late September when he termed Clinton too ``erratic'' to
hold office and called for the petition drive.
</P>
<P>
   The effort, loosely coordinated through Perot's Dallas-based
Reform Party, has more than 140,000 people circulating petitions,
said the party's executive director Russell Verney. He said he had
no estimate of the number of signatures collected.
</P>
<P>
   Planners backed away from Perot's proposal to have petition
gatherers at the polls on Election Day, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be more organized after the election,'' said Anne
Merkl, a Newnan, Ga. Reform Party activist. ``You'll see us after
the election in parking lots and Wal-Marts.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida organizer Pauline Klein, of Key Largo, said that she has
just begun contacting hundreds of volunteers. ``I'm swamped,'' she
said of the stack of mail from the state. However, she also said
the focus will be after the election.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers said they are aiming for a truck caravan that will
bring the petitions to Washington on Dec. 7.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
