   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-MIDDLECLASS _ MOSCOW _ Alexander and Lilia Kazintseva
were young and upperwardly mobile Russians enjoying all that the
post-Soviet economy had to offer: new furnishings for their
apartment and country house, vacations abroad and a private tutor
to teach English to their nine-year-old son, Anton. Now, the good
times have vanished. He lost his job as a corporate marketing
director. She believes her layoff as an executive headhunter is
just a matter of time. The brighter future is on hold. Russia's
economic crisis is squeezing out the middle class. While small, the
middle class was the great hope for the staying power of democracy
and reforms _ how you gonna send them back to the Soviet days after
they've seen cable TV and Disney World? (Holmes, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   With photos to be placed in the International folder on the Cox
Server.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving Thursday, Oct. 29.
</P>
<P>
   NIGERIA-WOLE _ Abdulsalami Abubakar, who met with Nelson Mandela
on Friday, has revived hopes for a return to democracy in Nigeria.
But to compare the general who has pledged an end to despotism with
the anti-apartheid leader who has become emblematic for democracy
in Africa is a gigantic stretch. Nigeria is still far from a South
African-style success story, Wole Soyinka said Friday. The
Nobel-winning writer, who teaches at Emory University in Atlanta,
suggested another event from the recent news as a more apt symbol
for Nigeria today: The gasoline-fed pipeline inferno in the village
of Jesse last week that killed an estimated 700 people. (Graham,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
