   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT _ WASHINGTON _ Advance testimony of an Apple executive
who will be the next witness in the federal antitrust suit against
Microsoft Corp. is released Friday afternoon. (Glass, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-COVERAGE _ How the tech media is covering the
Microsoft trial. (Katz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   MALARIA _ WASHINGTON _ Combining simple tools like
pesticide-soaked mosquito nets with satellite imaging, four
international agencies _ the United Nations Development Program,
the UN Children's Fund, the World Bank and the World Health
Organization _ Friday launch a new campaign against malaria, a
disease that sickens up to 500 million people a year and kills
3,000 children a day in Africa alone. (Nesmith, Cox News Service
500).
</P>
<P>
   TECH-AUSTERITY _ WASHINGTON _ Last spring, when Internet
entrepreneurs Ross Garber and Greg Peters were planning to take
Vignette Corp. public, they had visions of raising an amazing $30
million overnight. Their Austin, Texas, company, they hoped, would
join the ranks of such Internet blockbusters as Yahoo! and
Amazon.com. But before the team could even plan a road show to
advertise its initial public offering (IPO) of stock, their Morgan
Stanley bankers brought sobering news: In only 45 days, comparable
Internet companies had lost as much as 50 percent of their
valuations. Institutional investors were balking at new offerings.
In short, the IPO window was slamming shut. The Vignette team has
joined the legions of executives across the country postponing or
shelving plans to sell stock to the public. (Regan, Cox News
Service 1000).
</P>
<P>
   w/COX-TECH-AUSTERITY-DATA.
</P>
<P>
   Eds: MOVED Thursday in (w) Washington and (f) financial
categories and repeated Friday.
</P>
<P>
   SPACE-PRIVATIZE _ WASHINGTON _ As Americans relive the past
glories of a space race through the return to orbit of astronaut
legend John Glenn, a different sort of race for space is quietly
heating up. This time the competition is not between international
superpowers, but among a handful of scrappy startup U.S. companies
who are vying to build space planes and rockets that would fly so
cheaply that costly government vehicles would be left in the dust.
Even as NASA continues to rely on its huge and complex shuttle
system, costing $400 million to $600 million per flight, these lean
and mean space entrepreneurs are developing small, reusable
vehicles that could haul satellites and other cargo into orbit at
bargain-basement rates. (Malone, Cox News Service 880&AMP;add).
</P>
<P>
   Eds: MOVED Thursday and repeated Friday.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   LATINO-VOTERS _ WASHINGTON _ Republican strategists are watching
the gubernatorial campaigns of the Bush brothers in Texas and
Florida for clues on how to woo Hispanic voters in the next
presidential campaign. And some Democrats are worried. (Shepard,
Cox News Service 650&AMP;add).
</P>
<P>
   LATINO-VOTERS-DATA _ Graphics material on Hispanic population
and voting.
</P>
<P>
   Eds: MOVED Wednesday and repeated Friday.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTHERN-CONGRESSIONAL _ McCOMB, Miss. _ In neighboring
congressional districts in Mississippi and Louisiana, Democrats
hope to reverse the Southern Republican tide. (Sherman, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   GOP-ADS-GEORGIA _ A late-rounds gut punch of Republican Party
television attack ads seems to have most parties reeling in the
political ring of Georgia's Second Congressional District. In
Georgia, the ad campaign is intended to help the Republican
first-time candidate for Congress, Albany businessman Joe
McCormick, unseat three-term incumbent Democrat Sanford Bishop.
This district is one of about two dozen congressional races
targeted around the country in the $10 million effort. But it's
hard to tell who's getting hurt the most. McCormick sought to
distance himself from the ads last week. (Osinski, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   INITIATIVES _ When voters nationwide go to the polls Tuesday,
they'll be doing more than electing candidates. They'll also be
voting on ballot initiatives that range from marijuana for
medicinal purposes to term limits to campaign finance reform.
Voters in Michigan, home state to Dr. Jack Kevorkian, will
determine whether that state adopts physician-assisted suicide. In
all, 235 ballot initiatives _ including 10 in Georgia _ will be
decided Tuesday. (ABrice, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   GA-GOVPOLL _ ATLANTA _ Second Journal-Constitution political
poll. Concentrates on governor horse race where Republican Guy
Millner leads Democrat Roy Barnes 45-41, virtually the same lead he
held three weeks ago. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   GA-GOV-MONEY _ ATLANTA _ Roy Barnes has raised more money ($9
million) from more contributors (9,000) than any politician in
Georgia history, much of it from lawyers and doctors. Guy Millner,
who's used $11.5 million of his own money, raised about $3.5
million from about 4,400 people, many of them business executives.
Story will evaluate key sources of both candidates, and interview
contributors. (Mantius, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   GA-ATTYGENL _ ATLANTA _ Nineteen of the state's 41 DAs depart
from their normal policy of not publicly backing a state attorney
general candidate and endorse Thurbert Baker. They say he was there
when they needed him. Baker is decrying a TV ad by GOP challenger
David Ralston, saying it misrepresents what his office did in a
North Georgia death penalty case. (Rankin, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   TEX-HOUSE-RACE _ AUSTIN, Texas _ The Republican Party's push to
capture the Texas House has become an all-out battle of big money.
Texas-sized bucks, in fact, from both sides. Instead of the
$125,000 or so it has taken to mount a House campaign in the past,
double and even triple that amount is being spent in some races
this year _ all for a job that pays just $7,200 a year plus
fringes. One Republican challenger likely will spend more than
$400,000. ``In my 18 years in this business, I've never seen this
much money being spent on state House races,'' said Brian Eppstein,
a Fort Worth political consultant. (Ward, Austin
American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   TEX-GOV-RACE _ Gov. George W. Bush, campaigning Friday in North
Texas, said he hopes the Republicans can take over the House but
refused to talk about what should happen to Democratic House
Speaker if they do. We ask Democrat Garry Mauro, campaigning in
Dallas-Fort Worth, what he thinks of the GOP prospects. (Herman,
Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   TEX-LTGOV-RACE _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Most of the campaign between
Democrat John Sharp and Republican Rick Perry has demonstrated how
alike they are on many issues. But the two differ on some key
issues that the lieutenant governor could hold sway on next
session: abortion, tax cuts, educational vouchers and annexation
are among them. (Elizondo, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   OHIO-GOV-MONEY _ Bob Taft and Lee Fisher have spent nearly $10
million on their hotly disputed ads since June, according to the
latest campaign finance reports, with Fisher slightly outspending
Taft. (Gulliver, Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   OHIO-GOV-DEBATE _ CLEVELAND _ The final governor's race debate.
Audience asked questions and brought out issues they hadn't
addressed before; plus feisty exchanges afterwards between Fisher
family and Taft officials. (Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   NORLEANS-GUNSUIT _ NEW ORLEANS _ The mayor of New Orleans is
suing gun manufacturers to put safety devices on guns, and suing
them and some pawn shops for contributing to this city's crime
problem. He is doing this in conjunction with the Center to Prevent
Hangun Violence and he is the first mayor in the country to do
this. Apparently the prospect of such litigation was all the talk
at the last national mayor's conference, but New Orleans is first
out of the chute with an actual lawsuit. (Konigsmark, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   COMMUNITY-POLICING _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Former L. A. police chief
speaks at a a national conference on community policing and
recruitment of minority officers. (Banta, Austin
American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   OHIO-BATS _ Tonight is Halloween for the rest of us, but at a
former limestone quarry in Darke County furry black animals wrap
their wings around and hang upside-down everynight. You see, this
is a true bat cave, home to 25,000 bats, the largest colony in Ohio
and Pennsylvania, according to biologist Jackie Belwood, who runs
the bat program from the Cincinnati Nature Center. It is also home
to about 9,300 Indiana bats, which have been on the endangered
species list since 1967. This time of year the bats share the cave
with various ghosts and ghouls, when the Lewisburg Boy Scouts put
on a Haunted Cave. It is also here where they will hibernate for
the winter. (Dempsey, Dayton Daily News) WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   HALLOWEEN _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Without question, Halloween is a
yearly celebration of candy and Power Ranger costumes. In fact this
year, retailers are expected to set a new record selling $1.76
billion worth of candy. Rooted in a yearly ritual that included
masquerading as the dead to hide from evil spirits, Halloween has
changed a lot over the years from the yearly Sam Hain celebration.
A University of Dayton professor who teaches courses about
literature and the occult notes that ``Halloween has turned into
such a mild event. It's been turned into a collection of treats. It
has lost all sense of evil.'' (Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   SIERRA _ AUSTIN _ In Sierra Blanca, an ongoing fued between
Hudspeth County Judge James Peace and County Attorney Tom Chellis
has shut down all misdemeanor prosecutions in the county _ for a
year. Chellis, angry that Peace and county commissioners have
steadily cut his budget, stopped accepting new cases a year ago,
which means drunk drivers, assault suspects and others arrested on
class A and B misdemeanors get their cases quickly dismissed. Not
that it matters, because Peace, who presides over all misdemeanor
cases, stopped holding court a year ago, about the time that
Chellis filed criminal charges against him for official oppression,
which is another story altogether. A tale of border un-justice.
(Harmon, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   NURSING _ AUSTIN _ It's been a year since the board that
disciplines nursing home administrators passed new rules to crack
down on the industry. The board had sanctioned only one
administrator in four years, despite glaring inadequacies
documented at many homes. Over the past year, the board has
disciplined 50 administrators, including one who's been fired.
(Gamino, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   AIRPORT _ On a cool, overcast morning in southeast Travis
County, construction crews attach the first passenger loading
bridge to Gate 4 at Austin-Bergstrom International Airport. For the
toiling crews, it's just another step in a job that has spanned
four years already. But in a sometimes cynical city where ideas are
born, then changed, debated (and debated), shelved and maybe even
born again, that loading bridge, which will carry passengers to and
from waiting planes, is also proof positive of something many
Austin residents have doubted for years: we're getting a new
airport. In just six months passenger planes will _ barring natural
disaster or unexpected construction delays _ fly out of
Austin-Bergstrom International Airport. (Hiott, Austin
American-Satesman)
</P>
<P>
   w/TERMINAL GRAPHIC _ A large 3-D cutaway of the new airport
terminal that will show folks where everything from the restrooms
to the Salt Lick to the commuter gate can be found. (Calzada,
Austin American-Satesman)
</P>
<P>
   w/AIR BUDGET GRAPHIC _ Standing graphic showing how much it
costs, what the budget progress is, etc. (Hiott, Austin
American-Satesman)
</P>
<P>
   w/TIMELINE _ Standing graphic showing the timeline for
construction projects at the airport. (Hiott, Austin
American-Satesman)
</P>
<P>
   BOUNTY-HUNTERS _ ATLANTA _ Police file criminal charges against
two bounty hunters who broke down the door of the wrong house
earlier this week, terrifying the 14-year-old girl who was home
alone. Bonding companies claim bounty hunters have broad powers to
track down fugitives, and since they thought they were at the right
house, there was no criminal intent, these guys should not be
charged. Talking to legal experts, the district attorney etc. over
the legal questions here. (MacDonald, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BOUNTY-GEORGIA _ Bounty hunters like to say the courts have
given them virtually unlimited powers to bring in the bad guys, but
some legal experts disagree. The Georgia attorney generals office,
for example, says they have no more rights than anyone else to make
a citizens arrest. These guys are in fact just citizens _ they
aren't licensed in Georgia. Anyone can be one. (Torpy, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   TRIPLE-MURDER _ ATLANTA _ Latest developments in triple homicide
in the Atlanta Hilton &AMP; Towers. (Longa, Bixler, Martz, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   SUGAR _ CLEWISTON, Fla. _ Opening of new U.S. Sugar refinery;
it's the first new refinery to open in the United States in 25
years. (Waresh, Palm Beach Post). 10. WITH PHOTO. MOVED
</P>
