<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    APPLE EXECUTIVE CITES MICROSOFT THREATS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Microsoft forced Apple Computer to dump Netscape's
Web browser for its own product by threatening to drop support for
an Apple version of Microsoft's popular word processing program,
according to testimony of a senior Apple executive released Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In 46 pages of written testimony released in the ongoing federal
antitrust trial, Senior Apple Vice President Avadis Tevanian Jr.
also recounted how Microsoft had allegedly blocked Apple's
development of software to play sound and video because it would
compete with Microsoft's own multimedia offerings.
</P>
<P>
   Tevanian is due to take the witness stand Monday and to be
cross-examined by Microsoft defense lawyer John Warden for much of
the week.
</P>
<P>
   Warden is expected to portray his client as having come to
Apple's rescue in August 1997 through a deal under which the
software giant made a critical $150 million investment in Apple,
which pioneered the graphical approach to personal computing that
has become the hallmark of Microsoft's Windows operating system.
</P>
<P>
   Under that deal, Microsoft and Apple also agreed to
cross-license their patents and to settle their outstanding patent
disputes over that so-called ``interface.''
</P>
<P>
   Industry studies currently give Apple's about 5 percent of the
overall market for operating systems that run on personal
computers. Microsoft Windows accounts for more than 90 percent of
these programs, which control such applications as word processors
and spreadsheets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pressures exerted by Microsoft compelled Apple to resolve
(their) disputes on terms that gave significant advantages to
Microsoft's operating system,'' Tevanian wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Under the bargain, Apple agreed to bundle Internet Explorer on
all of its Macintosh computers and its operating systems for the
next five years. While Apple is free to also bundle Netscape's
competing browser, it is barred from promoting any browser other
than Microsoft's.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after Tevanian joined the then beleaguered company last
year, he met with an unnamed software developer who was working on
a product that would complement Apple's multimedia reader, known as
Quicktime, which also runs on Windows.
</P>
<P>
   The developer urged Apple to quit producing any products for
Windows. Otherwise, he told him, ``Microsoft would take any
necessary action to drive Apple out of that business.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time, I found his comments to be odd,'' Tevanian wrote.
``Eighteen months later, after the events described (in my direct
testimony), I appreciate the prophetic import of his words.''
</P>
<P>
   In response to the testimony, Microsoft said it ``competes with
Apple to make Windows the innovative platform of choice, but we
also cooperate in many ways to ensure that our respective tools and
