   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Saturday, Oct. 31. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The N.Y. Times News Service
Night Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Undated) _ The United States gross domestic product
rose 3.3 percent in the July-September quarter, considerably higher
than economists had predicted, as healthy consumer spending offset
a continued decline in exports and a lapse in business investment.
President Clinton says the economy is the strongest in a
generation. By Sylvia Nasar. With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   G-7-BAILOUT (Washington) _ President Clinton and the other major
industrialized nations announce a series of steps to stem 16 months
of mounting financial turmoil around the world, giving new powers
to the International Monetary Fund to aid fundamentally healthy
countries threatened by global upheavals. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-CALIF (Los Angeles) _ Moderation is the watchword in
the Golden State this year, and Lt. Gov. Gray Davis, a 23-year
veteran of state government widely mocked as the dullest politician
in the state Democratic Party, appears on the verge of a major
victory in the campaign for governor. By Todd S. Purdum. (with
photo)
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-WIVES (Washington) _ Candidates' spouses used to appear
in campaign ads sitting silently alongside their neatly dressed
children. This year, the wives of many candidates _ Democratic
candidates in particular _ are out in front, with greater
prominence and a new purpose. By Melinda Henneberger.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS-HACKERS (Undated) _ The rapid growth of the Internet
has transformed what was once a hacker playground into among other
things, a far-reaching political platform. Radical groups are
discovering what hackers have always known: Traditional social
institutions are more vulnerable in cyberspace than they are in the
physical world. In recent months, groups as diverse as the Animal
Liberation Front, Radio4All and international teams of teen-agers
with cyber pseudonyms like Milworm and causes like anti-imperialism
have increasingly begun pumping political protest through the
Internet's security holes. By Amy Harmon. 2,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   PINOCHET-SPAIN (Madrid, Spain) _ The Spanish High Court rules
that Spanish courts do have the jurisdiction to try former Chilean
President Gen. Augusto Pinochet for crimes against humanity,
seemingly opening the door to a raft of other prosecutions of
former Chilean and Argentine strongmen. By Marlise Simons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
