</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-COVERAGE31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Internet reporter takes Microsoft, U.S. to task
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Michael Lewis has a front row seat at the Microsoft
trial. He's filing regular dispatches for Slate
(http://www.slate.com), the subscription-only ($19.95 per year),
Microsoft-owned online magazine. While some might accuse him of
being a shameless Microsoft shill, it is nice to see someone from
the Microsoft side of the trial write about it in a colorful and
interesting way.
</P>
<P>
   He also appears to be the only online journalist writing about
the trial in some detail on a fairly regular basis.
</P>
<P>
   It's important to note Lewis isn't reporting _ he is painting an
impressionist portrait of the courtroom, the witness, the lawyers
and even the relative comfort of the chairs and benches in the
courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, author of ``Liar's Poker'' and ``Trial Fever,'' is
mindful the man signing his checks is also the defendant in the
case he is covering. But his colorful articles are not straight
journalism, they focus on personal impressions and general
observations.
</P>
<P>
   This type of writing gives Slate _ which has vowed to remain
neutral in all things Microsoft _ just the wiggle room it needs
with a story like this.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis' ``dispatches,'' posted to the site in the form of e-mail
messages, tries to give readers a ``you are there'' feeling.
Descriptions such as this from Day One are typical:
</P>
<P>
   ``I can understand why the wheels of justice must grind slowly.
But must they also grind unpleasantly? The district court in
Washington, D.C., has the charm and efficiency of a Soviet customs
office.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis takes Microsoft and the government to task sometimes on a
very personal level. He fires potshots at the Justice Department
lawyers prosecuting the software giant including David Boies, who
Lewis notes was wearing his signature cheap suit on opening day.
</P>
<P>
   However dissing the prosecutor's wardrobe choices and his New
Jersey homeboy accent (Lewis devotes as much time to how people
says things as he does to what they actually say) is just one of
Lewis' tactics.
</P>
<P>
   Of Microsoft lawyer Warden, Lewis describes him in his
cross-examination of Netscape CEO Jim Barksdale as a man ``intent
on booming out as many insults as possible in the rudest possible
tones ... if Warden were naturally so repellent he could hardly get
through life; he'd spend his days being tossed out of taxicabs and
restaurants.''
</P>
<P>
   Is this an indictment of Warden as a belligerent trial lawyer or
a portrait of a shrewd legal mind, staging a calculating
cross-examination. It's hard to tell. And maybe Slate and Microsoft
like it that way.
</P>
<P>
   But so far, Lewis' best nugget of courtroom drama comes in his
description of Gates, in his taped testimony ``looking as if he had
swallowed a bad oyster,'' Lewis writes, ``denying much of what he
had written.''
</P>
<P>
   He's also unimpressed with the Microsoft legal team and
concludes the Microsoft defense so far ``is not much more than a
gloriously indiscriminate, flailing attack on Netscape.''
</P>
<P>
   When the trial ends, this will surely make a great book. Lewis
understands the trial for what it is: a tangle of legal and
economic deeds and misdeeds that nobody, not even those involved,
can quite make sense of.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end,'' Lewis says, ``I'd like to think that after the
facts are out, other things being equal, the judge will favor the
lawyer who minimizes the workload.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
