A6453 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NIGERIA-WOLE31-COX     10-30 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIGERIA-WOLE31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Soyinka finds reports of Nigerian democracy unsatisfactory
 &HT;    By Keith Graham
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Nelson Mandela traveled to Nigeria on Friday to spread
the word: Nigeria is on the march toward restoring democracy.
</P>
<P>
   But in Atlanta the most outspoken critic of Nigeria's long and
brutal domination by the military was sounding much less joyous.
</P>
<P>
   Wole Soyinka, who just returned from a visit to his homeland
last week, said the country still remains far from the kind of
success story Mandela has engineered in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Mandela went to Nigeria for the annual summit of the Economic
Community of West African States and added his voice to a chorus of
praise for Gen. Abdulsalami Abubakar. Abubakar's plans to turn over
power to an elected government are a ``courageous step by a man of
true vision,'' Mandela said.
</P>
<P>
   It was a meeting of real symbolic value for the government. But,
citing numerous tensions and unresolved issues, Soyinka pointed to
another event from the recent news as a symbol for Nigeria today:
The gasoline-fed pipeline inferno in the village of Jesse last week
that killed an estimated 700 people.
</P>
<P>
   The 64-year-old author is currently the Robert W. Woodruff
Professor of the Arts at Emory University, and his recent visit
home was his first since Abubakar's government lifted trumped-up
treason charges against him as a gesture to the democratic
opposition.
</P>
<P>
   While there, Soyinka, who is widely regarded as his nation's
most famous exile, made several ``thunderbolt-heaving speeches,''
according to press reports.
</P>
<P>
   Soyinka chuckled at the description: ``Let's say that I went
there specifically _ because of the timing _ to set what I hope
will be a direction of genuine debate toward the new nation, the
new Nigeria.''
</P>
<P>
   But he was clearly not satisfied with what he witnessed.
</P>
<P>
   Since coming to power after strongman Sani Abacha's death from a
heart attack in June, Abubakar has released many political
prisoners and begun a process leading to elections to restore
democracy. As Mandela's visit suggested, reaction to the
government's change of direction has been generally favorable.
</P>
<P>
   Also Friday, the European Union decided to lift most of its
anti-Nigeria sanctions enacted in 1995. The EU said it would begin
easing the sanctions Sunday because of the new government's moves
toward democracy and economic reform.
</P>
<P>
   But Soyinka, best known as a playwright whose works have delved
into such issues as colonialism and the forces that allow
dictatorships to exist, said that during his visit he was depressed
to find many enemies of democracy have yet to come around.
</P>
<P>
   Cobbled together by the British, the ethnically-diverse country
has long suffered because people's differences have been
``shamelessly exploited by a power hungry minority,'' Soyinka said.
</P>
<P>
   In the nation's oil-rich south, several ethnic groups are
fighting each other for control of local government and oil
resources.
</P>
<P>
   Civil war remains a possibility, Soyinka said: ``I think that
threat will become very real if segments of the country refuse to
accept the necessity of restructuring.''
</P>
<P>
   As outlined by Abubakar's government, the path to a restored
democracy begins in earnest in December with local elections. A
series of elections will follow, leading up to a vote for a new
president in February. Abubakar has taken himself out of the
running for that post.
</P>
<P>
   But Soyinka said reform of the military _ which has dominated
Nigerian life for much of its modern history _ has not moved as
quickly as he would like. ``Genuine reform will not take place
until the military goes back to barracks,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He criticized Abubakar for rejecting calls to step aside for ``a
national unity government'' while a new constitution could be
adopted and for failing to acknowledge the need for a truth
commission, much like the one headed by Archbishop-emeritus Desmond
Tutu in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Like South Africa, Nigeria needs a truth panel probing into what
went awry in its history, Soyinka said. Like the South African
commission, the proposed Nigerian panel would hear from both
victims and their torturers. But, unlike fellow Emory professor
Tutu, Soyinka did not stress the idea that such a process leads to
reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that reconciliation is something we must leave to
people themselves,'' Soyinka said. ``We just want to make sure that
memory is kept alive. Justice for me is paramount, but first we
must have memory.''
</P>
<P>
   Though there have been calls for him to seek the presidency,
Soyinka said he has no plans to be a candidate. And, despite his
reservations about the election process, he did not rule out the
possibility that a leader could emerge who could unite the country.
</P>
<P>
   Nigeria ``has the potential to be a viable entity,'' he said,
explaining that the regional and ethnic differences that have been
exploited in the past are really the kind of plurality that makes a
nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's one reason to be optimistic,'' he added. ``And that is
the evidence of the resiliency of the Nigerian people. One thing I
found when I was there: The indomitable spirit of the people has
never been touched.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
