A6457 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INITIATIVES31-COX     10-30 1087
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INITIATIVES31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Voters to decide wide-ranging intitiatives; pot use most debated
 &HT;    By Arthur Brice
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When voters go to the polls nationwide on Tuesday,
they'll do more than elect candidates. In 44 states, including
Georgia, voters also will decide 235 ballot initiatives on such
wide-ranging issues as medicinal marijuana, campaign finance and
animal rights.
</P>
<P>
   Voters in Michigan, home state to suicide advocate Dr. Jack
Kevorkian, will determine whether that state becomes the second in
the nation to allow doctor-assisted suicide. And voters in Alaska
and Hawaii will have a say on same-sex marriages.
</P>
<P>
   Although there are fewer ballot initiatives this year than in
1994 or 1996, the trend for voters to decide controversial issues
directly has increased significantly during the 1990s. This year,
citizens initiated 60 ballot questions in 24 states.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a general dissatisfaction that people have been
expressing about government,'' said Jennie Drage, a research
analyst with the National Conference of State Legislatures, a
bipartisan lobbying group with offices in Washington and Denver.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most controversial measures this year involves
allowing the legal use of marijuana for medical purposes, which is
on the ballot in Nevada, Oregon, Washington and Alaska. A marijuana
initiative also could be on Colorado's ballot, depending on a
judge's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an unbelievable controversy here,'' Drage said of the
Colorado measure.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of legal use want doctors to be able to prescribe
marijuana for the treatment of cancer, AIDS, glaucoma, chronic
pain, seizures and muscle spasms. Opponents say there's no credible
medical evidence to support legalization.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton's drug czar, Barry McCaffrey, garnered some
powerful support last week when former presidents Bush, Carter and
Ford publicly declared their opposition to legalization.
</P>
<P>
   Polls, nonetheless, indicate that voters support the marijuana
initiatives in Alaska, Oregon and Washington. The Nevada vote could
go either way.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to medical use, Oregon also is considering a measure
that would make possession of small amounts of marijuana a
low-level misdemeanor.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona has a measure that would require Food and Drug
Administration approval before doctors could prescribe such
Schedule I drugs as heroin, LSD and marijuana. That effort is
lagging in polls.
</P>
<P>
   Voters in Arizona also will consider an initiative to enact
voluntary campaign finance and reporting guidelines. Massachusetts
voters will consider a similar measure. Both initiatives mirror
Clean Elections Acts passed in Maine and Vermont that provide for
public financing but which have not gone into effect yet.
</P>
<P>
   On a related political front, voters in Alaska, Colorado and
Idaho will consider measures on term limits for elected officials.
These so-called scarlet-letter laws, because candidates often have
to declare their position on term limits and that information is
placed on ballots next to their names, usually do not survive legal
challenges.
</P>
<P>
   ``Term limits in the '90s have been up in some shape in every
election,'' said Drage. ``Campaign finance has been out a lot in
the '90s also. They are two measures that voters tend to pass. I
suspect it has to do with all the frustrations people feel.''
</P>
<P>
   Initiatives related to the environment and animal rights also
are popular this year.
</P>
<P>
   Alaska has measures prohibiting billboards as well as outlawing
the trapping of wolves with snares. In Arizona, voters will weigh
in on cockfighting, and California will consider banning certain
traps and poisons. Ohio will decide whether to outlaw the hunting
of mourning doves. New Jersey will vote on setting aside $98
million a year to preserve open space and farmland.
</P>
<P>
   Montana residents will decide whether to ban the use of cyanide
in most open pit gold and silver mining. The poison is prized by
miners for its ability to extract gold and silver from rock, but
spills that contaminated water sources have caused concern among
environmentalists.
</P>
<P>
   Oregon environmentalists placed an initiative on the ballot to
prohibit many current timber harvest practices and to impose more
restrictive regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Abortion, a divisive issue for the past 30 years, is on the
ballot in Colorado, where voters will consider measures on
partial-birth abortions and parental notification. Washington
voters also will consider an abortion measure.
</P>
<P>
   Another controversial issue _ same-sex marriages _ will be
decided in Alaska and Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   Alaska will vote on a constitutional amendment passed by the
legislature that reads: ``To be valid or recognized in this state,
a marriage may exist only between one man and one woman.''
</P>
<P>
   Hawaii, which nearly allowed same-sex marriages through the
courts recently, will consider amending the constitution to give
the legislature authority ``to reserve marriage to opposite-sex
couples.''
</P>
<P>
   Gay activists reportedly are more hopeful about their chances in
Hawaii than Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina also will look at the institution of marriage,
with an initiative to remove the section of the state constitution
that outlaws marriages between blacks and whites. According to
Drage, the state hasn't enforced that provision since the U.S.
Supreme Court ruled a similar law illegal 30 years ago in Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   On another controversial subject, Michigan voters will look at
doctor-assisted suicide. Oregon has passed a similar measure, but
Michigan's chances are hindered by Kevorkian's stigma, little
financial support and disorganized support.
</P>
<P>
   Affirmative action will get a hearing in Washington, where
Coretta Scott King has implored voters to maintain it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately,'' she said in an open letter, ``we do not live
in a society that is truly color-blind, and until that day comes,
affirmative action remains a necessary and vital tool towards
equality.''
</P>
<P>
   Pollsters say the vote is too close to call.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia has 10 measures, none considered controversial. Among
them are initiatives on property taxes for churches and veterans
and a measure to exempt former prisoners of war from having to pay
ad valorem taxes on their motor vehicles. Other measures would
create a Land, Water, Wildlife and Recreation Heritage Fund, a
Brain and Spinal Injury Trust Fund and a Roadside Enhancement and
Beautification Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
