   MARKET (New York) _ Stock prices barreled ahead Friday after
industrialized countries unveiled a new mechanism for stabilizing
distressed economies and the United States said its growth was
faster over the summer than analysts had predicted. By Robert D.
Hershey Jr. (Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m. ET.)
</P>
<P>
   (Display)
</P>
<P>
   HALLOWEEN-HOTSPOTS (Orlando, Fla). _ Strange things are going on
at Universal Studios Florida. Roving bands of chain saw-brandishing
hoodlums pursue fleeing customers through darkened streets. In the
words of one Universal employee, the theme park wants ``to try to
make you scream until there's no sound left.'' The park has been
harvesting millions of dollars from its Halloween Horror Nights _
perhaps as much as $11 million this year. By Edwin McDowell. (With
graphic) (MOVED)
</P>
<P>
   (Top Center)
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ Shortly after Avadis Tevanian
Jr. started work as a senior executive for Apple Computer last
year, he said, a software developer warned him to stop selling a
highly successful software product because if Apple did not,
``Microsoft would take any necessary action to drive Apple out of
businesss.'' Tevanian will take the stand in U.S. District Court
Monday morning as a government witness in the antitrust trial
against Microsoft. By Joel Brinkley. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m.
ET)
</P>
<P>
   (Bottom)
</P>
<P>
   OXFORD-EARNINGS (Undated) _ By cutting costs and shedding
troubled businesses, Oxford Health Plans appears to be reducing the
losses that have plagued it over the last year. The managed-care
company said Friday that it had lost $47 million, or 58 cents a
share, for the quarter ended Sept. 30, on revenues of $1.2 billion.
Wall Street had been expecting a per-share loss ranging from 65
cents to more than $1. By Reed Abelson. (Scheduled to move by 9
p.m. ET.)
</P>
