</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-ECONOMY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. ECONOMY DEFIES EXPECTATIONS, MAY BE HEADING FOR A `SOFT
LANDING' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DAVID IVANOVICH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The nation's economy steamed ahead in the third
quarter, defying expectations the economic crisis in Asia and Latin
America would prompt a more dramatic slowdown here.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. gross domestic product _ the sum of all goods and
service produced in the country _ grew at a robust 3.3 percent for
the three months ending Sept. 30, the U.S. Commerce Department
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
   That was nearly twice the 1.8 percent rate for the second
quarter and substantially better than the 2.2 percent most
economists were predicting.
</P>
<P>
   ``This means the economy still has a lot of life in it, still
has a lot of momentum behind it,'' said Bryan Jordan, economics
analyst for Banc One Investment Advisors in Columbus, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   The surge in growth, however, does not mean the economy has
completely shaken the effects of an economic crisis that has
ravaged much of the rest of the world, several economists said. The
quarterly growth numbers include volatile inventory figures, which
were skewed by the end of the General Motors strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's some cause to celebrate, but you don't want to go
overboard,'' said Bob Brusca, chief economist for Nikko Securities
in New York. ``There are things that should slow the economy
down.''
</P>
<P>
   The economy is no longer chugging along at the hefty 4.2 percent
growth rate of year ago or the 5.5 percent pace of the first
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   But with a growth rate of 3.3 percent a ``recession is not in
sight,'' said Sung Won Sohn, chief economist for Norwest Corp. in
Minneapolis. Instead, the economy may be heading for the kind of
``soft landing'' experts have been hoping for, Sohn said.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton hailed the Commerce Department data Friday as
evidence his administration has helped create ``an American
economic renaissance.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our economy is continuing to grow in a strong manner, at a
solid 3.3 percent,'' Clinton said from the White House's South
Portico. ``It is continuing to expand opportunity, to create
wealth, to lift the hopes of working families. In the face of
worldwide economic turmoil, our economy remains the strongest in a
generation.''
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street cheered Friday, with the Dow Jones Industrial
Average rising 164 points during the day before settling up 97.07
points to close at 8,592.10. By the end of trading, the Dow had
racked up its best monthly advance in more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Bond prices retreated on fears the upbeat economic report,
coupled with figures showing wages rising at their fastest pace in
eight years, would give ammunition to those at the Federal Reserve
Bank reluctant to cut interest rates further.
</P>
<P>
   The central bank reduced its overnight lending rate by a quarter
of a percentage point on Sept. 29, and then cut it by another
quarter point on Oct. 15. Federal Reserve policy-makers are slated
to meet again on Nov. 17.
</P>
<P>
   The Commerce Department report, however, did not suggest a
return of inflation. The GDP deflator _ a broad measure considered
a more accurate indicator of inflation than the better-known
consumer price index _ grew at a mere 0.8 percent in the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really, inflation is nowhere to be found,'' Jordan said.
``That's as close as you can get to price stability.''
</P>
<P>
   As evidence the economy is slowing down, some economists pointed
to a drop in personal spending growth from 6.1 percent in the first
half of the year to 3.9 percent in the third quarter, which is
still a healthy rate.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a little bit like going from 80 miles per hour to 70;
you're still north of the speed limit and really moving,'' Brusca
said.
</P>
<P>
   Home sales fell for the third month in a row in September, the
Commerce Department said in a separate report Friday. Sales of new,
single-family homes dropped 1 percent to 822,000 units, after
falling 4.9 percent in August.
</P>
<P>
   In Houston, the economy is slowing much more dramatically. With
energy prices languishing below $15 a barrel, a number of energy
service companies have cut hundreds of jobs in recent weeks,
including Nabors Industries, Baker Hughes and Cooper Cameron.
</P>
<P>
   Between July and September, Houston lost 3,700 jobs, compared to
an average increase of 11,000 jobs in the same period over the past
three years. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
