<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ALBANIANS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAVEN FOR REBELS SHOWS SCARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MALISEVO, Yugoslavia _ The Albanian separatists of the Kosovo
Liberation Army used to strut around this town like they owned it.
In some ways, they did.
</P>
<P>
   But in July, the Serbs took back the town _ and did so with a
vengeance, shelling houses and shops with abandon. And last week,
as they were leaving, the Serbs torched parts of town, even the
local hospital. Malisevo was punished mercilessly for being a haven
for the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Malisevo today looks like a ghost town. Nearly every window pane
in town is broken. A shopping plaza that once marked the town
center is now rubble. About 15,000 people lived here before July,
but only a few have returned, and then only to survey the damage
and shake their heads. The only people who stayed in town for more
than a cursory look around were the police officers tucked behind
sandbags at a heavily-fortified police station that might as well
be called Fort Apache.
</P>
<P>
   About 90 percent of the 2 million people living in the Serbian
province of Kosovo are ethnic Albanians who have no allegiance to
Yugoslavia. Here in central Kosovo, where the bulk of the fighting
took place during the nine months that the KLA mounted attacks on
the Serbs and the Yugoslav forces responded with a brutal
offensive, there are mostly two kinds of Albanians: those who are
too afraid to return to their homes, and those who don't have homes
to return to.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday and Tuesday, Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic
ordered an accelerated withdrawal of Serb troops from Kosovo to
avert threatened air strikes by NATO. But while there has been a
steady flow of some 300,000 Albanians displaced by the fighting who
are heading back to their homes, few are staying, either because
they fear the Serb police and soldiers will attack them or because
their homes look like those after a tornado has passed through.
</P>
<P>
   About 10 miles outside of Pristina, the provincial capital, the
devastation begins in Lapushnik, once the KLA's front line. The
Serb checkpoint is gone, lifted on Tuesday as part of Milosevic's
concessions to NATO. But houses with the roofs blown off and huge
shell craters in their sides dot the countryside.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look up there,'' said Zekeria Cana, a teacher, pointing to a
hill not far from Lapushnik. In the distance was the outline of
Serbian vehicles, including a wagon that carries a rocket-propelled
grenade launcher. ``How can our people return to their homes when
the Serbs are up there, ready to shell us?''
</P>
<P>
   Interviews with dozens of Albanian refugees suggest that most of
them believed the deal reached two weeks ago between US special
envoy Richard Holbrooke and Milosevic called for the complete
withdrawal of all Serb forces from Kosovo. In fact, it called for a
reduction of the forces to levels similar to last February, when
the KLA began attacking police and Milosevic responded with a
brutal crackdown that killed an estimated 700 Albanian civilians,
some of them in horrific circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   That reduction in forces is not good enough for most Albanians,
who either saw the results of Serb atrocities firsthand, or, more
likely, heard accounts that, in a time-honored Balkan tradition,
get worse with each retelling.
</P>
<P>
   At an abandoned gas station, on the road between Pristina and
Malisevo, an ambulance was parked. The policeman behind the wheel
said he could not talk to reporters. In the back of the ambulance,
two Serbian soldiers fingered their rifles nervously. It was
unclear why the soldiers were sitting there, hidden from view.
</P>
<P>
   The gas station had been occupied by Serb forces until they left
this week. On one wall there was a crudely painted picture of a
Serb soldier raping a woman dressed in a KLA uniform. On another
wall, there was graffitti aimed at the rebellious Albanians: ``If
you'll be good, we'll leave.''
</P>
<P>
   But that's just the point, say Albanians. The Serbs won't leave,
and it seems to be a recipe for disaster, somewhere down the road.
</P>
<P>
   As long as the fighting does not resume, UN officials believe
they can head off a giant humanitarian disaster this winter.
Sitting in his Pristina office, Fernando del Mundo, a spokesman for
the UN High Commissioner for Refugees, said there were few people
still living in the hills of central Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   He said his agency's main concern was to get emergency kits with
plastic sheeting and hammers to families so they can have at least
one warm room. He said the unsanitary conditions in makeshift
refugee camps had led to cases of dysentery and other health
problems, but that there was no sign of major disease which would
have developed had the crisis continued much longer. Nor did hunger
appear to be a major problem yet, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mundo said that nearly 300,000 people were forced out of their
homes because of the fighting this year. Of that figure, 200,000
were displaced somewhere in Kosovo, while about 42,000 fled to
Montenegro, 20,000 each to Albania and Bosnia, and 10,000 to
Serbia. Except for those who fled to Serbia, nearly all of those
displaced are Albanian, he said. Mundo said most of the 200,000 in
Kosovo were living with relatives or friends, but said an
undetermined number remain in the hills and woods, afraid to come
out.
</P>
<P>
   In the village of Carraluka, Avni Kastrati, 26, a farmer,
assessed the damage done to the home of his friend, Rrusten Hoti.
Hoti and his extended family of 24 have been living with Kastrati
and his extended family of 10 for nearly three months. It is
crowded and uncomfortable, Kastrati explained, and he hoped to
repair his friend's house enough in the next month so that the Hoti
family can move back.
</P>
<P>
   The field that leads down to Hoti's home has two clearly
delineated foot paths, the grass patted down. Normally, people
would walk across the field any which way they chose, but they have
been warned about mines left behind by the Serbs. A man was killed
by one on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   As a knot of young men stood around discussing Hoti's
predicament, a boy looked toward the field and nodded, saying,
``Oochicka.'' _ the phonetic sound for the acronym UCK, which in
Albanian stands for KLA.
</P>
<P>
   A man dressed in battle fatigues, a Kalishnakov rifle slung from
his shoulder, was approaching. The guerrilla introduced himself as
Soldier Struga, and declined to be more specific. He came down
because he noticed the Belgrade license plates on the car and
wanted to make sure the locals were all right. He stood in the
open, unfazed by the Serbian police cars that had been routinely
passing on the road above.
</P>
<P>
   Over what seemed to be a brand new Motorola two-way radio
attached to his uniform, Albanian voices crackled about patrols.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are worried about the mines,'' Soldier Struga said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what the KLA can do for all the displaced people, Soldier
Struga shrugged his shoulders and said, ``We can only morally
support them.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the KLA will honor its cease-fire, but when asked if it
bothers him to see Serbs still moving freely through what was a KLA
stronghold, he replied, ``There will come a day when they won't
move so freely.''
</P>
<P>
   As a group of villagers clustered around the mysterious
guerrilla, it became obvious that to them he is not a terrorist, as
the government claims, but the only one around with a gun who is on
their side.
</P>
<P>
   Back in Malisevo, 14-year-old Muhamet Mazreku cut a lonely
figure as he wandered around the town, looking for his three lost
cows. He hasn't seen them since he and his family fled the town
``with just the clothes on our backs'' in July. Muhamet, whose
family has been living with friends outside town, looked in on
their house, but found it was ransacked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything's been stolen,'' he said glumly.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, a man appeared from an alleyway and yelled at Muhamet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come!'' the man shouted. ``We have to run away!''
</P>
<P>
   Without a word, the boy turned and ran, as fast as he could. He
never looked back.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
