<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-30 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6503 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WARSH-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      10-30 1440
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHANGING THE SYSTEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Watching the shuttle go up last week, I tried to put my finger
on what it was that had changed since the 1960s, or even the 1980s,
when Challenger blew up. It wasn't just the woman's voice narrating
the flight, or the simple instrument panel graphic on the TV
screen, or that the president and his wife were present at the
launch _ the first president willing to risk the possiblity he
might preside over an explosion.
</P>
<P>
   The really striking difference had to do with the presence on
board of John Glenn. I don't mean just Glenn the senior citizen,
but Senator Glenn the public figure, a veteran of the S&AMP;L crisis
and the Whitewater controversy as well as early spaceflight. What
was this guy doing strapped into Discovery?
</P>
<P>
   As it happens, I have been reading Thomas Hughes' new book,
``Rescuing Prometheus,'' published in August. Its subtitle
elaborates: ``The story of the mammoth projects _ SAGE, ICBM,
ARPANET/Internet and Boston's Central Artery/Tunnel _ that created
new styles of management, new forms of organization and a new
vision of technology.''
</P>
<P>
   I was astonished at the extent to which John Glenn's flight
illustrated Hughes' central thesis about how the technological
world has changed in the last 30 years: that a key characteristic
of the new approach to technological systems-building is public
participation.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Hughes, 75, trained as an engineer himself, is today the
nation's single most distinguished historian of technology. That
puts him on a par with Daniel Boorstin, Alfred Chandler, William
McNeill, David Landes, David Hackett Fischer, Nathan Rosenberg,
William Cronon, and a handful of other contemporary historians who
have contributed durable visions of America to our stock of
self-images. Professor emeritus at the University of Pennsylvania,
Hughes now shuttles back and forth between Philadelphia and the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
</P>
<P>
   He began his career as an author with a scholarly biography of
Elmer Sperry, &UR;  &LR; who is remembered best for his gyroscopic
controls, &UR;  &LR; as one of Thomas Edison's few rivals as an
inventor-entrepreneur. Hughes then moved on to write ``Networks of
Power,'' a comparative study of the electrification of Chicago,
Berlin, and London at the end of the 19th century. Analysis aside,
it is among the most beautiful books I have read in the past 25
years. And it makes abundantly clear the powerful role of culture
in shaping technology to local tastes.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989 Hughes published ``American Genesis: A History of the
American Genius for Invention.'' Here for the first time emerged
full-blown Hughes' interest in inventor-entrepreneurs as
``system-builders:'' that is, architects of whole industries for
the production of goods and services and, of course, of the values
of order and control necessary to make them work. The race between
Edison and Nikola Teslawas recounted, as were the programs of
Samuel Insull, Henry Ford, the Bauhaus movement, and the adventures
and misadventures that most ambitious industrial visionary of all,
Nikolai Lenin.
</P>
<P>
   Included also were the stories less familiar entrepreneurial
heroes, of Bell Laboratories and the General Electric Research Lab
and the Edison-headed Naval Consulting Board _ the first,
unmistakable foreshadowing of what in due course Dwight Eisenhower
would dub ``the military-industrial complex.'' Hughes followed the
history of government's economic role through the Manhattan project
to develop the atom bomb and the Tennessee Valley Authority project
to bring electricity to the rural South.
</P>
<P>
   Then, with equal tenderness and affection, Hughes described the
backlash elicited by all this technological enthusiasm: the rise of
a counterculture deeply skeptical of all that had been wrought.
Citing the work of Lewis Mumford, Jacques Ellul, and Amory Lovins,
as well as the Challenger disaster and the nuclear accidents at
Three Mile Island and Chernobyl, the historian gave a full hearing
to the critics _ too full, for some readers' tastes. But he noted,
``In the modern world, systems do sometimes fade away, but even
larger and more complex one often displace them.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, in ``Rescuing Prometheus,'' Hughes has taken up where he
left off, describing the complicated new systems that have enfolded
the old. The result is a triumph, a history of how the Cold War
changed America that is different _ and deeper _ than any other. By
zeroing in on managerial institutions rather than science and
engineering itself, Hughes makes it clear how much has changed.
</P>
<P>
   Just as the River Rouge automotive plant and the Hoover Dam were
the icons of the age that perhaps will forever be known as Modern,
so SAGE and ICBM, ARPANET, and the new system of underground
roadways for central Boston are the characteristic programs of our
own time.
</P>
<P>
   Who now remembers MIT's SAGE (Semiautomatic Ground Environment)
project? This radar-based plan to deploy Nike missiles against
long-range Soviet bombers was obsolete by the time it was deployed
in 1958. Yet Hughes compares it to the building of the Erie Canal
as a learning experience. Its planners put high-speed digital
computing at the center of military applications _ and lured an
old-line firm named International Business Machines into the
business to make them.
</P>
<P>
   ICBM? &UR;  &LR; It started out in 1946 as a $1.4 million Air Force
contract with Consolidated Vultee Aircraft Corp. (Convair) to
design a missile that would fall within a mile of its target 5,000
miles away. Before long it was the full-fledged intercontinental
ballistic missile (ICBM) project, its technical possibilities fast
expanding, whose descendent the astronauts rode into space last
week. The chapter on Gen. Bernard ``Benny'' Schreiver and Simon
Ramo and the ``Western Development Division'' of the Air Force is
great reading.
</P>
<P>
   And you simply won't find a more engaging account of how the
Internet came to be than the chapter that chronicles the career of
J.C.R. Licklider, head of the Information Processing Techniques
Office of the Defense Department's Advance Research Projects Agency
from 1962 to 1964 _ the years when the key contracts for its
ARPANET computer network were let.
</P>
<P>
   Many other brilliant citizens set their hands to creating this
astonishing system, but no contribution was more fundamental than
the vision of a dense network of interactive time-sharing computers
that was developed by Licklider during his years as head of the
psychoacoustics lab at Bolt Beranek and Newman of Cambridge, Mass.,
in the late 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   Only when you come to Hughes' chapter on Boston's ``Big Dig'' _
its project to burrow the city's central highway artery in a tunnel
well below the town _ is the full novelty of his analysis born in
upon you. He describes the sprawling complexity of the project,
involving federal, state, and local agencies, not to mention every
sort of interest group imaginable, and describes the tolerant
democratic style that former state Transportation Secretary
Frederick Salvucci evolved to cope with it _ in certain ways the
opposite of Benny Schreiver's approach to missile-building.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes says that Big Dig and the Internet are history's first
``post-modern'' engineering projects _ and that their
post-modernity can be ascribed ``in no small part'' to the
counterculture values that spread in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many Americans blamed the tragedy of the Vietnam War on their
government's amoral use of large-scale military technology. The
distrust of government and technology focused not only on military
technology but on large-scale technology in general. Hierarchy,
bureaucracy and governance by experts fell into disfavor,'' he
writes. Public participation in the design of new technologies has
become the accepted rule.
</P>
<P>
   It is a considerable insight. The very same reactions that
motivated the 1970's tax revolt may be embedded in slightly
different form in the Internet, the most important technology of
our time, &UR;  &LR; one controlled by no government agency or corporation.
The same impulse that led to the Prague Spring of 1968 _ a
particularily forceful protest against Soviet hegemony _ may be
discerned in the reaction to various attempts to impose big
unsightly bridges on the Boston landscape in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's what John Glenn is doing up there in orbit even
though his role in its ``medical mission'' has been scrubbed. He no
longer needs an excuse.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   David Warsh writes about economics for the Boston Globe. His
e-mail address is warsh(at)nws.globe.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-30-98 1948EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
