<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-30 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6505 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      10-30 1331
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AWAITING WORD FROM MOUNT MO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The message has not come down from Mount Mo. Yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are waiting to see what it is going to take,'' said Red Sox
CEO John Harrington after meeting with his top executives in
Florida to chart the course for next season. ``Our No. 1 priority
is still signing Mo Vaughn. We will know, one way or another, if we
can get a new contract done by the end of next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our people (Elaine Weddington Steward and Dan Duquette) have
been in touch with Mo's agents. They will be in Orlando over the
weekend talking, but I don't think anything will happen until next
Thursday or so. Up to that point, teams are not allowed to give a
specific offer to a free agent from another team. So I think Mo's
people will wait until that time to see what offers they have from
other teams and every detail of those offers.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that time, we think we will find out for the first time
exactly what it will take for us to re-sign Mo. We don't know now
how much money he'll be looking for. We don't know how many years
he wants to sign for. We'd like to sign him for three. But we
offered him four years last summer at the All-Star break, and if he
wants four, we'll go four.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrington says the Red Sox will move quickly one way or another
when Vaughn's agents tell them what it will take to sign the free
agent slugger.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can't meet what they want,'' said Harrington, ``then we
will move on and get someone else signed with the money we have
slotted for Mo. If there is no one player, then we will use it to
get two very good players. Our top priority (after Vaughn) is still
a front-line pitcher. We asked Jimy (Williams), and his wish is for
more pitching.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrington was asked if he thought the record-breaking
seven-year, $91 million contract the New York Mets gave catcher
Mike Piazza would affect the Vaughn negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Piazza is the standard for this year,'' he said. ``I
don't think anyone is going to get that kind of money. I look
around baseball and I don't see it coming from any other team. The
Mets are in a unique situation. They are fighting the battle for
the back pages in New York (tabloids) with the Yankees and they've
been losing. They have to try to keep themselves in the news to
generate positive publicity. That's why they went out right away
and got Piazza this deal and signed (pitcher Al) Leiter. And I'm
sure they will spend more money before they are finished. But they
are the only team that I can see that is in that kind of
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   How about the reports of Boston interest in White Sox free agent
Albert Belle?
</P>
<P>
   ``This I find interesting,'' said Harrington. ``I keep reading
all summer about how players don't want to play for the Red Sox,
about how they don't want to play in Boston. What a bunch of
blather. We have been contacted by the agents of just about every
player out there. And you know what they tell us? `Our player loves
the Red Sox. Playing in Boston is his No. 1 priority.' Belle? We
read he wanted to play in Boston. We checked it out. He does. When
the time comes, Mike Port will be talking to his agent to see what
it will take. Will we give him $14 million a year (which reportedly
is what Belle is looking for)? The answer is no.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrington says that without signing a single new player for
1999, the Sox already have one of the top five payrolls in baseball
and will be subject to a luxury tax. ``One (salary) survey already
has us second,'' he said, ``so it isn't like we are not spending
money. We have spent money and we will spend more.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Flutie's big day &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tomorrow is the day Doug Flutie starts to cash in. In order to
get another shot in the NFL, Flutie signed with the Bills for the
minimum _ $250,000 _ which is chump change for a veteran of 13 pro
seasons. Luckily for him, his Boston-based contract agent, Jack
Mula, had 34 bonus provisions written into the contract. The first
bonus kicks in tomorrow when Flutie faces the Miami Dolphins in
Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   His contract reads that if he's in for 25 percent of the
offensive plays during the season, he gets an additional $100,000.
That will happen vs. Miami. For every 10 percent after that, he
collects another $100,000. If he's in for 70 percent of the plays
and Buffalo wins 10 games, Flutie's bonuses would reach $1 million
_ and they'll climb beyond that if the Bills make the playoffs and
keep advancing. Even better, these bonuses will be added to
Flutie's base salary next year.
</P>
<P>
   Flutie apparently will be Buffalo's starting quarterback for the
next few weeks. Rob Johnson, sidelined by a rib injury, started to
throw this week, but it doesn't appear he'll be able to play soon.
And if Flutie keeps winning, he'll keep starting.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots visit Buffalo in 15 days, and incredibly, there are
still 25,000 tickets left for that game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our game with Miami was sold out before Doug started to
play,'' said Bills ticket manager Jerry Foran. ``If he keeps on
playing and winning, then I think he will sell a lot of tickets for
the Patriots game. If anyone down there wants to come up here, they
can call us (1-877-228-4257) and we will take care of them.''
</P>
<P>
   None of the Flutie phenomenon in Buffalo would have happened
without Mula. When Flutie was given a 30-day window of opportunity
in January to leave the Canadian Football League for the NFL, Mula
contacted every team. At first, none responded. Then he got a
glimmer of hope from Bills scout A.J. Smith, who had watched the
CFL and liked Flutie. However, GM John Butler said Mula would have
to convince new coach Wade Phillips first.
</P>
<P>
   So with money out of his own pocket, Mula got on a plane to San
Francisco, where Phillips was watching the East-West Shrine Game
practice sessions. He walked up to Phillips and introduced himself.
Phillips said he was willing to give Flutie a shot, and that opened
the door.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
More work on NBA &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   People close to the NBA labor negotiations think it will take
another three weeks to get resolved and three weeks after that
before the games begin. Despite what has been said publicly, the
league will do everything it can to reschedule as many missed games
as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked with other arena managers,'' said FleetCenter boss
Rich Kreswick, ``and all of us feel that these games will be made
up. They are not going to walk away from all of that money. None of
us have a policy on what we are going to do to repay the luxury
box- (and seat-) holders. We have to see how it all ends up.''
</P>
<P>
   The players are now trying to bad-mouth NBC-TV for paying the
owners while the lockout is ongoing. What they don't seem to know
is that the networks paid out money to the NFL when its players
were on strike. There was no way NBC would have gotten the NBA
contract unless it agreed to the pay schedule the league wanted.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
L.A. may get football nod &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here's the scoop out of the latest NFL meetings. The majority of
owners are leaning toward Los Angeles to get the 32d team even
though Houston seems better prepared. The league will choose the
next city in February or March. When that happens, the NFL will
realign into eight divisions with four teams each.
</P>
<P>
   It was recommended that the teams within each division, as
presently constructed, talk with each other to see who would not
mind shifting. The Cleveland Browns will be in the AFC Central next
year. Commissioner Paul Tagliabue will make a ruling within three
weeks as to when the new Browns and other teams can start
approaching coaching candidates who are under contract to other NFL
teams. It is expected that coaches with teams who don't make the
playoffs can move right away and that Tagliabue will allow Super
Bowl coaches to talk with other teams in the off week before the
game.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(Will McDonough is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
