<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-TEMPTATIONS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GET READY FOR NBC'S `TEMPTATIONS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Check local listings for time and channel.)  
 By JAMES SULLIVAN  
 c.1998, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Temptations were not too proud to beg. They also argued
viciously, broke up time and again and recorded a half-dozen songs
that every living American knows by heart.
</P>
<P>
   These are good qualities for a miniseries.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Temptations,'' an NBC made-for-TV biopic, begins Sunday
night and concludes Monday.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to see how the network could attract such talent for
this sweeps production. Heck, the director, Allan Arkush, is the
guy responsible for the original dancing-baby episode on ``Ally
McBeal.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only did the long-running vocal group endure all kinds of
internal strife, but most of the members' lives ended in tragedy _
suicide, overdose, cancer. Add to that the fact that the
Temptations have spanned several decades of pop music, inspiring
the costume department to re-create fashions from Tony Curtis
pompadours to Chevy Impala chic, and the result is some eminently
watchable TV.
</P>
<P>
   With a string of gold records, the Temptations became Rock and
Roll Hall of Fame inductees by bridging the doo-wop era (``My
Girl'') with disco (former lead singer Eddie Kendricks' ``Keep on
Truckin'''). In between, they defined the Motown sound with
activist anthems (``Get Ready'') and hard-soul laments (``Papa Was
a Rollin' Stone,'' for which there's a wonderful video-style
montage in the movie).
</P>
<P>
   The miniseries is based on the recollections of Otis Williams,
the group's sole surviving original member. Cast members are young,
limber and expressive. Their lip-synching in the musical sequences
is a marvel, and they do their level best with the one-dimensional
caricatures they're given to portray.
</P>
<P>
   ``You ever been a part of something that's bigger than
yourself?'' Temptation Melvin Franklin asks his doctor, who is
trying to persuade the performer to retire. ``It's a beautiful
thing, doc.''
</P>
<P>
   Played by D.B. Woodside, whose acting experience encompasses
both a drag queen and Malcolm X, the deep-baritone Franklin is the
loyal Temptation. He gets shot in a struggle with a car thief, ends
up in a wheelchair and dies at home in his mama's house.
</P>
<P>
   Williams (Charles Malik Whitfield) comes across as the stoic
Temptation. ``You ain't just a success in show business,'' his
dying mother tells him as they sit on a porch together, tears
flowing. ``You're a success as a man.''
</P>
<P>
   Other characters fit their slots just as neatly. Kendricks
(Terron Brooks) is the satiny, easygoing crooner. David Ruffin,
played by screen veteran Leon (``Waiting to Exhale''), is the
explosive prima donna with a drug problem; Paul Williams (Christian
Payton of ``Hoodlum'') is the alcoholic who gets kicked out of the
group.
</P>
<P>
   The movie doesn't offer a lot of insight into the Temptations'
rise and fall. The group's relationship with longtime manager
Shelly Berger is barely explored, and the fascinating inner
workings of Motown are reduced to a few fraternal scenes outside
the ``Hitsville'' studio. A cameo by Smokey Robinson, singing at a
funeral, feels glued on.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's all swell entertainment. In one early exchange on
the Hitsville lawn, the fledgling group is looking for a name
change. As they toss around a football, members holler suggestions.
``The Radicals!'' ``The Spectacles!''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Testicles!'' blurts Franklin, before he can catch himself.
</P>
<P>
   A hearse drives by. ``The Stiffs!'' someone tries.
</P>
<P>
   Happily enough for those looking to knock off a little time in
front of the tube, there's plenty of life in this made-for-TV
movie.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
