<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981030.0331 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-30 20:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6520 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAMPAIGN-CALIF-ART-2N     10-30 0455
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-CALIF-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 LOS ANGELES: safety locks.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It has helped that Fong, a former Air Force officer and member
of the state Board of Equalization and Assessment, has been
tentative in debates and has not drawn the unalloyed support of the
national Republican Party, which can get a bigger bang for its
advertising dollars in battleground states where television time is
less costly.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief appearance in Los Angeles' Chinatown on Thursday,
intended to rally support among Asian-American voters, Fong left
without taking any questions. Instead, he turned the podium over to
his campaign manager, who played videotapes of new television
commercials, including one featuring the candidate's mother, March
Fong Eu, the longtime former Democratic secretary of state here,
saying Boxer ``should be ashamed'' of her attacks, and another
branding the senator ``too liberal and ineffective for
California.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Lungren has been hard-pressed to move his campaign
much beyond the issue of crime. On a visit to the Robert E. Lee
Elementary School in a minority neighborhood in his hometown of
Long Beach on Wednesday, Lungren read a Halloween story but spoke
listlessly to parents and teachers about education, never
mentioning his main proposal: giving government vouchers to allow
parents of children in troubled public schools to send them to
private or parochial schools.
</P>
<P>
   Only the next morning, at a ceremony honoring crime victims in
which Mayors Rudolph Giuliani of New York and Richard Riordan of
Los Angeles participated, did Lungren seem to come alive.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem for the Republicans here, Ms. Jeffe said, is
that their own base of party activists is increasingly dominated by
conservatives who produce candidates like Lungren, while elections
are won in the center. President Clinton showed the national appeal
of that brand of centrism two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Carrick, the Democratic consultant, noted that Californians of
both parties tend to migrate here from other states in search of
one kind or another of freedom from their old worlds, ``and that by
definition makes them more open-minded and far less judgemental''
than voters in many other regions. But he predicted that
California's penchant for moderation could become its latest
export.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, it's a big influence in and of itself, just because
of its size,'' Carrick said. ``But in terms of the ability of the
political trends here to translate to other places, I think there's
going to be a continuing counter-reaction to the increasingly
conservative brand of Republicans in other parts of the country,
and then we're going to look back in 10 years and say it started in
California.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
