<HEADLINE>
HEALTHY GROWTH FOR ECONOMY,   BUT SOME ANALYSTS SEE OMINOUS SIGNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Consumers spent money freely over the summer,
making the US economy an island of solid growth amid a troubled
world economy, the government reported yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Several economists, however, saw bad news in the numbers and
predicted that economic growth would cool in the next few months.
``Things look very strong on the surface, but it's not so strong
when you probe around underneath,'' said Cynthia Latta, principal
US economist at Standard &AMP; Poor's/DRI in Lexington, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   The Commerce Department reported that gross domestic product,
the broadest measure of goods and services produced in the United
States, rose at an annual rate of 3.3 percent in the
July-to-September quarter, seasonally adjusted. Analysts had been
expecting growth only a little above 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The 3.3 percent rate compares to growth of 5.5 percent in the
first quarter of this year and 1.8 percent in the second quarter, a
time when the Asian financial crisis began cutting into orders at
US companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our economy is continuing to grow in a strong manner. ... In
the face of worldwide economic turmoil, our economy remains the
strongest in a generation,'' President Clinton said. The stock
market also cheered the Commerce report, sending the Dow Jones
industrial average up 97.07 to close at 8592.10.
</P>
<P>
   But several analysts said the government report contained some
ominous signs.
</P>
<P>
   Exports declined at a rate of 2.9 percent, the third quarter in
a row that they fell. Equally troubling, businesses invested money
in new buildings and equipment at a slower pace. ``You've got two
major weaknesses in the GDP: exports are still a disaster, and now
you have problems with business investment,'' said Nicholas Perna,
chief economist with Fleet Financial Group Inc. ``You have to ask
yourself how long the economy can go along with those areas being a
drag on the whole thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The troubling news did not end there. Much of the economic
growth in the third quarter came as businesses added to their
inventories. Their shelves are now stocked, but it is unclear
whether they will sell off those goods and place new orders with
manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, consumer confidence has been slipping, a fact given
more weight Friday as the University of Michigan index of consumer
sentiment slipped to 97.4 in October from 100.9 in September..
Consumer spending drives about two-thirds of economic activity.
</P>
<P>
   The government report Friday gave mixed news on consumer
spending, saying it grew at a robust 3.9 percent annual rate in the
third quarter. At the same time, consumers are spending just about
everything they earn. According to Latta, the government reported
that the savings rate is now at a troubling 0.1 percent, down from
0.4 percent in the second quarter and greatly lower than about 5.5
percent in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Both Latta and Oscar Gonzalez, an economist with John Hancock
Mutual Life Insurance in Boston, said the newest GDP numbers would
likely prompt them to revise their estimates downward for growth in
the final quarter of 1998. Because some growth likely occurred in
the third quarter that they had expected to come in the fourth,
Gonzalez said he would probably forecast growth for the last
quarter of the year at 2 percent or 2.5 percent, while Latta pegged
it at something less than the 2.8 percent in her most recent
analysis.
</P>
<P>
   More problematic, growth could slow to under 1 percent in the
first part of next year, Latta said. ``And if you're used to 3.5
percent growth, that feels like a recession,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``All you need is a couple of things to go wrong to move you
from slow growth into negative growth,'' said Perna. He said the
chance of a recession in the near future is about 30 percent or 35
percent.
</P>
<P>
   One open question is whether the Federal Reserve will try to
stimulate the economy by again lowering interest rates. Several
analysts said the strong GDP numbers Friday made it unlikely that
Fed policy-makers would cut rates at their November meeting. But
Perna predicted a half-point cut, possibly in two stages, over the
next few months.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
