<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-CASINOS-$ADV01-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOUGH ODDS AS CASINOS MULTIPLY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Nev.)  (For release Sunday, Nov. 1) 
(af) 
 By ANDREW POLLACK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mark Greenberg, portfolio manager of the Invesco Leisure fund,
stayed at the new Bellagio hotel in Las Vegas last week, while
attending the Salomon Smith Barney Leisure Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Widely considered the most luxurious and spectacular resort in
Las Vegas, the Bellagio boasts Picasso paintings on its walls,
Italian marble on its floors and a man-made lake with more than
1,200 fountain spouts on its grounds.
</P>
<P>
   The accommodations were indeed grand, but Greenberg was a bit
unhappy about the price. ``I wish my rate wasn't so good,'' he
said. ``It's $99 a night.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenberg's fund has a small amount of its money invested in
Mirage Resorts Inc., which owns the Bellagio and hopes to charge
$200 a night on average, a new high for Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Greenberg got his room for $99 _ albeit on a
weekday during a slow time of the year _ could be a sign of deep
trouble for Las Vegas, the nation's largest gambling center.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Picassos aside, the Las Vegas picture is not pretty,
at least for casino companies and investors. A looming oversupply
of rooms and falling profits have battered their stocks; the
hardest hit, like Circus Circus Enterprises and Primadonna Resorts,
have fallen by about half this year.
</P>
<P>
   But that might not mean that such stocks are bargains. ``In that
environment, the better question is not who thrives but who
survives,'' said Harry Curtis, an analyst with BancBoston Robertson
Stephens.
</P>
<P>
   A glut of rooms is not the only concern. The Asian economic
crisis has reduced visits by Asian high rollers. Revenue from
baccarat, their game of choice, is down 24 percent through August
this year.
</P>
<P>
   And Californians will vote Tuesday on a proposition that would
expand Indian-run casinos in their state. The could siphon gamblers
from Las Vegas, which drew 28 percent of its visitors from
California last year.
</P>
<P>
   The 3,000-room Bellagio, which opened on Oct. 15, is the first
of four splashy hotels that together will increase the number of
rooms in Las Vegas by more than 12,000, or 12 percent, in the
coming year. The three others are Circus Circus' Mandalay Bay,
Hilton Hotels' Paris and the Venetian, owned by Sheldon Adelson,
who made his fortune from the Comdex computer trade show.
</P>
<P>
   Still more hotels are set to open in 2000, bringing the room
count to 128,000, up nearly 22 percent from 1997, according to the
Las Vegas Convention and Visitors Authority.
</P>
<P>
   The new hotels represent a shift upward in price and luxury as
casino operators hope to attract wealthy people, even if they are
not gamblers, who might otherwise vacation in Palm Springs or
Aspen. Instead of luring visitors with cheap rooms and 99-cent
shrimp cocktails, the new hotels hope their fancy rooms,
restaurants and shops will be profit centers in their own right.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, new hotels have attracted enough visitors to more
than fill the new rooms they created. In 1993, the number of hotel
rooms jumped by 12 percent with the opening of Treasure Island,
Luxor and the MGM Grand. The next year, the number of visitors
soared 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But some analysts say that while the latest hotels will bring in
more visitors, the increase will not be enough to fill the new
capacity, in part because airline service to Las Vegas is
insufficient.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis predicted that the visitor count would rise 4 percent to
4.5 percent a year, but that 6 percent would be needed for Las
Vegas casinos as a group to meet earnings expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, a belief that each new round of hotels must be more
spectacular than the last means higher construction costs, thus
lowering potential returns. The Bellagio cost $1.6 billion, not
including the Picassos.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no doubt that the returns on investment during this
round of capital investment will be less than they were last
time,'' said Andrew S. Zarnett, an analyst at Ladenburg Thalmann.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts recommend a flight to quality. ``Some of the
better operators will glean the lion's share of the profits and
others will be working very hard to make less money,'' said John J.
Rohs, an analyst with Schroder &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   By consensus, analysts saw Mirage Resorts as the safest bet,
though they differed on how safe it would be. It is the only casino
company on Schroder's list of recommended stocks, and Rohs
predicted that Mirage shares would be at $24 a year from now,
compared with $16.937.
</P>
<P>
   Zarnett is a bit more optimistic. He said the talk in Las Vegas
was that the Bellagio was already drawing increasing numbers of
visitors. In addition to Mirage Resorts, he recommended MGM Grand,
with a price target of $35, up from $26.125 on Friday. It has good
management, a pristine balance sheet and a new convention center to
help fill its rooms, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Jason N. Ader of Bear, Stearns said he would not invest in
any Las Vegas casino operators right now. While the Bellagio should
do well, Ader said, it might cannibalize business from other Mirage
Resorts hotels. (He recommends Sun International Hotels, which is
opening a casino on Paradise Island in the Bahamas, where it will
face virtually no competition.)
</P>
<P>
   Greenberg, despite small positions in Hilton and Mirage Resorts,
is not buying any more Las Vegas casino stocks, quite a statement
for a fund manager whose mission is to invest in leisure
industries. ``I don't know what they are going to do to get out of
this problem,'' he said of the oversupply.
</P>
<P>
   So perhaps the best reason for buying casino stocks now is that
no one else seems to want them. This is what is known in Las Vegas
as a long shot.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
