s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-NY-MUTUAL-ART-     10-30 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-NY-MUTUAL-ART-$ADV01-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST IN NEW WAVE OF CONVERTS IS A MODEST BET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., Fla., Mass., N.Y.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(For release Sunday, Nov. 1) 
(af) 
 By JOSEPH B. TREASTER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After 155 years as a life insurance company that concentrated on
providing policies at low cost rather than on turning a profit, the
Mutual Life Insurance Co. of New York is preparing to enter the
turbulent world of publicly traded companies.
</P>
<P>
   The big question for investors is whether management can turn a
tortoise into something more closely resembling a hare.
</P>
<P>
   There is money to be made if Michael I. Roth, the chief
executive, succeeds. For like other sluggish mutuals that have made
the transition to stock ownership, MONY, as it is known, should
come out of the gate in the next few weeks at a big discount.
</P>
<P>
   At an expected price of about $20 a share for its initial public
offering, it would trade nearly 44 percent below the company's book
value of $35.58 a share.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, publicly held life insurers are trading at about
twice their book value.
</P>
<P>
   But the discount is not there for nothing. ``Mutual life
insurance companies have deeply ingrained cultures,'' said Eric N.
Berg, an analyst for CIBC Oppenheimer, an investment bank. ``They
can change. And some have. But changes in such conservative
companies are hard fought.''
</P>
<P>
   Recent history is encouraging.
</P>
<P>
   The Equitable Life Insurance Co., now the Equitable Companies,
shifted from a mutual to a stock structure in 1992 with an initial
public offering at $9 a share. After rising to about $20, the stock
plateaued for several years before climbing to a peak of $84.1875
last July.
</P>
<P>
   It closed on Friday at $49. The State Mutual Life Assurance
Company of America in Worcester, Mass., now the Allmerica Financial
Corp., went on the market in late 1995 at $21. It gradually rose to
a peak of $75.25 this summer, and closed on Friday at $50.
</P>
<P>
   These companies have picked up the pace. And MONY may do so,
too. But MONY and its brethren are unlikely to ever be mistaken for
sprinters. ``This is a company for the long haul, something you
might want to put in your kid's college fund,'' said Randall Roth,
an analyst at Renaissance Capital, an initial-offering research
firm in Greenwich, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   MONY's is the first of a new wave of recently announced
conversions, as big mutuals scramble to raise money for expansions
aimed at gaining greater market share and economies of scale.
</P>
<P>
   MONY's offering is being watched by other mutuals that are
converting, like Prudential and John Hancock, as well as others,
like Metropolitan Life, that are leaning that way.
</P>
<P>
   MONY plans to issue 34 million shares to its 900,000
policyholders, who are the formal owners of the company, and to
sell 11.3 million other shares, expecting to raise more than $200
million. (MONY had planned to sell 15.3 million shares before the
stock market began to lose its zip.)
</P>
<P>
   Underscoring that investors may be getting a bargain, some
policyholders have said the offering should be delayed until the
market improved. But Roth said at a New York State Insurance
Department hearing two weeks ago that no one could be sure when
that would be. And, down the road, he said, prices ``could be
worse.''
</P>
<P>
   MONY got into serious trouble in the late 1980s when it had lots
of real estate and junk bonds _ more than many competitors _ and
the value of both dropped sharply. While the company has been
recovering, its return on equity is about 4 percent, below even the
stolid 7 percent average for other mutuals and well below the 13
percent for publicly traded competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Some who have looked at the company's books do not like what
they see. Robert Mescal, an analyst at the Institute for
Econometric Research in Deerfield Beach, Fla., said he is skeptical
about the company's reports that profits have risen sharply in the
last 18 months though revenues have been flat, at about $2 billion,
for several years.
</P>
<P>
   MONY's prospectus shows the profit increase comes from capital
gains on real estate sales, which many analysts say they eliminate
in evaluating a company.
</P>
<P>
   It does not look like a case of management trying to gussy up
its performance, said Michael A. Frinquelli, a principal of
Renaissance Fund Advisers, an investment fund. MONY looks like ``a
value stock,'' he said, adding that he was still researching but
``we're predisposed to buying it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
