<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOUNTY-GEORGIA31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Debate over bounds of bounty hunters renewed in Georgia
 &HT;    By Bill Torpy
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The popular image of a bounty hunter is Clint
Eastwood, a stogie clenched in his teeth, riding into town with a
trussed up ne'er-do-well thrown over a horse. It didn't matter how
he got the varmint. He just did.
</P>
<P>
   That notion has persisted and was reinforced this week when two
bounty hunters kicked in the door of the wrong house in South
DeKalb County where a terrified 14-year-old girl was home alone.
The men were charged criminally Friday, reopening debate over just
how far bounty hunters can go.
</P>
<P>
   Don Geary, a Gwinnett County prosecutor who convicted two bounty
hunters in Fulton County three years ago after a shootout, said the
profession has no oversight and there's a common myth that bounty
hunters are somewhat beyond the law.
</P>
<P>
   Bounty hunters ``govern themselves by an 1830-something case
that says they have basically unfettered power,'' said Geary. ``But
they don't have near as much authority as they think they have.''
State law enforcement officials say the civil contract signed by
people bonded out of jail forfeits some of their rights, but does
not give bounty hunters carte blanche in their pursuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``They sign away some of their rights,'' said Geary. ``But they
have no right to go into the homes of people not involved. They
don't have more rights than police officers.''
</P>
<P>
   DeKalb County District Attorney J. Tom Morgan said a 1983 DeKalb
County ruling upheld by the Georgia Supreme Court ``says they
(bounty hunters) have the same rights as police officers, although
I disagree with that vehemently. ``
</P>
<P>
   Magistrate judge Alan Harvey told the two bounty hunters in the
DeKalb case Friday that their job gives them the right to enter a
house looking for a suspect.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you do not have the right to damage property,'' Harvey
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Jenkins, owner of a Marietta debt collection agency, said
he left the bounty-hunter business four years ago ``because there
are too many crazies out there who'll kick in doors thinking
they're Wyatt Earp.''
</P>
<P>
   But there's an effort afoot by some bail bonding agents to clean
up the industry and establish guidelines regulating who should be
able to chase down ``skips.'' Currently, Georgia has no
requirements for bounty hunters. They don't have to be licensed and
no criminal background checks are performed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want the felons out of doing recovery,'' said Ray Krebs,
owner of A Accommodating Bonding in Marietta and regional director
of Professional Bondsmen of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Krebs, who said bounty hunters perform a public service by
capturing 28,000 bail jumpers a year, worked with state Rep. Kem
Shipp (R-Kennesaw) this year in an unsuccessful attempt to pass a
law that would require training and licensing for bounty hunters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can never legislate out stupidity,'' said Krebs. ``But
there are laws dealing with stupidity. They broke down the door and
got charged.''
</P>
<P>
   Shipp unsuccessfully tried to put his plan under the umbrella of
the state Peace Officers Standards and Training Council and then
the Secretary of State's office. Both agencies said they did not
have the staff for the job.
</P>
<P>
   Shipp, who said he started the effort after bounty hunters
terrorized a friend's daughter one night, amended the bill to have
bounty hunters pay for their own training. Convicted felons would
be excluded. They would also be required to register with the
county sheriff. He plans to push the bill again next year.
</P>
<P>
   Krebs said he requires his ``recovery agents'' to have a gun
license and good references before he interviews them. ``You say,
`Isn't it fun to kick in doors?' If they say yes, whoa, they're
gone,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want management, training and screening,'' said Krebs.
``Right now some (bondsmen) don't care who they hire.''
</P>
<P>
   Contributing: Staff Writer R. Robin McDonald
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
