<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-ATTYGENL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tough image marks attorney general race
 &HT;    By Bill Rankin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ State Attorney General Thurbert Baker took the
offensive this week in his bid to win re-election, picking up key
endorsements and hitting the airwaves to say his GOP opponent's
``negative ads are a lie.''
</P>
<P>
   The closely contested race pits Baker, the former state
legislator appointed to the post last year by Gov. Zell Miller,
against state Sen. David Ralston (R-Blue Ridge) and Zebulon lawyer
Walker Chandler, the Libertarian candidate. During the final weeks
of the campaign, both Baker and Ralston have aired TV ads that make
it sound as if each candidate is going to be the toughest lawman
possible. At the same time, each criticizes the other for being
soft on crime.
</P>
<P>
   At a Friday news conference outside the Capitol, Baker announced
he had received endorsements from 19 of the state's 47 district
attorneys. Three metro area DAs _ Paul Howard of Fulton County, J.
Tom Morgan of DeKalb and Bob Keller of Clayton _ stood at Baker's
side. On Thursday, Baker picked up an endorsement from the National
Rifle Association.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan said it is the first time he knows of that district
attorneys have endorsed a candidate for statewide office.
``Thurbert supported the DAs when he was floor leader for Governor
Miller,'' Morgan said. ``We don't forget that.''
</P>
<P>
   In response, Ralston made note that less than half of the
state's district attorneys formally endorsed Baker. He added: ``We
have not asked for DAs to endorse us because most all the DA's we
talk with view their office to be outside politics. It troubles me
he's bringing them into a political fight.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ralston has received support from at least one district
attorney, Roger Queen of the Appalachian Judicial Circuit. During a
recent debate, Ralston criticized Baker for not responding to a
Dec. 10, 1997, letter from Queen, who asked for help in the appeal
of a pretrial ruling involving the death penalty prosecution of
Tommy Lamar Pickren. Pickren, who shot and killed Gilmer County
Deputy Brett Dickey, was sentenced to life without parole. Baker
says his office assisted Queen's prosecutors in the case, even
though he did not personally answer Queen's letter. And District
Attorneys Morgan and Howard both said Friday that the attorney
general's office during Baker's tenure has helped prosecute death
penalty cases.
</P>
<P>
   In his advertising campaign, Ralston also criticizes Baker for
voting to kill legislation requiring violent criminals to serve 85
percent of their sentences and for his vote against legislation
that proposed to allow nonunanimous verdicts in capital sentencing.
</P>
<P>
   Baker, who now says violent criminals should serve their entire
sentence, said his ad calls Ralston's claim ``a lie'' because it
misrepresents his record. Baker said he voted against the
85-percent proposal because it may have weakened a state law
requiring life sentences for anyone convicted a second time of one
of the ``seven deadly sins.''
</P>
<P>
   In a show of support for the death penalty, one Baker ad notes
that he ``ordered'' the June 9 execution of a convicted murderer.
Although Baker's office successfully argued for James Cargill's
execution, it was actually a judge who ordered the execution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
