<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-30 20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6530 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GA-GOV-MONEY-COX     10-30 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-GOV-MONEY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Barnes raises record $9 million for Georgia governor's race
 &HT;    By Peter Mantius
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Republican Guy Millner, a multimillionaire businessman
with no experience in government, has campaigned for governor on
the promise he'll apply business principles to state government,
but Georgia's business establishment appears to be at least as
comfortable with Democrat Roy Barnes.
</P>
<P>
   That' picture emerges from a study of the two candidates'
campaign finance disclosure reports through October 19.
</P>
<P>
   Millner has invested at least $11.5 million of his own money in
the race and raised another $3.5 million from 4,400 contributors.
But Barnes, a state representative from suburban Atlanta, has
beaten the bushes for a record $9 million from 9,000 contributors
who represent a broad spectrum of economic interests, including
banking, real estate, healthcare, timber and poultry.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some true believers who think any Democrat won't be
friendly to business,'' said Keith Mason, an Atlanta attorney who
has worked on the staffs of Gov. Zell Miller and President Clinton.
``But some of the more informed people in business understand that
government has a role to play in areas like producing an educated
workforce.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes received contributions from the CEOs of Georgia-Pacific
Corp., Georgia Power Co., Chatham Steel and from CNN's Ted Turner.
Millner accepted contributions from the CEO of Equifax and from
Bear Stears and Flowers Industries.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers Wade, who has given to both parties and recently
contributed $5,000 to Millner, said many of the state's
conservative Democrats and established businesses have sided with
Barnes because they are leery of radical change.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're staying with what they know,'' said Wade, president of
the non-partisan Georgia Public Policy Foundation. ``They don't
know Guy Millner. This may be his third go-round, but they still
don't know him.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, the Tarbutton family, which runs a hugely
profitable railroad that serves the kaolin industry in middle
Georgia, contributed $23,500 to Barnes after initially supporting
Republican Mike Bowers, whom Millner defeated in the primary in
July.
</P>
<P>
   If Millner hasn't made much headway with certain established
Georgia businesses and political action committees, he's done quite
well with newer, entreprenurial firms, Wade said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of new money out there,'' Wade said. ``The names
of the companies don't register with any of us, but they're making
jillions of dollars and are run by very bright young people. I
think the Republican went after that new money.''
</P>
<P>
   John Stuckey, a former head of the state Republican Party, said
many entreprenurial types lean toward Millner because they don't
want government to create obstacles to their success and
Republicans are generally associated with less intrusive
government.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes, on the other hand, has solid labor support. He also
inherits an advantage in fundraising from PACs and big companies
because those interests ``have been used to Democrats running the
show.''
</P>
<P>
   But that is beginning to change as Republican prospects
brighten, Stuckey added.
</P>
<P>
   Perennial contributors AFLAC, the Columbus insurance giant, and
Synovus, the Columbus bank holding company, gave substantial sums
to both Barnes and Millner.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, A.W. Dahlberg, the CEO of the Southern Co., gave
$1,000 to each, while the energy holding company's law firm,
Troutman Sanders, gave $5,000 to each.
</P>
<P>
   But as a group, attorneys overwhelmingly supported Barnes.
</P>
<P>
   More than one-fourth of the $4 million Barnes raised in the
11-week reporting period ended October 19, came from lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Stuckey said Barnes' $1 million came almost entirely from
plaintiff attorneys, not from regulatory and corporate defense
attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a very distinct break in the bar,'' said Stuckey, a
regulatory attorney who contributed $1,250 to Millner. ``Trial
lawyers are a very well-organized part of the bar and they
traditionally vote Democratic.''
</P>
<P>
   But Barnes has done extensive work as both a plaintiff attorney
and a defense attorney for doctors, and he reported contributions
from prominent corporate lawyers at King &AMP; Spalding: Griffin Bell,
a former U.S. Attorney General, and Sam Nunn, a former U.S.
senator.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
