u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GA-GOVPOLL-COX     10-30 0910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-GOVPOLL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Millner hangs on to narrow lead in race for Georgia governor
 &HT;    By Kathey Pruitt
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Four days before the vote, Republican Guy Millner
clings to a tenuous lead over Democratic rival Roy Barnes in an
ever-tightening race for governor, a new poll for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution/WSB-TV shows.
</P>
<P>
   Millner's 5-point edge over the veteran state legislator is a
milestone for Republicans who have not led at this stage of the
game during their 130 year struggle to win the state's top office _
or at least since political polling began. Millner, the party's
nominee for the past three statewide contests, used it Friday as
further evidence that he will prevail. ``I think we're going to
win,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But by no means does Millner's 45-40 lead over Barnes in the
poll guarantee a victory at the ballot box. The poll showed 11
percent of voters undecided, and how they break on election day
could change the outcome. The narrow margin separating the two
major candidates almost falls within the poll's margin of error, a
fact that had spin machines cranking overtime in both camps to
claim a bump from the results.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trends are on our side, the people are on our side, the
momentum is on our side,'' Barnes said.
</P>
<P>
   Close scrutiny of the numbers may give Barnes good cause for
optimism in a race that promises to be one of the tightest in
Georgia history.
</P>
<P>
   Among the encouraging factors for Democrats is that Mark Taylor,
their nominee for lieutenant governor, surged to a comfortable
13-percent lead in the new poll. The possibility of a solid turnout
among south Georgia Democrats to support their hometown boy _
Taylor is from Albany _ could pump up vote totals for Barnes.
</P>
<P>
   The Mableton attorney, who closed the race by one percent since
the newspaper's last poll, now is picking up almost two-thirds of
the white swing vote, a group that could help decide the
gubernatorial contest, according to the poll. Those voters
generally broke Republican in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Millner still falls short of the 60 percent support he needs
among white voters to win, the poll shows, while Barnes is much
closer to the 40 percent threshold he must cross with white voters
to build a winning coalition.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not for Millner a comfortable lead by any chance,''
said Merle Black, an Emory University political scientist. ``This
looks like everything is virtually dead even.''
</P>
<P>
   The poll of 709 registered likely voters, conducted Oct. 24-28,
has a 4 percentage point margin of error. It tracks with other
polls released in the last few days indicating the contest is a
dead-heat.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last month, Millner shored up his support among voters
below the age of 30, and he continues to do well among Georgians
aged 45-64. Millner's message of tax cuts and government
streamlining may have contributed to his strong appeal among white
males.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not a professional politician, that's the first plus,''
said poll respondent Doug Duncan, a firefighter and emergency
medical technician from Cobb County. ``He's successfully managed a
business, and the governor is an administrator.''
</P>
<P>
   Among women, Millner's support has declined somewhat since the
last poll, despite months of wooing by the Republican. Millner's
favorability rating also dropped during the last month as Barnes
stepped up ads criticizing Millner's business record. During that
same time period, Millner drew a hard-line with commercials
opposing affirmative action, an issue that stirs many women and
minorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Millner doesn't come across well to me,'' said June DeLauder,
a homemaker from Woodstock. ``I don't care for some of the things
he's promoting.''
</P>
<P>
   The poll shows Barnes continuing a lopsided lead among blacks,
traditionally one of the Democrats' strongest voting groups. But
his support level _ six out of 10, according to the newspaper poll
_ is short of the level Democratic candidates have come to expect,
political scientists said.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes and other political watchers raised questions about the
poll's distribution of the black vote. Internal Democratic polls
show Barnes carrying almost 80 percent of the black vote, more
consistent with previous campaigns. That amount gives Barnes a
tentative lead.
</P>
<P>
   Black voters contacted for follow-up interviews said their
support for Barnes is strengthened by Millner's push against
affirmative action. ``I just don't think the Republicans care that
much about blacks,'' said Lillian Reese, a 46-year-old federal
employee from Decatur. ``The only time you see Republicans putting
a black in front of them is if they're running for something.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes also polled well among the over-65 set. Retirees like
Dora Burnett, a former teacher from Marietta, found Barnes'
two-decades experience in the Legislature reassuring. ``Roy is as
solid as dirt,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to Republican projections that metro Atlanta may be a
key to victory, voters in the five metro counties are almost evenly
divided. A final wildcard in the contest may be the presence of
Libertarian Jack Cashin, who polled what may turn out to be a
crucial 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a hard, hard one to pick,'' said James Jolly, a
retired trucker from Henry County. ``Frankly, it's kind of reach in
the hat and pull out one and hope they'll do what they say they'll
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
