</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GINGRICH31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Democrats target Gingrich's role in GOP ads
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _Newt Gingrich became the focus of Democratic
campaigning Friday after published reports that the House speaker
personally approved Republican ads that refer to the Monica
Lewinsky scandal.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans, meanwhile, continued their onslaught of
advertisements in the final days of the campaign, a product of the
GOP's massive financial edge over Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt (D-Mo.) sent Gingrich a
letter Friday saying that his alleged role in approving the ads is
at odds with the speaker's pledge for a bipartisan impeachment
inquiry. ``It is clear that you have forfeited your legitimacy as
speaker,'' Gephardt said.
</P>
<P>
   A Democratic National Committee radio ad released Friday says:
``Newt Gingrich orchestrated these pro-impeachment negative ads. Do
you want another year of investigations or a Congress that works
for you?''
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore also joined the fray by raising the
specter of endless investigations if Republicans do well in
Tuesday's election.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich campaign spokesman Mike Shields denied a report in the
Washington Post that the speaker signed off on or managed the
content of three ads that either explicitly or implicitly invoke
the Clinton sex scandal. ``It's just not true,'' Shields said. ``I
was there when he was told these ads were running. He said, 'That's
nice. They sound effective.' But even though reporters in
Washington don't believe it, he is not involved in the nitty-gritty
of the campaign. To this day, he hasn't seen any of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich campaigned Friday in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic response to Gingrich's alleged involvement in the
ad campaign illustrated the party's last-ditch efforts to make sure
their most loyal supporters go the polls next week. It recalled the
1996 campaign, when Gingrich was the constant target of Democratic
candidates who tried to hang the unpopular speaker around the necks
of their Republican opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, spending $10 million in the last week on behalf of
House candidates nationwide, see in the new ads the ability to
motivate their base.
</P>
<P>
   Other ads that are part of the GOP blitz target specific
candidates on education, taxes and ethics. Republican ads are
running in at least 29 congressional districts, suggesting that GOP
strategists believe the party can pick up six to 12 seats, which
many analysts have said is a reasonable forecast.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
