</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLENN-MEDIA31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Glenn mission may have prompted record media turnout
 &HT;    By Timothy R. Gaffney
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KENNEDY SPACE CENTER, Fla. _ John Glenn's nostalgia-rich return
to space on Thursday prompted possibly the biggest news media
turnout in the history of manned space flight.
</P>
<P>
   About 4,000 news people pre-registered for press credentials
here, and NASA spokesman Bruce Buckingham estimated 3,000 news
people were on the scene by the time Discovery lifted off. TV
trucks and trailers turned the press site's parking lot and part of
a once-grassy field into a high-tech mobile home park.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Apollo 11's launch in 1969 generated 3,497 press
requests, with 2,700 actually covering the launch. The biggest
turnout on record was the first space shuttle launch in 1981, which
drew 2,707 reporters, photographers and support crews, according to
the space agency.
</P>
<P>
   But the 77-year-old space pioneer was not the only reason for
the intense interest by the news media. With Tuesday's election
looming, the press site was awash in politicians, and even
President Clinton flew in to watch Glenn rocket back into orbit.
</P>
<P>
   About 50 Spanish news people covered the launch _ not Glenn's,
but that of Mission Specialist Pedro Duque, who became the first
Spanish citizen to fly in space. Duque is an astronaut for the
European Space Agency, of which Spain is a member.
</P>
<P>
   With Thursday's launch, Duque became to Spain what Glenn was to
the United States when he made his first flight in 1962, said
Consuelo Ortega, a reporter for the national TV service Tele 5 in
Madrid.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very important. He's a hero,'' she said. Besides Spanish
reporters in U.S. bureaus, about 20 came from Spain to cover the
launch, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Shoko Yamamoto, a spokeswoman for the National Space Development
Agency of Japan, said her nation has a heightened interest in the
flight because payload specialist Chiaki Mukai, a medical doctor,
is Japan's first female astronaut. This is her second space flight.
</P>
<P>
   The international nature of this mission spurred the French news
service Agence France-Presse to send its Washington, D.C.-based
science correspondent Guy Clavel to the launch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't come here regularly,'' he said. ``This is exceptional.
The main story is of course Glenn, because he's a unique man. It's
a unique situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn is the overwhelming reason for the intense American news
coverage, from CNN to Lester Gingold, 76-year-old publisher of The
Best Times, a magazine for ``active mature Memphians'' in
Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Gingold said his interest stemmed from ``the fact that a
77-year-old man can go into space and I can vicariously go with
him, and what I believe is the important scientific research in the
field of aging'' that Glenn is to do.
</P>
<P>
   Space launches aren't new to science journalist Andrew Chaikin,
author of A Man on the Moon, a history of the Apollo program.
Chaikin said he watched the last moon mission, Apollo 17, blast off
in December 1972.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he said, he thought this mission was worth witnessing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to be here for the history of it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
