<HEADER>
A6534 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOP-ADS-GEORGIA-COX     10-30 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-ADS-GEORGIA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GOP ad message centered on Clinton scandal offers slim choice
 &HT;    By Bill Osinski
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   VALDOSTA, Ga. _ A late-rounds gut punch of Republican Party
television attack ads seems to have most parties reeling in the
political ring of Georgia's Second Congressional District.
</P>
<P>
   The tactic was as subtle as a Mike Tyson ear nuzzle. The ads,
which capitalize on President Clinton's Monica Lewinsky
relationship, seek to frame Tuesday's election as a referendum with
two choices: ``Reward Bill Clinton for lying, or vote Republican.''
</P>
<P>
   The ad campaign is intended to help the Republican first-time
candidate for Congress, Albany businessman Joe McCormick, unseat
three-term incumbent Democrat Sanford Bishop. This district is the
only one in Georgia that is part of a $10 million GOP campaign in
30 congressional races around the country.
</P>
<P>
   But it's hard to tell who's getting hurt the most in this south
Georgia district.
</P>
<P>
   McCormick sought to distance himself from the ads.
</P>
<P>
   His heavyweight campaign visitor, former Republican presidential
candidate Bob Dole, backed off from negative campaining and
recalled when he'd been hurt 10 years ago by a similar late blow _
one delivered by his Republican opponent, George Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop's corner has so far kept their man above the fray.
</P>
<P>
   And some regular folks in the district appear ready to throw in
the towel on what they see as below-the-belt politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think this is going to get the Republicans anywhere,''
said Charles McCleod, as he breakfasted on ham-and-grits at a
Valdosta diner. McCleod, who described himself as a political
independent who voted for Dole in 1996, said he was unimpressed by
the ads.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people are sick of Clinton, but most people are sick of
this kind of politics,'' he said. ``Especially in this year's race,
people are going to vote for individuals, not national parties.''
</P>
<P>
   At another restaurant, Gigi Taylor, an active Republican, said
that while she subscribed to the message of the ads, she's not sure
how effective they'll be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, I don't think it will change people's votes,''
she said. ``They don't care (about Clinton's sexual scandals). I
care, but a lot of other people don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Highsmith, who said she tends to vote Democratic, said
she was offended by the implication of the ad campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's pathetic and thoughtless,'' she said. The ads may
backfire, she said, generating more interest in the elction among
black voters, who overwhelmingly support Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a bit of hostility out there,'' Highsmith said. ``I
think the American public is intelligent enough to reject all this
negative campaigning.''
</P>
<P>
   Rita Bumgarner, a Democrat who said she is ``trying to forget
Bill Clinton every chance I get,'' added that she nonetheless
separates the president's problems from her vote. And as for the
Republican campaign that has spent millions to try to connect those
elements, she said, ``I think it's outrageous.''
</P>
<P>
   The ads may be effective in some targeted markets, but in south
Georgia, even the intended beneficiary didn't seem too happy about
them.
</P>
<P>
   After a campaign event in Valdosta on Thursday, McCormick said
of the ads, ``Those are things that are being done independently of
this campaign.'' He added that he has sought to keep his campaign
focused on issues that are most important to the people of the
district.
</P>
<P>
   McCormick did not mention Clinton or the ad campaign at the
Thursday event.
</P>
<P>
   Dole spoke out against negative campaigning in general: ``I
don't go around knocking the opponent. And I'm not running around
the country saying the president ought to resign.''
</P>
<P>
   Dole knows too well how it feels to be on the receiving end of a
late-in-the-game blitz of negative ads. During the 1988
presidential primaries, Dole came out a big winner in the Iowa
primary, while then vice president Bush finished a humbling third.
</P>
<P>
   That put everything on the line in the New Hampshire primary. On
the last weekend of that campaign, Bush unleased a barrage of
television ads that claimed Dole would raise their taxes, a threat
that plays at least as dramatically as a sex scandal in New
Hampshire. Bush won, and on election night on national television,
Dole pleaded with voters to ``tell George Bush to stop lying about
my record.'' Dole's anger may have been righteous, but his campaign
was finished.
</P>
<P>
   Selby McCash, Bishop's press aide, said he doesn't think the
late avalanch of Republican ads will have a significant impact on
the Bishop-McCormick race.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far, voters in general haven't transferred blame for
Clinton's behavior to local Democrats,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   McCash noted that his office received only a small number of
angry calls earlier this month, after Bishop voted against the
Republican impeachment inquiry plan. Most people in the Second
District have accepted Bishop's overall credentials as a
conservative, and Republican attempts to slap the liberal label on
him are ``somewhat amusing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
