<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-30 20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6535 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWORLEANS-GUNSUIT-CO     10-30 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWORLEANS-GUNSUIT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New Orleans shoots down gun industry with lawsuit
 &HT;    By Anne Rochell Konigsmark
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ The most famous city in the state that calls
itself the ``Sportsman's Paradise'' declared war on the gun
industry Friday, filing an unprecedented lawsuit against 15 gun
manufacturers, three trade associations and several local
pawnshops.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, filed by New Orleans Mayor Marc Morial, seeks to
recover damage to the city from the gun industry's sale of guns
that are not ``personalized'' with safety devices that would
prevent their use by children and anyone else other than the owner.
It is the first such suit to be brought against the gun industry by
a government.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe the technology exists to make guns smart,'' Morial
said. ``We will not rest until we make New Orleans the safest city
in America.''
</P>
<P>
   There are several safety devices in development. One requires
the shooter to wear a ring embedded with a computer chip that
transmits a message to the gun. Another recognizes the owner's
fingerprints.
</P>
<P>
   The president of the National Shooting Sports Foundation, a
defendant, called the lawsuit ``crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This technology is not yet proven,'' said Bob Delfay. ``They
are suing an industry for not including unproven technology in its
products. I thought it was supposed to be the other way around.''
</P>
<P>
   The suit alleges that guns violate the state's product liability
laws because they are ``unreasonably dangerous,'' lacking safety
features and adequate warning labels. The manufacturers and
distributors of these guns fail to prevent their use by
unauthorized people, the suits says, including children and
criminals who steal the guns and use them in robberies and murders.
</P>
<P>
   Safety devices have been available, the suit alleges, but the
defendants have failed to incorporate them into their products. The
suit specifically attacks semi-automatic weapons, because people
have been killed when they were unaware of a round of ammunition
left in the chamber even after the ammunition magazine has been
removed. Almost one-fourth of the annual 1,500 accidental shooting
deaths in the United State occur because the user didn't know a
round of ammunition was in the gun, according to the General
Accounting Office. Delfay said manufacturers agree guns need to
stay out of the hands of children and unauthorized users, but he
said safety devices aren't the solution. The National Rifle
Association called the lawsuit ``absurd.'' The NRA is promoting
Project Exile, a program in Richmond, Va., that soon will be
duplicated in Philadelphia. The program steps up enforcement of an
existing federal law that imposes a five-year prison sentence on
any felon caught with a gun. Since Richmond began Project Exile 18
months ago, the homicide rate there has decreased 65 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take criminals off the streets and your streets are safer,''
said Bill Powers, an NRA spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   New Orleans Police Chief Richard Pennington, who is credited
with reducing his city's crime rate by 40 percent in four years,
had a quick response to the NRA's suggestion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We already do that,'' he said. ``We do that every day, we just
don't have a fancy name for it.''
</P>
<P>
   The New Orleans police took 2,500 guns off the streets in 1997,
and 1,700 this year, he said.
</P>
<P>
   M. David Gelfand, a professor with the Tulane University School
of Law, said the suit bears a strong ressemblance to the recent
successful suits against the tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``This suit builds upon a pretty well-established body of law
regarding product liability,'' he said. ``And this situation is in
a way even stronger than the tobacco argument. The fact is, there
is a defect: The failure to include easily included devices that
would personalize the gun and make it useable only by the owner.''
</P>
<P>
   However, he said, the city may have a tough time proving the
so-called ``chain of causation.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
