<HEADER>
A6536 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOUTHERN-CONGRESSIONA     10-30 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHERN-CONGRESSIONAL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Democrats hope to reverse stronghold of GOP in South
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUMMIT, Miss. _ Between shouts of praise for Jesus, Delbert
Hosemann delivered a campaign homily that was heavy on Mississippi
values.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our moral compass in Mississippi is straight,'' Hosemann, the
Republican candidate for Congress, told worshipers at the Wednesday
night service at Calvary Apostolic Church in nearby McComb.
</P>
<P>
   There is no mention of President Clinton, but the message is
clear, particularly when coupled with the airing of a new
Republican Party ad that plays on Clinton's initial denial of his
relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   But in Mississippi, so-called family values issues are not the
exclusive province of Republican candidates. Told about Hosemann's
event, Democrat Ronnie Shows said he too spent Wednesday evening in
a Pentecostal church, this one in Natchez, where the animated
pastor invited Shows to follow him around the sanctuary. ``I
believe we'll do real well in the Pentecostal churches,'' Shows
said.
</P>
<P>
   The nip-and-tuck race in Mississippi's 4th Congressional
District and the campaign in the neighboring 6th district of
Lousiana offer Democrats rare opportunities to pick up
congressional seats in the South with candidates who defy easy
labels.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that Republicans aren't trying, armed with a flood of
money from national GOP organizations and well-worn tactics. Shows
is soft on crime, supportive of gun control and prone to raise
taxes, according to the GOP ads.
</P>
<P>
   In Louisiana, ads on Baton Rouge television stations call
Democrat Marjorie McKeithen a ``liberal'' and Republican Rep.
Richard Baker, a 12-year incumbent, a ``conservative.''
</P>
<P>
   Voters in both districts scoffed at the negative ads (although
Shows has not aired any attack ads). But political analysts and
campaign officials credit those ads with making the races closer
than they otherwise would have been.
</P>
<P>
   African-Americans make up 40 percent of the Mississippi district
and 30 percent of the one in Louisiana. Highlighting the importance
of black turnout to the Democratic Party, pleas from Rep. John
Lewis (D-Ga.) and other black politicians are airing on Baton
Rouge's black radio stations.
</P>
<P>
   The Louisiana campaign is typical of the state's colorful
politics.
</P>
<P>
   McKeithen, a 32-year-old attorney in her first campaign, is the
daughter of Republican Secretary of State Fox McKeithen and
granddaughter of former Gov. John McKeithen.
</P>
<P>
   Family features prominently in her campaign, which got an
initial boost from the familiarity of voters with the McKeithen
name.
</P>
<P>
   A anti-abortion Democrat who spoke of the importance of
``Christian morals'' at a recent forum, McKeithen has kept the
incumbent on the defensive through much of the campaign by raising
questions about Baker's ethics, including an allegation that he
used political influence to obtain a scholarship for his daughter
to attend Tulane University. Baker has denied any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   The effectiveness of McKeithen's attacks prompted Rep. John
Linder (R-Ga.), chairman of the National Republican Congressional
Committee, to label Baker, 50, his top concern among incumbent
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Now, negative ads from both sides fill the airwaves. Recent
salvos from Baker hit McKeithen for not voting in some elections
and hiding the source of her income. She has apoloigized for
missing some votes and released a list of clients.
</P>
<P>
   John Maginnis, editor of a political newsletter in Baton Rouge,
said Baker may still have an edge. ``I'm not sure she is
penetrating beyond the chronic voter,'' Maginnis said. ``Do black
voters have a real reason to go vote? I'm not sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats are spending heavily to mobilize their voters, but
must contend with several wild cards that include the possible
indictment of former Democratic Gov. Edwin Edwards and the weather.
</P>
<P>
   Bad weather typically depresses vote totals, and Republicans
generally do better when only the most determined partisans make it
to the polls.
</P>
<P>
   Weather and poor turnout also are concerns of Mississippi
Democrats, who hope to take back the seat they held until Rep. Mike
Parker left the Democratic Party for the GOP in 1995. Parker is
retiring.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike McKeithen, Shows is on the receiving end of an onslaught
of negative ads. His campaign grew so worried about Hosemann's
charge that Shows favors gun control that Shows's father, a World
War II veteran, recorded a radio ad refuting the Republican's
assertion.
</P>
<P>
   Shows, 51, an elected state transportation official, asked for
support Thursday from students at Summit's Southwest Mississippi
Community College by noting that his opposition to abortion rights
and gun control ``kind of go against the grain of the national
Democratic Party.''
</P>
<P>
   His populist campaign is aimed at depicting Hosemann as a
wealthy Jackson tax attorney who is out of touch with Shows' native
rural Mississippi. ``I do live in the country; my opponent does
not,'' he told a Western civilization class.
</P>
<P>
   Hosemann, wearing khakis and an open-collared shirt in the
Pentecostal church, also is seeking to cultivate a down-home image,
even though he has spent more than $100,000 of his own money on the
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The church's pastor, the Rev. Steve Hancock, introduced him as a
lawyer who has not worked ``to spring criminals out of deserved
lengthy sentences, but who has instead promoted a fair and
equitable system for small businesses and citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   The national Republican ad that asks viewers to vote Republican
as a counterweight to Clinton might be expected to resonate among
this region's conservative church-goers. But, in dozens of
interviews in Louisiana and southern Mississippi, the predominant
view of the Clinton sex scandal from Republicans and Democrats was
that voters would not make Democratic candidates atone for
Clinton's sins.
</P>
<P>
   Gloria Stockton, a cashier in the community college cafeteria,
condemned Clinton's behavior and the Republican-led impeachment
inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he did was wrong,'' Stockton said. ``But this is a witch
hunt.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
