A6537 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MORTGAGE-PENNER-PROFI     10-30 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORTGAGE-PENNER-PROFILE-ART-$ADV01-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIDETRACKING THE LOCOMOTIVE OF CAPITAL AMERICA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., N.Y.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(For release Sunday, Nov. 1) 
(af) 
 By LAURA M. HOLSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Are you going to write that I'm an arrogant guy?'' the real
estate financier Ethan Penner asked a reporter, calling from his
car phone one afternoon in mid-October. ``I mean if you ask a lot
of my close friends, they'll tell you I'm not arrogant at all. It's
just when someone meets me for the first time that they think
that.''
</P>
<P>
   It was an interesting comment from a man who complained in 1988
that Morgan Stanley had shortchanged him by paying a $550,000 bonus
he had agreed to, instead of the $750,000 to $1 million he thought
he deserved. ``I was grossly underpaid,'' Penner still contends. Or
from a man who was taunted by colleagues at his first job, at a
savings and loan in Orange County, Calif., after boasting that he
could parlay his $12,000-a-year desk post into a $100,000 executive
suite within a year. (He didn't make it.)
</P>
<P>
   But Penner's outsized ambition _ pressed, he acknowledges he is
``borderline arrogant'' _ has colored his career.
</P>
<P>
   He popularized commercial real estate lending on Wall Street,
joining the American brokerage unit of Nomura Securities in 1993
and transforming it into an industry giant. But as quickly as the
markets shifted, so did his fortunes. He resigned in September amid
huge losses at the Capital Company of America, the subsidiary he
ran.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a corporate politician,'' Penner said in defense of
his tenure there. ``Every business has its ups and downs.
Politicians manage both, so when the down cycle comes they can live
for another day. That's never been my style.''
</P>
<P>
   Penner, though, will live for another day, too: his almost six
years at Nomura made him rich. He easily earned $125 million over
all at Nomura, doling out $32 billion in commercial loans. To add
to that Nomura gave him an additional $30 million upon walking out
the door _ an exchange for half of the 10 percent in Capital
America shares he has rights to.
</P>
<P>
   Penner can, at times, be charming, surrounding himself with
influential friends. Asked to name a few, he produced a list of 27
names, including A. Alfred Taubman, chairman of Sotheby's Holdings,
and the Knicks star Walt Frazier.
</P>
<P>
   One of those, Steve Scheer, a producer with CBS Sports, grew up
with Penner in Yonkers and has known him 30 years. When Scheer
broke his arm playing basketball as a teen-ager, Penner drove him
to the doctor. ``I know that if anything ever happened to me, my
wife and child would be taken care of,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Penner's troubles with Nomura date back to April 1997. That, he
said, is when he confronted top executives at Nomura Holding
America, the company's United States brokerage unit, and threatened
to quit if the business he ran was not turned into a subsidiary, of
which he would be a part owner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had an investor who would back me,'' he said, adding that it
would be foolish ``not to let Nomura match that.'' His bosses did
not see the matter so benignly. ``They thought they had a gun to
their head,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nomura acquiesced _ the lending business was a cash cow _ but it
drafted more than 25 pages of terms, including a limit of $500
million in equity capitalization for the new subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   It took 14 months to negotiate the spinoff. At that point,
Penner told his bosses that he needed $700 million in equity
capital. Nomura balked, by Penner's own account. (A spokesman for
Nomura said the company would not discuss Penner's employment.)
</P>
<P>
   ``They said, `Here are the documents,' '' Penner recalled,
describing a meeting in New York on June 29. `` `If you don't
shrink the equity capitalization to $500 million by January of
1999, you lose your job. If you don't sign, then you don't get the
spinoff.' ''
</P>
<P>
   He signed, becoming chief executive of Capital America. But he
still continued to seek outside financing and in mid-July arranged
for executives of Cerberus Partners, a New York-based private
investment fund, to fly to his office in San Francisco to examine
the subsidiary's books, Penner said. Cerberus would not comment.
Still, Nomura executives back in New York did not want a partner.
</P>
<P>
   As it became increasingly clear to Penner that he would be
ousted if he failed to meet Nomura's terms, he began to negotiate
his exit. He gave up management responsibility for the Capital
Company of America, becoming vice chairman in mid-August.
</P>
<P>
   His timing was uncanny; within days, the commercial
mortgage-backed securities market collapsed. On Sept. 17, he was
out for good. A month later, Nomura announced a $1.16 billion loss
for the six months ended Sept. 30, attributing most of the deficit
to losses in its mortgage-backed securities business.
</P>
<P>
   In August, the final words playing over the loudspeaker at the
last big party Penner threw for investors was ``It's the End of the
World as We Know It'' by rock band R.E.M. Maybe the band knew
something Penner didn't.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
