<SLUG> BC-DIPLOMAT-DENY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ex-ambassador to Eritrea denies he was fired
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ John F. Hicks, former U.S. ambassador to Eritrea,
denied Friday that President Clinton fired him last year after
complaints from two embassy employees that Hicks made improper
sexual advances.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington Times reported that Clinton fired Hicks, who was
named ambassador in May of 1996, while the president was involved
in what he has called an inappropriate relationship with former
White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, there is no truth to the statement that Mr.
Hicks was fired by President Clinton or anybody else,'' according
to a statement Friday from Kalijarvi, Chuzi &AMP; Newman, the
Washington law firm representing Hicks. ``He resigned from the
State Department for personal reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   Contacted at home in Silver Spring, Md., Jacqueline Hicks
declined comment. She said her husband, a career member of the
Foreign Service who grew up in Goldsboro, N.C., was not available.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper quoted the State Department's inspector general as
concluding that ``Ambassador Hicks' behavior was both severe and
pervasive in creating a hostile work environment for these women.
It was unwelcomed, repeated, unsolicited and clearly of a sexual
nature.''
</P>
<P>
   Presidential press secretary Joe Lockhart said the inspector
general transmitted a report on the case to Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright in August 1997. Hicks resigned three weeks
later.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Hicks denied the allegations and was prepared to
vigorously defend himself at an administrative hearing,'' according
to the statement from his lawyers. ``However, Ambassador Hicks
decided to pursue employment opportunities in the private sector
rather than having his family go through the personal indignities
and legal expenses that would result from him defending himself
against these baseless accusations.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that point, Ambassador Hicks resigned,'' the statement
said. ``His desire then and now is to close this matter and move on
with his life.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
