<HEADLINE>
ACTOR TOMMY LEE JONES SCRAPED, BRUISED AFTER FALL FROM POLO PONY 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RUTH SoRELLE 
and T.J. MILLING 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Academy Award-winning actor Tommy Lee Jones, scraped
and bruised in a fall from a polo pony, was airlifted to Hermann
Hospital Friday afternoon from a ranch in San Felipe, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's doing quite well,'' said Dr. Drue N. Ware, in a taciturn
description of the 52-year-old actor's injuries. ``He has multiple
contusions but no neurologic impairment.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Jones had suffered some bruises, a few scrapes and may
have even lost consciousness briefly after falling from his horse
about 2 p.m. Ware said Jones would stay in the hospital overnight
and might be released Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The actor underwent a physical examination and several X-rays to
determine the extent of his injuries, Ware said.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, an avid polo player, was competing in a match at Estancia
Del Pueblo Viejo, a private polo club about 45 miles west of
Houston. His horse was galloping downfield when it stumbled,
throwing Jones in front of it and stepping on him, his publicist,
Jennifer Allen, said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's doing great,'' Allen said. ``He took a fall, but he's
fine. His quote was, `I'm not hurt, just a little sore.' ``
</P>
<P>
   Jones, a San Saba native, had finished work in Louisiana on
Monday on the film ``Double Jeopardy,'' scheduled for release next
fall. Allen said polo is the actor's main off-camera pursuit and he
raises polo ponies on his San Saba ranch, which overlooks the San
Saba Polo Club. He also is featured on the cover of the
September-October issue of Polo Magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's his passion,'' she said. ``It's his life.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who won the Oscar for best supporting actor in ``The
Fugitive,'' was treated by a private ambulance at the polo grounds
until Life Flight helicopter arrived. The helicopter carrying Jones
landed at Hermann at 2:53 p.m., and Ware began assessing the
injuries soon after.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, during a riding competition, actor Christopher Reeve
was thrown from his horse and suffered a spinal cord injury that
paralyzed him from the neck down. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
