u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLENN-MISSION-HNS &LR;      10-30 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLENN-MISSION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLENN GETS HIGH MARKS FROM SHUTTLE COLLEAGUES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Glenn, the world's oldest astronaut, received high marks
Friday from his colleagues for his first 24 hours aboard the
orbiting shuttle Discovery.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's doing very, very well,'' said Dave Williams, NASA's
director of life sciences research at the Johnson Space Center.
</P>
<P>
   The bespectacled 77-year-old, who more than 36 years ago became
the first American to orbit the Earth, proved a harsher critic.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a lot of problems like eating food,'' confessed
Glenn, who on Feb. 20, 1962, remained strapped in the seat of his
tiny Mercury capsule and unable to float around during his near
five-hour flight. ``If it gets away from you, it gets on
everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Most astronauts would have been much too proud to reveal what
Glenn disclosed next: ``Like this morning. I had some oatmeal and
raisins. One little speck wound up on my glasses,'' said Glenn. ``I
guess with old folks you normally think it falls down on an old
man's necktie, but this time it wound up on my glasses.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn is one of seven astronauts who blasted off Thursday aboard
Discovery for nine days of research, including a series of
experiments that will compare how young and elderly astronauts
adapt to the rigors of spaceflight.
</P>
<P>
   During several minutes of televised discussion with mission
control, Glenn's neck and face appeared puffy, a response to the
absence of gravity in which the bodily fluids migrate from the
lower torso to the chest and head.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yesterday, everyone was puffy faced around here and looked
like the Poppin' Fresh Doughboy,'' Glenn noted. ``I guess I'm still
a little round faced today. That is something I understand goes
away in a couple of days.''
</P>
<P>
   More than half of astronauts, according to past medical studies,
also experience a queasiness because their nervous systems are
disoriented by the absence of gravity. The adjustment takes about
three days, and the shuttle is equipped with anti-nausea
medications.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fortunately, the crew up here has felt fine this time,'' said
Glenn, not entirely ruling out he may have experienced some of the
discomfort.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Glenn has focused most of his attention on medical
experiments, downing a vitamin pill-sized, miniature thermometer
with a tiny radio transmitter. During the two to three days the
pill remains in his digestive tract, the pill signals a recording
device clipped to his waist of changes in his core body
temperature, one of the protocols for a sleep experiment he is
participating in.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went right to work,'' said Discovery commander Curt Brown,
ticking off a list of first day accomplishments that included a
minor repair to a leaky water line and the deployment of a small
experimental communications satellite built by students at the
Naval Postgraduate School in Monterrey, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've stayed pretty much on the time line with a few hiccups
here and there.''
</P>
<P>
   There was time for a moment of nostalgia for Glenn as he spotted
the city lights of Perth, Australia from Discovery, just as he did
during his Mercury flight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks even brighter now then it did back then,'' said
Glenn. ``They really got it lit up tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks beautiful,'' he added. ``Please pass that along to
the people of Perth. We send our best regards.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1962, the lights of Perth symbolized the far-flung support
for Glenn's endeavor at a time when the United States was locked in
a Cold War-era race to the moon with the former Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, NASA confirmed that an 18-by-22-inch panel covering
the drag chute compartment on Discovery's tail section broke loose
moments before Thursday's liftoff from the Kennedy Space Center.
</P>
<P>
   Though an assessment of potential safety hazards is under way by
ground-based shuttle engineers, it appears the biggest threat
occurred during the lift off when the falling panel struck one of
Discovery's rocket nozzles, said NASA's Jeff Bantle, the mission
operations director.
</P>
<P>
   Bantle said the drag chute that helps to brake the shuttle when
it lands will not be used when Discovery returns to Earth on Nov.
7.
</P>
<P>
   The missing panel is situated on an area of the spacecraft that
does not experience high temperatures during the shuttle's re-entry
through the atmosphere, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Engineers believe it is possible the aluminum cover plate was
improperly installed before the flight and rattled free because of
the vibration of the igniting rocket engines. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
