<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HILLARY-DEMOCRATS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST LADY: A CAMPAIGN ROAD WARRIOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ Hillary Rodham Clinton, a one-woman
campaign machine, is on the road and on a roll.
</P>
<P>
   As the election-day clock ticks down and she crisscrosses the
country one more time, the first lady has a single-minded mission:
To help Democrats pick up seats in the US House, hold down losses
in the Senate, win a few more governorships, and, not incidentally,
remind the nation it needs President Clinton as much as he needs
her.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's crusade, with stops in New York, Florida,
California, New Jersey, Iowa, Illinois, Minnesota, Pennsylvania,
and Ohio over this last week of campaigning, feels more like a
victory tour than a get-out-the-vote drive.
</P>
<P>
   All 5,000 tickets to the Democratic rally she headlined here
Thursday were snapped up in a day. Admirers, some who came from as
far as Miami, packed the convention center and waved ``Hillary for
President'' signs. The mostly female crowd interrupted the first
lady's impassioned stump speech a dozen times with cheers,
applause, and standing ovations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Show her some love tonight, show her some love!'' bellowed
Representative Corrine Brown of Jacksonville, who introduced Mrs.
Clinton with a mix of sympathy and affection many have felt for her
in the humiliations of the last few months. ``Show her how we
appreciate her and the things she does for this country, especially
for women and children.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown, a three-term lawmaker and the first African-American
since Reconstruction to hold a House seat from Florida, is in a
competitive race with a better-financed Republican. She begged Mrs.
Clinton to come into her district and whip up Democratic voters.
``It's a victory for us just getting her here,'' said Gretchen
Hitchner, Brown's spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Brown was one of the lucky ones. According to Melanne
Verveer, Mrs. Clinton's chief of staff, the first lady has had many
more requests for appearances than she can fulfill, even though she
has campaigned this season in nearly 20 states for scores of local
and statewide candidates, raised millions of dollars, and done
almost 100 radio ads for Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's exhausting, but the first lady is very committed to the
issues and believes there is nothing so rewarding as doing what she
is doing,'' Verveer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Energized'' is the word used most to describe her, and indeed,
there's been something stirring in Mrs. Clinton in October that was
clearly missing, maybe even lost, back in the low days of August.
Politicking on issues she loves, like education and child care, and
against the GOP she despises, Mrs. Clinton is radiant, zestful,
funny, and combative. Nobody even ventures to ask anymore how much
it hurts that her husband had a 16-month affair with a White House
intern and lied about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's got to be really hard for her,'' said Sherron Kenski, an
elementary school principal in Jacksonville whose only reason for
attending the Democratic rally was to see Mrs. Clinton. ``She's got
a lot of class, and by standing by her husband instead of leaving
him, she shows that two wrongs don't make a right. I admire that.''
</P>
<P>
   Swanee Hunt, the former US ambassador to Austria and a longtime
acquaintance of the first lady, attended a recent fund-raiser with
her at the Brookline home of Democratic activist Elaine Schuster
and said she had never seen Mrs. Clinton more relaxed.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I could think was, she has nothing to fear, no more
skeletons can come dancing out of the closet,'' said Hunt, director
of the Women and Public Policy program at Harvard's John F. Kennedy
School. ``There is no question that she feels absolutely stabbed,
but she has this inner strength that allows her to keep her eye on
the ball and carry on.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats are delighted that the first lady, who was badly
discredited for pushing too hard on health care reform in Clinton's
first term, is now the party's deadliest weapon against Republicans
and her husband's most precious political asset. Polls show that
she is more popular than the president _ her approval rating is 63
percent while his is 54, according to a recent USA Today/CNN/Gallup
poll _ and 72 percent of Americans believe she has shown courage.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has been incredibly helpful in talking about issues and
rallying the Democratic faithful to get out and vote,'' said Olivia
Morgan of the Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee. Poll
watchers noted that in Rhode Island, Democratic candidate Myrth
York pulled even with incumbent GOP Governor Lincoln Almond after a
visit earlier this month from Mrs. Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Crawford, Morgan's Republican counterpart, says there is
``no question'' Mrs. Clinton is an effective campaigner, partly
because people feel sorry for her, partly because she has no choice
but to stand in for her husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the president's scandal, the first lady becomes all the
more important to Democrats, because his utility on the stump is
quite limited,'' Crawford said. ``For some reason, she doesn't seem
to carry the same baggage he does.''
</P>
<P>
   Normally the president would play a large role in the midterm
elections, but Clinton avoids campaigning for candidates who are
not sure if a visit would hurt or help. Mostly he has been assigned
to large, private Democratic Party events safe from hecklers and
the press, surrounded by his most stalwart defenders, and on stage
with Senate candidates who really need the big money he can raise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hillary Clinton is the public face of the White House in this
campaign, and it's a smart strategy for the Democrats,'' said
Sherry Bebitch Jeffe, a political analyst in Los Angeles. ``There
is a great deal of sympathy for her, and she can energize women.
It's also important that she is visible because it reinforces the
notion that she has forgiven her husband, and the country should
get over it and move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton has also made the practical calculation that the
more Democrats elected to the House and saved in the Senate, the
fewer Republican votes there would be for impeaching the president.
She has made a herculean effort to help Representative Charles
Schumer of New York defeat GOP Senator Alfonse D'Amato, who chaired
the Whitewater hearings, and she did a rousing rally in Rhode
Island for Democratic Representative Patrick Kennedy, who has been
one of her husband's most vocal allies.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, she has appeared with Democrats Scott
Harshbarger, &UR;  &LR; John Tierney, James McGovern, and Michael Capuano,
among others.
</P>
<P>
   ``Talk to every person you know _ call them on the phone, e-mail
them on your computer, stop them on the street _ and tell them this
in no ordinary time, no ordinary election,'' Mrs. Clinton said at
the Jacksonville rally. ``The next Congress will decide the future
of Social Security, the future of Medicare, the future of the
minimum wage, the future of public education, the future of health
care.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that doesn't matter to you, then I don't know what does
matter, because these are the issues that will affect how you live
and how your families live,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   There was nothing in her speech about impeachment, Monica S.
Lewinsky, a right-wing conspiracy, or her relationship with her
husband. She talked about her husband's policy initiatives and good
works but not about his personal healing process. She criticized
Republicans repeatedly for misguided policies and being captives to
special interests, but only once did she refer to them as ``people
who want to spend time tearing others down.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond her remarks, no one gets a chance to question Mrs.
Clinton, who turned 51 on Monday. Her appearances are tightly
controlled, the press is kept penned up a good distance away, and
no reporters are allowed to travel on her plane or meet her at the
airport.
</P>
<P>
   It is doubtful she even saw the handful of protesters outside
the convention center who carried signs saying, ``Impeach the
Clintons,'' ``Monicagate,'' and ``Hillary is a hypocrite.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She goes around saying she is for children, but what kind of
message is she sending to our daughters when she stays with a
philandering husband?'' said Jeanne MacDonald, a Jacksonville
homemaker. ``What she cares about is her own political career, but
I think she's a coward. She's not getting my vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Harvard's Swanee Hunt doubts this is the first lady's audition
for a campaign of her own. With her political savvy, experience,
and connections, Hunt speculated, Mrs. Clinton someday will be ``a
headhunter's dream.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
