<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-30 20:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6581 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOVERNORS-ROUNDUP-BOS     10-30 1274
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOVERNORS-ROUNDUP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP APPEARS TO HOLD ADVANTAGE IN RACES   FOR GOVERNOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ His great-grandfather was president of the
United States, his grandfather and father senators. And now,
Republican Robert Taft, heir to the nation's most enduring
political dynasty, has made some history of his own, becoming the
first candidate in Ohio ordered to remove an advertisement from the
airwaves because it contains intentional lies.
</P>
<P>
   With that, the race for governor here has descended into
name-calling and smears, notable for its breathtaking avoidance of
substantive issues and its singular devotion to roundhouse negative
ads.
</P>
<P>
   ``You lie, you lose,'' the latest televised spot for Democratic
gubernatorial candidate Lee Fisher, blares across the television
airwaves. In an immediate counter attack, a Taft ad declares:
``Lie. Lose. Lee.''
</P>
<P>
   Such recess-time rhetoric has become commonplace across the
nation, as the autumn campaign limps toward its finish Tuesday. As
much of the public attention is focused on the races for the House
and Senate, 36 governorships are on the line, with Republicans
appearing to hold an advantage in virtually every large state but
California.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, in Ohio, in states from the East Coast to the
West Coast, gubernatorial candidates are raising record amounts of
money, then pouring the cash into expensive negative TV
commercials, all contributing to voter apathy and even antipathy.
</P>
<P>
   In Ohio, for example, polls show that nearly 33 percent of the
electorate has yet to decide how to vote in the governor's race
with less than a week to go _ a figure that has only spurred the
two candidates to intensify their attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Void of Washington-based issues such as Monica S. Lewinsky,
gubernatorial candidates are simply focusing on each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``The campaigns have kind of degenerated, as they often do, to
negative advertising,'' said Governor Howard Dean of Vermont, a
Democrat without serious opposition this year. ``The more money the
candidates have, the less they pay attention to issues. They just
throw the junk on TV.''
</P>
<P>
   While the rhetoric is small-bore, the stakes are anything but.
As crucial as the Congress is to the national psyche, it is in the
50 state capitals that much of day-to-day government is done, on
issues ranging from implementing welfare reform to funding new
education programs.
</P>
<P>
   As an added incentive, the party that captures the governorships
in the largest states will inherit a significant tactical advantage
in the 2000 presidential campaign, providing a massive, ready-made
political organization to launch a candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governors are extremely influential,'' said Clinton Key,
executive director of the Republican Governors Association in
Washington. ``The difference between them and Congress is the
governors run things. They run states. And they are in the home
state on a daily basis, having direct contact with local leaders.
When you're running for president and you have a governor's
support, he can do a lot for you, from raising money to introducing
you to the people you need to know.''
</P>
<P>
   As it stands now, Republicans are in danger of relinquishing
their 16-year reign in California, as state attorney general Dan
Lungren, the GOP candidate, trails Democratic Lieutenant Governor
Gray Davis by a handful of percentage points in several recent
polls.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans are in position to maintain their hold on the
next seven largest states _ Texas, New York, Florida, Pennsylvania,
Illinois, Ohio, and Michigan. In New Jersey, the nation's ninth
largest state, Republican Governor Christine Todd Whitman does not
face reelection. In the 10th most populous state, Georgia, the open
race between Republican businessman Guy Millner and Democratic
state Representative Roy Barnes is too close to call, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   Across the nation, political namesakes have emerged or enhanced
their image. In Texas, Republican Governor George W. Bush, son of
the former president, has picked up endorsements from state
Democratic officials and could defeat his opponent, Land
Commissioner Garry Mauro, by 40 percentage points or more.
</P>
<P>
   In Florida, Jeb Bush, George W.'s brother, is making his second
bid for the governorship and holds a wavering lead over Democratic
Lieutenant Governor Buddy MacKay.
</P>
<P>
   In Minnesota, Democratic Attorney General Skip Humphrey, son of
the late senator, holds a statistically insignificant one-point
lead over St. Paul Mayor Norm Coleman in a poll released this week.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans currently hold 24 of the 36 governorships now
contested, and party officials predict a gain of two or three.
Democrats believe they will pick up three or four states and are
especially buoyed by their prospects in California. Victory there
would significantly undercut the GOP boast that 75 percent of
Americans are governed by a Republican governor.
</P>
<P>
   In California, Lungren has run a universally derided campaign,
wrapping himself in the Reagan legacy, continuing to be outspoken
in his opposition to abortion rights, and thumping the fading issue
of crime. Davis, as politically colorless as his first name
implies, has forged his lead with straightforward constituent
politics learned from years of political campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ``There seems to be a tide running for Davis,'' said Merv Field,
the head of the Field Poll in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   In Maryland, where polls show a tight race, incumbent Democratic
Governor Parris Glendening has launched a new negative advertising
campaign with the help of President Clinton. In the radio ads,
Clinton attacks Republican Ellen R. Sauerbrey's civil rights
record, specifically taking her to task for a 1992 vote in the
Maryland General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Ohio, residents appear to have long ago abandoned the
possibility of a good campaign, or even a fair one. Two weeks ago,
in an unprecedented move, the Ohio Elections Commission ordered
Taft to pull a negative ad off the airwaves because it contained
lies about Fisher's crimefighting record and personnel cutbacks
when he served as attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Taft has lashed out at Fisher for lies about the
Republican's stand on property-tax cuts. Fisher has appeared
reenergized and accused Taft of being a liar at every turn.
</P>
<P>
   Polls vary widely, with one showing a 16-point Taft lead and
another showing just a four-point edge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We teach our children to tell the truth,'' Fisher said at a
debate Wednesday night. ``The bottom line here is that Mr. Taft has
engaged in a very negative and deceitful campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview after the debate, Fisher added, ``Mr. Taft is a
candidate who blames other people and doesn't take
responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, and even after a long one, Taft, the secretary
of state and great-grandson of President William Howard Taft,
appears an unlikely target for such criticism. At 56, he seems as
bland as an Ohio winter. He talks in slow, short spurts, as if
reading from a children's book and constantly needing to turn the
page.
</P>
<P>
   In the debate, he agreed with Fisher on the need for better
school safety, better protection for patients against insurance
companies and HMOs, better education funding, and tax relief.
</P>
<P>
   About the ads, he said: ``I value my family's reputation for
integrity and my reputation for integrity. I think Lee Fisher and I
both share some of the responsibility for those negative ads. ...
The test of leadership is not whether you make mistakes; it's
whether you own up to them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
