<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-30 20:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6586 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TURNOUT-DEMOCRATS-BOS     10-30 1072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURNOUT-DEMOCRATS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS SEEK TO GALVANIZE BLACK VOTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ The Democratic Party, in a last-ditch effort
to increase black voter turnout, is making Tuesday's election a
referendum on the impeachment of President Clinton in some close
congressional races that could be decided by black voters.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats are undertaking an unprecedented effort to galvanize
black voters, whose support for Clinton has been unwavering, even
through the Monica S. Lewinsky scandal, but who are less likely to
vote in a non-presidential election year.
</P>
<P>
   With projections of a low turnout, Democrats have seized the
opportunity Republicans recently handed them to nationalize the
election on the sex-scandal issue, using it to energize their base,
especially among blacks.
</P>
<P>
   This midterm election ``is about as presidential as you can get
without having the actual Clinton name on the ballot,'' said
Representative Charles B. Rangel, a New York Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Rangel said Republicans, who in some districts have started
airing three ads connecting Democratic candidates to Clinton's lies
in the Lewinsky matter, gave Democrats a gift. ``Why in God's name
they want to bring it up again, I don't know,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And with new reports of House Speaker Newt Gingrich's
involvement in preparing the ads, Rangel and other congressional
Democrats have pounced on the speaker's unpopularity among blacks
to try to trigger a backlash against Republicans at the polls.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich spokeswoman Christina Martin Friday told Reuters Friday
that the ads are accurate, but that reports of the speaker's
involvement are not. ``Newt Gingrich was aware but not involved in
either the scripting or the execution of these ads,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   At a kickoff here Thursday for a three-day, five-city bus trip
called ``Take Back the House _ Get Out the Vote,'' several
Congressional Black Caucus members railed against Gingrich, saying
he is trying to suppress the black vote by focusing on the sex
scandal and trying to bring down Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're talking about Gingrich, you ain't talking about
fairness,'' Rangel, clutching a baseball bat, told a small crowd at
the entrance of the Louisville Slugger Museum.
</P>
<P>
   Representative John Conyers of Michigan, the ranking Democrat on
the House Judiciary Committee that will hold impeachment hearings
against Clinton next month, said there is a ``very sinister thing
going on in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When Newt Gingrich reaches the level of lowness in which he
would invoke'' the impeachment statue ``to get his goal of taking
over the White House and driving out both President Clinton and
Vice President Al Gore, make no mistake, this is politicaly
motivated,'' Conyers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a crisis on hand,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the 1994 midterm election, the Democratic Party is going
all out this year to take advantage of Clinton's popularity among
blacks to boost turnout. The party has poured thousands of dollars
into get-out-the-vote ads on black radio stations, some featuring
Clinton and first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton. On Sunday, the
president will appear at a black church in Baltimore at the
invitation of Representative Elijah Cummings, a member of the black
caucus.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee is distributing
fliers in black communities that feature a sour-faced Gingrich with
the words: ``Newt Gingrich and his Republican friends don't want
you to vote on Tuesday, November 3rd. Stand up and prove them
wrong!''
</P>
<P>
   ``What's crucial for Democratic success in a number of critical
districts is turning out the African-American voter, and one way to
do that is to remind those communities of what's at stake,'' said
Olivia Morgan, spokeswoman for the campaign committee.
</P>
<P>
   In places like Kentucky's 3rd Congressional District, where
Democratic candidate Chris Gorman, a former state attorney general,
is in a statistical dead heat in his bid to unseat incumbent
Republican Representative Anne M. Northup, African-American votes
are considered crucial.
</P>
<P>
   The district is one of 30 that Democrats have targeted to
increase black voter turnout. In 1994, black turnout was 37.1
percent compared with 47.3 percent for whites. It rose in 1996, a
presidential election year, to 50.6 percent, while white turnout
climbed to 56 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The African-American vote is 18 percent in this district, and
it's incredibly important we make sure we have a strong get-out-the
vote effort,'' Gorman said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   He has appealed to black voters by critizing Northup for voting
in favor of the Republicans' open-ended impeachment inquiry. ``We
do not need to spend the next two years in this Congress
investigating our president's sex life,'' he said the other day,
garnering applause from his largely black audience.
</P>
<P>
   While Democrats also need to motivate their base of women and
senior citizens, the black vote is an easier target because it
tends to be concentrated in the cities, said David Bositis, a
senior policy analyst at the Joint Center for Political and
Economic Studies, a black think tank in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Courtney Russell, a black 30-year-old stagehand in Louisville,
said during a lunch break that he was distressed by Republicans and
Democrats ``bad-mouthing each other so much you don't know who to
vote for.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, he has concluded that Republicans are ``making a
mountain out of a molehill'' with the Clinton scandal, and he plans
to vote to ``make my voice heard.''
</P>
<P>
   Bennie J. Smith, a black musician who is a renegade candidate
for mayor here, said: ``Everybody is tired of the negative
campaigning,'' which he predicted would motivate some people to go
to the polls.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis Gans, director of the nonpartisan Committee for the Study
of the American Electorate, said Republicans at the last minute
injected an issue of national consequence into what had been an
election based on local issues. The GOP move is a ``wild card''
with an unpredictable outcome, he said.
</P>
<P>
   While Democrats may succeed in getting out the black vote, their
ballots could be offset by an energized religious right.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is each party is going to try to maximize the vote
from the various constituency groups,'' Gans said. ``And victory
will have a lot of authors and defeat will be an orphan.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
