<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-30 20:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6595 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-BRIEFS-$ADV01-NYT     10-30 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-BRIEFS-$ADV01-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS NEWS ITEMS ON PEOPLE AND PERSONALITIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Mass)  (For release Sunday, Nov. 1) 
(af) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Charles K. Gifford, chief executive of BankBoston, loves to
escape to Nantucket, with its cobblestone streets and calm harbors.
Or at least he used to.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, he has been getting an earful from the locals about the
service they have been getting at the venerable Pacific National
Bank since it was acquired by BankBoston late last year. A
chastened Gifford apologized in an interview in Nantucket's
Inquirer and Mirror newspaper in September, saying the acquisition
``didn't live up to my expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   The mea culpa, however, didn't placate Steve Bender, owner of
Fishers Fiddle Catering, who switched to a rival bank. ``The
changeover was sloppy,'' he said. ``They sent out a user-unfriendly
brochure with all the new fees.''
</P>
<P>
   Gifford says the complaints are getting to him. ``Do I like to
go to the market and have somebody come up and tell me, `My ATM
card doesn't work'?'' he asks. ``No, I don't! And I'm there in my
swimsuit and T-shirt.''
</P>
<P>
   He vows that service will improve. BankBoston says reports of a
customer exodus are overblown. And on Thursday, the Nantucket
bank's president of six months resigned.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sasha Cavender &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Corporate directors are at times a hunted lot. The teamsters'
union has a list of ``least valuable directors.'' The AFL-CIO has
published a report asserting that compliant boards too often
overpay chief executives.
</P>
<P>
   But Director's Alert, a newsletter for Fortune 1000 chief
executives and directors, has assembled a list of America's top 10
directors, based on the opinions of more than 100 other directors.
</P>
<P>
   The mahogany-colored envelope, please: Silas S. Cathcart,
retired chief executive, Illinois Tool Works; Hanna Holborn Gray,
retired president, University of Chicago; Gerald Grinstein,
chairman, Delta Air Lines; Roderick M. Hills, former chairman,
Securities and Exchange Commission; Ellen Marram, former chief
executive, Tropicana; David T. McLaughlin, president emeritus,
Dartmouth College; Paul H. O'Neill, chief executive, Alcoa; John M.
Richman, retired chief executive, Kraft Foods; Benjamin M. Rosen,
chairman, Compaq Computer, and Patrick G. Ryan, chief executive,
Aon.
</P>
<P>
   All 10 win high marks for the advice they give. But some details
stand out. Cathcart is fond of organizing field trips with fellow
GE board members to the company's plants.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gray is known for opposing stock buybacks, preferring to use
the money for research and marketing. And McLaughlin was
instrumental in the 1996 merger of Chase Manhattan and Chemical
Bank that eliminated 15 directors _ including him.
</P>
<P>
   _ Adam Bryant  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's not easy to change a reputation, and few people know this
better than George Steinbrenner. He is still the go-to guy for
comedy writers when they need an easy punch line, even though
recent profiles of him suggest that he may be softening slightly
around the razor-sharp edges.
</P>
<P>
   Still, his choice of management books signals that he may indeed
be trying to refine his leadership style. According to USA Today,
his current reading includes ``Cigars, Whiskey &AMP; Winning:
Leadership Lessons from General Ulysses S. Grant'' (Prentice Hall;
1998).
</P>
<P>
   Section headings include: ``Avoid Humiliating Your
Subordinates,'' ``The Organization Doesn't Revolve Around You,''
``Recognize the Limits Of Your Authority'' and ``Know When to Keep
Your Mouth Shut.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Adam Bryant  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As long as he is traveling on official business, Robert W.
Pittman, president of America Online, flies his own plane at
company expense.
</P>
<P>
   William H. Gates, who owns $55 billion worth of Microsoft stock,
has a second fortune totaling several billion dollars and invests
some of it through a company called Castle Gate.
</P>
<P>
   And Steve Wynn, the Las Vegas casino mogul, owns almost 5
percent of Activision, a California maker of computer-game
software.
</P>
<P>
   Those telling details are disclosed in Securities and Exchange
Commission records circulated on the Internet. Digging out such
nuggets, though, has been a chore because the agency's files are
organized by company, not by people.
</P>
<P>
   But starting Monday it will be easy to tie names to companies
with a new Internet search engine called Edgar-Online People, found
at www.edgar-online.com/people. Searches will be free for two
weeks; after that, access to documents other than proxy statements
will cost $9.95 a month.
</P>
<P>
   _ David Cay Johnston
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
