<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-DIARY-PERSONAL-$ADV01-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERSONAL BUSINESS NEWS ITEMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Nov. 1) 
(af) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   That 9-to-5 workday is in little danger of going the way of the
long-vanished six-day workweek. But employers are increasingly
trying to provide their workers with alternatives to traditional
schedules.
</P>
<P>
   William M. Mercer Inc., a New York consulting firm, polled more
than 1,800 employers and found that 61 percent, up from 40 percent
in 1993, offered flex time, in which employees decide their workday
hours within guidelines set by the company.
</P>
<P>
   An additional 12 percent were considering it. Growing even
faster is the opportunity to telecommute _ to work at home on a
computer linked to the office. A third of the companies offer the
option, up from 6 percent in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   _ Daniel M. Gold  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   New Internal Revenue Service rules, effective Monday, phase out
a maneuver that some investors have been using to reduce 1998 taxes
in converting their traditional individual retirement accounts into
new Roth IRAs.
</P>
<P>
   Some investors have converted IRAs to coincide with sharp drops
in the stock market. Because assets shifted to a Roth IRA are taxed
at regular income-tax rates, converting after a plunge means a
lower tax bill.
</P>
<P>
   But some people went back and forth from traditional to Roth
IRAs several times when the market was falling, knowing that the
IRS counts only the last conversion for tax purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the IRS changed the rules: only one more
conversion-reconversion is allowed the rest of this year, and
another in 1999. After that, permanent rules should be in place.
Conversions are limited to taxpayers, single or married filing
jointly, with adjusted gross incomes of $100,000 or less.
</P>
<P>
   _ David Cay Johnston
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After a month of wide movements, mortgage rates settled down
last week. While rates at individual banks in specific markets
still showed volatility, a survey of 200 lenders by Bank Rate
Monitor, the tracking service in North Palm Beach, Fla., found that
the average 30-year, fixed-rate mortgage rose just 0.01 percentage
point, to 6.79 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Brian O'Connor, managing editor of the company's Web site,
www.bankrate.com, said the consensus of lenders was that there
should be no sharp moves at least until the Federal Reserve's
policy-making committee meets on Nov. 17 to decide whether to cut
short-term rates further.
</P>
<P>
   _ Daniel M. Gold
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
