<HEADER>
A6605 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOUNTY-HUNTERS31-COX     10-30 0629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOUNTY-HUNTERS31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bounty hunters catch felony charge for busting into wrong house
 &HT;    By R. Robin McDonald
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Two bounty hunters found themselves in handcuffs
Friday and charged with felonies for kicking in the door of the
wrong Ellenwood house Monday night where a 14-year-old girl was
home alone.
</P>
<P>
   Vindex Levado Wallace, 29, a former police officer from Raleigh,
N.C., and Olatunji Andrew Spencer, 24, of Decatur were charged with
second degree criminal damage to property.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace was also charged with simple battery in connection with
an alleged attack on the 14-year-old, the daughter of Stephenson
High School teacher Vivian Morrow.
</P>
<P>
   The men turned themselves to authorities on Friday and were
released on bond following a magistrate court hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's any question they (the bounty hunters)
did not have the right to do this,'' said Morrow's lawyer, Terry
Lloyd, a former assistant district attorney and federal prosecutor.
``I don't believe under any stretch of any law, a bounty hunter, on
a rumor that a fugitive may be in a house, can willy-nilly kick in
a door. Their intent was to go in and terrorize whoever was in that
house.''
</P>
<P>
   The bounty hunters, working for Delta Bonding Co., were seeking
a man wanted on a half-dozen misdemeanor traffic warrants and for
failing to appear in court.
</P>
<P>
   After learning that the suspect did not live at the address on
the bond, they said they were directed by residents there to the
Morrow home
</P>
<P>
   They later told police and a county sheriff's deputy that they
had spotted the fugitive leaving the Morrow home. But they never
said why they decided not to either follow him or detain him at
that time. Instead they returned to the Morrow house in search of
him six hours later.
</P>
<P>
   Carrying badges identifying themselves as bail enforcement
officers in violation of a memo to Delta Bonding Co. from DeKalb
County Sheriff Sidney Dorsey warning against such practices, they
demanded entry from the 14-year-old shortly after 9 p.m. Monday.
</P>
<P>
   When the teenager refused to let them in, locked herself in her
mother's bedroom and called a friend and then 911 for help, the
bounty hunters broke down the door, police said. They ransacked the
house looking for her, broke down the door of the bedroom where she
was hiding, dragged her from a closet, and snatched the telephone
from her, said police and the girl's mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``They grabbed my baby, shined lights in her eyes, and threw her
on the bed,'' Morrow said. Then, they shoved a picture of the
wanted man in her face and demanded to know if her daughter knew
him, Morrow said.
</P>
<P>
   After the bounty hunters realized they had the wrong house, they
waited for police.
</P>
<P>
   Police said the two men told them they were working with the
DeKalb County Sheriff's Department, where they had obtained their
badges, an assertion Sheriff Sidney Dorsey denies.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Dorsey said he has asked the court to consider signing
additional warrants charging the bounty hunters with making false
statements to police. In telling police they were working with the
Sheriff's Department, Dorsey said, ``They deceived investigating
officers who arrived at the scene.''
</P>
<P>
   Those statements, Dorsey said, ``could have gone a long way to
keep them from being arrested... The statement they were working
under the color of the sheriff's department probably caused police
to back off.''
</P>
<P>
   Dorsey also said he has summoned Delta Bonding to a hearing next
week to determine whether their authority to post bond at the jail
should be suspended or revoked ``based on the criminal actions of
the bonding agents.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
