<HEADER>
A6606 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRIPLE-SLAYING-COX     10-30 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRIPLE-SLAYING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Handgun links two triple killings in Atlanta
 &HT;    By Lyda Longa
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The same .45-caliber handgun was used _ probably by
the same person _ in the slayings of a teen-ager at a motel outside
Atlanta and three out-of-town businessmen at the Atlanta Hilton &AMP;
Towers, police confirmed Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The shooting of Laderis Hawkins in the College Park Days Inn on
Oct. 15 is similar, but not identical to the Atlanta killings; for
example, while police believe the killer knew his victim in College
Park, they are not convinced the same is true in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Georgia crime lab has determined that the same gun was
used to kill all four victims,'' Atlanta police Maj. Mickey Lloyd
said at a press conference at Atlanta Police headquarters. ``The
weapon used was a .45-caliber handgun. We have real reason to
believe that the same man that killed the person in College Park,
killed the people in Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   Lloyd said ballistics tests completed by the state's crime lab,
as well as shell casings found at both crime scenes helped police
reach their conclusions earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   College Park Police Chief Lewis Harper said because Hawkins, 19,
opened the door for his killer, it adds to their suspicion that he
knew the man. Hawkins had been living at the Days Inn on Old
National Highway since August.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted to do this guy in specifically,'' Lt. Richard
Chromi said, referring to Hawkins. ``We have strong indications
that he was somehow involved with drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   Lloyd said though drugs were ruled out earlier last week as a
possible motive in the Atlanta killings, no motives are being ruled
out now. He also would not speculate on whether the Hilton incident
was random or planned.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still haven't closed the door on a motive,'' Lloyd said.
``We do know that the types of killings were similar _ both were
done in a hotel and both were done with the same gun.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerrold Shropshire, 50, of Altamonte Springs, Fla.; Ronald
Gutkowski, 51, of Leesburg, Fla; and Phillip Dover, 31, of
Gainesville, Ga., were found shot in the head on the 24th floor of
the Hilton on Oct. 18.
</P>
<P>
   Three days earlier, Hawkins was found shot in the face. All four
victims were shot more than once. Each was found in their
underwear. There was no forced entry into either of the rooms,
police have said. Except for Dover, all of the victims' keys and
wallets were taken as well.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Cobb police spokesman Robert Quigley has said that
agency is working with Atlanta to determine whether a robbery at
the North Atlanta Hilton is related to the Atlanta homicides. He
would not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Lloyd and Harper also said Friday they believe no one had been
in the room with either of the four victims before their killer
arrived. Blood found at both crime scenes belonged only to the
victims.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if the man they are looking for could be a serial
killer, Lloyd and Harper frowned.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hate to say serial killer, but at this point it's entirely
possible,'' Lloyd said.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta police have already released two video shots of a man
they're calling a ``possible witness'' in the Hilton incident. The
first tape released last Friday shows Dover walking to the hotel
elevators at 2:10 a.m. with an unidentified man dressed in a neat
khaki shirt and matching pants. The man, hefty in size, is also
sporting a dark cap. The man and Dover are seen chatting.
</P>
<P>
   Dover, hotel officials have said, had purchased a sandwich at
the hotel's 24-hour Cafe Express. He is seen holding a white paper
bag in one hand as he walks toward the elevators. The stranger was
holding a can of beer in his right hand.
</P>
<P>
   All three Atlanta victims had walked to the Steak and Ale on
International Boulevard and ate steaks and drank a couple of beers
before returning to the hotel earlier that evening, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week Atlanta police released a second video shot of
the same stranger entering the Hilton lobby sometime after
midnight. He brushes by several lobby plants and then is seen
veering toward the left where the all-night hotel eatery is
located.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators have said the three Hilton victims died shortly
after 2:10 a.m. Their bodies were found at 8 a.m. by a hotel
housekeeper.
</P>
<P>
   Lloyd said police have questioned several people, but still need
to talk to several more.
</P>
<P>
   He also said two Atlanta homicide investigators arrived in
Central Florida on Thursday to speak to police in Altamonte
Springs. Earlier this week someone broke into Shropshire's
apartment, rifling through papers in a living room drawer.
Altamonte Springs Deputy Chief Mike Deal said Thursday that
investigators have not ruled out a connection between the break-in
and the triple homicide at the Hilton, but that such a connection
seems unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   Lloyd and Chromi said they hope Friday's announcement will get
results.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've now realized that this is much bigger and we hope that
people will come forward,'' Chromi said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
