<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-30 21:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6608 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-DIARY-$ADV01-NYT &LR;      10-30 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-DIARY-$ADV01-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT BUSINESS ITEMS ON COMPANIES AND PRODUCTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Nov. 1) 
(af) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The epic courtroom battle between the Justice Department and
Microsoft has now ground through eight days in court, and the
defense's strategy seems to take new twists daily.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's lawyers, cross-examining the government's star
witness, James L. Barksdale, president of Netscape Communications,
spent several days trying to make Netscape out as a crybaby unable
to stand the rough-and-tumble of a business battle fought hard but
clean by Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   When that approach found little traction, the defense tried to
paint a crucial 1995 meeting between Microsoft and Netscape
executives as a ``setup'' meant to entrap Microsoft into
incriminating itself.
</P>
<P>
   The government riposted with a new batch of documents, including
a handwritten note from Fred D. Anderson Jr., chief financial
officer of Apple Computer, to Barksdale describing how Microsoft
strong-armed Apple into choosing its Internet browser over
Netscape's.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorneys then tried to get a senior vice president of
America Online, David M. Colburn, to say his company chose to ally
with Microsoft because Microsoft's browser was superior, but
Colburn said that a promise of a prime spot on the Windows
operating system's desktop display was the real reason.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft lawyers succeeded in dragging out Colburn's testimony
long enough to deny prosecutors the chance to play a tape of
Microsoft's chairman, Bill Gates, sparring with lawyers during his
deposition; the tape will have to wait until sometime next week,
giving Microsoft more time to devise new legal strategies.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was once uncommon to find telephone-company executives
anywhere but phone companies. Nowadays they are increasingly
crossing over into senior jobs in other businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Raymond W. Smith, who is due to retire as chairman of Bell
Atlantic at the end of the year, said last week that he would take
his experience acquiring Nynex and GTE to the investment banking
world, where he will head up the Rothschild Group's North American
holding company.
</P>
<P>
   But some don't stray so far: Alex J. Mandl, who quit as
president of AT&AMP;T in 1996 when it became clear he wasn't in line to
become chairman, said his wireless telecommunications start-up,
Teligent, was now open for business in 10 cities. ... Sprint
decided to hold off taking its wireless operations public until
markets calm down.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Market turmoil may be causing some companies to tighten their
belts, but environmental spending appears to be escaping the
cost-cutter's ax. A survey of corporate environmental managers
found that U.S. industrial companies planned to increase
environmental spending next year by an average of 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The BTI Consulting Group, which does the survey annually, said
it was the first time in seven years that industry planned to
increase its environmental budget. BTI suggested that companies
might feel they finally have other costs under control and are more
comfortable budgeting for cleanup, and that many may be sprucing up
properties and divisions that they hope to sell.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The economy grew at a faster-than-expected 3.3 percent annual
rate in the third quarter, damping fears that a recession is
looming. Durable-goods orders rose 0.9 percent in September;
analysts had expected a decline.
</P>
<P>
   But home resales fell last month, and consumer confidence sank
to its lowest level in nearly two years. ... Brazil laid out
details of an $80 billion package of spending cuts and tax
increases in a bid to stabilize its finances. ... Southwest
Airlines said it would put a toe in the nonstop transcontinental
flight arena with an experimental pair of $99 flights between
Oakland and Baltimore on Thanksgiving Day.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Having long since saturated every mass medium and most public
places with ``brand awareness messages,'' marketers constantly
search for fresh opportunities to stuff an ad into the few
remaining unsold seconds of a consumer's waking hours.
</P>
<P>
   Usually that means finding a new way to invade the home _ and a
rationale to make the incursion go down easier with a suspicious
public.
</P>
<P>
   A recent classic of the genre proclaims that ``two of America's
leading names in laundry are teaming up in a new consumer-education
effort'' to help simplify the lives of consumers by providing
``useful cleaning information when and where they need it most.''
</P>
<P>
   How is this great beneficence to be wrought? By permanently
imprinting an ad for Procter &AMP; Gamble detergent and fabric softener
inside the lids of new General Electric washing machines.
</P>
<P>
   The ``helpful tips'' range from ``Tide helps keep whites white''
and ``Downy rinses in to help gently protect fabrics'' to
lifesavers like ``Step 2: Add clothes'' and ``For best results,
read the `use and care' book that came with your washer.''
</P>
<P>
   The proud concocters of this idea boast in their news release
(which came with an actual steel washer lid) that the average
household will have to look at the ad on the lid 4,368 times over
the planned 12-year life of the machine.
</P>
<P>
   Or you could buy a front-loader.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
