<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-TRUTH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TUTU ASSAILS ANC, OTHER CRITICS OF APARTHEID REPORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KURT SHILLINGER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG _ Archbishop Desmond Tutu leveled a stinging attack
Friday on critics of the Truth and Reconciliation Commission's
final report, saying the African National Congress in particular
had squandered its moral high ground by attempting at the last
minute to block the document's public release.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't struggle in order to remove one set of those who
thought they were tin gods to replace them with others who are
tempted to think they are,'' Tutu told reporters. ``Reconciliation
is not saying a wrong has not happened.''
</P>
<P>
   The five-volume report _ the culmination of more than two years
of inquiry into the most repressive decades of the apartheid era _
accused senior leaders and parties on both sides of the conflict of
committing gross violations of human rights. Released Thursday, the
document was supposed to foster a collective understanding about
South Africa's strife-torn past. Instead it has sown division and
drawn fire across the political landscape.
</P>
<P>
   Thabo Mbeki, president of the ANC and deputy president of the
country, accused the truth panel of ignoring the party's objections
to the report and said the commission was gravely mistaken to have
found the ANC guilty of serious abuses.
</P>
<P>
   The National Party, which devised apartheid and ruled with
increasing repression for 46 years, accused the commission of
``failure to achieve reconciliation.'' The party's senior former
politicians were deemed guilty of the worst crimes.
</P>
<P>
   The Zulu-based Inkatha Freedom Party called the panel a ``circus
... a body crippled by political bias (that) could never hope to
achieve proper reconciliation.'' The commission held the party and
its president, Mangosuthu Buthelezi, ``responsible ... for 3,800
killings in the Natal and KwaZulu area.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his deep disappointment, particularly at the ANC
response, Tutu long expected that the commission's final report
would spark anger. ``You can see that truth is explosive,'' he said
in an interview a few months ago.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' he continued, ``if we didn't seek to delve deeply and
people thought they were healed, then the poison would still
perhaps be in their systems. The devil that should be exorcised
would still possess them and we would have an explosion down the
line that we had not in fact expected because we thought a healing
had happened.''
</P>
<P>
   The report is already complicating the immediate political
future of South Africa. Several parties, including the Afrikaner
Volksfront _ whose leader, former general Constand Viljoen, was
implicated in some of apartheid's worst cross-border atrocities _
are now calling for a blanket amnesty. The truth commission process
was so biased and flawed, they argue, that the only way to promote
reconciliation is to end the ``witchhunt'' for perpetrators from
all sides.
</P>
<P>
   That might be an appealing idea even for the ANC, whose
opposition to that approach five years ago led to the political
compromise ultimately establishing the truth commission. The truth
panel found the ANC guilty of abuses ranging from torture in its
military training camps to the systematic assassination of Inkatha
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Among those named as specific offenders were people now in
senior government positions _ Defense Minister Joe Modise, Deputy
Defense Minister Ronnie Casrils, and ANC Deputy President Jacob
Zuma.
</P>
<P>
   The commission, according to Deputy Chairman Alex Boraine, ``has
a great deal of information referring to people who have not
applied for amnesty, which will be turned over to the attorney
general's office.'' Under the law establishing the commission,
anyone who did not apply for amnesty or was denied the provision
can be prosecuted with the aid of material gathered by the truth
commission.
</P>
<P>
   The ANC originally sought general amnesty for all its members,
but that attempt was overturned by a court ruling and now each case
will be considered on its own merits. A blanket amnesty might be a
convenient way to protect senior ANC members now named in the
report, but the party risks a popular political backlash when
national elections are only six months away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Catharsis can be very uncomfortable,'' says Ronald Suresh
Roberts, coauthor of a book on the truth commission. ``The
commission is not about trying to make everyone feel good. It is
about broad notions of political and collective responsibility. One
of the most important outcomes is to get people to acknowledge what
happened.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
