<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-30 21:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6623 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OXFORD-EARNINGS-ART-N     10-30 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OXFORD-EARNINGS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OXFORD CUTS LOSSES, BUT NO PROFITS ARE EXPECTED SOON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., Pa., Ill.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By REED ABELSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   By reducing costs and shedding troubled businesses, Oxford
Health Plans appears to be reducing the losses that have plagued it
over the last year. The managed care company said Friday that it
had lost $47 million, or 58 cents a share, for the quarter ended
Sept. 30, on revenue of $1.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Having disappointed analysts last quarter when it reported a
loss of $507.6 million, Oxford surprised them Friday with
significantly better-than-expected results. Wall Street had been
expecting a per-share loss ranging from 65 cents to more than $1.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hardest parts of the turnaround have already been
accomplished,'' said Norman Payson, brought in as chief executive
earlier this year as part of sweeping changes at the company, which
has its headquarters in Norwalk, Conn., and which was once a
darling of Wall Street because of phenomenal growth. Oxford
stumbled badly last year after it lost control over medical costs
and fell months behind in paying doctors and hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Besides reducing the company's administrative costs, Payson
said, Oxford is selling or dropping some of its most unprofitable
plans, including those in Pennsylvania and Illinois, and sharply
cutting back participation in government-sponsored programs like
Medicare and Medicaid, where it was losing money.
</P>
<P>
   As other managed care companies reported good results, investors
pushed Oxford's stock up almost 16 percent this week. It closed
Friday at $11.8125, up 56.25 cents for the day.
</P>
<P>
   But while Oxford appears to have gained some breathing room,
health care consultants and analysts say it is premature to predict
that Oxford will return to profitability anytime soon. To do so,
Oxford must both raise premiums and reduce what it pays doctors and
hospitals. But those changes could make it hard to offer the broad
network of providers it is known for and could make its services
less popular with consumers. ``This is the critical quarter,'' said
Barry Barnett, a principal at Kwasha HR Solutions, a unit of
PricewaterhouseCoopers.
</P>
<P>
   Oxford said it had already increased premiums by about 9 percent
for many of its plans. ``The competitive environment has gotten
better,'' Payson said. He added that many employers had agreed to
higher rates because other plans were also charging more.
</P>
<P>
   While benefits consultants say that most of Oxford's corporate
clients appear to be sticking with the company, they say some may
decide to pass any higher costs onto their employees. These people
will have to pay more to keep Oxford _ in premiums, deductibles or
co-payments _ and if given a choice of other plans, they could
decide to leave Oxford.
</P>
<P>
   Enrollment has already dropped slightly, to 1.9 million members,
according to the company. Payson said Oxford could lose about 10
percent of its enrollment in its commercial plans, but many
companies and employees are still in the midst of making their
decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are just not going to have a good handle on this until
year-end,'' said Bob Braddick, a consultant with William M. Mercer
in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Oxford's medical costs also remain high. Its medical-loss ratio,
the percentage of a premium that goes to medical expenses, is 88.9
percent. ``Clearly and absolutely, improving the medical-loss ratio
is our primary challenge,'' Payson said.
</P>
<P>
   Oxford's relationship with its doctors is improving, he said,
and there have been ``almost no resignations.'' But the company's
conflict with some New York-area medical societies over unpaid
bills is unresolved. Earlier in the week, two medical groups sued
Oxford. The company called the $1 billion in damages they sought
absurd.
</P>
<P>
   All of this uncertainty makes it unclear when exactly Oxford
might return to profitability. The company's cash flow losses have
been reduced but it is still far from making money after it pays
hefty interest charges and other costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The return to positive earnings territory appears to be
farther out than in 1999,'' said Roberta Walter, an analyst with
Merrill Lynch. Oxford, which earlier in the year said it expected
operating losses to continue until the third quarter of next year,
did not offer any additional forecasts Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
