<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHOTO-FULL-UPDATE-NYT </SLUG>
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 10/30/98. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) CHAMPLIN, Minn. -- Oct. 30, 1998 -- CAMPAIGN-MINNESOTA,
10-30 -- Jesse Ventura, a former professional wrestler running for
governor, joins football practice at Champlin-Park High School. He
is favored by nearly a quarter of voters, according to the polls.
(Steve Woit/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) ESPANOLA, N.M. -- Oct. 30, 1998 -- CAMPAIGN-NEWMEXICO,
10-30 -- Rep. Bill Redmond, R-N.M., left, with former Democratic
Lt. Gov. Roberto Mondragon at a rally in Espanola. Redmond is
facing a strong congressional challenge from Tom Udall, the state's
attorney general and a Democrat. (Steve Northup/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) NEW YORK, -- Oct. 30, 1998 -- MERTON-SOCIOLOGY-PROFILE,
10-30 -- Robert Merton, who coined the phrase ``self-fulfilling
prophecy'' and developed the idea of role models and of deviant
behavior, is seen in New York. If those ideas have seeped into
daily conversation, dozens of other, less familiar ones have helped
lay the foundations of modern sociology and are still invoked in
today's heated battles over the nature of scientific truth. (Lois
Raimondo/New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) NEW YORK -- Oct. 30, 1998 -- POLITICS-HACKERS, 10-30 --
Stefan Wray, Carmin Karasic and Ricardo Dominguez of the Electronic
Disturbance Theater speaking at a panel discussion in New York this
month. Increasingly, activists have adopted computer hacking as a
tool. (Barbara Alper/NYT Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NORWALK, Conn. -- Oct. 30, 1998 -- OXFORD-EARNINGS,
10-30 -- ``The hardest parts of the turnaround have already been
accomplished,'' says Dr. Norman Payson, who was brought in as chief
executive of Oxford Health Plans earlier this year. By cutting
costs and shedding troubled businesses, Oxford appears to be
reducing the losses that have plagued it over the last year.
(George Ruhe/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) SALEM, Mass. -- Oct. 30, 1998 -- CAMPAIGN-MASS-WITCH,
10-30 -- Laurie Cabot, right, in her Salem, Mass., store, The Cat,
the Crow and the Crown, with Teri Kalgren. Every once in a while, a
political campaign comes along that offers evidence that a
particular group has become influential and must be reckoned with.
(Rick Friedman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) SANTA MONICA, Calif. -- Oct. 30, 1998 --
CAMPAIGNPCALIF-3, 10-30 -- Sen. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., at a press
conference in Santa Monica on Wednesday. Ms. Boxer finally appears
to have opened a solid lead over her Republican challenger, State
Treasurer Matt Fong - but only by outspending him 2 to 1 in
television advertisements that paint him as extremist. (Monica
Almeida/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) LONG BEACH, Calif. -- Oct. 30, 1998 -- CAMPAIGNPCALIF-2,
10-30 -- The Republican nominee for gpvernor of California, State
Attorney General Dan Lungren, after a campaign appearance in Long
Beach. Lungren, a staunch foe of abortion, trails his Democratic
opponent, Lt. Gov. Gray Davis, by double-digits in the polls.
(Monica Almeida/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- Oct. 30, 1998 -- CAMPAIGN-CLINTON, 10-30 --
Rep. Charles Schumer, left, looks on as President Clinton greets
supporters during a rally in New York on Friday. President Clinton
showed up to support Schumer, the Democrat locked in a tight race
with Sen. Al D'Amato. (James Estrin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- Oct. 30, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., NOV. 1 --
FURSTENBERG-MODEL-2, 10-30 -- Diane Von Furstenberg, in person at
her new offices in Greenwich Village, and on the walls as she was
captured in the 1970s by Andy Warhol. Her steely will is the legacy
of her mother, Lily Halfin, a survivor of Ravensbrueck and
Auschwitz, and clearly the designer's most inspiring role model.
(Philip Greenberg/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NEW YORK -- Oct. 30, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., NOV. 1 --
CHURCH-SOCIAL-2, 10-30 -- Across the city, religious leaders, both
Christians and Jews, say they have noticed the most unlikely
phenomenon: Bible-oriented social groups have become popular
singles scenes. Jannette Clemenceau, left, and Debra Straw, two
members of Marble Connection single's group, freshen up after a
brunch. (Miles Ladin/New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- Oct. 30, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., NOV. 1 --
CHURCH-SOCIAL-1, 10-30 -- Across the city, religious leaders, both
Christians and Jews, say they have noticed the most unlikely
phenomenon: Bible-oriented social groups have become popular
singles scenes. Hineni, a Jewish outreach group, is one such
meeting venue. At a New York restaurant known as ``Mustang,'' some
members of Hineni gather for an impromtu dinner. (Miles Ladin/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) MOSCOW -- Oct. 30, 1998 -- RUSSIA-MIDDLECLASS-C0X, 10-30
-- Lilia and Alexander Kazintseva were young, upperwardly mobile
Russians enjoying all that the post-Soviet economy had to offer.
Now, Alexander has lost his job as a corporate marketing director
and Lila believes her layoff as an executive headhunter is just a
matter of time. The middle class is getting squeezed by Russia's
economic crisis. (Grigory Tambulov/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) COLTON, Calif. -- Oct. 30, 1998 -- CAMPAIGN-CALIF, 10-30
-- Lt. Gov. Gray Davis - a 23-year veteran of state government who
has been widely mocked as the dullest politician in the state
Democratic Party - appears on the verge of a major victory in the
race for governor. Davis greets supporters at a campaign rally held
in Colton, east of Los Angeles, on Tuesday. (Monica Almeida/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- Oct. 30, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., NOV. 1 --
FURSTENBERG-MODEL, 10-30 -- Diane Von Furstenberg and daughter
Tatiana arrive for a movie premier of ``Life Is Beautiful'' at the
Gotham Theater in New York. Ms. Von Furstenberg surely had the most
photographed cheekbones of the 1970s. So it is jolting to see those
famous contours soften. (Frances Roberts/New York Times Photo)
*LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) BALTIMORE -- Oct. 30, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., NOV. 1 --
BIZ-BANK-FEES, 10-30 -- Peter Clough of Baltimore, a longtime
customer of the First National Bank of Maryland, is angry that his
reclassified account, promoted by the bank as ``altogether
better,'' requires him to pay new fees. He and his daughter are
shown recently visiting their local branch. (Ann Grillo/New York
Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) SADDLE BROOK, N.J. -- Oct. 30, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
NOV. 1 -- BIZ-LENDERS-2, 10-30 -- Floor Concepts ``had plenty of
business, but what we really lacked was cash to fund our
business,'' says Len Gleeson, a company partner. Although it cost
Floor Concepts considerably more to get cash from Quantum Corporate
Funding (a factor based in New York) than the company might have
paid on a short-term bank loan, Quantum is prepared to advance
funds without insisting on collateral that banks usually demand.
(Frank C. Dougherty/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- Oct. 30, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., NOV. 1 --
BIZ-LENDERS-1, 10-30 -- Craig Sheinker, the president of Quantum
Corporate Funding, a factor in New York, says he often receives
calls from bank officials, looking for a place to refer clients. In
a growing number of instances, factors are gaining customers and
working in business partnerships with an unlikely ally: banks,
their main competitors. (Andrea Mohin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) ATLANTA -- Oct. 30, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., NOV. 1 --
COKE-IVESTER, 10-30 -- These are tough times for multinational
companies, but Coca-Cola's chief, M. Douglas Ivester, says the
company should stick to its philosophy that markets can always be
widened. ``Mindset to me is setting a destination,'' says Ivester.
``It's not a matter of if we're going to get there. It's a matter
of when. I've been that way my entire life.'' (Alan S. Weiner/New
York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) SAN FRANCISCO -- Oct. 30, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., NOV. 1
-- MORTGAGE-PENNER-PROFILE, 10-30 -- Ethan Penner put real estate
lending in overdrive, but his fortunes shifted with those of world
markets. ``I'm not a corporate politician,'' says Penner, who
resigned in September amid huge losses at the Nomura subsidiary he
ran. ``Every business has its ups and downs. Politicians manage
both, so when the down cycle comes they can live for another day.
That's never been my style.'' (Peter DaSilva/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) HOUSTON -- Oct. 30, 1998 -- MCBRIDE-BOOK-PROFILE-HNS,
10-30 -- Author James McBride. McBride's book, ``The Color of
Water'' (Riverhead Books, $12), has been on the New York Times
best-seller list for 87 weeks. It is a poignant account of his
mother's life. He recounts how she, a Jewish woman and a Polish
immigrant, braved family and societal scorn by marrying two
African-American men and raising 12 children in abject poverty.
(Betty Tichich/Houston Chronicle Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) HOUSTON -- Oct. 30, 1998 -- FASHION-BUCHMAN-2-HNS, 10-30
-- Clothing designer Dana Buchman during a recent visit to Houston.
``The women I dress don't want to be on the cutting edge of
fashion, but they are chic, sophisticated and love fashion,'' she
says. ``They're funny, witty and intelligent.'' Ms. Buchman has
long been a favorite of women who wear comfortable and stylish
clothes. (Karen Warren/Houston Chronicle Photos)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) HOUSTON -- Oct. 30, 1998 -- FASHION-BUCHMAN-1-HNS, 10-30
-- Models wearing Dana Buchman's latest fashions on the runway
during the Fashion Group International's Facing 2000 Forum. At left
is a red chenille sweater with matching textured pants. At right is
a luxurious white cashmere sweater paired with a full-length black
taffeta skirt for evening wear.(Karen Warren/Houston Chronicle
Photos)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
