A6629 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDONESIA-TIMOR-NYT &LR;      10-30 0370
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-TIMOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDONESIA DENIES IT FAILED TO PULL OUT TROOPS FROM EAST TIMOR  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ The military denied on Friday that it had
not reduced the number of troops in disputed East Timor after the
government had announced a withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Information such as that is misleading and is only engineered
by irresponsible parties to disturb the comprehensive and peaceful
settlement of the East Timor problem,'' the armed forces commander,
Gen. Wiranto, said.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times had reported on Friday that opponents of
Indonesia's control over the territory said that documents leaked
from the Defense Ministry showed that the army was not withdrawing.
</P>
<P>
   The military, accused of widespread human rights abuses since it
invaded East Timor, a former Portuguese colony, in 1975, says it
has removed all combat troops and reduced the number of personnel,
to 6,000 territorial troops and 6,000 local troops, with no combat
units.
</P>
<P>
   The documents show that 17,941 soldiers were in East Timor at
the end of August. Adding paramilitary groups and pro-government
youth groups used by the military, the personnel under armed forces
control totaled more than 21,000.
</P>
<P>
   A Western diplomat who insisted on anonymity said there was
little doubt about the accuracy of the information in the documents
after comparing it with other information on military activity.
</P>
<P>
   The gradual removal of combat troops was widely seen as a
critical first step in earning the trust of the 800,000 residents
after decades of military repression under President Suharto and an
important element in President B.J. Habibie's promise to grant
greater autonomy to the region and win international recognition of
Indonesian sovereignty over East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   Estimates of the number of pro-independence rebels in the
territory vary. But the majority of the residents, mostly Roman
Catholic in predominantly Muslim Indonesia, are believed to be
sympathetic to the long fight for self-determination.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiators from the two sides are reportedly in Austria to
prepare for settlement talks next month.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations has not recognized Indonesian rule.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
