<HEADLINE>
INVESTING ITEMS ON COMPANIES, PLACES AND SURVEYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Nov. 1) 
(af) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   October was yet another month when small-capitalization stocks
lagged behind large-cap ones. But here is a reason that small caps
might soon come around: the Federal Reserve's cuts in the discount
rate last month.
</P>
<P>
   A recent report by Prudential Securities said small caps respond
particularly well to such rate cuts. Looking at the 12 months that
followed the start of the Fed's last 10 rate reductions, small
stocks did better than large stocks by an average of eight
percentage points, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 10 periods tracked, starting in 1954, the small caps
outperformed large caps in eight of them.
</P>
<P>
   The effect seems to work, to a lesser degree, on mid-cap stocks
as well. The report found that for the 12 months after the start of
the rate cuts, mid caps outperformed large caps by 6.2 percentage
points, on average. They outperformed in the same eight instances.
</P>
<P>
   The report, by Claudia E. Mott, director of small-cap research
at Prudential, said investors might be heartened by what happened
in the mid-1970s.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1973-74 recession, small stocks suffered, losing about
one-half their value at the low point. But after the Fed cut the
discount rate in December 1974, small stocks eventually rebounded.
</P>
<P>
   For a year, they merely tracked large caps. Then, at the end of
1975, they soared. ``The kind of undervaluation one sees in the
small caps today was evident back then, and perhaps some of the
large-cap overvaluation exists as well,'' Ms. Mott wrote. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Reed Abelson  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For years, municipal bond investors had no way to tell if the
price of a bond quoted by a broker was good, bad or indifferent,
unless they canvassed other brokers. That will end this month when
the Bond Market Association, a trade group, begins daily postings
on its World Wide Web site of 1,000 muni transactions tracked by
the Municipal Securities Rulemaking Board.
</P>
<P>
   The data will be available free at www.investinginbonds.com. The
site will include credit ratings, insurance data and yields,
courtesy of J.J. Kenny, the muni bond brokerage subsidiary of
Standard &AMP; Poor's.
</P>
<P>
   _ Abby Schultz  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not all hedge funds are hush-hush. Consider the tiny Loring
Fund, with $1 million in assets, managed by Patrick O'Neill of
Loring Investments in Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   The fund's strategy and holdings are disclosed on his Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched Peter Lynch and Jim Rogers telling what they are
buying and what they are selling,'' O'Neill said. ``I thought, `Why
shouldn't hedge funds do the same thing?' So I decided to put mine
on the World Wide Web.''
</P>
<P>
   The fund is relatively straightforward by hedge fund standards,
with 7 percent of its assets in cash and a moderately hedged
position. Top holdings include Netscape Communications, Johnson &AMP;
Johnson and a clutch of small-cap stocks.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill said he began the fund in 1996 with $200,000 and lost 17
percent that year, ``trying to figure out what to do.'' The fund
returned 72 percent in 1997, and 34 percent so far this year
through Oct. 1. The Web site is www.stockbook.com.
</P>
<P>
   _ Geraldine Fabrikant
</P>
<P>
   A play on Cuba? Sure. Thomas J. Herzfeld, an investment adviser
in Miami, plans to offer a closed-end Cuba fund that would invest
primarily in companies permitted to do business there.
</P>
<P>
   If the trade embargo against Cuba is lifted, the fund will also
invest directly in Cuban businesses, according to a Securities and
Exchange Commission filing.
</P>
<P>
   Herzfeld already runs the $9 million closed-end Caribbean Basin
fund, which invests in companies that operate in the Caribbean and
that should also benefit from a lifting of the embargo.
</P>
<P>
   Its only Cuban investment is $160,000 of Republic of Cuba
sovereign debt, which the fund values at zero because of a lack of
reliable trading data.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have always believed that the lifting of the Cuban embargo
would be the single most important economic factor in the region,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Carole Gould
</P>
</TEXT>
