<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATION'S ECONOMIC OUTPUT SURPASSES EXPECTATIONS
</P>
<P>
   The nation's gross domestic product grew at a surprisingly
strong 3.3 percent pace this summer, as auto makers rebuilt
inventories after the General Motors strike and consumers spent
money as fast as they earned it. In addition, the inflation rate
fell to its lowest level since 1963. The most comprehensive measure
of inflation rose at a mere eight-tenths of 1 percent annual rate.
</P>
<P>
   The figures indicate that America's economy is holding up far
better than most experts had expected despite months of financial
turmoil and heightened anxiety about contagion from the rest of the
world. The news sent stock markets soaring.
</P>
<P>
   PLAN TO CONTAIN TURMOIL ENDORSED
</P>
<P>
   The leading industrial nations endorsed President Clinton's
proposal to help protect vulnerable but healthy nations from the
kind of currency and stock market upheavals that have battered
nations from Asia to Latin America in the last year. The proposal
would establish a line of credit making billions of dollars
available to some countries to thwart speculative selling of their
currencies.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil stocks surged 7.78 percent on the agreement, which could
lead to a $45 billion credit line for Latin America's biggest
economy. Other Latin markets also rose sharply.
</P>
<P>
   BONDS TUMBLE, PUSHING UP YIELDS
</P>
<P>
   The price of 30-year bonds plummeted as a wealth of good news
sapped demand for Treasury securities. The declines rounded out the
worst month for 30-year bonds in more than a year, as signs of
stability in world markets and two interest rate cuts by the
Federal Reserve prompted investors to begin buying riskier
securities again. The yield on the 30-year bond rose to 5.15
percent from 5.08.
</P>
<P>
   BRITISH AIRWAYS DELAYING ALLIANCE
</P>
<P>
   British Airways said that it would phase in its alliance with
American Airlines over the next five years because of delays by
European and United States regulators.
</P>
<P>
   CASINOS SPENDING HEAVILY FOR VOTES
</P>
<P>
   Facing vital ballot initiatives and continuing to fight for
increased acceptability across the country, the gambling industry
and its supporters this year have contributed about $85 million in
campaign funds leading into next week's election.
</P>
<P>
   HANG SENG INDEX JUMPS 2.25 PERCENT
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong stocks closed higher as cash-rich foreign investment
funds streamed into the market, putting sidelined money back to
work. The Hang Seng index gained 223.48 points, or 2.25 percent, to
close at 10,154.94, its highest point since May 4.
</P>
<P>
   KELLOGG EARNINGS DECREASE
</P>
<P>
   Kellogg said third-quarter earnings dropped 31 percent because
of softness in the cereal market and the cost of investments
intended to strengthen its international position.
</P>
<P>
   PROTESTS IN CYBERSPACE
</P>
<P>
   Until they declared ``Netwar'' against the Mexican Government,
Ricardo Dominguez and Stefan Wray earned their activist credentials
the old-fashioned way, attending rallies in support of the
Zapatista rebels, handing out pamphlets, shouting political
slogans. Now, the two New Yorkers, founders of the Electronic
Disturbance Theater, organize ``virtual sit-ins'' and recruit
computer programmers to attack the World Wide Web sites of any
person or company they deem responsible for oppression. Their new
rallying cry: ``The revolution will be digitized.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
