<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMMUNITY-POLICING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    APD seeks more diversity, improved community policing
 &HT;    By Bob Banta
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Austin area police agencies can improve
community policing by creating programs to help minority officers
become managers, the retired chief of the Los Angeles Police
Department said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Willie Williams, who took over the Los Angeles force in 1992 and
piloted it through the turbulent aftermath of the Rodney King
beating, spoke to more than 100 law officers at a seminar at
Huston-Tillotson College in Austin. The gathering occurred as the
Austin Police Department's has been working to attract more African
Americans, Hispanics and women to its ranks.
</P>
<P>
   Giving minorities a chance to rise to command positions is an
important part of a police department's ability to diversify, said
Williams, who is African American.
</P>
<P>
   ``You must identify those individuals in your department who
display leadership and give them career support,'' he said. ``There
is great strength in having a minority officer who can talk with
people in a neighborhood and say: 'I know what you're going
through. I've been there.'''
</P>
<P>
   So far, Austin police recruiters says they have fallen short of
their goal of hiring officers with minority backgrounds for their
January cadet class. Of the 43 eligible candidates, 9 percent are
Hispanic males, 16 percent are black men, 7 percent are white
females, and 2 percent are Hispanic females.
</P>
<P>
   Austin Police Chief Stanley Knee said Friday that despite those
shortfalls, he expects the demographic breakdown of sworn officers
to meet city diversity standards by the fall of 1999, when three
more cadet classes will have graduated. Those standards call for a
police force that is 11 percent African American, at least 20
percent Hispanic, 3 percent Asian and at least 15 percent women.
</P>
<P>
   Knee said that the lack of ideal ethnic diversity in the ranks
is being offset by extra ethnic-sensitivity training for officers.
Every officer on the force has been given 10 hours of diversity
training. Additional sensitivity training is also woven into
academy curriculum.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as career management, over the next 18 months, we hope
to implement improved management and supervisory courses for our
officers,'' said Knee. ``I think by having a diverse department, it
makes it easier to do (community policing).''
</P>
<P>
   Under the principles of community policing, officers discuss
neighborhood problems with residents on their beats to solve crime
problems before they become crises.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who retired as chief of the L.A. force in 1997, said
Friday that when he first became an officer on the Philadelphia,
Pa., police force in 1964, the only career support he received was
from a black police captain who held study groups at his home for
officers preparing to take tests for promotion.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of his own experiences, Williams urged minority
officers to seek out mentors in their own departments and to form
their own study networks to get ready for tests.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
