<SLUG> BC-FBC-UGAMATCH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    How the Bulldogs and Florida match up
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   RUSHING OFFENSE
</P>
<P>
   Both teams have struggled running the ball this season, but it
appears the Gators may be taking some drastic steps to correct it.
Florida has shuffled its offensive line, inserting run blockers
Corey Yarbrough at center, Cheston Blackshear at right guard and
Cooper Carlisle at right tackle. The Gators need a strong
performance from first-time starter Eugene McCaslin, who's probably
better than Georgia's runners, who will have a tough time against
an outstanding defense.
</P>
<P>
   ADVANTAGE: FLORIDA
</P>
<P>
   PASSING OFFENSE
</P>
<P>
   Florida quarterback Doug Johnson has been inconsistent
throughout his three-year career, plagued by mental mistakes and
very poor decisions. Georgia needs to put plenty of pressure on the
junior and contain wideout Travis McGriff. Georgia freshman Quincy
Carter has been outstanding, carrying the Dogs to a 6-1 record. The
Bulldogs need big games from senior Tony Small, tight ends Jermaine
Wiggins and Larry Brown and two-way star Champ Bailey against a
questionable Gators secondary. Can Georgia give Carter enough time?
</P>
<P>
   ADVANTAGE: GEORGIA
</P>
<P>
   RUSHING DEFENSE
</P>
<P>
   Both teams have been outstanding, but Florida may have the
nation's best front seven. The Gators are allowing only 74 yards on
the ground per game; Georgia is averaging 161.4 yards rushing. The
Bulldogs need to shut down Florida's running game, which would
force Johnson to throw early and often. ADVANTAGE: FLORIDA
</P>
<P>
   PASSING DEFENSE
</P>
<P>
   Again, both defenses have done extremely well against the pass.
Georgia's secondary is more experienced with All-America candidate
Bailey at cornerback and strong safety Kirby Smart. The Gators are
using redshirt freshman Bennie Alexander at right cornerback and
first-year starter Rod Graddy at strong safety. Both teams need to
establish a strong pass rush.
</P>
<P>
   ADVANTAGE: GEORGIA
</P>
<P>
   SPECIAL TEAMS
</P>
<P>
   Both teams' kicking games have been inconsistent. Florida has a
walk-on place-kicker in Jeff Chandler; Georgia has a walk-on punter
in Wynn Kopp. But the Gators lead the nation in kickoff returns and
have two sprinters in John Capel and Robert Gillespie. That could
be a key in field position.
</P>
<P>
   ADVANTAGE: FLORIDA
</P>
<P>
   COACHING
</P>
<P>
   A matchup of two of college football's best offensive minds.
Spurrier admits that Georgia's Jim Donnan out-coached him last
year, using a plethora of offensive looks to confuse the Gators
defense. But Spurrier has had this game circled for months, and
he's had two weeks to prepare.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
