<SLUG> BC-TEX-GOV-RACE31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Governor candidates speak on capturing House majority
 &HT;    By Ken Herman and Mike Ward
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHERMAN, Texas _ Republican Gov. George W. Bush, cheerleading
for his ticket on Friday, declined to say that Republican control
of the state House should guarantee election of a GOP speaker.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, confronted with the question at campaign stops in Sherman
and Wichita Falls, clung to a hands-off position.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will let the decision of the House members be the decision
of the House members,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The House will pick a speaker when it convenes in January. Pete
Laney, D-Hale Center, is expected to win re-election if the
Democrats retain control of the House.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that as many Republicans win as possible,'' said Bush,
expressing hope that the GOP has a chance at picking up the eight
seats the party needs to have a majority in the 150-member House.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Laney have forged a solid working relationship. Laney
has steered clear of endorsing Democratic challenger Garry Mauro in
the gubernatorial race.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro on Friday dismissed the speaker speculation as moot. The
Republicans, he said, will not gain a House majority next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they really think they are, then they are going to be in
for just as big a surprise as George W. Bush, who thinks he's going
to win, too,'' Mauro said on a campaign day that took him to
Austin, Houston, Grand Prairie and Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who also campaigned Friday in Texarkana, was joined in
Sherman by Rep. Ron Clark, a Republican seeking re-election, and in
Wichita Falls by Ron Buffum, a Republican seeking an open House
seat. Like Bush, Clark and Buffum declined to say the House should
be led by a Republican if that party has a majority in the chamber.
</P>
<P>
   Though Bush has appeared in campaign brochures for House
candidates around the state _ including some Democrats _ he said
Friday there is not much he can do to influence legislative races.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing a governor can do is help a candidate become
well-funded,'' Bush said in Wichita Falls. ``But state House
politics are very local elections. What matters most in a state
House race is coffee house chatter.''
</P>
<P>
   Mauro said the GOP capture-the-House strategy is a part of an
overall big-bucks effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republicans think they can win just by throwing money
around,'' he said. ``That's how they think they can solve problems
_ with money, not by addressing issues or problems. But Texans
aren't going to buy that.''
</P>
<P>
   Mauro noted that the GOP spent $2 million on a registration
drive for suburban voters, with what he insisted are minimal
results. ``Early voting is way down. Their suburban voters aren't
materializing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But if Republicans should take control of the state House and
retain control of the Senate, Mauro said he sees no problem working
with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to be so shocked that I beat George Bush that
they will know Texans have sent a message. We'll work closely
together,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In other campaign news Friday, abortion rights proponents
endorsed Democratic attorney general candidate Jim Mattox. The
Texas Abortion Rights Action League said Republican John Cornyn
supports reversing the court decision that established abortion as
a woman's right.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn opposes abortion personally ``but he will uphold the law,
period,'' said his spokeswoman Michele Kay.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
