<HEADER>
A6649 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEX-HOUSE-RACE31-COX     10-30 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEX-HOUSE-RACE31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Battle continues in race for Texas House seats
 &HT;    By Mike Ward and Dave Harmon
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The Republican Party's push to capture control
of the Texas House has become an all-out battle of big money.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of the $125,000 or so that political consultants say it
typically takes to mount a House campaign, candidates in targeted
districts have raised at least that much in the last 30 days alone,
according to Texas Ethics Commission records.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans need to capture eight additional seats to take
control of the Texas House for the first time this century and in
the past 30 days GOP loyalists and political action committees have
dumped more than $2 million into campaigns in 16 districts that
they believe they can win _ with GOP candidates in 15 of those
districts receiving in excess of $100,000 each.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic candidates in those same districts have raised
$850,000 in the same one-month period that ended Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my 18 years in this business, I've never seen this much
money being spent on state House races,'' said Brian Eppstein, a
Fort Worth political consultant whose resume includes electing more
Republicans to the House than any other adviser _ among 160 House
races that include successful campaigns for 43 current lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a total war for power in the House.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the GOP candidates receiving large contributions include
Larry Taylor of Friendswood, who raised $220,515 in 30 days as he
tries to unseat incumbent Democrat Craig Eiland of Galveston in the
24th District. Eiland raised about $88,000 over the same period.
</P>
<P>
   Close behind is Eddie Schauberger, a Republican from Liberty
taking aim at Democrat Zeb Zbranek in District 20. Schauberger had
raised about $47,000 in three months before three PACs began
funneling money into his campaign. Of the $188,566 Schauberger
raised between Sept. 25 and Oct. 24, more than $100,000 came from
Texans for Lawsuit Reform, Associated Republicans of Texas, and
Eight in '98 _ political committees whose goal is GOP control.
</P>
<P>
   Zbranek, a three-term incumbent who raised about $10,000 less
than his challenger from July to September, is suddenly $164,000
behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those (PACs) have been recruiting my opponents the last
several times,'' said Zbranek, who spent less than $30,000 when he
won the seat in 1992. ``They want me to vote the way they want on
their special issues. They've tried to pressure me, and I've said
no, and this is the recourse they take.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, both sides are cautiously claiming victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to get to the majority, and we're going to make
that,'' said a confident Milton Rister, director of the Eight in
'98 campaign which is driving for a GOP majority _ and a
speakership for Rep. Tom Craddick of Midland _ and expects to spend
$700,000 on this year's House elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 64-dollar question right now is just how many seats we
will take.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Black, spokesman for the Republican Party of Texas,
predicts they will win at least 10 additional seats. But GOP
consultant Karl Rove says he expects to win half as many, slightly
less than a majority.
</P>
<P>
   And while Harold Cook, the Texas Democratic Party's political
director, sees little chance Republicans will win a majority,
``they think they can take the House and they're sure blowing a lot
of money because of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they're running some second-rate candidates against
qualified, experienced Democrats and they've got to buy a lot of
makeup to make them look good to voters,'' Cook said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republicans are spending whatever they think it will
take.''
</P>
<P>
   Black and Rister say Democrats are just as reliant on big-money
donations from their own special interests. In the past month,
Black said trial lawyers alone have contributed $1.7 million into
Democrat coffers. Forty Democratic contributors have contributed a
total of $2.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Republicans have raised less than that, and we have 1,690
contributors,'' Black said. ``You tell me who's the Big Tent
party.''
</P>
<P>
   Cook insists Democrats are just trying to keep up. ``The
Republicans raised the bar in the House races . . . and we will
match the Republicans this year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With Republicans steadily gaining clout in elections this decade
_ 1996 marked the first year the party was on the primary ballot in
all 254 Texas counties _ Black, Rister and others said they think
the outlook for controlling the Texas House is rosy.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the strength of our governor and the strength of our
ticket, we think the dynamics are such that we will win,'' Black
said. ``If there is a Clinton factor, it will be in our favor. We
have more Republicans running in grassroots races than ever before
_ more than 1,000 _ and their families and friends and neighbors
are voting Republican.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, with just days to go before Election Day, most
consultants on both sides concede privately that races in as many
as 15 of the most hotly contested House races are too close to
call.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, there is hand-to-hand combat going on in 12 to 15
legislative races that could go either way,'' Eppstein said. ``And
these races are tight, not because of any local issues, but because
of the amount of money that is being spent by both parties. For the
first time, state rep races are a boon to the state's economy this
year because of the amounts of money that are being spent on
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
