<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-30 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6652 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLENN31-COX-1STLEDE     10-30 0703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLENN31-COX-1STLEDE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Glenn gives video report on experiments
 &HT;    (Eds: Tightens lede, fourth graf, combines GLENN-DOOR info.)
 &HT;    By Scott Montgomery
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. _ Sen. John Glenn reported from space
Friday that he has adjusted easily to weightlessness. Then, as if
to prove he was feeling fine, he used a video uplink to once again
talk up the scientific purpose on his flight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is right on the timeline so far,'' Glenn said while
holding himself in place with his arm against a middeck bulkhead,
``and we just want to keep it that way and make sure we get back
all the good results we thought we'd get on all the research
experiments that are on board because that's the main reason we're
up here.''
</P>
<P>
   Since being named to the shuttle crew last January, Glenn, 77,
has pushed relentlessly to focus the limelight on Discovery's
scientific payload and away from his historic return to space after
36 years.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's attempt to divert attention from the space-pioneer
legend was a tough sell. As happened throughout the eight months of
training for the flight, Glenn's joyful reminiscences continually
crept into practical matters.
</P>
<P>
   Like the nighttime pass over a luminescent Perth, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a long time ago that I looked at the same thing and it
looks beautiful,'' Glenn said as the space shuttle flew 340 miles
above the earth.
</P>
<P>
   In 1962, the year of Glenn's first orbital flight, the people of
Perth burned every light in their coastal city so he would see it
as he passed over. Some even staked white sheets to their lawns to
reflect the light.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lights show up very well and thank everybody for turning
them on, will you?'' Glenn said during that original flight.
</P>
<P>
   Friday was the first full day in orbit, after Thursday's launch,
which Glenn called a ``great ride.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was keyed in with every little noise and quiver we made on
the way up,'' he said. ``It was quite different from the ride I got
before, of course, a long time ago...''
</P>
<P>
   One hitch in the otherwise perfect launch was the loss of an
11-pound, 18-by-22-inch door to the dragchute compartment in
Discovery's tail. A TV camera on the launch pad showed it bouncing
off a shuttle engine.
</P>
<P>
   A technical ``tiger team'' is analyzing potential impacts the
loss of the panel could have on the flight and landing, NASA's
chief flight director said Friday at Johnson Space Center in
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be a meeting every day for probably the next four
or five days'' to examine safety issues, said Jeff Bantle,
operations director for the mission.
</P>
<P>
   Bantle said Mission Control plans to have the winged orbiter
land as usual at Kennedy Space Center. The pilots will not deploy
the dragchute, and they will be ready to jettison it quickly if it
deploys during landing.
</P>
<P>
   Of more concern to Glenn was fully experiencing weightlessness
for the first time. He said he did not go through the period of
nausea that is common for astronauts adjusting to weightlessness,
although he worried that he would. Although he's never been prone
to getting air sick, Glenn has been vulnerable to seasickness.
</P>
<P>
   In 1962, Glenn could only loosen the straps of his seat in the
capsule, so he didn't experience weightlessness then the way he has
now.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out, he likes it.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the personal side of it, to be able float around like this
in zero g,'' he said, ``I just wish everyone could experience
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Last time, Glenn flew for just under five hours, the primary
purpose being to prove it could be done.
</P>
<P>
   His current mission will have him in space for nine days. He
returns next Saturday, and this trip he has a lot more to do.
</P>
<P>
   But with all of the shuttle's tasks well on schedule _ in fact,
some things were activated early _ the only on-board problem
reported so far was a mishap with his oatmeal as he dealt with
floating foodstuffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``One little speck wound up on my glasses,'' Glenn said,
smiling. ``I guess with old folks you normally think it goes down
on an old man's necktie, but on this one it went up on my
glasses.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
