<SLUG> BC-HALLOWEEN31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fright night now just a `candyfest', professor says
 &HT;    By Marcus Franklin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ University of Dayton Professor Jim Farrelly
remembers a time in the 1940s in north Newark, N.J., when he and
his childhood friends made their own, unpretentious costumes for
Halloween.
</P>
<P>
   He remembers when they were satisfied with treats such as
homemade popcorn balls, candied or caramel apples or two or three
pennies, and they indulged in yearly hi-jinks.
</P>
<P>
   These days, he said, Halloween has become merely a ``candyfest''
for children and an opportunity for adults to make political
statements with their costumes at parties, said Farrelly, an
English professor who teaches courses on literature and the occult
at U.D.
</P>
<P>
   ``Halloween has turned into such a mild event,'' Farrelly said.
``It's been turned into a collection of treats. It has lost all
sense of evil.''
</P>
<P>
   Halloween is the top holiday for candy sales and is expected to
generate a record $1.76 billion in candy sales this year, according
to Larry Graham, president of the National Confectioners
Association and the Chocolate Manufacturers Association in McLean,
Va. The holiday has become a celebration of candy and
``pseudo-scary festivities,'' Graham said.
</P>
<P>
   The holiday has come a long way from its origins partly because
of ``marketeers'' who have commercialized Halloween, which hardly
resembles its predecessor, a celebration called Sam Hain.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Hain was celebrated thousands of years ago in areas now
known as Ireland, Scotland and Wales, Farrelly said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a time when people actually believed the dead walked
the earth and witches practiced sabbaths,'' Farrelly pointed out.
``People tried to develop ways to avoid them so if they were going
to leave their house, they would put on a costume they thought
would put them in company with the dead so that they wouldn't be
recognized.''
</P>
<P>
   Farrelly said residents also placed candles in windows to mark
their homes as safe havens.
</P>
<P>
   Halloween no longer resembles the All Hallow's Eve harvest
celebration that was established after Irish immigrants moved to
the United States in the mid-1850s and brought remnants of Sam Hain
with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mischief came in the context of city life in the 20th
century with industrialization and when people began tenement
living,'' Farrelly said.
</P>
<P>
   Gone are the days when soap, mischief and tomato nights used to
prelude Halloween, he said. Instead, expect to see throngs of kids
on candy hunts disguised as Power Rangers, princesses, ninjas and
ballerinas, among other characters, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost like an extortion activity,'' Farrelly said with a
chuckle. ``Often times they don't even say 'trick or treat.' They
just hold their bag out and expect to get a treat. If you don't
give them something good such as chocolate, they'll say, `Why'd we
stop here.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
