</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHIO-BATS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Something batty going on in limestone cave
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    By Dale Dempsey
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Near the opening of a former limestone quarry
near Lewisburg, a small bat swoops into the tunnel toward a group
of explorers. Like a terrain-hugging fighter jet, the bat climbs
and banks to avoid the people. It is followed by another bat and
another.
</P>
<P>
   On the stone ceiling, tiny bats wrap their wings around and hang
upside-down. The cave is where they will hibernate until spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Soon the ceiling will be covered with bats,'' said Mark
Schaefer, owner of the 100-acre cave.
</P>
<P>
   The Halloween season is filled with ersatz bats, fanged cutouts
on windows and costumed trick-or-treaters, but real bats are just
as fascinating and a lot less frightening. And there's no better
place to see them than here.
</P>
<P>
   Schaefer's bat cave is home to 25,000 bats, the largest colony
in Ohio and Pennsylvania, according to biologist Jackie Belwood,
who runs the bat program from the Cincinnati Nature Center. It is
also home to about 9,300 Indiana bats, which have been on the
endangered species list since 1967.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is certainly the largest population in Ohio of the Indiana
bat,'' said Belwood.
</P>
<P>
   This time of year the bats share the cave with various ghosts
and ghouls, when the Lewisburg Boy Scouts put on a Haunted Cave.
</P>
<P>
   Belwood, however, would like to change the bat's Halloween
image.
</P>
<P>
   She has written a field book, In Ohio's Backyard: Bats , the
first in a series planned on the state's wildlife by the Ohio
Biological Survey.
</P>
<P>
   One place she could start is by changing some of the common
names of bats, such as the big-eared bat, the small-footed bat, the
long-nosed bat or the hoary bat. It seems a bit impolite to point
out that something that already looks like a flying rodent has big
ears, too.
</P>
<P>
   But bats are not rodents, which is one of the myths dispelled in
the book. They're mammals, closer in kind to monkeys and humans,
perhaps the only mammals besides the Wright Brothers to have
mastered winged flight. The bones in the micro-thin wings are
really elongated arms and fingers.
</P>
<P>
   Belwood said bats are in trouble in Ohio and elsewhere, through
loss of habitat, increased use of pesticides, and human lack of
understanding.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1960 and 1995, the number of Indiana bats has declined
from around 800,000 to 350,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that rate, it is estimated they will be extinct by 2010,''
Belwood said.
</P>
<P>
   Bats play an important ecological role. They eat thousands of
insects. Each one consumes about its own body weight each night.
Fewer bats could mean greater use of pesticides.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without them, insect pests would multiply at an alarming
rate,'' Belwood said.
</P>
<P>
   Belwood's book corrects some common misinformation about bats.
</P>
<P>
   They're not blind. All bats have eyes and can see. Hunting for
food at night, however, bats use echolocation, a sensory system
based on sound that allows them to avoid objects and locate food.
</P>
<P>
   Bats don't fly into people's hair. All bats avoid people, using
echolocation and eyesight to stay clear.
</P>
<P>
   Bats live a long time for their size. A Little Brown Bat has
lived to be 34.
</P>
<P>
   Bats can contract rabies, but it is rarer than commonly assumed.
The disease is present in less than one-half of one percent of bat
populations. Wildlife professionals do recommend that people don't
touch a downed, wounded bat. They bite if trapped.
</P>
<P>
   In the tropics, where most of the world's 1,000 bat species
live, bats pollinate plants and disperse the seeds of bananas,
mangoes, avocados, dates, figs, cashews and almonds.
</P>
<P>
   Medical studies of bats' echolocation is being used for learning
ways to treat human deafness.
</P>
<P>
   Because of their fast, erratic flight, bats can be difficult to
study. Their migratory paths are largely unknown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Historically bats get ignored because they are difficult to
work with,'' said Belwood.
</P>
<P>
   And although bats usually return to the same nesting areas each
year, they show some adaptability. Most of the species in the U.S.
use abandoned mines as roosts.
</P>
<P>
   In Preble County, wildlife officials have installed grates on
many of the entrances to the cave, which keep people out but let
the bats come and go. There are nine entrances and the bats occupy
spots deep inside, away from the people lined up for the haunted
cave.
</P>
<P>
   At least most of them do.
</P>
<P>
   Schaefer recalled that last year two bats took up residence in a
barrel by the ticket booth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here were thousands of people walking by, throwing their
ticket stubs in the barrel and they were right next to a couple of
bats,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
