<HEADER>
A6681 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OHIO-GOV-MONEY-COX     10-30 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHIO-GOV-MONEY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Taft, Fisher vie on funding field, spending $10 million combined
 &HT;    By David Gulliver
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Kenneth Rhoads fears the power of money in
politics today. That's why he gave $300 to Lee Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that when you are in a fight, you fight with the
armaments that are there. And what's there is money,'' said Rhoads,
a retired Dayton school administrator.
</P>
<P>
   Karl Zengel builds houses for a living, builds them carefully
and solid, and he sees much of that in Bob Taft. That's why he gave
the Republican $105.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't go for anything that's untried, untested,'' Zengel
said. ``I believe in working slowly.''
</P>
<P>
   Zengel lives off Mad River Road, in the the heart of Taft
Country, Montgomery County. People in the two ZIP codes covering
parts of Kettering, Miami Township and Centerville gave Taft more
than $60,000 this year, over one-fifth of the money he raised in
the entire Miami Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Rhoads lives in the Dayton View neighborhood, a hotbed of Fisher
support. The area between and around Main Street and Salem Avenue
gave the Democrat $19,698, second only to downtown, where law firms
and unions gave heavily.
</P>
<P>
   While Fisher has raised slightly more money overall, Taft is
drawing much more money locally than his opponent, roughly $3 for
every $2 by Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   Taft's heaviest support is the big-money southern end of
Montgomery County, where he reaps thousands from business titans
like the Berry, Mathile and Danis families.
</P>
<P>
   The findings come from a computer analysis of the two
candidates' contributions through mid-October, filed earlier this
week with the Secretary of State. They also can be searched on the
Internet at the Ohio Citizen Action or Secretary of State's
websites.
</P>
<P>
   Among the findings:
</P>
<P>
   The two candidates have spent nearly $10 million on advertising
since June, when their media blitzes began in earnest. Fisher has
spent $4.8 million, slightly more than Taft's $4.6 million_ on
average, $7 out of every $10 raised.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their mudslinging over the health insurance issue,
neither has closed its wallet to the industry. Taft has accepted at
least $41,000 from HMOs and their executives, but Fisher has
received at least $7,600.
</P>
<P>
   Both amounts are dwarfed by the overall contributions: Fisher
has raised more than $7 million in individual contributions, while
Taft has raised $6.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher leads Taft in money coming from political action
committees (PACs), groups representing a business or issue, with $1
million compared to his opponent's $852,000.
</P>
<P>
   Taft swamps Fisher almost 4-to-1 in Miami County donations,
raising $19,820 to his opponent's $5,050 in the Piqua, Tipp City
and Troy areas. But in northern Warren County ZIP codes, closer to
Taft's Hamilton County roots, he holds only a slim contribution
edge, $23,330 to $19,032.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Taft raised almost $281,000 in the Miami Valley, from
Sidney in Shelby County to Lebanon in Warren County, compared to
about $191,000 for Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   Money is the lifeblood of political campaigns, especially
high-profile statewide races that compete in multiple media
markets. But Fisher supporters say Taft's edge in local money
doesn't mean more local votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republicans usually out-raise us 2-to-1, 3-to-1, 4-to-1,''
said Dennis Lieberman, chairman of the Montgomery County Democratic
Party. ``Our support is not usually big-money-based.''
</P>
<P>
   The two candidates are on more equal fund-raising ground this
time because it's a statewide race, said Jeff Jacobson, chairman of
the Montgomery County Republican Party. Ohio law limits individual
contributions in state office campaigns, unlike local races,
blunting a usual GOP edge. Fisher's experience as attorney general
also gave him ties to Dayton law firms, Jacobson said.
</P>
<P>
   Given Dayton's traditional Democratic roots, Taft backers are
pleased. ``We're doing better than we'd hoped to,'' said Brett
Buerck, Taft's campaign spokesman. He said a low average
contribution_ more than half are $100 or less_ means people are
giving money because they support Taft, not to gain access.
</P>
<P>
   Zengel, for example, said he believes Taft shares his same
beliefs: Government should be more business-friendly and less
intrusive, especially when things seem to be going well. ``I say,
what was wrong with the last six years? Seems like we were living
pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   Rhoads believes in his candidate, too. ``I think he has a feel
for people who have children in school. He wants to solve the
problem, because of the children involved, because of the parents
involved, not because of the politics involved. I distrust his
opponent... I believe the opportunity for the people to be heard is
greater with Lee Fisher.''
</P>
<P>
   Money often tips the balance in politics, but it's not clear yet
if that will be the case in Montgomery County. Lieberman said a
party poll last week showed Fisher and Taft in a dead heat_ with
one-third of voters still undecided.
</P>
<P>
   ``So is money indicative of votes?'' Lieberman said.
``Absolutely not.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
