<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-30 22:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6683 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OHIO-GOV-DEBATE-COX     10-30 1131
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHIO-GOV-DEBATE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fisher repeatedly fires against GOP hopeful Taft in last debate
 &HT;    By Debra Jasper
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ This time, it was Democratic gubernatorial candidate
Lee Fisher who came out swinging.
</P>
<P>
   In the third and last debate, before a rowdy crowd of 650 at the
Cleveland City Club, Fisher repeatedly bashed his Republican
opponent Bob Taft.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher said Taft backed a failed workers' compensation
initiative that he said would have harmed injured workers, and he
said Taft didn't respond when Anthem Blue Cross and Blue Shield
threatened to cut health care coverage for 20,000 Ohioans. When a
Piqua woman called both campaigns and asked for help fighting
Anthem's decision, Fisher said Taft did nothing: ``Only one of us
responded.''
</P>
<P>
   Taft disputed Fisher's claims, saying he supports a strong, fair
workers compensation law and HMO reform.
</P>
<P>
   As the candidates attacked each other, the partisan crowd
reacted almost as if they were at a football game. Some jeered and
a couple of times even booed at the other side's remarks, and then
cheered when their candidate spoke.
</P>
<P>
   And what a difference they made. Despite the harsh questions
asked by members of the audience, all the candidates seemed more
relaxed and confident in this debate, the first held outside a TV
studio environment.
</P>
<P>
   Taft in his opening speech joked about the nonflattering
descriptions of him, noting that Bobby Kennedy and Ronald Reagan
had spoken before the City Club and assuring the audience he
``would not let my charisma overshadow these famous gentlemen.''
</P>
<P>
   Taft, 56, a Cincinnati native, also tried to take some of the
home-team edge away from Fisher, saying he's campaigned in Cuyahoga
County 122 days and feels very much at home here.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher, 47, an attorney who emphasized his roots as a native of
the Cleveland suburb of Shaker Heights, exhorted the audience to
look at the candidates' records, not what they say. He then chided
Taft, saying, ``Be consistent. Don't run away from your record.''
</P>
<P>
   Taft was quick to use Fisher's plea that voters look at their
records. When asked why he once voted against the death penalty as
a legislator but now supports it, Fisher said as Ohio's attorney
general he worked with the father of a murdered boy and other crime
victims and came to believe some criminals commit such vicious acts
they deserve the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   That's why, Fisher said, as attorney general he fought former
governor Dick Celeste's decision to commute some death sentences.
</P>
<P>
   Taft shot back that Fisher's record is clear. ``The one time he
had the chance to vote on the issue, he voted against the death
penalty.''
</P>
<P>
   John Mitchel, 51, The Reform Party candidate, a retired air
force officer from Beavercreek, said he also changed his mind on
the death penalty. However, while he once supported it he now
opposes it, and said he will remain opposed to it until death row
inmates can afford ``$400-an-hour attorneys.''
</P>
<P>
   Natural Law Party candidate Zanna Feitler, 47, a transcendental
meditation teacher from Shaker Heights, asked the crowd early on to
wave their hands in the air to support their candidate instead of
clapping, in order to minimize interruptions. The request was met
with laughter; the applause continued.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about campaign finance reform, Taft said when he ran
for secretary of state, he supported limiting individual and PAC
contributions, he said, and supports closing any other loopholes.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher retorted that Taft's ``so-called campaign finance
reform'' allowed him to raise nearly $12 million from special
interests. ``True campaign finance reform is not tinkering as Mr.
Taft has done,'' Fisher said.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher said he favors spending limits, and giving free air time
to legitimate candidates to ``get money out of the system once and
for all.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisher also tried to score points by drawing attention to a Taft
quote in a recent Cleveland Plain Dealer article. Fisher told the
crowd Taft favors throwing seniors out of nursing homes if they
don't measure up to certain standards. ``Read the quote, Bob,''
Fisher said. ``That's exactly what you said.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisher was referring to an article which quoted Taft as saying
he would look for ways to save money in the Medicaid program, an
expensive federal-state health care program for the poor, ``One of
the issues that may bear looking at is whether all the patients who
are now in nursing homes really, in fact, need nursing home care of
whether they could be provided for in some lesser-skill facility,''
the article quoted Taft.
</P>
<P>
   Taft said during the debate that all state programs, including
Medicaid, must be examined to ensure taxpayers get what they pay
for. After the debate, however, he stressed that he would not
support removing anyone currently getting care from a nursing home.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher said after the debate that he was happy he could compare
records because Taft is ``inventing himself'' as he goes along.
Fisher, who has been trailing Taft in the polls, said the momentum
is on his side, and he will travel the state all weekend telling
voters about how he differs from Taft.
</P>
<P>
   While Fisher declined to say whether he beat Taft in the debate,
Fisher's wife, Peggy had no such qualms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lee gave (Taft) a black eye,'' she said, jubilantly. ``He
whipped him.''
</P>
<P>
   Walking out the door, she turned to Taft's spokesman, Brett
Buerck, and said he should come and visit them after the campaign
``if you need employment.''
</P>
<P>
   Buerck retorted, ``You are making campaign promises your husband
can't keep.''
</P>
<P>
   Taft repeated the phrases he used in prior debates, telling the
crowd they've heard friendly and not-so friendly discussion and now
must decide. He warned them not to return to the ``tax and spend
days of the 80s.'' He said a vote for him is a vote to ``keep Ohio
on the right track.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisher ended by telling the audience, ``Education, health care,
fighting crime. These are not words from my lips during a debate,''
Fisher said. ``This is the work of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Feitler closed by saying if voters chose her, she would put all
three of the other candidates to work. She said Taft is the perfect
candidate to tutor in a children's reading program; Fisher would be
a great ombudsman to help patients get treated fairly by their
insurance companies; and Mitchel could use his military experience
to root fraud, waste and abuse from the system.
</P>
<P>
   Elect her and ``make Ohio heaven on earth,'' Feitler said.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchel said they must choose from three candidates: himself,
Feitler or Taft or Fisher. That's only three candidates, he said,
because Taft and Fisher ``are both the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
