<HEADER>
A6705 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEX-LTGOV-RACE-COX     10-30 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEX-LTGOV-RACE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sharp, Perry differ on key issues
 &HT;    By Juan B. Elizondo and Scott S. Greenberger
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ It doesn't take a lot of effort for Texas voters
to note the similarities between lieutenant governor candidates
Rick Perry and John Sharp.
</P>
<P>
   Both men want to end social promotion in schools. Both agree
that teachers need pay raises and that public education needs
improvement. Each says laws governing cities' annexation powers
need strengthening.
</P>
<P>
   But there are key differences between the two major-party
candidates. Perry, the Republican, wants to start a pilot program
in which students in low-performing schools get state dollars to
attend other schools, including private and religious ones. Sharp
says that would only hurt the public and private education systems.
</P>
<P>
   Sharp, and fellow Democrat Garry Mauro, who's running for
governor, say there's a way to end a mandatory early release
program for prisoners jailed for crimes committed before Sept. 1,
1996 _ an idea struck down by the U.S. Supreme Court when Florida
attempted it.
</P>
<P>
   Perry says he would love to do the same thing. But he agrees
with Gov. George W. Bush that it would be extremely difficult, if
not impossible, because of constitutional restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Perry or Sharp becomes Texas' next lieutenant governor _
the state's No. 2 officeholder, the leader of the Senate and the
chairman of the powerful Legislative Budget Board _ those and other
issues are sure to crop up in the legislative session that begins
in January. And even on topics on which Perry and Sharp agree,
there are differences in the details.
</P>
<P>
   It's been the theme of nearly every campaign this year and a hot
topic every time lawmakers gather.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the last time the Legislature convened, Bush put out a
plan to cut local school property taxes by increasing the state's
share of public education spending. His plan _ to kick in $1
billion in state money and increase the number of businesses paying
the state's main business tax for even more money _ got inflated,
deflated and finally passed as a $1 billion property tax cut via an
increase in the homestead exemption. For many Texans, though, the
savings were eaten up by local school tax increases.
</P>
<P>
   Bush now says he wants to put $2 billion toward the effort and
another $1.6 billion for school districts to spend as they see fit.
He's hoping that the additional money will prevent schools from
raising tax rates, giving more Texans a chance at pocketing some
savings.
</P>
<P>
   Sharp and Perry mostly line up with Bush on the issue. Sharp
wants to increase the amount of money the state gives to schools
for each student. He also wants to raise the level at which
districts with a greater amount of local property tax revenue are
forced to share with others.
</P>
<P>
   As for Bush's plan, Sharp said parts sound like his, but he
would have to see the details before agreeing to it.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to similar plans, Perry wants to pay ``reading
masters'' an extra $5,000 a year _ $7,000 if they teach in
low-performing schools.
</P>
<P>
   Education
</P>
<P>
   Education concerns don't end at the public school doors.
</P>
<P>
   In the last several years, proposals to give students publicly
funded vouchers to pay for private and religious schools have
gained popularity, mostly among conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, however, a handful of liberal Democrats, mostly those
who represent urban, minority districts, signed on to vouchers for
students in low-performing schools.
</P>
<P>
   That idea also has the backing of Bush and Perry. But Sharp and
Mauro oppose it.
</P>
<P>
   Sharp once said he was ``intrigued'' by the idea as a way to
spur competition in education. Schools that lost students and the
money that goes with them would be encouraged to do better, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Sharp now has all but shut the door on the idea. He says
competition can be accomplished by allowing students in
low-performing schools to move to better public schools. That would
encourage improvement without taking money out of the public school
system, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Perry doesn't believe that's enough. He wants to provide
vouchers as a pilot program. If it improves education, he says
lawmakers could consider expanding it. If not, Perry says he'll be
the first to pull the plug.
</P>
<P>
   Decades after the U.S. Supreme Court's Roe vs. Wade decision,
lawmakers continue to haggle over possible restrictions on a
woman's right to have an abortion. One of the latest, which has
come close to passing in recent sessions, is parental consent and
notification before a minor receives an abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Perry supports both measures, but adds that he also would use
the lieutenant governor's office to promote abstinence and
adoption.
</P>
<P>
   Sharp, a Catholic, opposes abortion. But he said a parental
notification or consent bill would have to protect the rights of
minors who need an abortion and parents' rights to be involved in
such decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can get one that protects both sides, I would not have
a problem with that,'' Sharp said.
</P>
<P>
   Added Perry, ``I don't know if I know of any elected officials
who are against abstinence.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
