<HEADER>
A6707 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KAISER-SFCHRON &LR;      10-30 0524
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KAISER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Kaiser's Ailments Continue _ $111 Million Loss in 3rd Quarter  &HT;       
 By Tom Abate 
 &HT;     c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Warning it could close this year with a loss rivaling last year's
unprecedented shortfall, Kaiser Permanente Group said yesterday
that it lost $111 million on third-quarter revenues of $3.9
billion.
<P>
   Kaiser, the nation's largest health maintenance organization,
said its operating loss was slightly offset by $9 million it earned
primarily from stock investments.
</P>
<P>
   But so far this year, its operating losses, the most important
indicator of its long-term health, have totalled $240 million.
</P>
<P>
   Given that winter is typically the sick season, Kaiser said it
expects its losses will continue despite cost-cutting efforts. It
predicted it would end 1998 with a loss comparable to the $266
million shortfall it posted in 1997 _ the first loss in its
history.
</P>
<P>
   Wanda Jones, an analyst with the New Century Health Care
Institute in San Francisco, said Kaiser's ills are easy to diagnose
but will take time to cure.
</P>
<P>
   In the last couple of years, aggressive recruiting drives
swelled Kaiser's ranks. But while Kaiser was adding members, large
corporate insurance buyers were forcing all HMOs to hold their
rates flat, and that particularly affected Kaiser, which was 10
percent lower to begin with.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rates will have to go up,'' Jones said. ``In real dollars,
Kaiser and the other HMOs have seen as much as a 25 percent
reduction in real premiums since the early '90s.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser has already negotiated a 10.75 percent increase for 1999
with the California Public Employees' Retirement System (CalPERS),
its biggest customer.
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser Chief Financial Officer Dale Crandall said he is
``cautiously optimistic'' that rate increases will enable the
company to report a profit in 1999. He said the HMO will try to
raise rates in 2000 and 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Crawford, an HMO analyst with Fox-Pitt Kelton, said
Kaiser's rate increases will enable competitors like WellPoint
Health Networks Inc., Foundation Health Systems Inc. and PacifiCare
Health Systems Inc. to follow suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``They need to raise rates aggressively for the next couple of
years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason for Kaiser's current troubles, according to
Jones, is that during the past few years of stagnant rates, it
halted a $6 billion construction program it had planned in the late
1980s. In high-growth areas like Southern California, it has been
unable to treat all its new members in its own facilities, and has
been forced to pay higher costs by farming the excess out to other
hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser noted yesterday it has opened two new hospitals, one in
Baldwin Park in Southern California, and the other in Roseville,
north of Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   In California, where Kaiser has some 5.6 million HMO members,
the company reported operating losses of $55 million for the
quarter and $190 million for the year to date.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1945, Kaiser has some 8.5 million members in 17
states and Washington, D.C. It employs some 10,000 physicians and
90,000 technical, administrative and clerical employees.
</P>
</TEXT>
