A6709 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DIGITAL-SFCHRON &LR;      10-30 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Fingerprint Technology for Everybody  &HT;       
 By Tom Abate  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Grant Evans dreams of a day when millions of corporate workers will
routinely give their computers the finger.
<P>
   It's nothing personal. Evans is vice president of sales at
Identicator Technology, a San Bruno firm that sells tiny electronic
pads that read fingerprints.
</P>
<P>
   For years the Pentagon has used this type of pad to ensure that
only people with the right fingerprints enter secure sites.
</P>
<P>
   Now this spy-proofing technology has gotten cheap enough for
everyday use. Next week, Identicator will announce that Key Tronic
Corp., a leading keyboard maker, will begin shipping a $149
keyboard that includes this built-in fingerprint security feature.
</P>
<P>
   Plug the keyboard into a PC. Install Indicator's BioLogon
software. Put a finger _ the index or middle finger is recommended
_ on the translucent square on the left side of the keyboard. A
tiny camera inside the keyboard will record the distinctive aspects
of your fingerprints and certify that you _ and only you _ access
that computer.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an end user, you'll never have to remember another
password,'' Evans said.
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe, one day, if corporations adopt fingerprint systems
to replace passwords. But this is such a new technology that
Identicator _ a private firm with 50 employees _ would be thrilled
if it can ship 55,000 of these new keyboard systems by the end of
the year. The target is corporate buyers looking for better
security.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; So passwords will hardly vanish overnight. But Evans argued
that so-called biometric security devices are the wave of the
future. Biometrics is the science of identifying a person by
physical attribute, like fingerprints, retinal scans or voice
patterns.
</P>
<P>
   Whereas people often forget passwords or, worse, write them on
sticky notes where they can be copied or stolen, ``You can't leave
home without your fingerprint,'' Evans said.
</P>
<P>
   Protecting desktop computers from unauthorized access is only
the beginning. &UR;  &LR; Evans said laptop computers with fingerprint ID
systems will start appearing next year. So even if someone steals
your laptop, at least they won't be able to access your data.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Cream puffs? &LR;  International headlines alerted us in February
when a Belgian man hit Microsoft Chairman Bill Gates with a cream
pie. And Leah Garchik blew the whistle when Nobel Prize-winning
economist Milton Friedman suffered a similar fate at an October 9
appearance in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   A shadowy group calling itself the Biotic Baking Brigade claims
``credit'' for some of these, and other less-known, cream puff
pranks. And the group seems to be stepping up the pace of the
attacks.
</P>
<P>
   I spoke with a BBB agent who said it was one of his
collaborators who threw a pie at Monsanto Chairman Robert Shapiro
Tuesday night, just after Shapiro finished a speech at San
Francisco's Fairmont Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   And yesterday I got an e-mail that the same group, through
allies in the United Kingdom, planted a pie in the face of Renato
Ruggiero, Director General of the World Trade Organization, as he
was preparing to make a speech.
</P>
<P>
   My source said past BBB targets have included Charles Hurwitz,
the corporate raider who controls the Pacific Lumber Co. Indeed,
I'm told the BBB is headed by a dozen pranksters who my informant
says have a secret oven deep in the Headwaters Forest. Headwaters,
of course, is a shrine of the environmental movement. The state is
in the process of buying it from Hurwitz.
</P>
<P>
   This BBB collective is apparently plotting future pie attacks on
targets who personify greed, global trade, genetic engineering,
etc.
</P>
<P>
   Now I enjoy a joke as much as the next person, especially when
it's played on someone else. But the Biotic Brigade may be, shall
we say, half-baked, if I am correctly informed about future
targets.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so it makes some sort of sense to list Senator Dianne
Feinstein and Congressman Frank Riggs. Both figured in the
Headwaters drama. But why is Apple Interim CEO &UR;  &LR; Steve Jobs the
prime target of a campaign to pie ``computer executives for getting
us into the ... Y2K (mess)?'' Hell, I could have seen pieing Jobs
last year, when he killed the Mac clones. But why punish him for a
programming shortcut that occurred before his birth?
</P>
<P>
   And I'm told San Francisco Mayor Willie Brown ``should know
there's a pie with his name on it.'' His crime: being ``one of the
most pompous politicians in modern time.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeez, if that's a cause of action, even newspaper columnists may
not be safe!
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Got a tip, gripe or brainstorm? Tom Abate wants to hear it by phone
(650-961-2689), fax (650-961-5023) or e-mail ( &LR; abate(at &LR; 
 &LR; sign)sfgate.com &LR; ). &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
