<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-30 22:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6710 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIGGER-SFCHRON &LR;      10-30 0497
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIGGER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Bankrupt ISP Finds White Knight   &HT;       
 By Jon Swartz 
 &HT;     c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
An Internet service provider that promised Net access for life was
resurrected from the dead on Halloween eve.
<P>
   The bankrupt San Jose company _  &LR; bigger.net _ was acquired by
Brigadoon.com last night for an undisclosed sum. Its new owner
vowed to continue the company's service to about 40,000 customers
who paid $60 for lifetime Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have received an offer and accepted it,'' said Wendy Smith,
the &UR;  &LR; San Francisco attorney representing the U.S. bankruptcy court
trustee responsible for selling the remnants of  &LR; bigger.net.
``We're happy with what we got and, more importantly,  &LR; bigger.net's
customers will continue to receive the service.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; bigger.net filed for Chapter 11 reorganization last December,
but continued to operate until it filed for Chapter 7 liquidation
this month. In the past week, service has been limited.
</P>
<P>
   The tentative deal is subject to bankruptcy court approval.
</P>
<P>
   Under terms of the agreement, Brigadoon.com is required to pay a
``substantial sum'' by Monday to Concentric Network Corp., the
Cupertino company that has hosted  &LR; bigger.net services.
</P>
<P>
   Bankruptcy officials were given a deadline of yesterday to find
a buyer, or else Concentric would have pulled the plug on the
sputtering network, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said she received a pair of offers this week, but that
Brigadoon was by far the aggressor. The Bellevue, Wash., company is
a leading Internet service provider for schools, nonprofit
organizations and small- to mid-size businesses.
</P>
<P>
   In the confusion following the dismantling of  &LR; bigger.net, the
U.S. bankruptcy court of Northern California has acted as a
caretaker while looking for a buyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've tried our best to keep the service running until the
transfer of ownership,'' said Barry Milgrom, another lawyer
representing the bankruptcy court trustee. ``I'll admit it's been
bumpy, and that some customers were not receiving service.''
</P>
<P>
   While most of  &LR; bigger.net's customers said they are happy with
the service, investors and creditors may never be repaid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I doubt many of us will ever see our money,'' said one former
executive. ``Good luck to the next crew running that place.''
</P>
<P>
   Creditors are owed $1.5 million, according to the bankruptcy
court. One investor, National Financial Trust, had sunk $2.8
million over the past nine months into the company.
</P>
<P>
   Former  &LR; bigger.net executives said it will require $10 million
to $15 million to get the troubled company back on track.
Telecommunication costs alone run about $100,000 a month, sources
said.
</P>
<P>
   But the company has some upside. The company's name recognition
and customer base are enticing for potential advertisers, industry
observers said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, two local Internet service providers _ Netcom and
Pacific Bell Internet _ yesterday offered discounted services to
 &LR; bigger.net users.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-30-98 2239EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
