<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLF-TOUR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SINGH LEADS AFTER SECOND ROUND OF TOUR CHAMPIONSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The dour expressions, the clubs slammed to the ground
in frustration and the double-bogeys said it all. The season-ending
Tour Championship has become a grind, a grueling test at the East
Lake Golf Club on a course that is as demanding as it is
picturesque.
</P>
<P>
   How difficult was Friday's second round? For the first time in
his professional career, Tiger Woods completed back-to-back rounds
without a birdie, and he was alone in last place (11 over par).
</P>
<P>
   Only five players broke par today, even though the field
comprised the year's top 30 money-winners.
</P>
<P>
   Even Vijay Singh, who shot a brilliant 63 on Thursday, started
Friday in disastrous fashion: bogey, par, triple-bogey, bogey. So
instead of building his lead, Singh went into survival mode like
everyone else, happy to escape still holding first place.
</P>
<P>
   Setting up an unpredictable weekend on an unforgiving course,
Singh's even-par 70 Friday kept him at seven under par for the
tournament (133), two strokes ahead of Jim Furyk (five under par
after Friday's 68) and three strokes ahead of Hal Sutton, who shot
a 67 to equal the best round Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever wins this weekend will have accomplished something
special. The deep Bermuda rough and lightning-quick greens make
East Lake an adventure anytime, but Friday the wind picked up to
about 15 miles an hour at times, adding to the challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Singh showed admirable resiliency and composure, regrouping
after his horrendous start, shooting five under par over his final
13 holes. Not only did Singh end the day with the lead, he also
ended it with confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have shot 80 if I had lost it,'' Singh, who started
the day with a three-stroke lead, said. ``Yesterday's round was
free-flowing. Today, you're trying to crawl out of the hole you've
dug for yourself. It was always a battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very satisfied that I got it back and I'm still in the
lead. I know I'm not going to have that bad of a start tomorrow, so
I'm feeling good right now. A good night's rest, positive thoughts,
and tomorrow will be really good.''
</P>
<P>
   But other players, such as Billy Mayfair, may have trouble
sleeping. Mayfair shot a 66 on Thursday, but struggled to a 77
Friday. And it had to be embarrassing for Woods to see his name at
the bottom of board. Because there is no cut at the Tour
Championship, Woods must endure another 36 holes at East Lake.
Asked to describe Friday's 76 after shooting a 75 on Thursday,
Woods sounded like a part-time weekend player.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit it in the rough, the bunkers, the trees, the gallery,
the water _ you name it,'' Woods said. ``I had one six-foot putt
for birdie that I lipped out. The rest of the time, I had 20- to
40-footers. You can't make a living doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods never regrouped, but Singh did, even after taking a 7 on
the par-4, 387-yard No. 3. Singh's triple-bogey adventure started
when he hit his drive into a fairway bunker. He squirted the bunker
shot into another bunker. Then he skulled his bunker shot over the
green into the rough.
</P>
<P>
   Singh tried to bump his next shot through the rough and onto the
green, but the deep rough stymied him and stopped the ball before
it reached the green. Singh finally reached the green on his fifth
shot, pitching to five feet, but he missed the putt, then finally
tapped in.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you add them up, it comes to 7,'' Singh said.
</P>
<P>
   Singh three-putted on the next hole for another bogey, and
suddenly he was tied with Furyk and Sutton for the lead. But Singh
made a birdie on No. 6 to change the momentum and followed with
another birdie on No. 9. Then after a bogey on No. 10, Singh played
his best golf of the day.
</P>
<P>
   He hit a wedge approach shot eight feet from the cup at No. 12,
then made the putt for birdie. At No. 13, he hit another wedge
approach shot to eight feet, setting up another birdie.
</P>
<P>
   At the par-5 No. 15, Singh reached the greenside bunker in two
shots, then hit a beautiful bunker shot that landed three feet from
the cup, and he tapped in for birdie. Then Singh made his final
birdie at No. 16, making a 15-foot putt that put him back at seven
under par.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, with 10 players starting the weekend at even par or better,
almost anything could happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sitting in a good position,'' Furyk, who had a bogey-free
round Friday, said. ``But there's still a lot of golf left.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
