<HEADER>
A6792 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-USC-LADN     10-30 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOWL-STARVED TROJANS NEED A WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When he takes the Coliseum field today, linebacker
Chris Claiborne won't be thinking about USC's missed opportunities
or bowl possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   He'll be happy enough to finally face a Washington team that
doesn't enjoy the vast physical edge that has helped the Huskies
win the past two meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time since I've seen Washington they don't have
a huge running back and five huge linemen,'' Claiborne said. ``I
won't have to wear a tailpad.''
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies no longer have a Corey Dillon or Rashaan Shehee in
the backfield, and their top two linemen from last season _ Benji
Olson and Olin Kreutz _ left early for the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   But will that necessarily mean the Trojans can snap out of their
mini-funk, which has seen them drop two of their past three games?
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a whole lot of season left,'' wide receiver Billy
Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The seniors haven't beaten Washington. That's motivation for
me.''
</P>
<P>
   It just might be a narrow goal _ like finally beating the
Huskies _ that helps USC (5-3, 3-2) bounce back from its emotional
17-13 loss to 12th-ranked Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans need to win two of their final four games to become
eligible for a bowl, so today's encounter with the Huskies figures
to be crucial. If USC loses, it would have to beat Stanford next
week and either UCLA or Notre Dame at the conclusion of the season.
</P>
<P>
   As formidable as that sounds, USC coach Paul Hackett was still
talking about the Rose Bowl this week, even though the Trojans are
in fifth place in the Pacific-10 Conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we're totally out of the woods. It's a reach
right now,'' Hackett said. ``It would take some people helping us.
But I'm never going to come off that goal, this year, next year or
any year. It's not over until it's over.''
</P>
<P>
   It's highly unlikely the players actually believe that. Many of
them are tired of staying home the past two bowl seasons, and dread
the thought of another December watching bowl games on TV. They'll
be happy to go to any bowl, now that Rose Bowl aspirations have
virtually disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are sick of staying home,'' quarterback Mike Van
Raaphorst said. ``The last two years, everyone goes home and goes
their separate ways. It was tough last year watching other people
play.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Washington (5-2, 3-1) finds itself in a nearly
identical position. The Huskies barely beat Oregon State last week,
and now have a three-game stretch with USC, Oregon and UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still trying to find our personality with young players
and kind of mixing chemistry on both sides of the football,''
Washington coach Jim Lambright said.
</P>
<P>
   Especially in the backfield. The Huskies' running game has been
nonexistent; reserve quarterback Marques Tuiasosopo is the leading
rusher, with just 277 yards. Freshman tailback Willie Hurst is the
next-leading rusher, with 212 yards and a paltry 2.5 yards per
carry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can't get worse,'' Lambright said. ``This game is typical.
We've got a couple freshmen, Willie Hurst and Braxton Cleman, who
are going to carry the load.''
</P>
<P>
   There's been much talk in Seattle about Tuiasosopo, who lined up
at tailback for a few plays last week, moving full-time to running
back. But the position switch was more of a smokescreen than
anything else, designed to keep the opposing defense off-balance.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Trojans, they need to find a way to revive their
struggling offense. It just might mean more passing today, as a way
to keep Washington's blitzing defense from becoming too
free-wheeling.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the only way you can stop it. To throw quick stuff,''
freshman quarterback Carson Palmer said.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett will start Van Raaphorst, and said he doesn't want to
try and place too much pressure on Palmer, especially after he
played well against Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I don't want is to have a disaster. We've worked too hard
for success,'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   Notes: A crowd of 60,000 is expected for USC's homecoming....
USC is hopeful defensive tackle Aaron Williams (neck stinger) will
be available. Shamsud-Din Abdul-Shaheed will start in place of
Williams.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-30-98 2306EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
