<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-DEMS-GINGRICH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS FAULT GINGRICH FOR HIS ROLE IN ATTACK ADS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mo., Colo.)  (Duplication warning: Also filed in ``p'' category) 
(mk) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Seizing on Speaker Newt Gingrich's role in
approving new Republican campaign commercials that allude to the
Clinton scandal, Democrats led by Vice President Al Gore Friday
condemned Gingrich for using the commercials as a way to gain
support for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``These attacks, personally devised by Speaker Newt Gingrich,
are wrong,'' Gore said at a news conference. Gore said he was
``shocked'' to learn of Gingrich's involvement in the commercials,
intended to energize voters. He described them as ``more personal
ads, more personal attacks, more partisan investigations, more of
the politics of personal destruction.''
</P>
<P>
   In what appeared to be an orchestrated strategy, the Democrats
resurrected Gingrich as the favorite target he was in 1996, when
they demonized him as the symbol of a dangerous rightward lurch of
the Republican Party. Now they plan to broadcast a radio commercial
naming him as the leading Republican force for impeachment and
blaming him for deflecting attention from issues voters want to
hear about.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., the minority leader, joined Gore in
criticizing Gingrich. In a letter to Gingrich, Gephardt wrote that
the speaker's role in preparing the commercials had compromised his
promise to lead an impartial investigation into whether Clinton
should face impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is clear that you have forfeited your legitimacy as speaker
through your involvement in these latest Republican attack ads,''
he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Gingrich, Christina Martin, said the speaker's
contribution had been vastly overstated. She said he ``was aware
but not involved in either the scripting or the execution of the
ads.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact,'' she added, ``Newt Gingrich was no more a part of
these ads than Al Gore was a part of Bill Clinton's inappropriate
behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   Two Republican officials familiar with the development of the
commercials said that Joe Gaylord, the speaker's chief political
consultant, was the creative force behind them and that Gingrich
only approved the overall strategy.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic response Friday was the latest twist in a
fast-moving story that began on Tuesday with the first reports that
Republicans had turned to the scandal involving Clinton to firm up
support for Republican candidates in close races. By all accounts,
early predictions of huge Republican gains in the House and Senate
on Election Day have in recent days given way to expectations of
moderate increases.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to appeal to Democratic voters angered by attacks on
Clinton, Gov. Roy Romer of Colorado, general chairman of the
Democratic Party, introduced the radio commercial and complained
about Republican tactics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never could it be more clear than it is now that the strategy
of the Republican Party as we approach the final days is to
concentrate every way they can to impeach the president,'' Romer
said. ``All their cards are on the table.''
</P>
<P>
   The new 60-second radio commercial opens with an announcer
saying: ``This is no ordinary time. Republicans have made removing
the president from office their top priority.''
</P>
<P>
   It goes on to say that Gingrich ``is personally orchestrating
these pro-impeachment negative ads.''
</P>
<P>
   That radio advertisement followed one that the Democrats began
broadcasting on Thursday. It opens the same way as one Republican
television commercial, with one woman asking another, ``What did
you tell your kids?''
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with a constant Democratic theme this election season
_ hammering Republicans for legislation that did not pass, like
money for school construction _ the women review the Democrat
initiatives and one says: ``All Republicans talk about is more
investigations. They are obsessed with getting rid of the
president.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' says the other, ``it's time to get rid of those
Republicans.''
</P>
<P>
   In response to the Democrats' complaints, Jim Nicholson,
national chairman of the Republican National Committee, lashed
back, chiding Gore for what Nicholson called allusions to a
``partisan plot that was masterminded by the highest-ranking
elected Republican.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a distraction,'' he said. ``The real issue facing voters
this weekend is a simple one: Knowing what we do about Bill
Clinton's judgment, will we reward him by giving him a Democratic
Congress again?''
</P>
