<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-30 23:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6797 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAMPAIGN-MINNESOTA-AR     10-30 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-MINNESOTA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINNESOTA GOVERNOR'S RACE: CANDIDATES ARE NECK, NECK AND NECK 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
(duplication notice: also sent with `a' code) 
 (bl)  
 By PAM BELLUCK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITCHFIELD, Minn. _ Norman Degeest poked his head into the Main
Street Cafe on Wednesday morning to catch a glimpse of Norm
Coleman, the Republican candidate for governor, giving the
breakfast crowd a peppy plug for his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Then Degeest strolled a few yards across Main Street to where
the Democratic candidate, Hubert H. Humphrey III, was politely
pressing the flesh on the sidewalk outside Jimmy's Pizza.
</P>
<P>
   It was a stroke of serendipity that both candidates happened to
be in this small southwest Minnesota farming town at the same time
(forcing the candidates to shake hands gamely with each other in
front of Doffing's Smart Wear). But it did not help Degeest make up
his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really too close to call for me,'' said Degeest, 63,
who drives a tanker for a chemical company. ``I like them both.
That's why I'm undecided. In fact, there's three good people
running for governor.''
</P>
<P>
   Degeest is hardly the only one expressing confusion about what
has become a surprisingly close governor's race.
</P>
<P>
   While Humphrey, the state attorney general who is the son and
namesake of the former vice president and senator, had been way
ahead in the polls, that is no longer the case. Two polls in the
last two weeks have shown Humphrey, known as Skip, running neck and
neck with Coleman, the mayor of St. Paul _ each favored by a little
more than a third of those surveyed.
</P>
<P>
   And in a strikingly strong performance by a third-party
candidate, Jesse Ventura, a former professional wrestler, action
film star and talk radio host, who is running on the Reform Party
ticket, was the favorite of nearly a quarter of the voters polled.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is now a three-way race,'' said Professor Chris Gilbert,
chairman of the political science department at Gustavus Adolphus
College in St. Peter. ``Frankly, we the analysts and the media, we
regarded Ventura as a cute curiosity before the recent poll
numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   Experts still think it is unlikely that Ventura, a musclebound
and mustachioed 47-year-old nicknamed the Body, can win. But the
fact that Ventura, a former Navy Seal demolition expert who has
shown up at candidate forums in camouflage and whose governing
experience consists of a four-year stint as the mayor of the
Minneapolis suburb of Brooklyn Park, has made such headway has spun
the election into near unpredictability.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody saw it coming,'' said Steven Schier, chairman of the
political science department at Carleton College in Northfield.
``You got about a third of the state that's Republican and a third
that's Democrat. Very few people beyond those reliable votes are
moving toward Coleman and Humphrey.''
</P>
<P>
   Something about the colorful, straight-talking Ventura, who
describes himself as ``fiscally conservative and socially moderate
and liberal,'' has resonated in a state where populist messages
have often held sway and where 24 percent of the voters supported
Ross Perot, the Reform Party candidate for president in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   A more substantive candidate than experts expected, Ventura has
easily articulated opinions on most issues, like his pledge to give
the entire state budget surplus back to taxpayers and his
opposition to merit pay for teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going Jesse,'' said Greg Uken, a 28-year-old aircraft
mechanic in Willmar, about 100 miles west of Minneapolis. ``I don't
wear a suit and I don't put up with a lot of stuff and neither does
he.''
</P>
<P>
   Humphrey, 56, has the advantage of his venerable name, his
father's revered reputation, and his achievements during 16 years
as attorney general, including his highly publicized fight against
tobacco companies. His views are largely in the tradition of the
state's Democratic-Farmer-Labor Party, including a more modest tax
cut than his opponents have promised, a proposal to expand the Head
Start preschool program and a pledge to give tax credits to
families for help with day care, elder care and college tuition.
</P>
<P>
   But Gilbert said Humphrey had not managed to excite voters
enough, and that as a result his party risked losing both the race
for the governor's mansion and the party's control of the state
House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   Around noon Wednesday, in Willmar, shaking hands at the Town
Talk Cafe, Humphrey's low-wattage Scandinavian-prairie style was on
display. He apologized for interrupting a meal and deferentially
asked people to vote for him Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   A few blocks away, Coleman was showcasing a different style.
From a makeshift stage in the parking lot of Willmar Electrical
Services, he energetically promised the small crowd that he would
give $3 billion of the state's $4 billion surplus back to the
taxpayers. Somewhat more conservative than the outgoing governor,
Arne Carlson, a Republican, Coleman opposes abortion rights and
recognition of gay marriages, and favors the expansion of
Minnesota's existing school choice program, which does not involve
vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman, 49, seems quite a bit younger than Humphrey and in the
rough cadence of his speech it is easy to hear the grit of the
Brooklyn, N.Y., neighborhoods where he grew up. A long-haired child
of Woodstock in the 1960s and a Democrat until two years ago who
once worked for Humphrey in the attorney general's office, Coleman
has been trumpeting his success in bringing economic development to
St. Paul, often considered the scruffy, rundown twin to
Minneapolis. Critics call him an opportunistic political chameleon.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Ventura continues his unconventional, low-budget
campaign, waged largely through interviews on talk radio stations.
He has just broadcast his first radio and television
advertisements, including one where children play with a Jesse
Ventura action figure who fights with Evil Special Interest Man.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a warrior at heart, I'm an ex-Navy Seal,'' said Ventura,
who is clearly enjoying his campaign. ``I'm too old to wage war
anymore and so now I wage it mentally. And so I find politics very
stimulating; it's war without guns.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-30-98 2308EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981030.0454 </DOCNO>
