<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-FRANCHITTI-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLOW-STARTING FRANCHITTI IN HIGH GEAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL SCHLOTTER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FONTANA _ The numbers were unimpressive _ mediocre at best.
</P>
<P>
   But Barry Green, co-owner of the Team Kool Green racing program,
didn't become a successful talent scout on the FedEx CART
championship tour by relying on the numbers.
</P>
<P>
   So after watching young Dario Franchitti struggle through a
modest 1997 rookie CART campaign, Green ignored Franchitti's
20th-place finish in season points, pooh-poohed his season-best
ninth-place result at Australia and went out and hired the
25-year-old Scot away from Hogan Racing for the 1999 and 2000
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like a lot of people, I saw that he had very, very good
speed,'' said Green, who brought young Canadian Jacques Villeneuve
to the CART series in 1994 and won the series title with him in
1995. ``Even though he only had a ninth-place finish, it was pretty
easy to see this guy had talent.''
</P>
<P>
   What Green could see at the conclusion of the 1997 season
everyone is seeing now.
</P>
<P>
   Franchitti comes to Sunday's 1998 CART season finale at the
California Speedway in second place in season points, the winner of
three of the series' past five races. And he has won the pole
starting position a series-leading five times.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were pretty slow to get going at the beginning,'' said
Franchitti. ``But in the second half of the season, we've really
been the number one contender.''
</P>
<P>
   Number One _ period _ of course, has been Alex Zanardi who comes
to Sunday's Marlboro 500 with seven wins and the 1998 season title
already zipped up inside the hip pocket of his firesuit. But by
being Zanardi's top adversary in the final races of 1998,
Franchitti has earned new status as one of the favorites to replace
the Italian champion when he departs CART for Formula One after
Sunday's race.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how it is in any sport,'' said Franchitti. ``The older
drivers, they retire or they move on and it's up to us younger
drivers to move up.''
</P>
<P>
   A CART title in 1999 seems a long drive from Franchitti's
20th-place showing in 1997. But Don Halliday, Franchitti's race
engineer, said he realized early on that his driver has unusual
skill.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the course of last year, you could see flashes of
brilliance,'' Halliday said.
</P>
<P>
   Then Franchitti came to Team Green, and Halliday took him out on
the track for a test.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first impression was that he had a lot of what I would call
one-lap speed,'' Halliday said. ``I felt if we could multiply that
to race distance that we could win.''
</P>
<P>
   Franchitti came close for the first time with a runner-up finish
at the Long Beach Grand Prix in April. Then came a three-race
streak of accidents and mechanical problems that saw him finish
21st, 19th and 27th.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, at the Havoline 200 at Elkhart Lake, Wis., in August,
Franchitti made his breakthrough, beating Zanardi by seven seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks later, he was first again at Vancouver. Then came a
fourth at Laguna Seca, another victory in Houston and a runner-up
finish two weeks ago in Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Driver Greg Moore, Franchitti's best friend on the tour, gives
his pal credit for skill and tenacity on the track.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it doesn't hurt that he's driving the best package out
there,'' Moore said. ``Reynard (chassis), Honda (engine) has been
the best this year. I think he and Zanardi have proved that.''
</P>
<P>
   In a profession where drivers tend to go their own ways when not
competing, Moore, Franchitti and fellow driver Max Papis _ a trio
of young bachelors _ have become road companions.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're kind of like the Rat Pack of racing,'' said Team Green
publicist Ed Nichols.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're about the same age,'' said Moore, who at 23 is the
youngest of the tour's young stars. ``We like to do the same
things. We'll do anything once.''
</P>
<P>
   The list of activities has included mountain biking, go-kart
racing and nightclub hopping.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In Australia, I went bungee-jumping,'' Moore said. ``That's
about the only thing that Dario has refused to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Franchitti, who was a protege of Scottish racing legend Jackie
Stewart in his early youth, seems quiet to those who don't know him
well, Moore said.
</P>
<P>
   He'll have to get his two more-ebullient pals to teach him how
to open up. Because if he keeps on his present winning course, the
auto racing world is going to want to hear all about him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
