<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA OFFENSE EXPECTED TO SPLURGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ On UCLA's first offensive play of today's
homecoming game against Stanford, coach Bob Toledo will honor
alumni by recreating the serpentine huddle used in the 1950s under
legendary coach Red Sanders. The Bruins will break from their
huddle in a slithering movement and jog to the line of scrimmage
one behind the other.
</P>
<P>
   But from that point on, Toledo will blow tradition away with an
attack and philosophy unimaginable 40 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people believe you win with defense and special
teams,'' Toledo said. ``I've never believed that. I've seen great
defensive teams in 0-0 ties. If I wanted to do that. I'd go play
soccer...
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always argued with other coaches. How can you win if it's
a 0-0 tie? I'm different, I guess. But you've got to outscore your
opponent. It comes down to that.''
</P>
<P>
   Unless Stanford's defense comes disguised as anyone else's, the
No. 2 Bruins will score this afternoon. Slow, small and carrying
one of the smallest senior classes in the country, the Cardinal not
only has the worst defense in the Pacific-10, but one of the worst
defenses in Pac-10 history.
</P>
<P>
   It's allowing 480 yards and 38.9 points per game; both figures
are last in the league and near the bottom nationally. It has
yielded an average of 47 points in three road games, including 63
at Oregon. The yards-allowed differential between Stanford and
ninth-rated Washington (95) is greater than that between Washington
and No. 1 Arizona (60).
</P>
<P>
   Oregon State scored 30 points against the Cardinal in a rare
Pac-10 victory. San Jose State scored 35 against Stanford. Even
Notre Dame scored 35, and the Irish offense moves at glacial speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some point, our defense is going to have to step up and
make plays,'' Stanford coach Tyrone Willingham said, declining to
give an exact date. ``You still have to win with defense, to some
degree.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinal can't stop anyone and it can't run (88 yards per
game), but it can score. With playmaking receivers and a
three-quarterback rotation that includes Camarillo's Joe Borchard,
Stanford averages 332 passing yards per game and regularly
surpasses the 30-point barrier.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Willingham may get the shootout he dreads. The Rose Bowl
scoreboard may get the workout of a lifetime, and the 3:30 p.m.
game may not end until 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to throw 50 times, and that's the way we like
it,'' said UCLA cornerback Jason Bell, who watched six hours of
videotape this week in preparation for the Cardinal attack. ``They
live and die off throwing the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanford leads the Pac-10 in passing and passers. Todd Husak
will start at quarterback, with Borchard and Randy Fasani rotating
regularly. Against Arizona State 10 days ago, the trio sometimes
rotated by the play: Husak on first down, Borchard on second and
Fasani on third. Fasani, the No. 1 quarterback recruit in the
nation two years ago, may play tight end, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sought ways to involve them in the games, and ways they
could have an impact,'' Willingham said.
</P>
<P>
   Revolving quarterbacks won't alter UCLA's plan. The Bruins will
blitz from all angles, concede short passes, and try to overpower
the Cardinal with their running game. Perhaps the only obstacles
between UCLA and its 17th consecutive victory are turnovers and
lethargy.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the Bruins have avoided lethal doses of each. But if
they require an enthusiasm injection, Toledo will remind them of a
21-20 loss to Stanford two years ago at the Rose Bowl. The defeat
ultimately kept UCLA from a bowl game, and it may have been the
lowest moment for Toledo and quarterback Cade McNown, who shared
blame for a malfunctioning two-minute offense.
</P>
<P>
   McNown doesn't plan on a repeat performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't look at any game as a breather,'' he said. ``Stanford
has good players who could erupt at any time. We have to be ready
for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Notes: The first 10,000 fans entering on the east side will
receive a McNown fan mask....
</P>
<P>
   Between the first and second quarters, UCLA will honor Dr. Louis
J. Ignarro, who won the Nobel Prize for medicine....
</P>
<P>
   A crowd of more than 60,000 is expected, so fans are advised to
arrive early in the congested Arroyo. As usual, shuttle service is
available from the Parsons Engineering Building in Pasadena to the
Rose Bowl.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
