A6825 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOHLS-COLUMN31-COX     10-30 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOHLS-COLUMN31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bohls: No repeat of '96 upset
 &HT;    By Kirk Bohls
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Nebraska will beat Texas today. Long limb, huh?
</P>
<P>
   History says I'll be right. Before you insult my ancestry and my
IQ, be reminded I picked Texas to upset Nebraska in 1996 and was
considered Looney-Tunes then. Two years ago, however, the Longhorns
had the surprise factor working, everybody but the Cornhuskers'
water boy supposedly had the flu, and Nebraska fans had already
booked every hotel in New Orleans for the Sugar Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the site ain't neutral, the fans certainly won't be,
the Big Red has better special teams, and Nebraska will have a mad
on for Texas _ all reasons the Huskers will prevail by 27-17. They
almost always do, don't they?
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska has beaten 67 of the last 71 teams to line up against
it. Nebraska has beaten the last 47 teams that have had the guts to
tiptoe into Memorial Stadium. Nebraska beats everybody, except
Texas A&AMP;M in years ending in '98.
</P>
<P>
   Why, you ask, do the Cornhuskers never have a falloff? Why do
Texas, Alabama, Louisiana State, Southern Cal, even Notre Dame and
especially Oklahoma all slip from their pedestals from time to
time, but for Nebraska a bad year is 9-2 and a fire-the-coach year
is 8-3? Actually, Nebraska hasn't even had a losing season since a
3-6-1 mark in Bill Jennings' final year back in 1961, emphasis on
the final year.
</P>
<P>
   Only Penn State comes close to matching the year-in, year-out
success of Nebraska, and both are mirror images of one another.
Secluded settings far from major media markets. Legendary head
coaches Joe Paterno, Bob Devaney and Tom Osborne. Continuity in the
coaching staff with 135 years of experience from Nebraska
assistants, three of whom have stayed in Lincoln 22 or more
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska is the only Division I-A school in the state, meaning
unified, fanatical support, while 10 play in Texas. The Cornhuskers
do not have to share fans, dollars or limelight with a single pro
franchise, whereas the Longhorns share a stage with seven, if you
count the Dallas Mavericks. Twenty-eight states are represented on
the Huskers roster, plus a pair of I-backs hail from hotbeds
Belgium and Canada. Other than Gale Sayers (Kansas) and Larry
Station (Iowa), rare is the Nebraskan who leaves its borders.
</P>
<P>
   Simply put, Nebraska is a machine.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like the same players over and over again,'' Texas
tight end Derek Lewis said. ``It's almost scary. Nebraska's like GM
putting out great cars. They always have a fierce running back, a
smart quarterback, a front seven that keeps attacking you. It's
like they have 100 scholarships every year.''
</P>
<P>
   That isn't so far-fetched. Frank Solich's roster is 188 players
deep, thanks to more than 100 walk-ons. (Texas has 120 players.)
Nebraska has long been accused of profiting from ``county
scholarships'' in which each of the state's 93 counties financially
sponsors a walk-on who does not count against the school's
85-scholarship limit, a charge the program emphatically denies.
</P>
<P>
   Few schools can match Nebraska's walk-on numbers or its history
of success there with All-American players such as tackle Jimmy
Williams and all-conference players such as former tailback I.M.
Hipp. More than a third of the players on the team's current depth
chart, including quarterback Monte Christo, fullback Joel Makovicka
and the starting right guard and tackle, came as walk-ons. Having
the cheapest tuition rates in the Big 12 doesn't hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tom knew the importance of walk-ons and carried it forward,''
Solich said. ``It's been vital to us at a number of positions.''
</P>
<P>
   Some schools cannot keep as many walk-ons because larger numbers
would affect their compliance with Title IX gender equity
requirements. Nebraska carries more women's sports (14) than any
other Big 12 school and recently added women's rifle, probably to
post sentries and ensure football's supremacy.
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska's male-female athletes (67 percent men, 33 women) do
not come close to mirroring the student body, which comprises 53
percent men and 47 women. But school officials point to more Title
IX compliant scholarship expenses of $2.3 million for men and $1.5
million for women.
</P>
<P>
   If you think a lawsuit like the one that resulted in Texas
starting women's soccer, softball and rowing would adversely affect
Nebraska football, think again. Nebraska spends $8.5 million a year
on football. It reportedly takes in about $28 million, which can
pay for a lot of rifles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nebraska has said they haven't had requests for more women's
sports, but that's like asking the fox if the chickens are OK,''
said Donna Lopiano, executive director of the Women's Sports
Foundation. ``I don't see Texas cutting down its funding of its
football program any more than I do Nebraska. (A Title IX lawsuit)
would definitely be a red herring when it comes to killing a
football program.''
</P>
<P>
   And nothing is going to distract Nebraska from its football.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-30-98 2357EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
