<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-30 23:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6826 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HIGHWAY-BATTLE01-COX     10-30 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIGHWAY-BATTLE01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Debate surrounding highway proposal exemplifies race's intensity
 &HT;    By Ken McCall
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ If anything shows the degree of attention the
race in Ohio's 6th District is getting, the fate of Lt. Gov. Nancy
Hollister's highway gambit does.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal was run up to the very top of the political
flagpole and was killed by President Clinton's promise in
mid-October to veto the entire Omnibus Appropriations bill unless
the item was deleted.
</P>
<P>
   The lieutenant governor wanted to take money from the Portsmouth
bypass project in U.S. Rep. Ted Strickland's home base of Scioto
County and divert it to projects around the area. She got approval
of the state Department of Transportation and took it around to
local governments.
</P>
<P>
   But she didn't get approval of the one body created by Congress
to administer federal economic and highway development in the
region: the Appalachian Regional Commission. Instead, she went to
Rep. Ralph Regula, R-Navarre, who got House Speaker Newt Gingrich
to put the proposal into the giant federal budget bill that was
Congress' last order of business this year.
</P>
<P>
   Strickland says he got wind of the proposal when he was asked
about it by other members of Congress. Strickland says he was
outraged to discover that Hollister was trying to circumvent the
established public process and ``sneak something into a huge
appropriations bill.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The people in Portsmouth and Scioto County had no idea this
was being done,'' he says. ``Here I see a longtime promised project
being stripped away with no public hearings.''
</P>
<P>
   In desperation, Strickland says he called the White House to try
to stop the end run around the process. He was promised a return
call by Clinton, but it never happened. Then, a few days later,
Clinton and Strickland were able to talk at a public function and
the president promised to strongly oppose the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 16, White House Chief of Staff Erskine Bowles wrote a
letter to Gingrich stating that if the item was included, ``the
President would veto the bill.''
</P>
<P>
   Later that week, Hollister's campaign began faxing the letter
out to news organizations along with charges that Strickland had
killed $320 million for ``six major Southern Ohio highway
projects.''
</P>
<P>
   One Hollister press release was headlined: ``In Baffling
Reversal of Tactics, Strickland Hinges Campaign on Opposing
Progress for His Constituents.''
</P>
<P>
   In truth, however, no federal money was derailed, only
Hollister's ``de-designation'' of the Portsmouth bypass. The
district will still receive $25.5 million in federal funds for
highways.
</P>
<P>
   Hollister contends her plan would have cut through red tape, and
that much of the Portsmouth bypass is no longer feasible.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you have,'' Hollister says, ``is somebody put dots on a
map 25 years ago and nothing can be built there.''
</P>
<P>
   Hollister says she began having public discussions back in
February about the plan. In fact, she won endorsement of the
project from a number of public bodies, including the Portsmouth
City Council.
</P>
<P>
   Strickland doesn't have a program, she says, and should get out
of the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``This program is bigger than either one of us,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Strickland admits that some parts of Hollister's plan ``make
sense,'' but he objects to circumventing the established public
process for setting highway priorities in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, he points out, folks promoting a congressional action
simply for the good of the district almost always work through
their congressman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said all along, if this is not just a political maneuver,
why not bring it to me?''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
