<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   Germany: Inquiry on Holocaust Remark
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors have opened a formal investigation into the comment
made by a French nationalist leader, Jean-Marie Le Pen, last year
in Munich that the murder of 6 million Jews in Nazi gas chambers
was a ``mere detail'' of history. It is illegal in Germany to deny
or trivialize the Holocaust. Le Pen's immunity as a member of the
European Parliament was lifted on Oct. 6.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   Chile: Pension Funds Invest Abroad
</P>
<P>
   Privatized government pension funds, which have become a model
for many Latin American countries, have increased investments in
foreign stock and bond markets 314 percent in the last year,
according to regulators. The funds began to send money abroad late
last year, as the Chilean stock market stumbled. By September the
funds had invested $356 million abroad, mostly in Germany, Ireland,
Luxembourg and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico: 30 Salinas Accounts Frozen
</P>
<P>
   The government has frozen 30 more bank accounts said to belong
to Raul Salinas de Gortari, brother of former President Carlos
Salinas, the newspaper Reforma reported. One account had $16
million that Raul Salinas said he had given to his wife. Mexico is
scrutinizing at least 289 accounts here and abroad totaling $250
million for possible graft and money laundering.
</P>
